<SLUG> BC-LA-CRIME-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME DOWN IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes New Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Crime in Los Angeles and cross the San Fernando
Valley slipped to 1970s levels through Dec. 19, but still at least
one person is killed on an average day, according to LAPD figures.
</P>
<P>
   They include Jose Jimenez, a 26-year-old mechanic who was killed
with several shots to the head in suburban North Hollywood over the
Christmas holiday. And they include the horrific murder of Galdino
Venegas, a 38-year-old cook whose throat was slashed during a
takeover robbery at a restaurant in San Pedro, 25 miles south of
downtown L.A., on Dec. 13.
</P>
<P>
   These brutal slayings feed many people's belief that crime in
Los Angeles remains high, even as the numbers tell a vastly
different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception that it's out of control, when in fact
crime is down at least 50 percent from five years ago,'' said Los
Angeles police spokesman Lt. Anthony Alba of the figures released
Monday. ``We have to do a better job of selling the decrease in
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kleiman, a University of California, Los Angeles professor
who specializes in crime control, blames this distorted perception
on how TV news handles crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of homicides are falling. But the number of news
reports of homicides has actually been soaring,'' Kleiman said.
``People are terrified.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the drop in violent crime overall is significant in Los
Angeles and the neighboring cities of Burbank and Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Across Los Angeles, there were 410 homicides as of Dec. 26, as
compared to 566 last year, according to the LAPD's Crime Analysis
Section. In the early 1990s, the city logged about 1,300 murders
annually _ or some 3.5 a day on average.
</P>
<P>
   Crime fell 12.6 percent citywide and 10.8 percent in the San
Fernando Valley, from Jan. 1 through Dec. 19 this year, as compared
to year-end figures in 1997, according to the LAPD's computerized
crime analysis system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're apparently in the 1973 era of crime numbers,'' said
Detective Woodrow Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Criminologists and police attribute the decline to a vibrant
economy; stricter sentencing laws, including ``three-strikes'';
good police work; and fewer young men, the group traditionally
responsible for most crime.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Gil Garcetti warns that prosecutors and police
must not be lured into complacency because the population of young
men will bounce back by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to focus on truants and first-time offenders ... and
programs to work with schools to identify the chronic truant and
work with the child and parent,'' Garcetti said, adding that 78
percent of all convicted criminals are school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   Stiffer sentencing laws send a strong message to would-be
criminals that they will pay for even being connected to a crime,
he said. They include a new law for 1998 that Garcetti's office
sponsored, which toughens sentencing for people who are found to be
present during a crime involving a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will deter crime,'' Garcetti predicted. ``The gang members
are talking about this because they are all facing life
sentencing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alba agreed that the police must redouble their efforts to
address the roots of crime, not just the people who commit them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prevention is every bit as important as arresting offenders,''
he said, adding that the department's goals include establishing
programs for youngsters, including parenting classes, reading
programs and Explorer Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of rapes, which ominously spiked in Valley during the
first half of the year, have fallen off since then, with the West
Valley Division reporting the largest decline, 31 percent, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of robberies were also significantly down citywide and
in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Valleywide, homicides were down by about 11 percent, with Van
Nuys logging the most substantial decline: nine slayings this year
vs. 14 last year _ or 36 percent below last year. However, Valley
officials warn the statistics do not reflect the last two weeks of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The only LAPD Valley division reporting an increase was
Devonshire, where 14 people were killed as of Dec. 19, compared to
11 for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said Devonshire's figure could be attributed, at least in
part, to an increase in gang crime there.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a nationwide trend, the crime tally in cities around
Los Angeles also were poised to hit levels not seen since the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, north of downtown L.A., the number of slayings fell
by 60 percent, with two between Jan. 1 and November, compared to
five during the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Overall violent crime in Glendale was down 20.2 percent.
Theft-larceny was the only category that increased, by 3.1 percent
_ mainly stemming from break-ins of locked vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Burbank reported four killings from Jan. 1 through
November, compared to zero murders in 1997. But the 25-year average
has been five murders per year, said Burbank police Lt. Larry Koch.
Overall violent crime in Burbank was down 15 percent, with 581
fewer crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of the 581 represents an individual victim who didn't
have to be victimized,'' Koch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
