<HEADER>
A9654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-29 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ The movie Weekend at Bernie's comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of some wild kids taking advantage of a free
trip to paradise, fumbling around all over the place and ultimately
getting caught in the middle of something ugly.
</P>
<P>
   They try desperately to prop up the lifeless body of their boss,
who was suddenly and brutally snuffed out in his prime by
gangsters. They slap some sunglasses on him, mold a silly grin on
his face and cart him around town hoping no one will notice.
</P>
<P>
   These Kansas State Wildcats, their coach, Bill Snyder, and their
rabidly supportive fans with obviously short memories have come to
San Antonio like dead ringers, so to speak, for Bernie.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Cats have been brutally snuffed this bowl season, no doubt
about it. They probably deserve better than the Builders Square
Alamo Bowl. Sure.
</P>
<P>
   They should have a bigger stage and a better opponent than 8-4
Purdue. They should be New Year's Day and prime time, not Tuesday
night and a mid-level bowl on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the country realizes this. The Wildcats emphatically
have reminded us, and reminded us, and reminded us again ever since
Texas A&AMP;M pulled the rug out from under them in the Big 12
Championship Game and the Bowl Championship Series whacked them
when bowl bids were announced Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   But the 'Cats don't seem to know paradise or the opportunity to
still stake claim to the national championship when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   They have arrived by the thousands _ up to 30,000 purple-clad
supporters, by some estimates _ to a beautiful city, with a
beautiful history, restaurants and parties galore and weather
dialed up by the chamber of commerce _ sunny, 70-degree days and
cool, margarita-sipping nights.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 'Cats still consider it all a chamber of horrors.
</P>
<P>
   They drove for hours, as Wildcats fans are wont to do, and
rolled into town with chips on their shoulders and shoe polish at
the ready. Messages such as, ``Bring back the Big Eight'' and
``Forget the Alamo'' have been scribbled everywhere. A popular
T-shirt seen around town shows a bold, purple ``X'' transposed over
the letters ``BCS.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the River Walk on Monday night, a chant of ``We want
Tennessee'' went up, while throughout the week leading to tonight's
kickoff, players and coaches have tried futilely to do and say the
right things.
</P>
<P>
   It's all been as transparent as that smile on Bernie's face.
It's all been so lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious reason why the Wildcats should get over it is, well,
they didn't beat the Aggies. The secondary couldn't stop Branndon
Stewart. The offense couldn't protect a lead or hold on to the ball
in the waning moments. The greatest linebacking corps the 'Cats
have ever had couldn't tackle Sirr Parker on third-and-long.
</P>
<P>
   K-State offensive coordinator Ron Hudson said this week, ``To
lose to A&AMP;M when we were a better football team that was hard to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   But all the Wildcats had to do was prove they were better. They
didn't. And this is where the admittedly screwy bowl system dropped
them.
</P>
<P>
   All the 'Cats must do now is take the Alamo Bowl and turn it
into the stage they still think they deserve. Beat Purdue with
authority. Hold on to the ball and the lead. Send a message that is
more important and lasting than shoe polish on the hotel window and
letters on a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there's something about brutally cold, bowl-less and
windswept days in Manhattan, Kan., that the rest of us don't know
about, the once-dismal Wildcats more than any other program should
know there are worse places to be than San Antonio on a 70-degree
December day. The Wildcats should know there are worse situations
to be in than 11-1 and No. 4 in the country.
</P>
<P>
   They should know the national championship still is out there
and still a real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Win, Kansas State. Win big, and hope Ohio State and Tennessee
both lose, neither of which is out of the realm of possibility. And
leave it up to the Associated Press pollsters, who would be free to
vote Florida State or Kansas State No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo Bowl is not a booby prize but an opportunity. The
Wildcats blew their last great opportunity, the one about which
they all still seem inconsolably bitter. Their coach compared the
A&AMP;M loss to deaths in the family and the horrible automobile crash
that injured his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   What should bother people today is not what happened earlier
this month but how the Wildcats have reacted. From the head coach,
to the Heisman runner-up quarterback, to the thousands of fans
grumbling as they walk along the River Walk, it has become clear
the Wildcats feel something was taken away from them and it's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see a school like this come that close, I don't think it
will happen again,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not gone. Purdue is not Tennessee. San Antonio is not
Tempe. But a little help from Texas A&AMP;M and Florida State and a lot
of what got K-State through its first 11 games still might replace
those transparent smiles on so many faces with the real thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 0020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
