<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9656 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SHERRILL-HNS &LR;      12-29 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SHERRILL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ Nothing can get the orange blood of University of Texas
fans boiling faster than these two words: Jackie Sherrill.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saddam Hussein probably wouldn't rate as high on the list of
evil villains for UT fans as Sherrill, the former Texas A&AMP;M coach
who will lead Mississippi State against the Longhorns on Friday in
the Cotton Bowl. Hate may be too kind a word to describe the scorn
Longhorns have for Sherrill, who has coached his teams to seven
consecutive victories over UT.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sherrill won't admit it publicly, people close to him
will tell you the feeling is mutual. Lynn Amedee, the Mississippi
State offensive coordinator who coached under Sherrill for three
years at A&AMP;M before spending three seasons at Texas, knows the real
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is a big-time deal for Jackie,'' Amedee said.
``Being on that other sideline against them for so long, you just
have a natural rivalry. He has been successful against Texas, and
he wants to keep it that way. That's the purpose he has, and he's
serious about it. He reminds us that this is a big ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill's last game against the Longhorns (1992) prompted an
incident that will live in college football infamy. Sherrill had a
bull castrated at Mississippi State's practice to fire up his
players for the game, which the Bulldogs won 28-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bevo (the Longhorn mascot) is still upset about what
happened to one of his buddies,'' Texas coach Mack Brown kidded.
``We've gotten him some counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown may be able to joke about it, but that act crystallized
Longhorns fans' loathing of Sherrill and demonstrated his hostile
feelings about Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people get hung up in that,'' Sherrill said. ``I'm
sure for a lot of Texas fans who are caught up in their love for
that school, I'm not a very good word in their minds. But that's
part of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas defensive end Aaron Humphrey said the players are well
aware of how their fans feel about Sherrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, we know about it,'' Humphrey said. ``One of the
first things brought up to us was the games Jackie coached at A&AMP;M.
Nobody around Texas likes him a whole lot, to be blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know about him castrating the bull the last time they
played us. That gets us fired up a little bit. He kind of never
mind. I won't even start on that. He's a good coach, but yeah, we
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill insists he isn't obsessed with beating Texas but admits
he will have some special feelings when he returns to the stadium
where he led the Aggies to three consecutive Cotton Bowl
appearances from 1986-88.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think it will affect me that much,'' Sherrill
said. ``It probably will hit me when I go down that ramp. I'm not
real excitable until kickoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Amedee believes Sherrill may be the most misunderstood man in
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``People for some reason don't like him,'' Amedee said of
Sherrill. ``Over the years, there have been problems between Jackie
and the media. But when you work for him, shoot, I would do
anything for him. He's a boss you can sit down and talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill left A&AMP;M after the 1988 season amid scandal and NCAA
violations involving boosters, which led to probation for the
school. But Sherrill never was implicated in the violations. He
spent two years out of coaching, including a stint as a part-owner
of a Ford dealership in Baytown.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill said he had other offers before deciding to take the
job at Mississippi State before the 1991 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to high school in Biloxi, so I grew up knowing about
Mississippi State,'' Sherrill said. ``They had some good teams, but
they never had been able to win consistently. I think it was very
similar to the way A&AMP;M was when I took over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill has led the Bulldogs to a 49-42-2 record, including
four bowl appearances in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a coach's coach,'' Amedee said. ``You have to be
tough-skinned, because he is going to let you know how he feels,
but he's fair, and that's all you can expect from a coach. I think
a lot of the other stuff is people just not knowing the guy, and
he's hard to know sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill is seen as aloof and unemotional, but there is another
side he rarely reveals. Earlier this week, Sherrill was moved to
tears when asked about his most memorable Cotton Bowl moment.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill told a story about how his close friend Bob Bernath
died after watching the Aggies win the 1986 Cotton Bowl 36-16 over
Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good friend of coach (Bear) Bryant,'' Sherrill said.
``When I went to A&AMP;M, coach Bryant called him and said, `You take
care of Jackie.' So we became very close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were over there on Christmas Eve having dinner, and he was
upstairs in bed. It was clear he wasn't going to live much longer.
We had to call an ambulance to take him to the hospital. So I went
to see him before I came up here (to Dallas) on Christmas Day. He
said he was going to stay alive to watch the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was joking with him and said, `What do you want the score to
be?' He said, `I want you to beat them by 20 points.' We got our
Cotton Bowl watches early, and I gave him mine. He watched the
game, and then he passed away, but we beat them by 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill had to pause several times during the story because he
was choked up and couldn't speak. It isn't something most people
would expect from Sherrill, but he is a man of many faces.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best way to understand Sherrill is to ask his players
about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real person, and he's not going to tell you something
that isn't true,'' said Bulldogs running back James Johnson. ``
He's a straight shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Wayne Madkin said Sherrill is a teacher, not a
preacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't do all this yapping and hollering,'' Madkin said.
``But he has a unique way of getting you ready to play. He is a
calm, quiet voice telling you what you need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill's typical sideline attire is a long-sleeve white shirt,
a dark tie and a clipboard _ a no-nonsense look for a no-nonsense
approach to the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always relished playing coaches that jump on the table
and holler and scream and all those things,'' Sherrill said. ``As
soon as you get out there on the field and the player across from
you slaps you in the face, you realize this is the deal, not that
dumb coach yelling on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody spends too much time giving accolades to the coach.
Coaches can lose games, but I've never seen a coach win a game, no
matter what the fans think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
