<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROSENOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BADGERS HAVE SPECIAL EDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The participants have called it a matchup of
UCLA's potent offense against Wisconsin's stingy defense, and
Wisconsin's powerful running game against UCLA's young, wobbly
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But chances are, special teams will have a voice in the Rose
Bowl, and that appears to favor the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   Because bowl teams are permitted only 15 postseason practices _
they spend much of that time regaining lost rhythm and cramming for
opposing attacks _ special teams are often lost in the frenzy. When
kickoff arrives, anything can happen, and has.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk to our team, I'm going to remind them of West
Virginia-Missouri (in the Insight.com Bowl),'' Bruins coach Bob
Toledo said. ``There was a field goal blocked, a long kickoff
return and a blocked punt. The kicking game showed up huge in that
game. And Colorado had a kickoff return for a touchdown against
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kicking game is so vital, and the participants in bowl
games only have so many hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin may have the best special teams UCLA has faced this
season. Kicker Matt Davenport made 18 of 20 field goals, while
Kevin Stemke averaged 44 yards per punt. Both players were named
first-team All-Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers have blocked four kicks and returned three punts for
touchdowns. Nick Davis averaged 15.7 yards per return, also tops in
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   With punter/kicker Chris Sailer and punt returner Ryan Roques,
UCLA's special teams are as solid as they've been in years. But can
they match Wisconsin?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we can win that area, but we can't lose it,''
Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Big anniversary: Jan. 1, 1994 is a significant date in UCLA
history, and it has nothing to do with the Bruins' 21-16 loss to
Wisconsin in the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That day, over a thousand miles away, Texas A&AMP;M lost to Notre
Dame 24-21 in the Cotton Bowl. In the aftermath, Aggies coach R.C.
Slocum fired his offensive coordinator, Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew it was going to happen,'' said Toledo, who
eventually took the same post at UCLA and, on Jan. 4, 1996, became
the Bruins' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Pass the beef: The undisputed champion of Sunday's visit to
Lawry's Beef Bowl was offensive tackle Kris Farris, who said he ate
six slabs of 14- 16-ounce prime rib.
</P>
<P>
   Farris doubled the intake of offensive guard Andy Meyers, long
considered the Bruins' best eater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel OK, but I fell asleep at 7:30,'' Farris said.
</P>
<P>
   QB comparison: Wisconsin senior quarterback Mike Samuel had a
modest passing efficiency rating of 115.2 and averaged just 93
yards passing per game. But he has impressed Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like (Cade) McNown. He's a fierce competitor and he's a
winner,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   When told of Toledo's comment, Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez
grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both play the same position, they both take the snap from
center and they both won 10 games,'' Alvarez said. ``I don't see
much else similar. (Toledo) was being nice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
