<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PREDATORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS PUSH UNBEATEN STREAK TO 12
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Two months ago, the Nashville Predators would have been
just the type of team to give the Stars all sorts of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A tight-checking bunch with just enough shooters to be
dangerous, the NHL's latest expansion team came into last night's
game with the momentum of recent upsets over the Detroit Red Wings
and Washington Capitals in their back pocket.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Predators played a suffocating style that caused
the Stars some grief, it wasn't enough to stop the NHL's hottest
team. The Stars survived a strategic battle to take a 1-0 victory
against the Predators and tie a franchise record for consecutive
games without a loss at 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just on a roll right now and we want to keep it on a
roll,'' defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``We're not trying to do
anything fancy, we're just trying to win each game.'
</P>
<P>
   In the process of doing that, the Stars are also rolling up a
long list of accolades. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Tying the franchise record unbeaten streak at 12 games (9-0-3).
The 1981-82 Minnesota North Stars also went 9-0-3 in one stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Setting the franchise record for wins in a month at 10. The old
record was set several times at nine. The Stars have two games
remaining in December.
</P>
<P>
   Clinching the Western Conference's best record by Dec. 29, the
cutoff date to name coaches for the All-Star Game. That means Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock will be head coach of an All-Star team for the
third consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   Giving goalie Ed Belfour his third shutout of the season and
43rd of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Fans at the game might find it hard to believe that so much was
riding on a game that was, in many ways, a sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could call it boring,'' Sydor said in an
apologetic manner.
</P>
<P>
   While both teams generated their share of scoring opportunities,
both teams also didn't mind playing safe, defensive hockey. The
Stars got off 21 shots on net and had another 22 that missed the
mark. Their league-best power play moved the puck around the ice
but finished 0-for-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we moved the puck well on the power play, I didn't
think we got many good chances,'' Hitchcock said. ``All of our
shots were from the perimeter; we didn't get to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Predators goalie Eric Fichaud had a strong night and the entire
Nashville lineup did a great job of playing without captain Tom
Fitzgerald (death in the family), leading goal-scorer Sergei
Krivokrasov (leg injury) and top goalie Mike Dunham (groin strain).
But the Predators finished with 14 shots on goal because they
couldn't penetrate a tired but determined Stars defense that once
again was led by Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deserve a lot of credit for this many games in that
\Rtime\S span and still being able to play a strong defensive
hockey game,'' Hitchcock said of the Stars playing six games in six
different cities in 11 days, including squeezing the Christmas
travel rush into the time span. ``It was a good effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars showed their fatigue early as they had 11 shots miss
the net in the first period. It was a ``telltale sign,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Stars didn't get frustrated, stayed with the
defensive game plan and finally broke through an opening at the
12:31 mark of the second period. Grant Marshall fished a puck out
of the defensive zone and pushed it ahead to defenseman Shawn
Chambers, who was working through the neutral zone. Chambers then
sent a pass to Guy Carbonneau on the right wing and headed to the
net. Carbonneau made a slick pass back to Chambers on the
give-and-go, and Chambers redirected a shot over Fichaud for the
only goal of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was Chambers' second goal of the season, matching his total
for all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them now I don't have to score any more for the rest of
the year,'' Chambers joked after the game.
</P>
<P>
   But while there was some humor in the win, Hitchcock said plays
like that have helped the team stay on their 12-game roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the difference in our team from the start of the
season to now is that even with our energy level down a quart, we
stayed with the program,'' Hitchcock said. ``A lot of little things
happened good for us tonight. Shawn Chambers scoring a goal, we
needed someone other than our key people scoring because they were
frustrated. Right now, we're acting and behaving like a good
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
