<HEADLINE>
CARDS REMEMBER END TO THEIR LAST GAME VS. COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When asked yesterday whether the controversial
ending to the last meeting between the Cowboys and Arizona
Cardinals would have any impact on Saturday's wild-card playoff
game, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey took the high road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will have an impact,'' Gailey said. ``I
kind of think that was at the beginning of November.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood in Arizona regarding the Cowboys' Nov. 15 victory and
the last play _ on which pass interference could have been called
against Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith as he broke up a pass to
Cardinals receiver Rob Moore _ is quite different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough loss, and I still think about it,'' Cardinals
guard Chris Dishman said after Sunday's playoff-clinching victory
against the San Diego Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Dishman hung up his gloves from the Cowboys game in his locker
and vowed not to take them down until the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a day that goes by in the locker room that I don't
see those gloves. They are there for a reason, to remind me of a
loss that was the toughest I've ever had.''
SANDERS' EXAMINATION
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders had a magnetic resonance
imaging examination on his sprained left big toe yesterday and flew
to Palm Beach, Fla., where he was to be examined by specialist Dr.
Bill Hamilton last night.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys spokesman Brett Daniels said results of the examination
will be released today.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Hamilton finds, it's unlikely that Sanders will
available for Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Sanders, who is listed as ``out'' on the Cowboys'
injury report, was doubtful for the game. Sanders was injured Nov.
15 against the Cardinals. He has missed the past six games.
OFFENSIVE HIGHLIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   There was little not to like about the Cowboys' offensive effort
against the Washington Redskins on Sunday. The line protected
quarterback Troy Aikman. The wide receivers made big plays on the
outside, including a tempo-setting 51-yard reception by Michael
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   And running back Emmitt Smith had the cutting, twisting 26-yard
touchdown run that fullback Daryl Johnston called one of Smith's
greatest.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also got production from third-string tailback
Sherman Williams, who has become Smith's primary backup because of
an injury to Chris Warren. Williams rushed for a career-high 90
yards on 23 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the difference between the Redskins game, which
featured two second-quarter touchdowns and 20 first-half points,
and the previous three when the Cowboys combined for just two
touchdowns, was execution in the passing game and the big plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys hit on four passes longer than 24 yards against the
Redskins after connecting on just three big plays in the previous
three games combined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
