<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY QUESTIONS ON THE NFL PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The outcome of the 1999 Super Bowl tournament hinges on the
performance of Joe Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the marquee names poised to help the NFL
postseason entrants survive the monthlong battle of attrition that
begins this weekend with the wild-card games, the name of Joe
Abdullah hangs above them all.
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 teams. There are 11 games. There is one trophy.
And, on the eve of the playoffs, there are 10 questions, beginning
with:
</P>
<P>
   1) Who is Joe Abdullah?
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the Denver Broncos employed a practice-squad running
back named Joe Abdullah. In Week 1 of this season, Broncos rushing
sensation Terrell Davis _ with 2,008 yards the likely league MVP
and the singular key to who does what in these NFL playoffs _ was
dressing in the Mile High Stadium locker room when his name tag
fell from above his stall, revealing an old name tag underneath it.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since then, I always put it up there, `Joe Abdullah'
instead of `Terrell Davis,' '' Davis' teammate Howard Griffith
said. ``It's something we always tease him about.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos opponents wish they were planning to stop Joe Abdullah.
If they can't stop Davis, hang another Super Bowl MVP above his
stall.
</P>
<P>
   2) Are the Cowboys elite? Or elitists?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to ruin it for me,'' coach Chan Gailey said
after the Cowboys clinched a playoff berth. ``No matter how hard
you try.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was talking to the cynical news media _ but maybe he
should've pointed his acidic comments at his veterans, who
sometimes act as if their pedigree puts them above having to scrap
through a first-round playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally, you've got one foot in the grave, granted _ but
it's up to you whether you try to remove that foot or simply give
in and jump into the hole. If everybody gets into the trenches, the
Cowboys have a negotiable path to the NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   3) Who's healthy enough to play quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Steve Young has a dinged-up knee. New England's
Drew Bledsoe has a broken finger on his throwing hand.
Jacksonville's Mark Brunell has a severely sprained ankle.
Minnesota's Randall Cunningham has a broken (nonthrowing) hand.
Conventional wisdom says that if they're limping, so will their
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not true here,'' Vikings coach Denny Green said. ``With
Randall and Brad \RJohnson, the starter before an injury opened the
job and MVP candidacy to Cunningham\S, we've got strength I don't
think anybody else has.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, only Minnesota and Denver (where Bubby Brister has been
stellar in occasional relief of John Elway) figure to survive in
the long term if the injury bug bites under center.
</P>
<P>
   4) Are the Atlanta Falcons for real?
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson is. Receivers Terance Mathis and
Tony Martin are. But where Atlanta boasts an unheralded edge on
most opponents is on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Archambeau? Travis Hall? Shane Dronett? Chuck Smith?
</P>
<P>
   You don't know them. Watch the playoffs. You will.
</P>
<P>
   5) Isn't playoff experience a major determining factor?
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says it's so, and it might be true for
coaches in charge of wet-behind-the-ears programs such as Dan
Reeves in Atlanta. But in truth, it's tough to envision youngsters
like Jake Plummer of the Cardinals, Randy Moss of the Vikings and
Fred Taylor of the Jaguars suddenly running scared.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you're lining up against old-timers Cunningham (one
playoff win, lifetime), the Jets' Vinny Testaverde or Atlanta's
Chris Chandler (neither of whom have started a postseason game),
you can always hope for flashbacks to the days when they were
unsuccessful quarterbacks playing for unsuccessful teams.
</P>
<P>
   6) Are the Dynasty-That-Never-Was Packers finally out of gas?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Holmgren played with fire when he let his probable
lame-duck status be known to his world. It's tough to commit to him
when he's not committed to you, right?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, Green Bay has a defense that ranks with
any in the NFC, has improving health from offensive weapons in wide
receiver Antonio Freeman and running back Dorsey Levens, has a
psychological edge on first-round foe San Francisco and has Brett
Favre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't count us out,'' says Favre, who totaled a league-best
4,212 passing yards in a ``subpar'' season. ``We needed to get to
the playoffs. Now we've got a fresh start.''
</P>
<P>
   True. But now, while Favre is the QB you might pay $50 to watch,
he's not the QB to bet $50 on.
</P>
<P>
   7) Who has the best chance to pull a first-round upset? Arizona
at Dallas is the popular pick, an interesting study because the
teams are so divergent in playoff experience. But depending on the
health of the quarterbacks, the No. 6 seed in the AFC, New England,
could make it tough on No. 3 seed Jacksonville. The Patriots with
Bledsoe have a chance; the Jaguars without Brunell do not _ and
even with Brunell, they might be reeling from giving up 50 points
in a Week 15 loss to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   8) Will Bill Parcells' pettiness be adversity or an advantage
for the Jets?
</P>
<P>
   Parcells built the moribund Giants into a champion in 1986,
rebuilt them into a champion in 1991, then built the moribund
Patriots into a Super Bowl appearance two years ago, and has built
the moribund Jets into a Super Bowl contender.
</P>
<P>
   He does it his way, and insists it's the right way. But with a
stingy defense, a serviceable running game and a quarterback who
makes enough plays to win, who can argue with Parcells?
</P>
<P>
   9) Besides New York, winners of a first-round bye, what's the
difference separating the other AFC East teams clogging the
postseason?
</P>
<P>
   Depends who you ask. In Miami, Jimmy Johnson's alleged magic
represents the difference. In Buffalo, Doug Flutie's alleged magic
represents the difference. In New England, when the Patriots are
healthy, there is a reliance on actual talent.
</P>
<P>
   10) How is a Denver-Minnesota Super Bowl not inevitable?
</P>
<P>
   Let's let 'em play, OK? Who died and made you The Amazing
Kreskin?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
