<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEFENSIVE COORDINATOR TURNS UP HEAT ON DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When the going gets tough, the tough _ in this
case Texas defensive coordinator Carl Reese _ turn on the oven.
</P>
<P>
   No, not to stick his head into it. The former Missouri fullback,
who specializes in coaching linebackers, bakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pies, cakes, cookies,'' Reese said. ``It's a nervous habit.
But it helps me relax when I get home late and can't sleep. And it
fattens me up a little bit, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the pie's in the oven, Reese sometimes drifts into the
garage, picks up a wrench and works on the four-wheel-drive 1970
Toyota Land Cruiser he is restoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``A '55 Chevy might be the next thing I look for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the task Reese faced this season in restoring
efficiency and confidence to the Longhorns' wounded defense, and
after many nights when it must have been hard to sleep, the wonder
is he doesn't outweigh Octavious Bishop _ Texas' 330-pound
offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This defense has come about as far as any I've ever seen,''
Texas coach Mack Brown said. ``The job Carl and the defensive staff
has done getting these guys not to break and be so discouraged
because of the pressure they were under the year before, and
getting them to play so well and so hard, has been the difference
in our year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese characteristically shuns such credit. But he can go Brown
one better in measuring from there to here as the Longhorns brush
up on the defensive scheme they'll throw at Mississippi State on
Friday in the Southwestern Bell Cotton Bowl Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started last spring we were as bad as any group I've
ever started with,'' Reese said. ``And we've made more gains than
any group I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Formidable, however, is not a word one would use to describe the
Longhorns' defense. But the defense earned the respect of teams
such as Nebraska and Big 12 champion Texas A&AMP;M. And Mississippi
State running back James Johnson, who led the Southeastern
Conference in rushing, said he views the UT defenders with a wary
eye, even though Texas gave up an average of 30 points and 365
yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it's going to be like facing another
SEC defense,'' Johnson said. ``And there ain't no bad defenses in
that league.''
</P>
<P>
   Point made.
</P>
<P>
   Reese has had similar success at places such as Vanderbilt and
Louisiana State. But his job at Texas was complicated because he
inherited players low on self-esteem after shouldering much of the
blame for a 4-7 record in 1997. And that feeling, once conquered to
a degree, rose again after a 1-2 start and consecutive lopsided
losses to UCLA (49-31) and Kansas State (48-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a little like children who had been abused,'' Reese
said. ``It took a long time to get them out of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior member of Brown's staff did it with the right amounts
of teaching, scheming, challenging, pats on the butt and trust,
players said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a great guy,'' defensive end Aaron Humphrey said.
``Everyone has opened their arms to him. You sit back and listen
and do what he tells you, and you have the chance to make a lot of
plays. And I've never been around a coach who reads an offense like
he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Dusty Renfro said he'll cherish the experience of
finishing a distinguished career working with Reese.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's great,'' Renfro said. ``I give him most of the credit for
what we've accomplished. He's kind of a laid-back country boy who
is more of a teacher than anything else. I hardly ever hear him
yell or scream. He's worked so well with us that we all respect him
and trust completely in what we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the story of this season has been our constant
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Renfro did, however, have one critical thing to say about Reese:
``He's talked about it, but he's never brought us any of his
cookies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
