<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-OFFENSIVE-LINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU OFFENSIVE LINE ADDED BASIL TO DIET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ When TCU's season appeared to be finished way
back in November, tailback Basil Mitchell went to look at film for
a final time.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to remember individual yards that had led him to his
1,000-yard season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm looking at myself,'' Mitchell admitted with a
sly grin. ``In the background, though, I can see these guys jumping
up and down. It was the linemen. It was as if they were just as
excited as I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Horned Frogs tackle Russ Sanders promises that to be true.
</P>
<P>
   He admits to bragging to friends and family that TCU's 239.1
yards-per-game rushing average ranked eighth nationally. He admits
to bragging on Mitchell's feat so often that a few friends think he
gained a few yards himself.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Sanders and his fellow Frogs hogs did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brag about him,'' Frogs guard Greg Davis said. ``He had 166
attempts and 1,111 yards. That's probably 100 less attempts than
most 1,000-yard rushers. I'd like to think we had a hand in that.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione simply nodded. He realizes that
TCU's rushing prowess this season began with Sanders and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione had said coming in that he needed a big season from
his line. He needed a salty rushing game to build his team around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took establishing a good, strong running game as a personal
challenge,'' Frogs center Jeff Garner said.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges were plentiful early on.
</P>
<P>
   TCU struggled during spring practice, trying to blend a pair of
seniors in Davis and Sanders with a trio of underclassmen in
Garner, Michael Keathley and Jeff Millican.
</P>
<P>
   Size and strength were also problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial thought was, `Oh, I hope these guys are
overachievers,' '' Frogs offensive line coach Jim Bob Helduser
said, ``which they have proven to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Helduser asked them to get bigger and stronger and faster this
season, and Sanders and Co. willingly responded.
</P>
<P>
   Some tasks, like getting bigger, have been tackled with
unparalleled zeal; training has continued deep into Sun Bowl week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with appetizers,'' Davis said, describing Sunday's
training regimen. ``Chips and salsa and, of course, queso.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then bring on a thick, juicy steak, a baked potato loaded with
butter and sour cream,'' Garner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dessert,'' Davis said, ``well, that's got to be ice cream, fat
Blue Bell ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders had started laughing by then, adding: ``Of course, we do
this for Basil.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell smiled. It was like that day watching film all over
again. It's a good feeling, too, knowing that come Thursday he has
the five big guys on his side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
