r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-STEWART-TEXAS-A&AMP;M     12-29 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STEWART-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADJUSTING NOTHING NEW TO TEXAS A&AMP;M'S STEWART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Mentally, the transition to life after football
was in full swing for Branndon Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a week, the Stephenville native would be in
Virginia for his third interview with an industrial distribution
firm. The prospect of his first real-world job offer excited him.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the fifth-year senior owed his Texas A&AMP;M teammates
another afternoon of clipboard holding as the backup quarterback to
Randy McCown. As the Big 12 title game approached, Stewart shared
his deepest regret with punter Shane Lechler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm ever going to play again,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   That was before the start of a Wednesday practice. By the time
the workout ended, McCown was headed for X-rays that would reveal a
broken collarbone and Stewart was headed back to the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Within 72 hours, the normally reserved Stewart would be
shouting, ``That's for you, Lee Corso,'' into television minicams
after leading the Aggies to a stunning, 36-33 upset of Kansas State
to win the Big 12 title. Corso, ESPN's college football analyst,
predicted a three-touchdown victory by the Wildcats, who entered
the game as the top-ranked team nationally in the coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made that prediction laughable by throwing for 235 yards
and three touchdowns during the fourth quarter and overtime. The
performance also made him rethink plans about his football future,
although Stewart concedes he is ``geared for'' the idea that
Friday's Sugar Bowl against Ohio State will be his last appearance
in shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M (11-2), ranked No. 8 in The Associated Press poll, meets No.
3 Ohio State (10-1) at 7:30 p.m. in the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to think about playing your last game, but that's
what I'm geared for right now,'' said Stewart, whose turbulent
college career has been marked by two benchings during three
seasons in which he has compiled a 20-10 record as A&AMP;M's starting
quarterback. ``Throughout my career, I got some unjustified
criticism. But I've enjoyed playing here. I know people may not
think so because every game hasn't been great. It's been fun to me,
though, regardless of the comments and critiques. All of that stuff
goes away, eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stewart, the key has been learning to balance his own hopes
and dreams against outsiders' expectations. After leading
Stephenville to the 1993 Class 4A state championship, many
recruiters _ as well as Stephenville coach Art Briles _ predicted
Stewart was on a collision course with the Heisman Trophy, if not
an early exit to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has been a reliable college quarterback but never an
all-conference performer. These days, when Stewart talks about
playing in the NFL, it is in terms of a backup role. If he heads
off to the work-a-day world rather than some NFL camp after
completing his management degree in May, Stewart said he will have
no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   Football, he explained, has fallen in line behind other
interests on his personal pecking order during his tenure at A&AMP;M.
Among them: religion, academics and relationships with friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I learned how to put football in its proper perspective
with everything else, it was easy to put a bad game or a bad
practice behind me,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been plenty of both for a quarterback who ranks
fourth on A&AMP;M's career passing list, with 4,325 yards, yet never
threw for more than 10 touchdowns in any season. There have been
plenty of mountaintop moments as well, although none can top
Stewart's 324-yard effort in leading A&AMP;M to victory from a 27-12
fourth-quarter deficit against Kansas State. That one, after all,
triggered 47 congratulatory messages on Stewart's telephone
answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens against Ohio State, Stewart figures
the Kansas State comeback will be his A&AMP;M legacy. A&AMP;M coach R.C.
Slocum said he will remember something else. He has seen a young
quarterback mature into manhood and watched some of that maturity
rub off on fellow players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always empathized with Branndon because he lived in a
fish bowl and he was never the one who built himself up ... to be
this big-time, first-round draft choice with a pro-style arm,''
Slocum said. ``The reality is that most people who play college
football aren't great players. There are few legitimate stars.''
</P>
<P>
   How soon Stewart's real-world life will begin is open to
conjecture. The interview in Virginia, which took place two days
after Stewart's heroics in the Big 12 title game, led to a job
offer. But the strong showing on the football field has Stewart
wondering about how soon he wants to hang up his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could handle a backup role in the NFL,'' Stewart
said. ``But I don't talk about the pros. I don't even ask my
coaches about the pros. It's something I would love to do if I get
a chance, but I don't focus on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Stewart is focusing on making the most of his final
college game Friday night against Ohio State. After that, anything
is possible. Even a mental transition back to the role of full-time
football player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 0111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
