<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9688 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORRIN-HATCH-SPI &LR;      12-29 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORRIN-HATCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCH SAYS NOT ENOUGH SENATE VOTES TO CONVICT CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A powerful Republican Senate committee chairman said
here Monday night that there are not enough votes in the Senate to
convict President Clinton of impeachment charges and that censure
of the president is ``the only option left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think censure is not going to be a powerful tool
against him, you are wrong,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, told a
large audience of anti-Clinton conservatives at a Sea-Tac hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, said that any
penalty beyond censure, such as denying Clinton a pension or
imposing a fine, would violate the president's rights under the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, he said, the president could pay off any fine just
by holding two fundraisers at the Malibu estate of singer and
Clinton supporter Barbra Streisand.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton agrees to some form of censure, and his lawyers do
not challenge the legality of the impeachment action by the
outgoing Congress, ``My feeling is this could be over in a matter
of days,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch was in the Puget Sound area to visit his daughter, and
appeared Monday night as a guest of Wade Cook Seminars. Hatch
lectured on national policy after Cook spoke on money-making
techniques and gave out copies of his new book, ``Y2K Gold Rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch heaped scorn on Clinton, virtually pronouncing the
president's guilt on the impeachment allegation that he lied before
the federal grand jury convened by Whitewater independent counsel
Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was deliberate lying before a federal grand jury,'' Hatch
declared. ``If you were to do that, you go to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't he?'' demanded voices in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he is opposed to jailing presidents and believes that
Clinton deserves to be treated with respect because of the office
that he holds.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah senator did serve up plenty of partisan meat to an
appreciative audience. He described Vice President Al Gore as ``a
committed left-winger. ... He is committed to the far left.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he opposes calling any witnesses at a Senate trial of
the president, outside from House Judiciary Committee members who
are managing the impeachment case. He specifically opposed Senate
appearances by the academics who argued the president's case before
the House Judiciary Committee, ``these historians,'' as Hatch
called them, ``most of who are far-left liberals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch is a Senate grandee, a 22-year veteran of Congress' upper
chamber who delights in telling about his audiences with China's
President Jiang Zemin and the savvy advice he has given past
presidents that, to their detriment, they refused to take.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a Mormon bishop who has personally counseled
colleagues, kept their private confidences, and as a musician has
even composed a song to his Judiciary Committee colleague and
political opposite Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   This side of Hatch has been on display through much of 1998. He
privately urged Clinton's attorneys to settle the Paula Jones
lawsuit, which eventually gave Starr the vehicle to move on
impeachment. He went on Sunday talk shows to advise Clinton on how
to get out of the burgeoning Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't listen to me,'' Hatch said. He even argued the
case personally to Clinton during a half-hour phone call before one
Sunday talk-show appearance. After Clinton went before Starr's
federal grand jury, and later delivered a brief defensive speech to
the nation, Hatch was quoted as saying, ``What a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a jerk to blame Ken Starr for what he had done and put
the nation through,'' Hatch reiterated Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked by an audience member whether the title ``the
unhonorable'' should be attached to William Jefferson Clinton,
Hatch shot back: ``No. No. You should still have respect for that
office regardless of who holds it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the counselor in Orrin Hatch appear to have given up on
America's 42nd president any more than Richard Nixon, the 37th
president who was disgraced and resigned his office more than 24
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the blessings of my life was to have private one-on-one
meetings with Richard Nixon after he left office,'' Hatch said.
``He has worked hard to rehabilitate himself. He was one of
America's great statesmen when he died.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe William Jefferson Clinton can still do the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
