<HEADER>
A9713 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN     12-29 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER SAD TO SEE COLLEGE CAREER NEARING END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ The season ends in two days, and USC wide receiver
Billy Miller is feeling a bit melancholy as his career winds down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming to an end quick,'' Miller said. ``I realize I'm
not going to do this anymore, hanging out at the hotel with my
friends. It's very sad. It's another opportunity to make another
step in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Miller has rarely been thought of as the Trojans' go-to
receiver, and has often been overshadowed by R. Jay Soward, he is
currently fifth all-time on USC's career-pass catching list, and
will move into fourth place with two receptions in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny to me. People don't know. Even if you told them,
they wouldn't believe you,'' Miller said. ``If you asked someone in
Alabama who Billy Miller was, they wouldn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   It also surprises Miller how far he has come, considering that
he nearly quit playing football his sophomore season after becoming
upset with the coaches and wondering about his role on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, I wouldn't have even gone out at night if we
went to a bowl,'' Miller said. ``I would have felt like everybody
looked at me like I was a disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's thoughts are beginning to turn to the NFL, and he knows
his speed will be the biggest concern among teams that watch him at
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to shock a lot of people with how fast I
am,'' Miller said. ``A lot of people doubt my speed. I think I can
get down to a 4.4.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chamber of Commerce: USC offensive lineman Travis Claridge
never minces words, and had this opinion of spending the week here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the armpit of El Paso and they don't use deodorant,''
Claridge said.
</P>
<P>
   But just to make sure he didn't offend anyone, Claridge added,
``The people are really nice and considerate.''
</P>
<P>
   The thin red line: USC's defensive line is a little short on
depth, as sophomore Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed missed Monday's
practice with a sore shoulder. Aaron Williams is still less than
100 percent with an ankle sprain, meaning the tackle position could
consist primarily of Ennis Davis, Marc Matock and freshman Ryan
Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensive tackle is scary,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``Ryan Nielsen will have to play a big role.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson looks better: Hackett was encouraged by linebacker David
Gibson's recovery from a sprained ankle, and thought Gibson might
be able to start. If not, senior Marc Cusano will start.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Chad Morton (sore ankle) practiced sparingly but is
supposed to be OK for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bowl man: TCU has not played in a bowl since 1994, but wide
receiver Mike Scarborough is playing in his third bowl game.
Scarborough transferred from Texas, where he played in the 1997
Fiesta Bowl and 1995 Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Flip of the coin: USC clearly has an inferior practice site to
TCU, but it's partly the Trojans' choice. The teams held a coin
flip earlier in the month to decide who would have first pick for
hotels or practice facilities.
</P>
<P>
   USC went for the hotel site first, which meant TCU got to
practice at the nicer Socorro Athletic Complex, which has a
well-maintained grass field. USC practiced at a local high school
Sunday and Monday, on a field with virtually no green grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not dirt, it's dormant grass,'' Hackett joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
