<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FRANCHIONE-TCU-LA     12-29 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FRANCHIONE-TCU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCHIONE REINVENTS TCU TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ Dennis Franchione has become known as a quick-change
artist, but there's nothing deceptive about his act.
</P>
<P>
   It just seems like he's using tricks, because Franchione has
resurrected some of college football's sorriest schools in recent
years, and become a model for anyone hoping to turn around their
struggling programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess maybe that's what I've become known for,'' Franchione
said. ``I hope my reputation carries some other things too, but you
get known for something somewhere down the line. Hopefully, this is
my last turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Christian University certainly does. Franchione was hired
last December and brought back self-esteem to a school that won two
national titles in the 1930s but hasn't done much in the past 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs were 1-10 last season, and coach Pat Sullivan
was fired.
</P>
<P>
   With a no-nonsense style that combined discipline and loyalty,
Franchione has surprised even himself by leading TCU to a 6-5
record and a berth in the Sun Bowl against USC on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been much quicker than I expected,'' he said. ``I don't
think you can go into a season inheriting a 1-10 team and think
you'll go to a bowl game the first year. I don't know if you can
know what to expect for sure. I felt like there was talent there,
just some other ingredients were missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like faith. And trust. And positive reinforcement. Those were
the pillars Franchione used to build up the Horned Frogs, and his
players have completely bought into his philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of charisma and is a real genuine person,'' said
linebacker Joseph Phipps, an All-WAC first-team selection. ``When
you believe in someone, you're willing to do more for that
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The players feel anything is possible since Franchione arrived
and instilled self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes you feel like you can win, no matter who you're
playing against,'' added wide receiver Michael Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent from the season's first game. TCU traveled to
Iowa State and trailed 21-14 entering the fourth quarter. This
would normally be the time for the Horned Frogs to collapse and
take another typical loss.
</P>
<P>
   But they outscored Iowa State 21-0 in the final period and won
31-21. That might not sound like a big deal for a USC fan, but it
was TCU's first road victory in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a turning point,'' Franchione said. ``They didn't do
that last year. Every time something bad happened, the players
responded against Iowa State. In previous years, they would have
faltered.''
</P>
<P>
   The jewel of the season occurred two weeks later, when the
Horned Frogs upset Air Force 35-34, handing the Falcons their only
loss of the season and perhaps costing them a spot in a BCS bowl
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most memorable memories I've ever had was to be in
the locker room after the Air Force game,'' Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make Franchione a darling with the TCU fans. The
last TCU coach to post a winning record in his first season was
Dutch Meyer in 1934. The Horned Frogs' defense is allowing 19.6
points per game, the fewest points in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione has also become a master at learning how to handle a
'90's football player. ``Players today always want to know why. I
give them a lot of ownership in the decision-making process,''
Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Franchione appointed a leadership council
composed of players from each position on the team. They discuss a
variety of issues and report back to the coach with their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just figured out what style of bowl rings we wanted this
week,'' quarterback Patrick Batteaux said. ``We'll come together
collectively and decide things. He lets us have input.''
</P>
<P>
   Transforming a football program is hardly new for Franchione.
</P>
<P>
   At New Mexico, Franchione won 33 games in six years after the
team won a total of of nine games in the nine previous seasons
before he arrived. He took the Lobos to a bowl game, something they
hadn't done in 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask former UCLA defensive coordinator Rocky Long how tough
the New Mexico job could be. The Lobos were 3-9 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Before New Mexico, Franchione compiled two winning seasons at
Southwest Texas State, which had five straight losing seasons
before his arrival. At Pittsburg State in Kansas, he had a 53-6
record including a 45-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a struggling school is in need of a quick fix,
Franchione's name surfaces. He was mentioned for the Oklahoma job
way back in September, but said he wasn't interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep saying I'm not going to do it anymore. It's consuming,
but it's gratifying,'' Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he likes what he thinks he can build at TCU. There are
1.7 million people in Tarrant County, where TCU is situated in the
city of Fort Worth. That's about the population of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   There was no doubt in his mind that taking the TCU job was a
step up, not to mention the doubling of his salary to about
$400,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you survey Division I coaches, a lot of people said TCU was
a sleeping giant,'' Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean this could this be his final stop, after so many
makeovers?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd ask my wife, I'd say this is home,'' Franchione said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
