<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LOCKOUT RHETORIC HEATS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA could cancel the season in nine days, but
instead of that threat forcing the sides into compromise, it has
spawned a new round of insults and accusations that seem to
inevitably point toward a destructive ending to the 181-day
standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern nearly assured as much Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that in all likelihood, the season will be canceled on
Jan. 7,'' Stern said in a conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In his angriest sermon yet, Stern blasted union leadership and
insisted the league will make no further concessions. The league
made its final offer to the players union on Sunday, and Stern said
if the union rejects it, the season is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Union director Billy Hunter rejected the offer Sunday and
reiterated his position strongly Monday, setting the stage for a
tense final stretch in the six-month-old labor war.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter maintained, as he has all along, that owners would
not cancel the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got 29 franchises that in the aggregate are worth about
$5-$6 billion,'' Hunter said. ``Are you going to jeopardize your $6
billion investment, particularly when we're so close at the table,
over a few million dollars?''
</P>
<P>
   He chalked up Stern's threats to ``psychological games.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Hunter's comments, Stern responded incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he (Hunter) didn't believe that the National Labor
Relations Board would dismiss the unfair labor practice suit (by
the union), and he didn't believe that (arbitrator John) Feerick
would (rule) against him, and he didn't believe that the owners
would lock out, and he didn't believe that we would lose
regular-season games, and he didn't believe that we would miss
Christmas Day, and he didn't believe we would cancel the All-Star
Game,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, sarcastically, ``So his analysis of this is right
on target. ... And on Jan. 8, he'll turn to his players and say,
`Guess what, I was wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   The league's presumed final offer includes a guarantee players
will receive 53 to 54 percent of the league's $2 billion in
revenues. The union said it will not accept anything less than 56
to 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And while the union has agreed to numerous restrictions on
high-end salaries, Hunter said those concessions are dependent upon
more salary-cap exceptions for middle-class salaried players.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy commissioner Russ Granik, reflecting the league's new,
decidedly less diplomatic tone, responded, ``I think one of the
great lies from the other side ... is that this has anything to do
with the middle class. I think it's clear that what's going on is
about the high-end players.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter contended that if talks reconvened with full negotiating
committees, the gap could be bridged quickly. ``My players want to
participate in the process. I would think it's important enough
that they (owners) would want to participate also.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said he would not bring in the owners' negotiating
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate any more negotiations,'' Granik said. ``We
have given the fairest and most generous offer that we can and
still (be able to) operate the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the league has made its final offer, Hunter said he
will not send the proposal to the full union membership for a vote.
The union's 19-player negotiating committee, he said, is authorized
to accept or reject any proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hunter confidently asserted that ``80 to 85
percent'' of the 430 players support the union's position and would
reject the owners' offer.
</P>
<P>
   NBA officials believe otherwise and Stern plans to send his
offer directly to the players, repeating a strategy he used two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of players want the opportunity to vote on that
proposal, said Steve Woods, agent for the Toronto Raptors' Kevin
Willis and a vocal critic of Hunter. Woods and a half-dozen other
agents have been polling players and Woods said about 90 percent
would approve the NBA's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's reluctance to put this to a group vote really
illustrates the weakness of his overall position,'' Woods said.
``If he truly believes that 85 percent of the players support the
union's position on this, then it would only be to his advantage to
institute a blind vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
