</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN RELIES ON YOUTH, ENTHUSIASM OF BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You walk into UCLA's locker room at Pauley
Pavilion, see the bodies rolling around on the floor and assume
it's egos colliding. Isn't that the inevitable result, after all,
when so many exalted underclassmen are asked to share one ball?
</P>
<P>
   Then you hear the muffled giggles rising from the carpet and you
realize the kids are all right. Indeed, sophomores Travis Reed and
Baron Davis were just being playful (think Winnie the Pooh and
Tigger) after a lethargic win last week over American University. A
more energetic effort on the court tonight against Loyola Marymount
would be a welcomed sight, what with the Bruins' Pacific-10 opener
against Arizona a mere four days away.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, half the fun of following this season's squad will be
seeing which of its multiple personalities surface on any given
night. Imagine Sybil in knee-length shorts and you've got a clear
vision of a team whose first eight players average 19.3 years of
age. The UCLA team is so young, third-year coach Steve Lavin
recycles cliches that are older.
</P>
<P>
   A Lavinism that figures to get plenty of mileage this season is
``age is just a number.'' The youthfulness of the 1996-97 Arizona
team hardly was its downfall; those Wildcats won the national
championship with a top-eight that averaged 19.5 years.
</P>
<P>
   That Arizona squad didn't have a senior or a selfish player
among its regular contributors. Neither, at first glance, does this
band of Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Lavin wasn't worried at first. After landing the top
recruiting class in the country, Lavin had no idea how all the egos
would mesh. He wondered, would such an infusion of untested talent
erode team chemistry or enhance it?
</P>
<P>
   Much to Lavin's delight, the team has been, in his words, ``like
a pack of wolves or a flock of ducks in the pond.''
</P>
<P>
   They're like brothers, only without the baggage. The 10th-ranked
Bruins are a surrogate family out of necessity, so many of the
players having left behind all that is familiar for this shared
experience. The team boasts only three players from Los Angeles
(Davis, Billy Knight and Ryan Bailey). Everybody else is at least
an hour's drive or flight away from their comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of them are away from home,'' Lavin said, ``so it's a
commonality that they all share.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that sophomore Todd Ramasar took freshmen Dan
Gadzuric, who hails from Den Haag, Holland, and Jerome Moiso
(Guadeloupe, West Indies) home with him to Corona for Thanksgiving
and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that sophomore Earl Watson counsels freshman JaRon Rush
of Kansas City, Mo., on homesickness and Davis dispenses hugs in
the locker room as though they were towels and everyone really
looks forward to each day's practice, no matter how many line
sprints they end up doing.
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry on the court is hard to coach but easy to observe.
It's Davis being so focused on getting his teammates involved in
the offense that he sometimes forgets to take his own shots. It's
Moiso offering to bench himself to give Gadzuric more looks at the
basket. It's the perimeter players having no compunction at
throwing it inside and the players in the paint having no qualms at
kicking it back out.
</P>
<P>
   It's being 7-2 and feeling as though the best is yet to come
because everybody is really eager to share the ball, the credit and
a meal and movie afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's different than what we've had in the past,'' said
Lavin, who was a Bruins assistant coach for five years before
assuming the lead position in 1996 after Jim Harrick's abrupt
firing. ``There were other teams where the core players were really
close, but this is the closest-knit team we've had in terms of the
first man through the 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times this year I've gotten chills up my spine
because the things I've seen have transcended anything you can
articulate in words.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 14 players on this year's roster are 19 or 20. Three
of the freshmen (Ray Young, Gadzuric and Moiso) are in the upper
tier, age-wise, which has helped blur the distinction between
classes. That wasn't the case last year when the three seniors
(J.R. Henderson, Kris Johnson and Toby Bailey) who anchored the
team sort of drifted apart from their younger teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had that age difference,'' Watson said, speaking
of the gulf that divides someone old enough to vote from someone
old enough to drink. ``This year we're all on the same level.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the 1998-99 Bruins can scale the same heights as
the 1997-98 UCLA Sweet-Sixteen team remains to be seen. But say
this for them: they sure look like they're having a lot more fun
trying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
