<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-COYOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS TRAP COYOTES ON THE ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For nearly three months, little has gone right for the
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, almost everything did.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings got two goals from Luc Robitaille and two goals from
Jozef Stumpel, one of them _ gasp _ on the power play. The Kings
also got a strong performance in goal from Jamie Storr on his 23rd
birthday. And they got the appropriate emotional response when Doug
Bodger was viciously hit from behind by Coyotes winger Dallas Drake
in the waning minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to a 4-2 victory over the Kings' nemesis, the
Phoenix Coyotes, before a sellout crowd of 16,210 at the America
West Arena. The Coyotes (20-7-4, 10-2-1 at home) not only lost the
game, they lost star winger Keith Tkachuk to bruised ribs and star
center Jeremy Roenick to a possible concussion.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kings (11-21-3), it was their third win in their last
four games and their third consecutive victory on the road. Only
Bodger's sore right arm and a possible mild concussion to
defenseman Mattias Norstrom marred the Kings' night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big two points,'' said Robitaille, whose goals drew him
to within four of 500 for his career. ``We're starting to build a
lot of confidence as a team. This is the kind of game we want to
play every night, physical, in-your-face. We want to play like they
play. If we can do that, we can go a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr kept the Kings in the game by holding the Coyotes
scoreless in a first period in which Phoenix had a 13-4 advantage
in shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Stumpel - who entered the game with five
goals in his previous 46 regular-season and playoff games - gave
the Kings the lead off a pass from Pavel Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-King Rick Tocchet and Daniel Briere responded with goals to
give the Coyotes the lead, but with 38 seconds to play in the
second period (39 seconds after Briere's goal), Robitaille poked in
a pass from Donald Audette, tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille then gave the Kings the lead 12:09 into the third
period, scoring after Jyrki Lumme lost his balance - and the puck -
deep in the Coyotes' zone. Stumpel cushioned the lead 2:33 later,
on the Kings' first power play of the night, when he scored on a
breakaway set up by Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Drake's hit, possibly in retaliation for Bodger's hit
earlier in the third period on Roenick, a play on which Roenick's
head slammed against the glass.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:25 to play, Bodger was chasing the puck deep into the
Kings' zone, with Drake in pursuit. Bodger looked once over his
shoulder, then again. As he reached the boards, he was driven into
them from behind by Drake. Bodger said later he was woozy at first,
and his right elbow was wrapped in ice after the game. Drake's hit
will be reviewed by NHL vice president Colin Campbell, who may
respond with a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's not a suspension,'' Bodger said, ``there's something
wrong with this league. Getting hit from behind, there's a chance
you could break your neck.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bodger writhed on the ice, Ray Ferraro, then Robitaille, then
Sean O'Donnell jumped on Drake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Dallas Drake a long time,'' Ferraro said. ``Dallas
is a hard hitter and sometimes his hits border on the dirty side.
But that's the way he plays. The thing that was bad about the hit
was he didn't even make an attempt to slow down. His intent was to
hurt (Bodger), no question. That's why that hit has to be dealt
with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes had complaints of their own about the play, with
Coach Jim Schoenfeld claiming that O'Donnell had step out of bounds
in his retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call was made with the major and misconduct, and that's
fine, that's hockey,'' said Schoenfeld, adding that he didn't think
Drake's hit warranted a suspension. ``The eye-gouging from behind
(by O'Donnell) ... let's face up the two guys straight on.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell denied Schoenfeld's allegation, and Drake did not
speak with reporters after the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
