<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-DUKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WOMEN FALL TO DUKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Was it another stumble on the way to the Pac-10,
or was it another sign of things to come?
</P>
<P>
   The pattern has been established: The ninth-ranked UCLA's
women's basketball team relies on Maylana Martin and Janae Hubbard
inside and Erica Gomez and Marie Philman outside.
</P>
<P>
   When they click, watch out. When they're off, well ... it's
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the quartet was more off than on, and that
helped spell defeat, 85-80 to No. 17 Duke in front of 3,629 at
Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The loss follows a 100-77 defeat to No. 2 Tennessee a week ago.
It is the second time the Bruins (7-4) have lost two straight to
nationally-ranked teams. UCLA started the year with losses at Notre
Dame and at home to Connecticut before running off seven
consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe these two losses will mean another seven-game win streak,
which would mean a 6-0 start in the conference (UCLA closes its
nonconference schedule Wednesday at home against Pepperdine). No
one would complain if it were to happen, but the Bruins realize
that is getting a little too far ahead, especially when there are
things to be concerned about now.
</P>
<P>
   Like what to do when Martin, Hubbard, Gomez and Philman are off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marie Philman was something like 1 for 10 from the field,''
Gomez said. ``Philman's usually an offensive machine (12-point
average). To have two people off, that really hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just two, however. Martin, who has had a degenerative
disk in her back since last season, played Monday with a sinus
infection. She scored 14 points but had just three rebounds, well
below her 11.5 average.
</P>
<P>
   Philman did shoot 1 for 10 from the field but made all six of
her free throws. Hubbard has had the flu, so she was a step off,
finishing with 14 points and 9 rebounds but committing a critical
turnover in the last two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez had just four assists despite playing the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA went on a 29-6 run in the first half, only to give up runs
of 11-2 in the first half and 16-4 in the second half to bring Duke
back.
</P>
<P>
   The story was the same on defense. Duke (9-4) likes to go inside
to 6-foot-6 Michele Van Gorp, but the Bruins, helped by her
first-half foul trouble, limited her to 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   All that did was open the door to the outside game. Led by
Georgia Schweitzer's 22 points _ including 18 in the second half
and 10 straight at one point _ the Blue Devils shot 53 percent from
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-three percent, that's pretty good against UCLA,'' Duke
coach Gail Goestenkors said. ``We took what they gave us, and the
outside shot was there, especially in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there enough depth for the Bruins to compete in the Pac-10?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes and no,'' Gomez said. ``We need other people.''
</P>
<P>
   There was LaCresha Flannigan leading the Bruins with 15 points.
Needed, but not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had our people at 100 percent,'' UCLA coach Kathy
Olivier mused. ``I don't want to say it would be a different
outcome, but I'd like to think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 0222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
