<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-NEXT-SPI     12-29 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-NEXT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS FIRE ERICKSON, SEEK FOURTH COACH THIS DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Dennis Erickson leaves a team that is much
better than the one he inherited four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the Seahawks are not good enough, which is why
Erickson was fired Monday as head coach after compiling a 31-33
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks never reached the playoffs under Erickson, or even
posted a winning season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of stuck at this 8-8 hurdle for the last four
years,'' club president Bob Whitsitt said. ``And although that's a
good mark _ it's better than where the franchise was before Dennis
got here and I do think he did a good job getting us there _ we
need to get over that hurdle, and there are a few more hurdles we
have to get over.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt said he had reached the point where Erickson would
either be fired with one year remaining on his contract, or have
his contract extended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the organization) chose to shake hands and move on,''
Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks will now hire their fourth head coach in the 1990s
_ following Chuck Knox, the winningest coach in franchise history
who was fired after the '91 season; Tom Flores, who was fired after
the '94 season; and Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt said he had yet to begin compiling a list of
candidates, and no calls were made Monday to set up interviews or
ask permission to talk to coaches who are under contract with other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   But league sources said the Seahawks are expected to be a player
in the Mike Holmgren sweepstakes. Holmgren is under contract in
Green Bay, but has a clause in his contract that gives him a 21-day
window after the Packers are eliminated from the playoffs to take
another job if it includes the title of general manager and coach.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when Whitsitt was looking to hire a GM, he said he
wanted a general manager and a coach, not one person to handle both
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Whitsitt changed that tune, offering, ``We'll be open to
all possibilities and I don't want to rule anything out, certainly
not on the first day.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt also said, however, that he was not looking to make any
more changes in the front office. Asked about vice president of
football operations Randy Mueller, who has been handling the GM
duties without the title, Whitsitt offered, ``I think Randy's done
a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mueller: ``My ego is not a factor. I want us to get the
right guy for the job. ... I don't think we want to rule out
anybody or any type situation at this stage. Our search has to be
all-encompassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mucking up the Seahawks' pursuit is the fact that four other
head coaches were fired Monday, leaving seven vacancies in the
league. That could grow to 10, depending upon developments in
Washington, Green Bay and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like they trotted out the firing squad, and the blood
started running,'' Knox said about Monday's rash of dismissals.
``Everybody in the business knows it's a job with no security, but
you don't expect something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt did not seem overly concerned that so many other teams
also could be vying for the candidates the Seahawks might be
seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to rush it, and we're not going to drag our
feet,'' he said. ``We're going to get into the process and try to
do it in a timely fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no timetable, either, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because so many of the top candidates are coordinators
for teams that are in the playoffs and will be off limits to the
Seahawks until their seasons have been completed. That would
include Broncos offensive coordinator Gary Kubiak, Vikings
offensive coordinator Brian Billick and Jaguars offensive
coordinator Chris Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   Available immediately are George Seifert, the former 49ers coach
turned broadcaster who interviewed with the Carolina Panthers last
night; and Jim Haslett, the Steelers' defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Paul Allen wants the best coach available, and Whitsitt
believes the Seahawks offer the best situation.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, offensive guard Brian Habib has a
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Paul Allen wants to get the best coach in the National
Football League, he has to go to Denver and get Mike Shanahan out
of his contract, which I don't think he'll be able to do,'' Habib
said. ``If he can't do that, then he has to get somebody who was
either a mentor to Mike or mentored by Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of potential candidates is laced with these
mentor/pupil types. Seifert and Holmgren would be the mentors;
Kubiak the mentored.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it all over the league now,'' Habib said of the
ever-growing roots from the 49ers' family tree. ``All the
successful teams, a lot of the coaches there have come from the
49ers and the Bill Walsh system. Say what you will, I still believe
that is probably the best offensive system in the history of the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: The new coach will not come from the
assistants Erickson leaves behind.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of them have contracts that expire next month and it is
unlikely that any will be retained by the new coach. Six others are
under contract for at least another season. Management would like
to retain some of them _ especially special teams coach Pete
Rodriguez and linebackers coach Jim Johnson _ to ease the
transition. But those decisions will be up to the new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Those whose contracts will expire are free to pursue other jobs,
and defensive coordinator Greg McMackin is said to be in line to
join the staff that former Chargers coach June Jones is compiling
at the University of Hawaii. McMackin would be the associate head
coach and defensive coordinator, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   While most connected with the team, including the players,
figured Erickson was a goner for the past six weeks, Whitsitt said
it was a difficult decision that was made over a three-year
evaluation process rather than anything that happened in recent
games. Whitsitt said he talked to Allen on Sunday night after the
Seahawks lost their season finale in Denver, then broke the news to
Erickson Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he wanted to continue to coach this team,'' Whitsitt
said of Erickson. ``It's not one of the meetings you want to have.
... It's tough to get the words and it can be a lot more difficult
depending upon how the person reacts, and Dennis was very
professional in the way he handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson will be paid $1 million for the final year of his
contract, so he doesn't have to coach next season. But he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to coach,'' he said. ``That's the only thing I
know how to do. That's something that I would like to do and we've
just got to wait and see what happens. Right now, I'm just going to
sit back for a couple of days and just kind of look at the
situation and see what opportunities are there and then go ahead
and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondayh's move was a tough one, but also one management felt it
had no choice but to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis brought us to a certain level. He should be commended
for that,'' Mueller said. ``The unfortunate part of this business
is that if improvement isn't seen by the people at the top, then
changes have to be made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 0234EST &QL; 
