<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     12-29 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS HANG HELP-WANTED SIGN FOR BEST COACHING JOB IN NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Someone asked Seahawks president Bob Whitsitt Monday
if he had a short list of coaching candidates to replace the
dismissed Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no list,'' Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Whitsitt was smiling as he conceded the Seahawks have no
short list for their head coaching vacancy. Nor do they have a long
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to find the best person for the job,'' Whitsitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks, we are told, are starting from scratch. Actually, we
are told Monday's dismissal of Erickson should start ``smoking
out'' the best suspects for his successor.
</P>
<P>
   George Seifert, the only potential candidate with no strings
attached _ especially after the laconic Seifert was booted from his
CBS studio gig _ was not trotted out moments after Whitsitt
announced Erickson's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks cut Erickson loose with no replacement waiting in the
wings, which is understandable since many potential successors are
off-limits for interviews because their teams are playoff-bound.
</P>
<P>
   But picking the new Seahawk coach will be an interesting
learning process, Whitsitt said. Interesting, no doubt. Fruitful,
one can only hope, even for a franchise as loaded, as attractive as
the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it just got brutal out there.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Monday Morning Massacre that took place in the NFL
when five head coaches were axed before lunch, there are now seven
NFL teams in search of a new head coach. And there could be eight,
should Steve Mariucci leave San Francisco, as has been rumored.
</P>
<P>
   That is going to make for a wicked game of coaching musical
chairs, destined to stretch out until Mike Holmgren's season is
done in Green Bay, or one organization is going to have to make the
first, bold, shark-attack move in order to set the coaching
dominoes falling.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks, if we heard Whitsitt correctly, believe they have a
chance to set the tone, establish the market. If the Seahawks
lacked competitiveness on the field this past season, Whitsitt has
all but guaranteed Seattle fans _ and the NFL in general _ that the
Hawks now aim to level the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``But of course maybe I'm prejudiced,'' Whitsitt said about what
the franchise has to offer. ``I am very confident that Seattle is
the best opportunity. We're getting a new stadium. It's a great
place to live. There is a great talent base. ... I believe this is
the best place to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: In ranking NFL teams according to
attractiveness for potential new head coaches, how do the Hawks
rate? Whitsitt obviously believes Seattle is No. 1. He will get a
lot of support in that mindset, too.
</P>
<P>
   But there is room for quibbling here. For example, this is what
each job has to offer:
</P>
<P>
   1. San Francisco: Just because of history, tradition and the
system a coach would inherit.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cleveland: An expansion franchise stocked with former 49er
personnel in a football-crazed city that went nuts to bring back
its beloved Browns. No pressure to win right away. Great position
in draft. Great potential to become playoff contender after first
two or three seasons, just like Panthers and Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   3. Seattle: Loaded with talent and cash. Chance to win right
away. Summers in Cheney. Tough transition as new stadium is built
and Hawks play at Husky Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   4. Carolina: When they lost Bill Polian to Indianapolis,
Panthers lost a general manager who can put together a winner. This
is a job waiting for the Packers' Holmgren, who wants to be king as
well as coach.
</P>
<P>
   5. Chicago: Clueless owner, rash of bad personnel decisions
under Dave Wannstedt. But this is a town where Mike Ditka was
lionized, where Dick Butkus and Walter Payton ruled. If you win,
you're the toast of the town. Lose and you're just plain toast.
</P>
<P>
   6. San Diego: The weather.
</P>
<P>
   7. Baltimore: Art Modell.
</P>
<P>
   8. Philadelphia: Why is Ray Rhodes so happily whistling
``Philadelphia Freedom'' on his way out of town? Tough fans. Awful
stadium. Paltry roster. Tough town.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you slice it, Seattle comes out on top or near the top
of anyone's list. That said, no amount of confidence about how
great Seattle is can completely assure the Hawks of getting the
best person.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Steelers general manager Tom Donahoe about his trip to
Seattle last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, in the Hawks' attempt to lure a front-line general
manager, at least one top candidate left his interview session
dismayed at the lack of football know-how within the power ranks of
the Seahawk organization.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, maybe decisions by top candidates such as Holmgren,
Seifert, Rhodes or top assistants such as Denver's Gary Kubiak or
Minnesota's Brian Billick or Jacksonville's Chris Palmer aren't
quite so predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt is the first to tell you he is no football guy. Saying
the Seahawks are the most attractive opening out there does not
discount the kinds of circuitous negotiations that lead a candidate
to his final destination. Sometimes a ``destination city'' such as
Seattle gets rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seahawks are going to be here. The team's already been
saved. We want it improved,'' Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   To make that happen, Whitsitt may not have the hardest sell
among NFL teams in search of a new head coach. But he doesn't have
a slam dunk either.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
