<HEADLINE>
FULMER CLOSE TO $1 MILLION DEAL WITH TENNESSEE, PAPER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tennessee Coach Phillip Fulmer is close to signing a new
contract that will raise his financial package to more than $1
million per year, according to a published report.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessean said the deal is expected to come before Monday's
Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer had no comment Monday, but Volunteers Athletic Director
Doug Dickey, who is in the Valley for the game, told The Arizona
Republic that ``we don't speculate. When we do it, we'll do it and
it will come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer's current base salary is $150,000, plus $150,000 in
endorsements, $320,000 from radio and TV programs and a $125,000
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Just before last year's Orange Bowl, he received a one-year
extension through 2003 and a $145,000 raise that increased his
yearly package to $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer would earn close to a $40,000 bonus if the Volunteers
defeat Florida State and win the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee President Joe Johnson told the Associated Press that a
new contract with a raise was expected to be completed soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't signed off on anything yet,'' Johnson said. ``But
we will do one, and I assume quickly. We want to treat Phil
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The new contract would make him the second-highest-paid coach in
the Southeastern Conference behind Florida's Steve Spurrier, who
has a six-year deal worth $11.7 million. &QL;  &QL; 
Card game &QL;  &QL; 
Several Tennessee players said they were caught up in Sunday's
Cardinals victory over the San Diego Chargers, which was televised.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will play the Dallas Cowboys in the opening round
of the NFL playoffs Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for the city and it's great for the team to finally
get to the playoffs,'' wide receiver Peerless Price said. ``But
I've got to say, I hope they lose to Dallas. The Cowboys are my
favorite team.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Reunion &QL;  &QL; 
Tennessee tailback Travis Henry said there is special incentive to
play well against Florida State. One of his childhood friends,
running back Jeff Chaney, plays for the Seminoles. Henry grew up in
Frostproof, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played Little League with him,'' Henry said. ``I went to
junior high with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went home, I saw him. He said he hopes that I have a
good game. I hope he has a good game.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Destined? &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The top-ranked Volunteers (12-0) have acquired the ``team of
destiny'' tag for all of their close, last-minute victories.
</P>
<P>
   But they say none of that matters now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put our whole season behind us, how we won, all that,''
quarterback Tee Martin said. ``We're not thinking of us as the team
of destiny, but being the best team on Monday night.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Quick hits &QL;  &QL; 
The media demand for the game has far exceeded the typical 350 to
400 requests. Fiesta Bowl public relations manager Shawn Schoeffler
already has issued 500 passes for press box writers, 350 for
sideline photographers, 250 for special duty reporters in the
stands, 100 for messengers, 75 for ESPN and 300 for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   If Jeremaine Copeland is sporting a large Afro this summer,
that's bad news for the Volunteers. The receiver, who usually has a
close-cropped hairdo, is letting it grow long and said he will only
cut it if Tennessee wins. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
