<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLIDAY_CORNHUSKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKERS HAVE ROOTS IN DESERT  
 JOHNSON, CHEATHAM, BROWN FROM VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Nebraska's Kenny Cheatham, Eric Johnson and Mike
Brown had it all pictured.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would they crown their 1998 season with a national
championship, they'd win it at Sun Devil Stadium, just a few miles
from where each grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have preferred to play in Tempe,'' said Cheatham, a
senior receiver who played at South Mountain High School. ``That
would have been great, especially for us from Phoenix and for
myself because it will be my last game.''
</P>
<P>
   But that fantasy ended in the sixth week of Nebraska's season
when the Cornhuskers were beaten by Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Depleted by injuries, the Cornhuskers finished 9-3 and wound up
in the Holiday Bowl against the Arizona Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Cheatham; Brown, a junior rover from Scottsdale
Saguaro; and Johnson, a senior linebacker from Alhambra, it isn't a
bad consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us Arizona guys, playing the Wildcats is almost as good,''
Cheatham said.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially big for Cheatham and Johnson. Cheatham is a
second cousin to Arizona tailback Trung Canidate. And Johnson is
even closer to Canidate, having grown up in the same neighborhood
and having been a Pop Warner teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real special,'' Johnson said. ``Especially because of
Trung. We played together in the West Central Pop Warner. We both
played for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also ran track. I never got the chance to run against him,
but we used to compare our times and all that. I know his parents
real well, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheatham, a starting wideout with 13 catches for 155 yards in
Nebraska's option attack, said he wasn't that close to Canidate as
they grew up, and he didn't know they were related until he was a
junior at South Mountain and Canidate was a sophomore at Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``His dad and my dad are first cousins,'' Cheatham said. ``We
played against each other in high school, and he did his thing. He
scored a couple of touchdowns. But I did my thing, and we won by
two or three touchdowns. So I had those bragging rights after my
senior year.''
</P>
<P>
   The three Arizonans have developed close ties and have leaned
upon each other while adjusting to a different lifestyle in
laid-back Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to have some guys from your home state on the
squad,'' said Brown, who participated in a team-high 102 tackles
and had one interception. ``It's nice to have somebody you can
relate to. Those guys helped me adjust, and you're a little more
comfortable when you know some other guys have come here from
Arizona and made it.''
</P>
<P>
   All three also were recruited by Arizona, and Wildcats Coach
Dick Tomey winces when he thinks about how three good ones got
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great players,'' Tomey said. ``We couldn't get a visit
out of any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   All three did make unofficial visits, but none gave the Wildcats
serious consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really interested,'' Brown said. ``I really wanted to
get out of the state. That was one of my main objectives, and I
came to Nebraska because I think it's the best program in the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheatham and Johnson were even more adamant. They grew up as
Arizona State fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a good program, but I ended up being a Prop 48
(academically ineligible as a freshman), and I thought Nebraska had
a better support program,'' said Johnson, who is fourth in total
tackles with 70 and leads the team with six sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Cheatham said he remains an ASU fan, even though the Cornhuskers
lost to the Sun Devils two seasons ago in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a UA fan,'' Cheatham said. ``I grew up as a Sun Devils
fan, and I was hoping ASU would blow them out this year. ASU will
get them next year, and we'll take care of them this week.''
</P>
<P>
   And if not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still hearing it about that ASU game (in 1996),'' Cheatham
said. ``If we lose to Arizona, I might have to move or relocate.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 0346EST &QL; 
