r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-D     12-29 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-DICKEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA COACH, PLAYERS DRAW STRENGTH FROM TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ In an Arizona season with 11 victories, two
quarterbacks and many angles, there is a single moment at which it
all began.
</P>
<P>
   ``A defining point,'' Arizona Coach Dick Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   A tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   In June, offensive line coach Charlie Dickey lost his 3-year-old
daughter. Chanel Dickey died from a cancerous tumor near the center
of her head.
</P>
<P>
   For Dickey, it was the kind of crushing blow that forces a
re-evaluation of personal priorities. He made his living in a game.
He lived as a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football didn't mean very much, not much at all,'' said
Dickey, who first learned of his daughter's inoperable tumor a year
ago. ``Suddenly, there's a different spin on what things mean in
terms of wins and losses, that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember after certain games, especially last year, of
coming home and not thinking about the game. It was just about my
daughter. Football suddenly became a very, very small scope of
things in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But football also began to emerge as a powerful source of
strength. Dickey and his family began to rely on Arizona's
offensive linemen as they rallied to support him at a time of great
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they grew.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey grew beyond his grief. And Arizona's offensive line,
unknown and uncertain in September, grew into a cohesive force that
on Wednesday will face Nebraska in the Holiday Bowl at Qualcomm
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family,'' said junior Manuia Savea, a 6-foot-2, 296-pound
tackle from American Samoa. ``All of us knew about Coach Dickey's
daughter. We rallied around him. We wanted him to draw strength
from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe it's a reason we've played well. We've been
effective because we're together, and we're together because of
Coach Dickey.''
</P>
<P>
   For Arizona, Dickey's offensive line is another example of a
remarkably close, unselfish team. Tomey preaches family to the
point that it often begins to sound overblown and cliched. In the
age of Monica Lewinsky and presidential impeachment, it's just too
good to believe.
</P>
<P>
   But if the effective Keith Smith-Ortege Jenkins rotation at
quarterback is evidence, Dickey's offensive line is proof that
Tomey isn't just whistling a warm and fuzzy tune.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest test still awaits. Arizona's young line _ two
seniors, two juniors, a sophomore and a freshman _ has yet to face
a defense with the overpowering physical reputation of a Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Nebraska team has great speed and great strength,'' said
Dickey, who played at Scottsdale Saguaro High School and Scottsdale
Community College for two seasons, 1983-1984, before moving on to
Arizona. ``Against California, we had to deal with speed. But we
have never seen this kind of strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is difficult. But Dickey believes his linemen can
prevail, in large part because together, they already have. Their
trust in each other was born at about the time Dickey's daughter
was dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was gone through all of last spring's drills,'' said Dickey,
who has three other daughters and whose wife, former Arizona
basketball player Lisa Bradshaw, is expecting a son. ``My guys were
out there and working for me while I was gone. It's a great
testament to this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a whole lot of moments. When we found out about
Chanel's tumor _ God bless, she was able to live another year _
everybody just rallied around us. Again and again, the players
lifted my and my wife's spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good family comes together when times are a tough. My
players did that for me and my wife more times than I can even
recount. They're just kids who are as unselfish as they are tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to my daughter made me think and made them
think. They know that nothing can be taken for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   For Savea, guard Yusuf Scott, center Bruce Wiggins, guard Steven
Grace, tackle Edwin Mulitalo and end Mike Lucky, the lesson has
lasted a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach lost his daughter, but he will never lose his offensive
line,'' Savea said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
