<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS KNOWS MISSISSIPPI ST. OFFENSE NO JOKING MATTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES AND WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ There is quite a bit of mutual respect between
Texas defensive coordinator Carl Reese and Mississippi State
offensive guru Lynn Amedee, at least enough that Reese doesn't mind
taking a jab at the coach he'll be dueling Friday in the Cotton
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lynn has been around about 100 years,'' said Reese, at 55 two
years younger than Amedee. ``He was the offensive coordinator for
Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, not the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Amedee's offense is an interesting package, Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has every play and every trick play in the book,'' he said.
``They like to hammer you and make you soft in spots, but trick you
a little bit by misalignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to compete against him. It's like a chess game trying
to force him into doing something he doesn't want to do.'' \Nname:
_ Mike Jones
JOHNSON IN EXALTED COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   UT's Cedric Woodard, who Reese said will play both end and
tackle Friday, views Mississippi State running back James Johnson
as favorably comparable to the Longhorns' Heisman Trophy winner,
Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson gained a Southeastern Conference-high 1,383 yards
despite injury problems that limited in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great back,'' Woodard said. ``He runs hard, has good
speed. Nothing I could say bad about him. The only thing our back
has that he doesn't have is all the records. It's going to be a
challenge for us to stop him.''
BULLDOGS ON THE MOVE
</P>
<P>
   After two days of workouts on Texas Stadium's artificial turf,
Mississippi State moved to an Irving schools grass field yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the visitors to the workout was former Bulldogs and
Cowboys star D.D. Lewis, thrilled that his alma mater was making
its first trip to the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Also in attendance were two of Jackie Sherrill's former Aggies:
Kevin Murray and Chet Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who quarterbacked the 1985-86 teams to Cotton Bowl
appearances, now works in Irving. Brooks, a defensive back who
played three seasons with the San Francisco 49ers, is a builder in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin looks great, like he could just step right out there and
do it all again today,'' Sherrill said. ``But Chet, he's starting
to look like me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the practice, Sherrill announced that he will hold a
reunion with his former A&AMP;M players at 3 p.m. tomorrow at the
team's hotel, the Reunion Hyatt.
</P>
</TEXT>
