<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-ED30-COX     12-29 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-ED30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Educators tackle tough questions on HIV/AIDS education
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Health educator Frances Wright Thomas challenges
critics of Ohio's federally funded HIV/AIDS prevention program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not realizing that this AIDS disease is a reality.
You're playing around with a disease that is killing people every
day,'' said Thomas, supervisor of the Montgomery County Combined
Health District's AIDS program.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, does talking about safer sex encourage teens to
have sex?
</P>
<P>
   Some say it does. Others, including some of those who preach
abstinence, acknowledge that some teens are sexually active and
need to hear the message of safer sex.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Department of Education is weighing arguments on all
sides in the HIV education debate as the department develops a
model health and physical education program. The model is a
collection of goals students should be able to reach for each grade
level. Among those goals are learning about reproduction and ways
to prevent sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Many local school districts already include those goals in their
curriculum. The districts that don't would not be required to adopt
the state model.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the issue is divisive. Two weeks ago, a subcommittee of
the state board of education voted to modify the Programs that Work
training that teaches adults how to talk about preventing the
spread of HIV, the virus that causes Acquired Immune Deficiency
Syndrome. That action occurred after outgoing state Superintendent
John Goff imposed a moratorium on HIV/AIDS prevention training
because critics claimed it encouraged teens to have sex and was too
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   State and local educators and health officials accuse the
critics of using scare tactics and false information. Statistics
indicate that the increasing prevalence of prevention programs has
coincided with a decrease in risky sexual activity among teens.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a decade, the percentage of students who
are sexually active has dropped below 50 percent. The teen
pregnancy rate and gonorrhea rate are declining also, while the
percentage of sexually active students who use condoms has
increased to nearly 57 percent from 46 percent since 1991,
according to the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But those positive statistics do not diminish the threat of
contracting HIV. Half of all HIV infections are contracted by
people under age 25 and HIV infection is the sixth leading cause of
death among 15- to 24-year-olds in the United States, according to
CDC statistics released in September.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Ricky Boyd, director of the county health district's
division of special services and a Dayton school board member, is
convinced that local HIV prevention efforts are on the right track.
Montgomery County's program focuses on abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is the only key that we have,'' Boyd said. ``People
die for lack of knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the Ohio Department of Education's Programs That
Work (PTW) effort.
</P>
<P>
   Programs That Work, funded by the CDC, trains adults from
community groups, health departments and schools to talk to
teen-agers and others adults about preventing the spread of HIV.
PTW is comprised of five programs used across the United States
that have resulted in reducing sexually transmitted disease rates,
getting youth to delay the initiation of sexual activity and other
positive outcomes, said Joyce Brannan, the department of
education's consultant for HIV/Sexually Transmitted Disease and
Pregnancy Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Clarence Johnson, the health district's supervisor of
minority programs, both went to the PTW training sessions. ``I
don't consider anything we went through inappropriate or
offensive,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   High school students in the Dayton, Kettering, Northmont,
Trotwood and Jefferson Twp. districts are exposed to PTW education
by health district trainers. State law requires that health classes
include instruction about venereal disease.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Hoffman, vice president of Right to Life of Greater
Cincinnati, believes schools are teaching ``counterfeit
abstinence'' when they should be teaching children about the
sanctity of marriage. In addition, Hoffman said, talking to
students about condoms gives them a false sense of security because
condoms can fail.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, such as Hoffman, believe the state and federal
governments are trying to usurp the authority of local school
boards and parents. They've criticized the use of slang terms and
models of sexual organs in training sessions for adult trainers.
Critics say the CDC is trying to foist explicit sex education on
states and will force Ohio to adopt a health and sex education
state proficiency test.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say there is no plan to implement such a test.
But Hoffman isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a conspiracy theory. It is a conspiracy. It's just
not a theory,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Irish Keaney, who criticized PTW programs during her
unsuccessful effort to unseat 4th District State School Board
member Melanie Bates of Cincinnati, said discussions of sex and
contraceptives with students make them more likely to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   She also said programs ``sold to the public under the guise of a
health concern and stopping the spread of disease'' are too
explicit.
</P>
<P>
   Area educators disagreed, saying teachers will never encourage
students to have sex and the focus will always be abstinence
because it is the only sure way to avoid a sexually transmitted
disease. But because some students are already having sex, it would
be wrong to avoid talking about ways to lessen the chance of
catching a sexually transmitted disease, said Craig Williams,
Dayton's associate director of health and physical education.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and school officials from Cedarville, Xenia, Springboro
and Dayton all said parents are the schools' partners in discussing
sexuality. Parents are warned in advance of sensitive discussions
so they can ask that their children be excused if they object.
Those interviewed said such policies are typical of Ohio schools
and they could never imagine a scenario where the state would force
teachers into explicit discussions of sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything districts tend to err on the side of caution,''
said Randy Overbeck, Xenia Schools' director of instructional
services.
</P>
<P>
   A CDC researcher said repeated studies have found no evidence
that informing students about sexually transmitted diseases and
contraception leads them to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``HIV education has been increasing in this country for the past
seven years and at the same time we see some real positive trends
in delay (of sexual activity) and in condom use. It, in a sense,
counters the notion that in educating youth about HIV it will
enhance risk,'' said Janet Collins, branch chief for research in
the CDC's division of adolescent and school health.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
