u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATE-FLIGHT30-COX     12-29 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATE-FLIGHT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oft-delayed Delta flight is finally ready when you are
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Of all the flights to all the airports
across America, Delta's late-night hop from Atlanta to West Palm
Beach distinguished itself in the most irritating way.
</P>
<P>
   First, it made the federal Department of Transportation's List
of Shame, which ranks domestic flights that arrive late more than
80 percent of the time. It finished 1997 with the very worst
on-time record of any flight by the 10 major airlines required to
file reports.
</P>
<P>
   Then The Wall Street Journal _ factoring in crowding,
breakdowns, stomach-churning snacks and other miseries of the skies
_ pronounced it one of the 5 Worst Flights in America.
</P>
<P>
   How bad can any less-than-two-hour flight be? Especially between
two of the least-likely airports to be snowbound? Climbing aboard
was the only way to find out.
</P>
<P>
   It took a little checking to find out where and when to climb.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal noted that Delta had renumbered the flight four
times while trying to shed its reputation. A fifth change has since
occurred. Flight 284 gave way to Flight 1485 on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The takeoff time has been juggled too, from 8:55 p.m. to 10:05
p.m., allowing more time to ready the plane and allow connecting
passengers from so many spokes of Delta's hub to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   That change had already been made before the Worst Flights story
ran in July. It didn't help. The Journal reporter sat through a
two-hour repair delay (the story didn't give the date) and noted
that in the previous month, the flight was still running late 60
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Delta kept juggling, with considerable success.
</P>
<P>
   In its worst behind-time days, the flight started in Las Vegas
and went on to Salt Lake City before heading to Atlanta. Even when
it wasn't held up by delays on the previous legs, its 8:55 takeoff
time for West Palm Beach was in the thick of other departures, said
Delta spokesman John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The route changed completely in June, he said. Now the Lockheed
L-1011 flies from Fort Lauderdale to Atlanta, then heads for West
Palm Beach and stays there overnight.
</P>
<P>
   On-time performance has been getting better since, Kennedy said.
Department of Transportation statistics back up his claim.
</P>
<P>
   In three months leading up to the latest reporting date of Oct.
31, the flight actually arrived in West Palm Beach a minute early,
on average. It was more than 15 minutes late just 7 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics, of course, don't mean a thing when you're nodding
off on a lumpy pile of luggage at the airport gate. A true test of
the renumbered, reborn Flight 1485 could only be conducted midweek
in holiday season from a blue-cloth seat in coach.
</P>
<P>
   The plane taxied up to Hartsfield Airport's gate A21 well before
9 p.m. The mostly somnambulant passengers were aboard and belted,
their gift-wrapped packages stowed, as departure time came and
went.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've probably noticed it's past time to be pushed away,''
the captain finally announced. Delta 1485 was ready to go, but
another plane had trouble on the runway and was being towed back
for repair.
</P>
<P>
   More time passed as 1485 took its place in line: more than 45
minutes in all before it was finally up and away at 10:52. No
drinks or snacks were served during the wait; a flight attendant
explained they were locked in the galley.
</P>
<P>
   The wait might have seemed worse if the flight were full, but it
wasn't nearly. There were just two or three passengers in most of
the five-across middle rows and plenty of solo passengers in the
double seats along the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Once aloft, the trip was smooth and swift. Everyone was offered
headphones for music, a sack of pretzels and nuts, plus a choice of
soft drinks. It was hardly luxurious, but no great imposition for a
flight that lasted little longer that Orville Wright's.
</P>
<P>
   Here is one secret of 1485's on-time performance: It was
scheduled for an hour and 43 minutes, but it took just an hour and
12. The padding is purposeful, Kennedy said. Atlanta is the
second-busiest airport in the country and that means routine
takeoff delays.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the late takeoff, it arrived just 16 minutes late _
one more than the 15-minute limit used to determine on-time
performance. But that won't hurt the record much: 1485 was running
better than 80 percent on time for the month, a near-reversal of
its shameful days, according to Delta.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, it's hardly a contender for anyone's list of
annoying flights _ unlike U.S. Airways Flight 255 from Atlanta to
Philadelphia, the current shame-list leader. That one's running
late 80.77 percent of the time with an average delay of 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Or United's 320 from Chicago to West Palm Beach. The
July-October records show it with the longest delays of any flight
landing here. It was late exactly half the time, averaging 29.5
minutes beyond the scheduled 12:28 arrival time.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a much better bet than any flight from Atlanta for a
snow delay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
