<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ultimate compliment: The security of having parents
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Absolutely no one cares that I have two ugly,
twisted arthritic fingers on my right hand, or that my most
interesting body parts have
</P>
<P>
   succumbed to gravity. When I wail because the government is
sending me Medicare forms, it's a solo. And who's there to cheer me
up every morning when I
</P>
<P>
   look in the bathroom mirror? Certainly not that rutted map that
stares back at me.
</P>
<P>
   After much soul searching, I've finally figured out what's
really good about these years some nitwit has labeled the
``golden'' ones. It's the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Where would I rather be? Particularly if the south of France is
not an option? I've decided that for now, it's right here having
the chance to enjoy the adult my son has become.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend we were deep into one of our semi-philosophical
discussions of
</P>
<P>
   life, love, and why our checkout line is always the slowest,
when he asked, ``You know what's really good about us, Mom? We
don't get all bent out of shape over little stuff that doesn't
amount to a hill of beans. Like a couple of weeks ago when the
Pepsi truck chewed up the back end of your Bronco. No hysterics. No
histrionics. Just a simple, `Are you okay?' before we got on with
it.'' He's right. We learned a lot about each other that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor says he learned that I hadn't been blowing smoke all
those years when I preached that material stuff wasn't terribly
important and that what really mattered was character, love, and
honesty. And when he expressed his concern for the guy driving the
truck, I knew my son had become the man I'd hoped he would. ``He
just screwed up, Mom,'' he said sadly, ``and now he's worried about
his job.'' Later, when the police were finished at the scene, I was
proud when he shook the driver's hand and told him he hoped it
would be OK for him.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive home, when I commended him for his values and his
ability to deal with unfamiliar and unpleasant situations,
Kristofor flatly stated, ``I learned it all from you and Dad. You
guys were never negative with me and you encouraged me to try new
things and trust myself. My whole life has been like my first trip
to the ocean. Remember?''
</P>
<P>
   How could I forget? He was only a year old, but he'd often heard
the story of his first encounter with the biggest bathtub he'd ever
seen. As we rounded the corner of the rented beach house, he
spotted the ocean, wrenched his hand from
</P>
<P>
   mine, and raced to the edge of the water, hesitating only a
moment before diving in - clothes and all. His dad was right behind
him. Later we marveled that he hadn't been afraid, that he'd gone
in laughing and came out sputtering, but still laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my point, Mom,'' he explains. ``I knew I had backup. I
knew my folks were there. That attitude carries over and gives a
kid security and independence. Because I could trust you and Dad, I
learned to trust myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the woods around our house when I was growing up. I
don't remember
</P>
<P>
   Dad ever taking me out there and telling me where to go and
where not to go; I
</P>
<P>
   just remember venturing out a little further each time. It was
no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and Dad encouraged me to be curious about everything
around me. I was
</P>
<P>
   happy pulling over rocks and looking at the critters under them,
investigating
</P>
<P>
   plants and stuff. Heck, I still enjoy that. `Life is in the
details,' you said, and that's true. There is so much pleasure to
be had in the little stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember saying those things, but I never thought he was
listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember when I was six or seven, way too young to be messing
with Dad's
</P>
<P>
   old army surplus bayonet? You let me roam the woods with it as
long as I promised to follow Dad's rules and keep it in its sleeve
except when I was using it for important stuff like digging
trenches or saving Georgia's forests from kudzu
</P>
<P>
   (the insidious vine brought from the Orient to shore up railroad
embankments
</P>
<P>
   that now poses a bigger threat to the south than the traffic on
Atlanta's downtown connector).
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck and I used to dam the creek and then play Godzilla,
crushing it and watching the flood from a high place. And all of
those books you and Dad gave me - the science stuff? Naturally, I
tromped the woods looking for tigers and bears, but when I'd see
only squirrels and chipmunks, I'd still run back to pull a book off
the shelf and read about what I'd seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and Dad were my security and home was my haven. I never
had to carry a
</P>
<P>
   key and be alone. Whether it sounded like it or not, I really
appreciated having parents. It was the ultimate security.''
</P>
<P>
   And as far as I'm concerned, that's the ultimate compliment.
Guess I'll quit
</P>
<P>
   griping.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Send mail to: 320
West Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 0927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
