<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9862 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN30-CO     12-29 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sowing seeds of success
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Post-holiday letdown gives a lot of people the blahs. But it can
also be a breather and a time to look ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have some time off this week, or at least a slack
period at work. Most of us have been partying, spending and
generally going at warp speed for weeks now. And almost all of us
suffer from nagging suspicions that things have gotten complicated,
expensive and a little bit out of control.
</P>
<P>
   One way to recover is to try to get a grip on your financial
life. With a little organization and effort, you can begin to
recoup some feeling of control over your financial life.
</P>
<P>
   Think of these 10 steps as fairly concrete ways to get your
financial act together, shed bad habits and start building good
ones.
</P>
<P>
   1. Establish some goals
</P>
<P>
   Set aside an hour _ with spouse or significant other _ to figure
out where you want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Jot down all the achievements you can think of. For example, you
might write down the amount you want to save or invest for major
expenses _ a big vacation, a new home, even retirement. Paying off
the holiday debts on your credit cards might be another big item
right now. The important thing is to get them all together and sort
them out.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have your list, go through it again and rank them, from
most important to least. Then try to estimate how much each will
cost, and when you will need the money.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can begin to balance your aspirations to your means. If
you're saving a lot for a home down payment, for example, you may
have to keep retirement saving to a minimum for the time being. Bad
idea, but maybe necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Your goals may start with some or all of the next nine steps. If
all of this is overwhelming, then pick the one, two or three you
can really benefit from.
</P>
<P>
   But keep your feet on the ground:
</P>
<P>
   _ Set reasonable goals. Maybe you can divert $38.50 from each
week's paycheck, so you'll have a filled-up individual retirement
account at the end of the year. If that's too much, a reasonable
goal may to be to save $10 a week and leave it alone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be specific. ``I'm going to start saving'' is a pretty
sentiment. ``I'm going to save $10 a week'' is a goal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay positive. You want goals to work toward, not bad habits
to avoid. The point is to achieve, not to dodge.
</P>
<P>
   2. Get organized
</P>
<P>
   Nothing promotes confusion as much as jumbled or mislaid
records. If that's your problem, here is your solution:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gather up all your important financial and legal documents.
This includes insurance policies, bank statements, investment
records, deeds and mortgage records, wills, maybe even medical
records. And don't forget tax documents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish a filing system for records that keep growing, such
as health insurance claims and tax deductions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Decide where you will keep each record. Some records _ such as
appraisals of your valuables, stock certificates and deeds _ need
to go to a safe deposit box at the bank. Consider keeping a
fire-proof box at home for documents difficult or impossible to
replace. Those might include wills, passports and insurance
policies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a list of all those documents and where you put them.
Make sure your executor or some other responsible party has a copy
of the list.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pay off your consumer debts
</P>
<P>
   Paying high interest rates on credit cards is a waste of money.
Come up with a schedule for paying all your bills, not just paying
the minimums. Otherwise, you have converted your wallet into an
income stream for the lender.
</P>
<P>
   Often you can expedite the process by finding lower interest
credit cards. On the Internet, check out http://www.bankrate.com or
http://www.cardtrak.com for credit cards that will give you a lower
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   4. Review your checkbook
</P>
<P>
   This is a rough-and-ready substitute for a budget. Along with
your checkbook, review the charges on your credit cards for the
last three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   You are fishing for unpleasant surprises _ an unexpected amount
of money spent on restaurants or at fancy retailers, for example.
With luck, you'll spot some areas where you're willing to cut back.
</P>
<P>
   5. Review your investments
</P>
<P>
   Once a year, every investor ought to sort through the stocks,
mutual funds and other investments in his or her portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   As you look at each one, ask yourself: Would I buy more shares
today? Do I think this holding has more growing room? Is it selling
at a plausible price, compared to its earnings and compared to
similar investments?
</P>
<P>
   You may find some investments you want to sell. You may find a
few you would unload if the market gets scary again. Or you may
choose to hold on _ but with a much better understanding of what
you own, and why.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an asset allocation plan, you should check whether
you are still close to your chosen limits. Let's say you intend to
hold 50 percent stocks, 25 percent bonds and 25 percent cash. The
market's growth in recent years could have greatly increased the
percentage you have in stocks. You may want to shift some holdings
around, selling appreciated stock and putting the money into bonds
or money markets.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to include holdings in 401(k)s or other retirement
plans.
</P>
<P>
   6. Tune up your savings program
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey, 56 percent of Americans said they could
afford to save $20 a week. The chart shows how much money you would
save by investing that small amount over a period of years.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't do it by yourself, the best thing may be an
automatic savings plan. It's easy enough: Ask your bank or a mutual
fund company to set up an automatic transfer from your checking
account to a savings account. If you work for a large company, you
may be able have a payroll deduction made to a credit union. The
principle is if you don't see it, you won't spend it.
</P>
<P>
   7. Put money in your
</P>
<P>
   retirement plans
</P>
<P>
   Average people have a hard time coming by tax breaks these days.
Among the remaining ones are individual retirement accounts and
401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   You may get upfront tax deductions, and you will get
tax-deferred earnings on investments in those plans. In a 401(k),
employers often make matching donations _ free money.
</P>
<P>
   8. Review your insurance
</P>
<P>
   If you have gone through one of life's big events, such as
marriage or the birth of a child, you need to re-examine your life
insurance needs.
</P>
<P>
   Your property insurance may need a review, too. Is the coverage
still adequate? Could you lower your cost, perhaps by raising
deductibles? Did Santa bring you jewelry, an expenive camera or
other goodies that might require special-purpose policies?
</P>
<P>
   The problem with insurance is the field is full of variegated
products, eager salespeople and confusion. A good book to help
clear the confusion is Janet Bamford's ``Smarter Insurance
Solutions.'' It costs $19.95. You can order it by calling
1-800-233-4830.
</P>
<P>
   9. Keep on learning
</P>
<P>
   Rresources for personal finance information are innumerable,
including this and other newspapers, an array of magazines and many
books. The old reliable among all-purpose financial planning books
is Jane Bryant Quinn's ``Making the Most of Your Money.'' For
investing, take a look at ``Stocks for the Long Run'' by Jeremy J.
Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net, you can find advice and good links at
http://www.moneycentral
</P>
<P>
   .com, http://www.quicken.com, and http://www.investorama.com.
</P>
<P>
   10. Review your will
</P>
<P>
   You need to make sure it reflects major changes in your life,
such as births or divorce. Is your executor still available to
handle your estate?
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it's a good idea to prepare a list of
beneficiaries and their addresses. Leave a copy with your will.
</P>
<P>
   One more step: Consider executing a power of attorney for health
care and a living will. Those documents become important if you are
no longer able to make decisions for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail: hezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
