<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BET-SMILEY30-COX     12-29 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BET-SMILEY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who is Tavis Smiley, and why are so many black Americans
listening to him?
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tavis Smiley loves to talk. And talk.
And talk. And talk.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Smiley enjoy speaking, he relishes doing it
quickly, as if he gets paid by the syllable. If that were true,
Smiley would have a bank account even Bill Gates would envy. His
words come so fast and furious that listeners need to take a
breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a very precocious, people-loving kid. I've
always enjoyed running my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he gets paid _ reportedly more than $1 million a year _ to
run it. Smiley, 34, is the host of Black Entertainment Television's
BET Tonight with Tavis Smiley, a live, call-in talk show in The
Larry King Live mold. The 3-year-old show covers current events,
celebrities, politicians and hot-button issues pertaining to
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   BET Tonight is also known for boasting one of TV's most eclectic
guest mixes. One night, President Clinton is discussing his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. The next, the Artist (formerly
known as Prince) is talking about his recording career. The night
after that it's Lino Graglia, a University of Texas professor who
believes African-Americans and Hispanics can't learn on the same
level as whites.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the topic, black viewers are listening. Smiley, who was
selected in 1994 by Time as one of America's 50 most promising
young leaders under 40, is quickly becoming an important voice
among black Americans. He has, for instance, urged blacks to vote,
publicly blasted a national advertising firm over a racist memo and
successfully campaigned to bring Fox's Living Single back on the
air after it was shelved.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up poor is the main reason Smiley often uses BET Tonight
to inspire and empower others. ``I've learned that one can arguably
have a greater impact from the outside than from the inside,'' he
explains. ``The media can have such a vast influence on people vs.
elected officials who represent relatively small constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Smiley interviewed President Clinton, who at the
time was making his first public comments after the grand jury
testimony. The interview was an obvious coup for Smiley _ and BET _
since every major news organization was clamoring for it.
</P>
<P>
   But Smiley, who has been referred to as the black Ralph Nader
for justice, is more than just a talk-show host. He's a popular
twice-a-week radio commentator on The Tom Joyner Morning Show. He's
often a guest commentator on CNN, CNBC, Today and World News
Tonight with Peter Jennings. He's an author who's written three
political commentary books and a lecturer who commands hefty
speaking engagement fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tavis has a good blend of the new generation and the old,''
notes Ed Gordon, a former BET news anchor who now hosts MSNBC's
Newsfront. ``He understands his history and understands the people
that came before him. Yet he has the sensibilities of his
generation, which makes him more outspoken in all areas. He's not
afraid to stir things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Tang, BET Tonight's executive producer, is more direct.
``Tavis Smiley is a young old man.''
</P>
<P>
   That young old man lives by what he calls the three E's:
enlighten, encourage, empower.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to bed, I want to feel that something I did that
day, be it as a lecturer, talk-show host or radio commentator, hit
those E's,'' says the Indiana native.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley certainly did that earlier this year, when he got wind
that Christie's, the famous New York auction house, was auctioning
three reward posters for runaway slaves. What bothered Smiley was
that Christie's has a steadfast policy of not selling
Holocaust-related memorabilia. Those are often donated to museums.
So, Smiley used his Tom Joyner Morning Show segment to implore
Joyner's listeners to call Christie's and voice their displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what they did. In less than two hours, Christie's
called Smiley, practically begging him to tell his irate listeners
to stop calling. The president of Christie's even appeared on
Joyner's show to apologize and explain the auction house's
position. The items, by the way, were later donated to museums.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley takes his activist role seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a chance to talk to more African-Americans than anybody
else in this country on a daily basis,'' says Smiley, noting that
55million viewers watch BET and roughly 5 million people listen to
Joyner's show in 95 markets. ``That's what I call reach. I try not
to be high-minded or egotistical, but that's an awesome
responsibility. People are listening to what you're saying, and
they're acting on what you're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially women. When Joyner's syndicated show hits the road,
the still single, boyishly handsome Smiley has been mobbed by
screaming female fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black women are looking for someone to be our hero and for
someone to carry our cause because we know our cause has not been
completed,'' says Denise Pines, owner of Pines One Publications, a
Los Angeles-based publishing house that published two of Smiley's
books. ``He's young and attractive ... (and) he's saying what we
want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley almost never said what he had to say on BET. In fact,
when Robert L. Johnson, BET's CEO and chairman, was thinking of
launching a new late-night talk show, Smiley wasn't interested. He
wasn't even that impressed with BET.
</P>
<P>
   ``BET had taken some hits and deservedly so for not doing enough
creative programming,'' notes Smiley, known as an obsessed
perfectionist who watches tapes of his show every night. Indeed,
despite being on the air since 1980, BET remains mostly known for
airing music videos, old sitcoms and ho-hum infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't certain if BET was the place where I wanted to be,''
Smiley admits.
</P>
<P>
   But BET eventually wore him down. ``We showed him that it was a
show he could own,'' says BET Tonight producer Tang. ``When we told
Tavis that he would get a chance to stamp it with his name,
impression and personality, that made a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Tang says Smiley does have one slight problem: He talks as fast
as Walter Winchell on speed. ``He really tries to talk slower,''
says Pines, laughing. ``But he has so much to say in such a short
period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   His time with BET, however, has not always been pleasant. Even
Smiley says that his most recent contract negotiations were
``rough.'' He said he wanted three things: more money; to shoot the
show part-time in L.A.; and a stronger presence on BET.
</P>
<P>
   He got all three.
</P>
<P>
   But his major gripe was with what he felt was BET's refusal to
promote his program. ``I've worked pretty hard to make this show
the signature show on BET, and I thought the network needed to do
more to promote that fact,'' he says. ``Here I am doing the best I
can, and nobody knows I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gordon, who hosted BET's Lead Story before jumping to MSNBC,
says Smiley's complaints sound familiar. ``Tavis is fighting the
same battle I did, that the program is there, and it's viable,''
says Gordon. ``If BET wants to be MTV for us (black people), that's
great. Then someone should start up our CNN or MSNBC. I understand
his frustration.'' Smiley never thought he'd end up in
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in tiny Kokomo, Ind., young Smiley wasn't quite sure
where his life was headed. Then, in 1978, when he was 13, he met
Birch Bayh, Indiana's liberal senator, who paid a visit to his
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the awesome power that elected officials had to move
people and to get things done,'' he recalls. ``I got to become a
small part of his world, and when I got to meet him, I was moved by
his charisma and style. So I began reading up on this Birch Bayh,
and that's when the political bug really bit me.''
</P>
<P>
   It bit Smiley hard. Growing up as one of 10 kids in a cramped
trailer (he slept on a mattress on the floor), he was no stranger
to poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty was like my first cousin,'' says Smiley, who still
sleeps on a mattress on the floor in his Los Angeles townhome. ``So
I really wanted to do something to help people who were in the same
disenfranchised position.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley enrolled in Indiana University, where he did an
internship with then Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley. He graduated in
1987 with a degree in political science. After moving to Los
Angeles, Smiley, with Bradley's support, ran for city council. He
lost, but got name recognition. Bradley asked him to join his staff
as an administrative aide. It was the late mayor who taught Smiley
his first political lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me to be more concerned about getting things done
around the conference table than taking credit for it at a press
conference,'' he remembers. ``He was a quiet giant. ... Long before
Nike came up with `Just do it,' that was Tom Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley, a card-carrying liberal, makes no attempt to hide his
love for politics. He signs only one-year contracts because he
doesn't want to plan his life too far ahead. One-year deals also
give him more flexibility to, say, toss his hat into the political
arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a public servant is such a noble profession,'' he says,
almost lovingly. ``We've managed to screw that up, and, as such,
many Americans are cynical about the process, but when approached
in the right spirit, it can yield great benefits to masses of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Smiley's followers expect him to seek _ and probably win _
an elected office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a senator in his late 40s,'' says publisher Pines,
matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   And what does Smiley say?
</P>
<P>
   ``My life is not going to be unfulfilled or incomplete when I'm
no longer in broadcasting,'' he says. ``This wasn't my first love,
and it's still not my first love. My first love is still
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   And his second?
</P>
<P>
   Talking, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
