<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEYQUEST30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Act as a human pinball or create own roller coaster at
DisneyQuest
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Tired of playing with that talking Furby
already?
</P>
<P>
   Check out another fur ball's first big venture into high-tech
entertainment: DisneyQuest, a five-story, 100,000-square-foot mall
of interactive games.
</P>
<P>
   When Mickey Mouse builds a family fun center, he doesn't line
video games in a narrow room and hire a surly guy named Chuck to
yell at kids every time the change machine breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   DisneyQuest is not your father's video game ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   Here, your cutting-edge choices include a virtual reality
Aladdin Magic Carpet ``ride'' or Buzz Lightyear's AstroBlaster
bumper cars that fire foam cannonballs. You can paddle your way
along the virtual Jungle Cruise or design a roller coaster and
``ride'' the computer-generated simulation.
</P>
<P>
   DisneyQuest, part of the Downtown Disney West Side entertainment
complex, opened this summer with up to 30 more worldwide locations
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's patented escape into another world begins when you
enter DisneyQuest's first-floor rotunda. You don't ride an
elevator, you ride an out-of-control ``Cybrolator'' operated by the
ghostly image of Aladdin's Genie of the Lamp. You are delivered to
Ventureport, the crossroads that leads to four entertainment zones
on four floors: Explore, Score, Create or Replay.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, players bought units to play the games, instead
of a single admission. That confusing system was changed to a one
price plays all _ $25 for 10 and up, $20 for kids 3 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest accomplishment at DisneyQuest is that it's an
interactive middle ground for everybody from techno-wizards to
techno-phobes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mighty Ducks Pinball Slam, you spend about three minutes
on a bouncing pad with handlebars as you become a pinball on a huge
screen above the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hercules in the Underworld game, a team of four picks a
character for the 3-D chariot journey as you help Hercules rescue
victims of Hades.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular ``adventure,'' based on lines of teenagers, is
Create Zone's CyberSpace Mountain. You design a roller coaster on a
computer and then climb into a 360-degree pitch-and-roll simulator
to ride what you ``built.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Create Zone, you can take a 20-minute animation class and
take home your art work and a diploma. You can make stickers with
your own photo. Sid's Create-A-Toy is a computer that lets you
design a weird toy, and for $10 more you can have an
assemble-at-home kit of your creation.
</P>
<P>
   You can do a bizarre makeover of your face at Magic Mirror or
``paint'' a picture using elements from Disney animation at Living
Easel. If you fall in love with what you made at Magic Mirror or
Living Easel, you can buy a printout ($7 or $5).
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't cost anything to watch marriages erupt as couples
scream at each other in frustration playing Treasure of the Incas.
</P>
<P>
   The driver mans the steering wheel and gas pedal at a video
screen and moves the truck through a maze that's under a glass
floor. The driver's partner can follow the truck's movements and
shout directions to the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no. I said LEFT! NO! LEFT! Oh, jeez,'' is how it
frequently goes as 10 couples can play at once.
</P>
<P>
   For food, there are two stops run by the Southern
California-based Cheesecake Factory Express. On the fourth floor is
the Wonderland Cafe, where you find coffees ($1.65 to $3.70),
cheesecakes ($4.75 to $5.25) and other desserts, most under $4. At
the Cafe, you can cruise the Internet, send a cyber postcard or
record your visit with DisneyQuest's Eternal Journal, which
includes your photo.
</P>
<P>
   On the top floor is FoodQuest. The full menu includes soups
($2.95 to $5.50), pizza (under $4 a slice), pasta (under $7), hot
and cold wrap sandwiches (under $7) plus salads, burgers and more.
</P>
<P>
   This is the rare Disney attraction that can't handle a big
crowd. Admission is stopped at around 1,300 people to make sure
there's no more than a 12-minute wait for the major interactive
``adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   DisneyQuest is at Orlando's Downtown Disney West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: 10:30 a.m. to midnight Sunday through Thursday, and 10:30
a.m. to 1 a.m. Friday and Saturday. Internet: www.disneyquest.com.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $25 for adults, $20 for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Children under 10 must be accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Wear a sweatshirt. DisneyQuest is cold to keep the computers
humming.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call: 1-407-828-4600.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
