<HEADER>
A9866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUMMER-COLLIER30-COX     12-29 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUMMER-COLLIER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ailing drummer receives gift of music
 &HT;    By Dale Huffman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was a magical night for a man and his music
and his memories.
</P>
<P>
   And it happened Sunday because of a genuine friendship that
blossomed after Joe Collier met Edith Ellis 17 years ago, when he
was playing drums in a Dayton night club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my man, music touches the soul in so many ways,'' said
Collier, who is on oxygen and is fighting pulmonary fibrosis, a
serious lung disease. ``Music is the medicine that gets you right
over the tough times.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier, 77, remembers the night he met Ellis, who will
celebrate her 82nd birthday Wednesday. ``We were at the old
Limerick's club and she was so kind and sweet and appreciated the
music so much,'' he said. ``She worked for a Realtor at the time,
and musicians had a tough time making ends meet, so I later went to
her office and asked if she knew where I could get some part-time
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who had lost her husband of 40 years, said she was
impressed with Collier and his gentle personality. ``I hired him
right then to be a handyman around my home,'' she said. ``When he
came here all those years ago, I told him he would always have a
roof over his head as long as he lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, Collier took care of Ellis' home, her cars,
her lawn. On weekends, he would play at different musical gigs, and
often she would go with him.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, had lost his wife in death, and they formed a
friendship by helping each other.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Collier had a career that included stints
with the Count Basie band and Dizzy Gillespie. When he rattles off
some of America's music legends, they are the names of people he
knew and worked with.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Lena Horne gave him his first big break, he said. She
heard him play drums when she was appearing at a USO show during
the war. ``When I got out of the Air Force she hired me with her
band. I spent about a year travelling with her. I met some of the
greats. Man, that was the beginning of a beautiful musical career
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier kept at it until 1958, when he tired of the road and
returned to Dayton, where he'd made his home after the war. The
music almost stopped last year at this time. Collier had always
been a smoker, and the lung damage became so severe he could hardly
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Joe made it, he pulled through,'' Ellis said. ``He had
always been such a good friend and a God-send to me, and now I knew
that it was my turn to take care of him. He had his room in my
home, and I took it upon myself to be there for him. My grandmother
always told me that if you live by the golden rule, and help
others, that good things will come back to you 10 fold.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Collier is on the oxygen 24 hours a day, takes medicine, and
has a home health care attendant help him with his daily bath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally I spend the day in the chair, watching the
television, or sitting and thinking about the wonderful days and
the musical memories,'' he said. ``Sometimes I sit and stare at my
drums.''
</P>
<P>
   The drums are set up in a corner of the music room in the home,
across from the white baby grand piano. Sunday night the room came
to life.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of piano player Richard Bright, who is 74 and a
long-time friend of Collier, Ellis invited a group of Collier's
friends to their home for a jam session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be good for Joe. He misses the music,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bright, the musicians included drummer Red
Ashley, 74, guitar player Jimmy Thompson, 75, and bass player Eddie
Brookshire, 57; Raymond Herring, 72, who plays alto saxophone, was
there with his wife, Eleanor, who plays the piano; Bill Farrell,
67, was standing by to play drums and Pete Smith, 73, was ready to
join in with his trumpet.
</P>
<P>
   As Joe settled back in his chair, the impromptu jazz session
began. It was a warm, feel-good time that made you want to clap
your hands and tap your feet and smile.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, when the band stopped for a short break, Collier
stood up, and with help from friends, moved to the corner where the
drums stood, and maneuvered himself into position. As the music
began, he moved the sticks, slowly at first, then gaining momentum,
he broke into a drum solo, working like he did decades ago with
Count Basie.
</P>
<P>
   When he wound down, those in the room cheered and applauded, and
Joe Collier offered up a smile and a knowing nod of the head.
</P>
<P>
   A little later, still gasping to breathe comfortably, he said
being at his drums again was indescribable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't put it into words. It just got through to me. I felt
it.'' he said. ``For a few moments there, it was like the old days
when I was free to let go and feel the passion that a young body
can put into the music. For a time there I was young again. I've
got to thank Edith for this night. For this gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the session, Ellis stood on the circular drive
in front of her home as the happy sound of Dixieland music warmed
the air of a cold winter night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a good night for Joe, and for me,'' she said.
``The Lord has been good to me. I thank him for bringing Joe into
my life. Most of my friends are gone. Look at all the people I
would never have known if it were not for Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``And look at all the music I would have missed.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Huffman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
