<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROLLER-DERBY30-COX     12-29 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLER-DERBY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RollerJam: A little bit of sport, a little glitz and glamour
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The crowd is, for the most part, canned.
</P>
<P>
   These are theme-park visitors, people at Universal Studios in
Orlando who bump into someone on skates and get handed tickets.
Roller derby, they say.
</P>
<P>
   So the curious are shuttled to a sound stage and led inside, to
rows of aluminum bleachers around a banked track. They wait
politely while cameras are moved into place.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow they must be whipped into television-ready fans. The
announcer booms that roller derby, 25 years dead, is back. ``Pick a
team! Root for your team all night!'' People in the stands ask,
``Who's playing?''
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem. A couple of ``fans'' get last-minute makeup from
a woman in a white blouse. One, a girlfriend of a skater, wears a
fur-lined sweater, a tight skirt and very un-theme-park stilettos.
The camera will go to her for close-ups when her boyfriend gets
clocked _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   A few bursts of smoke, heavy-metal music comes up, and two teams
of 20 men and women roll past the big TV screen and onto the banked
track.
</P>
<P>
   They line up to begin, and the second they do, lights that have
been rigged to look like flashbulbs pop.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, the crowd catches on.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple. Pick a team, then scream while it scrambles around
a banked track on skates, shoving away opponents with hands, elbows
and well-placed knees.
</P>
<P>
   The game is simple, too. Men, then women, take turns trying to
break from the pack and lap members of the other team. Each person
lapped is a point.
</P>
<P>
   Almost anything goes. Referees ``frown upon'' kicking and
biting. And they break up fights.
</P>
<P>
   From his RV parked out back, Ross K. Bagwell Sr. watches and
fingers a long unlit cigar. Bagwell, a part-time Jupiter Island
resident, is trying to bring back roller derby. He is an executive
producer of RollerJam, which is taping its first season here. The
first game will be on TNN on Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The history, in brief, is this.
</P>
<P>
   1935: Starts as endurance skating, men and women just going
around a track.
</P>
<P>
   1938: Two skaters get into a fight one night in Miami. Writer
Damon Runyon talks roller derby creator Leo Seltzer into making
violence a part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   1948: Starts TV run.
</P>
<P>
   1973: Sport dies. Blamed on the oil crisis and bad economy.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer's son, Jerry, is part of the RollerJam group. The rest
are a few roller derby veterans and a lot of young in-line skaters
without a clue _ until they watched the old TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are experts at being elbowed in the head and sagging
halfway over the outside rail. The women tear off their helmets and
pull each other's hair. An entire pack wipes out, and an
enterprising skater leaps over them and scores six points.
</P>
<P>
   It is wrestling on wheels, some say, to which Bagwell responds,
``They don't script it, they skate it.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles. ``We do instruct them not to kill anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Harris, from Birmingham, Ala., sits in the crowd. He
remembers the old days. But his wife, Annette, 25, only knows
roller derby from an old episode of C.H.I.P.S. She decides to cheer
for the California Quakes, not the New York Enforcers, because she
prefers blue jerseys to black.
</P>
<P>
   Kari Johnston also is watching her first RollerJam game. But she
knows what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, from West Palm Beach, skates for the league's Texas
Twisters. She is 41 but looks about 30. She has been a dancer, a
competitive water-skier and a roller hockey player. She organized
South Florida's first all-woman roller hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   She got into roller derby this spring in Fort Lauderdale, where
a man named Patrick Schaefer installed an old banked track in a
warehouse near I-95. He wanted a revival.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't go well. For one thing, the warehouse had no
air-conditioning. And Johnston's first paycheck bounced.
</P>
<P>
   Then a teammate discovered RollerJam in Orlando and invited her
up. She had her doubts. But she also had a promise: RollerJam would
pay her, even for training. Once she finished EMT school in Delray
Beach, she started spending weekdays at RollerJam's rink in
Sanford, practicing blocks and plays.
</P>
<P>
   She won't say how much she makes (Bagwell says skaters make from
$300 to $1,000 a week), but it's enough to make roller derby her
full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps a stethoscope in her gym bag, in case someone _ or the
sport itself _ wipes out.
</P>
<P>
   A woman skater for the New York Enforcers hangs out beside the
sound stage, looking for her daughter in the crowd. She smokes a
cigarette. She already has been to the Roller Jam makeup artist.
``Can't you tell?'' she asks, pretending to powder her nose.
</P>
<P>
   The women skaters wear thongs over their padded shorts. They
wear cropped tops and several have tans. It does not hurt to look
nice, even when taking an elbow to the chin.
</P>
<P>
   Looks-wise, many of the men are crowd-pleasers, too. One is even
a former Mr. Finland.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are given nicknames: The Bod Squad. The Sisters of
Suffering. They get story lines: Some will fall in love. Some will
become enemies. The Enforcers are supposed to be the bad guys. The
crowd plays along: ``Hey, go back to New York!''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, who has a daughter and son, doesn't want a nickname.
``I'd rather not have a story line about me,'' she says, watching
the track. ``I'd rather be known for my skating.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a blocker. There's this cool move she did once in Fort
Lauderdale, flipping an opposing skater over her shoulder. ``I can
actually take my foot up and kick them in the face,'' she says.
``They might not allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game's first turn, the elbowing begins. A woman is
flipped over the rail and lands outside the track. More pushing.
The announcer works on his John Madden impression: ``Boom!''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd still needs prompting, falling silent between fights
and falls. The camera crews, hoping to boost the applause level,
flap their arms like sparrows on expresso.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks a lot better on TV than in actual live performance,''
Johnston admits.
</P>
<P>
   Behind her, Annette Harris nudges her husband. ``It's not such a
bad game.''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``Hmmmph. (Pause.) It's not as good as ice skating.''
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, they split. It is 24-17, Quakes.
</P>
<P>
   What's the right word for a roller derby competition? A game? A
match? A couple of younger skaters check the rules. (A game.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely what the public wants to see,'' says Andrea
Franklin, Johnston's roommate and former in-line skating instructor
from Miami. ``A little bit of sport, a little glitz and glamour.
Pretty girls, roughneck guys, you've got everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries, even. The woman knocked over the rail has a
concussion. One referee broke his left arm on the first day of
taping. (His X-rays will be featured on Roller Jam's Web site.)
</P>
<P>
   It is now 41-40, Quakes. But even though the scoreboard under
the lone piece of advertising, a banner from Auto Zone, says there
is one scoring period left, the players are leaving the track. The
crowd hesitates, confused. It's over?
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard changes. Oops, no periods left after all.
``Well,'' Johnston says. ``I guess that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roller Jam has a year to prove itself. Easy, says Seltzer, the
new league's commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   He says Madison Square Garden has called. The Forum, too.
``We've got places to play now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially since we're replacing the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Boom!
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
