</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If girls think pink, it's probably because of Barbie
 &HT;    By Alison M. Bour
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Just buy her something Barbie,'' says my
brother. ``She loves anything to do with Barbie.''
</P>
<P>
   Great. Shopping for my niece will be easy. A quick jaunt to a
nearby store to pick up ``something Barbie.'' It doesn't take me
long to find the very large, very pink Barbie department.
</P>
<P>
   There are millions of Barbies there. There are Barbies that ride
horses and Barbies that sit on their patio with friends sipping
lemonade. There are even Barbies that look like mermaids and are
capable of growing multicolored hair down to their ankles.
</P>
<P>
   There are Barbies who wear way too much makeup, and Barbies that
come with their own kitchens, hair salons and shopping carts. With
a few minor variations all the Barbies look like twins. And, except
for the baby Barbies, they wear exactly the same size clothes. Rows
and rows of perfectly formed plastic. Great.
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to feel a little sick to my stomach, and it's not
because I'm in an overheated store. OK, just stick to the clothes,
I think. After all, with all the Barbies being the same size, at
least they'll fit. I take a closer look at the billions of Barbie
outfits. Most of them look like something a dancer at a cheap strip
club would tear off in the middle of her act. I notice the fine
print: ``For ages 3 and up,'' it reads. Now I'm not only nauseated.
I'm appalled.
</P>
<P>
   Then, all at once to my surprise, I see her. Airline Stewardess
Barbie! She is part of the Barbies Can Have Any Career They Want If
They Put Their Minds To It Collector Series. Just like Frosty the
Snowman when he gets out of that hot greenhouse, I feel a glimmer
of hope well up inside of me. This Barbie looks excited, dashing
off to a promising job with a major airline. She's ready, she's
confident, and I'm sure she will be the best stewardess ever.
</P>
<P>
   If she is able to serve drinks standing on the balls of her
toes, that is. I commend Airline Barbie's courage to tackle the
real world but I'm worried about her health. It's bound to be
impossible to dash through a busy airport wearing 6-inch heels, and
it's going to cost the airline a lot of money when she needs back
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   I also wonder why Stewardess Barbie's breasts look like Mount
Rushmore compared with the rest of her delicate, fragile frame. If
the plane hits a little bit of turbulence, I'm certain she is going
to topple over, snapping her rib cage in several places. Then how
will she help the passengers exit down the escape slide if there's
an emergency?
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that teachers, even those who think they are aware
of sex role stereotypes, still accidentally encourage intellectual
development in boys more so than they do in girls. Standing in the
middle of the very large, very pink Barbie department, no one can
blame the girls for not protesting. By that time they've been
brainwashed by Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few Barbie knock-offs to choose from. They are
called Ms. Glamour _ or something like that _ and they are also
packaged in pink. I don't find anything interesting in that aisle
either _ no Barbie architects, computer wizards, engineers or race
car drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, something encouraging catches my eye. Dr. Barbie! A
physician outfit complete with a stethoscope, surgical mask and
sensible shoes. ``Paging Dr. Barbie, paging Dr. Barbie.'' Cool. I
like the sound of that.
</P>
<P>
   I should have known better. The doctor outfit is nicely packaged
in a pink box but it's not for Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   It's for Dr. Ken.
</P>
<P>
   He wears the doctor pants in this family.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie is too busy shopping and fixing her hair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I am overheated.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm tired, too. Eventually, I decide on a Barbie car. It's a
convertible and looks like it would be fun to drive. The car comes
with its own detailing and seat beats, and my decision on which one
to purchase is made easier because the Barbie car comes in only one
color. Any guesses?
</P>
<P>
   While I'm standing in line, I decide to pursue a new career
designing Barbie dolls and dreaming up realistic lives for them. My
favorite Barbie is sexy, beautiful, smart, successful, rich and
famous.
</P>
<P>
   At a size 12, she represents the majority of women. She saves a
lot of money because she wears little or no makeup. Sure, there are
times when she wishes she had bigger breasts, but she's too busy
saving lives at the hospital to worry much about it.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone envies my Barbie. She's popular and has a really cute
boyfriend. They go to lots of fun parties together. Barbie's
boyfriend is a flight attendant with a major airline so he always
wears sensible shoes. I'm feeling better already.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'll call my new invention Brain Surgeon Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   Alison M. Bour writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
