<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALFTIME30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgian ensures plenty of action on the football field during
halftimes
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LILBURN, Ga. _ Most of the time, it's the big, sweaty guys in
shoulder pads who hog all the glory during this, the football
season's climax. But when the gridders head for the lockers at
halftime, Pam Antista becomes the belle of the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, Antista has been choreographing razzle-dazzle
cheerleader spectaculars for many of the biggest college and pro
football classics, including the Orange Bowl, the Sugar Bowl, the
Gator Bowl and the Super Bowl _ 54 bowl games in all.
</P>
<P>
   She has hand-picked and trained hundreds of cheerleaders,
majorettes and cloggers.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-something (she coyly refuses to tell her age) Antista has
been shaking pompons ever since she was a kid. Blond and taut,
she's a hard-charging, cliche-spouting, cheerleading true believer
who _ except for her gender _ might have made a gutsy all-state
tailback for some proud coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always used to say, `You couldn't play football so
you did the next best thing,' '' Antista recalls of her dad, Harry
Newberry, a former high school coach in DeKalb County, Ga., where
she grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're the coach's daughter, everybody wants to pick you
up and play with you and teach you all the cheerleader moves,'' she
says. ``I thought that waving my arms and cheering all the time was
what I was supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Antista worked the sidelines at high school and later at the
University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   After college, she opened a gym for cheerleaders, then another
several years later. She also trained cheerleaders at Georgia Tech
and did choreography for the Atlanta Hawks dance troupe.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she became one of America's top go-to girls for
rah-rah, razzle-dazzle halftime shows.
</P>
<P>
   Every football season she endures sleepless nights, impossible
deadlines, missed dinners with her husband and 6-year-old daughter
and countless hours of training.
</P>
<P>
   She demands ``110 percent'' of herself and her staff, she
declared during a break at her cheerleader gym, USA Cheers, where
her teams train for bowl games and cheerleading competitions.
``When you really care as much as I do, you want everything to be
as good as it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the chaos of somersaults and scissor kicks, Antista is a
calm but coiled presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good. That's good. Annnnd up!'' she commands as her
squad performs a maneuver called a ``cuppie,'' which entails beefy
cheer-guys hoisting cheer-gals into the air with one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Antista choreographs each routine, copies it on videotape, then
mails tapes to the high school and college cheering squads she has
recruited for her halftime extravaganzas.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process demands _ contrary to certain cheerleader
stereotypes _ a good deal of mental acuity, organization and
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just wonderful,'' said Sue Ann Jenkins, national
director of Bowl Games of America in Salt Lake City. The company
hired Antista for the Orange, Sugar and the Gator bowls this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the ability to bring together quickly and put together
a very athletic show with routines that are very difficult and
exciting to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   While the groups might have months to prepare before arriving in
the bowl city, they often have less than 12 hours to practice with
other participating squads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many parts to fit together, and you've got to
know what you're doing,'' said Melanie Dangerfield, a former
twirler for Georgia Tech who has worked with Antista for 11 years.
``We're working in these big arenas, and no matter where we are on
the field, she always knows what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, into every cheerleader's life a little bad confetti must
fall. Several years ago, while her business was booming, Antista
was on the verge of career burnout.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to quit, she contacted Texie Waterman, the grande dame
of the Dallas Cowboy Cheerleaders, whom she had seen on reruns of
the 1970s sitcom ``The Love Boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Waterman invited her to Dallas and put the Georgian through her
paces: First they performed some basic cheers to ``Turkey in the
Straw,'' then moved into more complex jazz and Broadway-style dance
routines.
</P>
<P>
   Waterman, Antista recalls, ``pulled out a whole different side
of me that I'd never seen before. She showed me when you run into a
wall, bounce off and head in a new direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Antista returned home refreshed. She has been a fixture of the
college bowl circuit ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Her defining moment was ``Rocking Country Sunday,'' the halftime
show she helped stage in the Georgia Dome for the Super Bowl on
Jan. 30, 1994. It featured 2,200 performers.
</P>
<P>
   But Antista doesn't dwell on past glories. This cheerleader for
cheerleading has more work to do, that old stereotype be darned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this so much, and I'm sharing it with the people who
count _ the performers and the fans. I can't make everyone love
sports or cheerleading, and you can't worry about people laughing
at you. I would only say to them, `Just watch.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Catch Pam Antista's halftime handiwork this weekend during three
big bowl games:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gator Bowl, 12:30 p.m. Friday, NBC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sugar Bowl, 8:30 p.m. Friday, ABC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Orange Bowl, 8:30 p.m. Saturday, ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
