<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-DRUGS98-TAKE1-     12-29 1948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-DRUGS98-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The year of playing dangerously
 &HT;    (EDS: TAKE 1 OF TWO TAKES)
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On the playing field, 1998 was the best of
years.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa blasting past Babe Ruth and
Roger Maris. It was the Denver Broncos and the Tennessee Lady
Volunteers pursuing perfection, and the New York Yankees attaining
their own slice of immortality.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Atlantic, 1998 was France wildly
celebrating its World Cup soccer win and the cycling world
thrilling to the remarkable ride of Marco Pantani in the Tour de
France.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, off the field, 1998 was the worst of years for the sporting
world.
</P>
<P>
   For every great thrill, there was an eerie chill about what was
powering those electrifying performances. For every cheer, there
was a gnawing fear in sport's Year of Playing Dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   It was not only a year of home runs, touchdowns and goals, but
one of pills, powders, police raids and tribunals. It was a year
when performance-enhancing substances stole headlines in a wide
spectrum of sports, on a range of continents. It was a year that
made 1988, the infamous one stained by Ben Johnson's Olympic drug
scandal, look almost pristine.
</P>
<P>
   This year was a bottle of androstenedione sitting ominously in
McGwire's locker while record-setting shot-putter Randy Barnes was
getting banned for life for using the same substance.
</P>
<P>
   It was the French police busting the Tour de France and getting
huge hauls of everything from human growth hormone to the
endurance-enhancing substance erythropoietin (EPO).
</P>
<P>
   It was a doping scandal that rocked Italy's top soccer league,
bringing down that country's highest ranking official in sports,
Italian Olympic Committee head Mario Pescante. There, fans yelled
``drogati'' _ druggies _ at Juventus, one of Italy's most storied
teams.
</P>
<P>
   It was Chinese swimmers getting kicked out of the World
Championships in Australia for drugs and Ireland's Michelle Smith,
a triple gold-medalist in the Atlanta Olympics, being banned for
four years for tampering with her drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   It was rugby leagues in both Ireland and Australia, after years
of denial, discovering that steroid use had infected their sports,
perhaps critically.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the year that creatine, a legal but controversial
food supplement with unknown long-term effects, became the
breakfast of champions.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's football players began their title run by fighting
heat cramps in their creatine-laced muscles in their opening win
against Syracuse. The Super Bowl-champion Broncos used it quite
conspicuously for fuel. They also raised the NFL's level of concern
when John Elway, Terrell Davis and other Broncos wore hats with the
logo of Experimental and Applied Sciences during Super Bowl week.
The Colorado-based company is one of the biggest producers of
creatine products and the Broncos were estimated to be the NFL
leaders in creatine consumption and endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   The record-setting New York Yankees, the Texas Longhorns and
even France's world-champion soccer team have been proponents of
the muscle-builder that was the rage of pro, college and even some
high school teams this year.
</P>
<P>
   1998 also flashed back to use of performance-enhancing
substances in years past. In Berlin, two trials dredged up the
sordid performance secrets of former East German sports officials
and doctors who gave steroids to young swimmers. They were part of
that country's systematic sports doping program that may have
involved as many as 10,000 athletes. The trials brought home three
sobering facts of performance-enhancing substances: they can
dramatically improve performance, they can cause long-lasting
health problems and sophisticated users can escape detection.
</P>
<P>
   Even more chilling, 1998 gave us a glimpse of the future.
Advertisements for creatine aired during the Little League World
Series. And researchers in Massachusetts found that boys as young
as 10 are taking steroids and that junior-high girls had caught up
to their male counterparts in the use of that illegal substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No sport was immune from steroid abuse,'' said researcher
Avery Faigenbaum. ``And as far as androstenedione, sales up here
have gone bezonkers. The greatest ad for it is Mark McGwire.
Adolescents are thinking `I want to get bigger, faster and
stronger, and I want it right now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the Canadian sprinter banned a decade ago, surveyed
today's sport scene and warned in a London paper that ``the whole
world was pointing at me and saying I was the big, bad guy _ the
only guy taking substances. Now they can't hide from the truth. Now
the world has seen that no sport is fair, that there is no level
playing field _ that cyclists are at it, Dennis Mitchell and Randy
Barnes, the East Germans, the Chinese, everybody is at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Barnes, a 300-pound Olympic champion shot-putter,
test positive for a banned muscle-builder, so did a 58-year-old
Japanese snooker player and an Indonesian badminton player before
the Asian Games. When a London newspaper, the Independent,
conducted an extensive survey of the elite in British athletics,
only 3 percent of athletes responded that they thought their sport
was perfectly clean. A greater percentage thought that at least 60
percent of the athletes were cheating.
</P>
<P>
   A disparity in rules
</P>
<P>
   Performance-enhancing substances are found in an ever-increasing
array in sports and their legality can vary from sport to sport. By
baseball's definition, McGwire was not cheating when he used
androstenedione. It's legal there and in the NHL and NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione is, however, banned by the International Olympic
Committee and the National Collegiate Athletic Association, because
it is a precursor for testosterone (the body converts it to
testosterone).
</P>
<P>
   Raising the level of testosterone, a natural steroid, is one way
athletes can attempt to get an edge in strength and explosiveness.
Taking steroids such as nandralone and stanozolol is another.
Although steroids are banned by Major League Baseball, there's no
testing for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a speed limit with no cops. It's an autobahn,'' said
Terry Todd, a University of Texas professor who's an expert on
human performance and who has reported on drug problems in sport.
``Something is juiced in baseball, but it's not the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Steroids can be detected by tests. Currently, human growth
hormone cannot. It can produce steroid-like gains and its use is so
widespread that some have labeled the 1996 Atlanta Games the HGH
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A widening spectrum
</P>
<P>
   Another substance that has kept some athletes a step ahead of
the drug police is EPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPO is to endurance what steroids do for strength,'' Todd
said.
</P>
<P>
   It can increase the oxygen-carrying capacity of blood, but in a
worst-case scenario it can also turn a person's blood into so much
sludge and cause death.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, no one knows if creatine has any adverse effects other
than causing muscle cramping when used without proper hydration.
The substance is found naturally in the body and in foods such as
meat, but not in the huge proportions ingested by today's athletes,
who use a variety of creatine products.
</P>
<P>
   Performance-enhancing substances made news almost as soon as the
new year began. In January, many of the world's best swimmers
gathered in Perth, Australia, for the World Championships. The
Chinese swimmers, who created controversy in the 1990s with their
record swims and failed drug tests, arrived intent on cleaning up
their image.
</P>
<P>
   But on Jan. 8, Chinese swimmer Yuan Yuan, a silver-medalist in
the 1994 World Championships, was stopped at the Sydney airport.
Authorities checked a Thermos and found 13 vials of Somatropin, a
human growth hormone. She was kicked out of the competition, and a
few days later four other Chinese swimmers tested positive for
Triamterene, a masking agent.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, a notable absentee from the Championships,
Michelle Smith, was given an out-of-competition test in Ireland.
International swimming officials said her urine sample came back
with a high enough concentration of whiskey in it to kill a person
_ or to render a drug test useless. Smith, a heroine for Ireland in
1996, was later banned for four years by swimming's international
governing board, FINA. Smith has repeatedly denied using
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think never in the history of doping has there been an
instance where someone who got caught admitted it,'' Todd said. He
said many athletes rationalize it by assuming that their
competitors are on something and, ``they don't want to get caught
taking a knife to a gunfight.''
</P>
<P>
   British swimmer Michael Fibbens, a three-time Olympian, said,
``You spend your whole life trying to get to the top of your sport,
and when you eventually get to the top five in the world, the four
people above you are possibly cheats. And then you've got to deal
with the fact you wasted so much time to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fibbens tested positive for benzoylecgonine. He said the
metabolite of cocaine was from recreational use, but it's also a
stimulant. He received a one-year ban.
</P>
<P>
   Tour de France's turmoil
</P>
<P>
   The doping scandals reached unprecedented proportions in the
summer, when teams at the Tour de France were busted by police
after authorities found what amounted to rolling drug labs for some
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still shocked at what was going on with the Tour'' said
Bill Stapleton, a former UT swimmer and chairman of the athletes
advisory committee for the USOC. Stapleton also represents cyclist
Lance Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance has been racing against cheats,'' Stapleton said. ``If
they don't clean it up his sport is going away. Because of what
happened on the Tour, sponsors are saying enough is enough, or
we're out of it. The athletes have been screaming for 15 years. If
they don't fix it, they can kiss the Tour de France goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   When a van for the Festina team was stopped at the
French-Belgian border, authorities say they found 235 doses of EPO,
82 shots of human growth hormone and 60 doses of testosterone,
along with syringes and masking agents.
</P>
<P>
   Festina was later kicked out of the Tour after admitting to an
organized drug-taking program. Another team, TVM, quickly became
caught in the spreading scandal. Before the 12th stage riders from
all the teams staged a two-hour strike to protest their treatment.
But as the authorities kept pressing, teams began dropping out of
the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, problems were beginning to surface in
professional soccer in Italy's prestigious Serie A. The coach of
the Roma club, Zdenek Zeman, was asked what he thought was wrong
with Italian soccer. He said he thought players spent too much time
at the chemist. That statement triggered investigations that
resulted in some of the highest officials in Italian sport
resigning and the country's main drug-testing lab losing its
certification. By December the soccer drug scandal, in which human
growth hormone and EPO were again at the center of allegations,
still wasn't wrapped up. Two more high-ranking officials were
questioned this month about possible coverups in the drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   Another doping matter still unresolved is the curious case of
flamboyant Sri Lankan sprinter Susanthika Jayasinghe, who aims to
be the Flo-Jo of the 2000 Olympics in Sydney. She showed up for the
Asian Games even though she was under an international suspension
for testing positive for a steroid in April.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
