<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9879 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-DRUGS98-TAKE2-     12-29 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-DRUGS98-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPORTS-DRUGS98 _ TAKE 2 OF TWO
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Continued from Take 1)
</P>
<P>
   Doping's past history
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Jayasinghe was making news, the court trials in
Berlin of former East German doctors and trainers demonstrated how
long doping practices have been influencing the outcome of sporting
events.
</P>
<P>
   East Germany built a sports factory that churned out Olympic
medals, but when that Communist regime collapsed, its secret
police, the Stasi, was not able to destroy many of its massive
surveillance files.
</P>
<P>
   One dark secret exposed was the often-suspected _ but never
proved _ doping of East German athletes. The files showed that the
doping was larger and more systematic than almost anyone had
suspected. The trials of former swimming officials at two Berlin
clubs are just the beginning on a legal effort that may last beyond
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that German prosecutors have 90 cases against 680
defendants to pursue. The athletes involved, who often were told
they were ingesting vitamins, suffered a variety of side effects
from the doping, ranging from acne and deepened voices to heart and
liver damage.
</P>
<P>
   The swim trials, which produced several convictions, had added
interest in this country, because U.S. Swimming was seeking medals
and recognition for swimmers who had lost to illegally doped East
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Sterkel, now the women's swimming coach at the University
of Texas, was the youngster on the 1976 U.S. swimming team in
Montreal that arrived with typically high expectations and a new
worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd hear deep voices in the locker room,'' Sterkel said. ``I
knew they were big, but I thought we could beat them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. There were 13 Olympic gold medals awarded in women's
swimming in 1976, and the husky and husky-throated East Germans won
11 of them. Sterkel was part of the U.S.'s only gold, a freestyle
relay, as the U.S. team was crushed physically and emotionally .
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our 20-year reunion in 1996,'' Sterkel said of that
1976 American team. ``I didn't realize how badly they were hurt. It
was their meet, but they didn't go home as heroes. Their homecoming
was not real pleasant. They felt embarrassed to be part of the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   No one suffered a bigger disappointment than Shirley Babashoff.
Projected as an Olympic heroine, she swam good times but couldn't
beat the East Germans. When she complained of possible steroid use
she was dubbed ``Surly Shirley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It affected Shirley's life,'' Sterkel said. ``She was seen as
a crybaby, a sore loser. I don't think anything could take away
that kind of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. sought a gold medal or some form of recognition this
year for the medley relay team of Babashoff, Lauri Siering, Linda
Jezek and Camille Wright. Bu the International Olympic Committee,
not wishing to get bogged down in what one official termed a
``bottomless swamp,'' chose not to change medal standings in past
events.
</P>
<P>
   Sterkel also swam in the 1988 Games in Seoul, where she finished
tied for third in the 50-meter freestyle behind winner Kristin
Otto. Otto was not involved in either trial, but her name has come
up in the Stasi files.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I wouldn't tell them no, but I don't think it's
important,'' Sterkel said of any medal hopes. ``Now, they're paying
for it with their lives. It seems a little petty for me to want a
medal. They were worse victims than me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched what happened to Shirley and learned to be quiet. My
whole career, it wasn't equal. I knew how good I was and if the
rest of the world doesn't know, I'm OK with that.''
</P>
<P>
   A questionable future
</P>
<P>
   One of the arguments against rewriting history is that there is
no way of knowing that the athletes beaten by the East Germans were
clean themselves, since athletes were able to beat the existing
tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard too many stories,'' Sterkel said. ``I think the
U.S. has been involved, maybe at the Olympic Trials so they don't
test positive at the Olympics. You hear stories of other big names
that didn't get thrown out of the Olympics. The biggest joke in the
athlete's village was how Ben Johnson was dumb enough to get
caught. It makes you wonder what others were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton said the USOC, like other governing bodies, is aware
of the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been accused of being the fox guarding the hen house,''
Stapleton said. Frequently, when an athlete runs afoul of an
international governing body over a failed drug test, the first
ones to champion his or her cause is the national governing body of
the athlete's home country. It happened with Smith and Jayasinghe
this year, and U.S. Track and Field has cleared such athletes as
Mary Slaney and Dennis Mitchell before the International bodies
were satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Said researcher Stapleton, ``the buzz word is externalization.''
The IOC, USOC and other bodies want to let drug testing be done by
disinterested parties.
</P>
<P>
   Drug testing is becoming more sophisticated, but drug cheats
have managed to beat the system for more than two decades. And in
1998 it looks like a new generation of rule-breakers is on the way,
according to groundbreaking research reported in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Said Faigenbaum: ``From talking to parents, from understanding
what goes on in youth sports, we had a feeling steroid use was
there. We attempted to get baseline data. We found that about half
these kids knew that steroids make you bigger and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   His group also discovered that 2.6 percent of the girls and 2.8
percent of the boys in four junior high schools that were sampled
had used illegal steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found some disturbing trends,'' said Faigenbaum, who saw
steroid use in gymnastics, where it does just about everything an
obsessed coach could want. ``In addition to strength and power, it
can also stunt your growth with a premature closure of the growth
plate,'' Faigenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   With the rapid rise in popularity of supplements such as
creatine and androstenedione, Faigenbaum said he is sorry he didn't
ask about more substances in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creatine is legal, but it raises interesting issues,'' he
said. ``Why is that 10-year-old taking creatine? What are we asking
our kids to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently nothing that hasn't been done in the past. This year
the most infamous sprinter of all time, Johnson, crowed, ``So Ben
Johnson is not the only one doing it. And I was never alone. In
1988 I was never alone. The majority at Seoul were on some
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   That year, 1988, was the most disturbing in sports. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   John Maher writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
