<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9903 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-OSU-GERMAINE     12-29 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-GERMAINE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Germaine wins respect through calm attitude
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ When Rob Murphy first saw Ohio State quarterback
Joe Germaine three years ago, the Buckeye offensive lineman could
hardly believe his eyes. This freckled-face, clean-cut,
boyish-looking guy was going to lead OSU's offense; stand in the
pocket and take devastating hits, rally the troops when the game
was on the line?
</P>
<P>
   ``You just looked at him and he didn't look like a quarterback.
I thought he was trying out for the cheerleading squad,'' Murphy
said Monday during the Buckeyes' preparation for Friday's Sugar
Bowl showdown with Texas A&AMP;M (11-2).
</P>
<P>
   Today, Murphy realizes his first impression couldn't have been
more wrong. Germaine, who will be playing in his final game as a
Buckeye on Friday, is frequently the player his OSU teammates and
coaches point to as the toughest guy on the team.
</P>
<P>
   But his toughness is not from the Chuck Norris or Mike Tyson
mold. It's much subtler than that. Murphy describes it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something to be said about looking into a
quarterback's eyes and kind of knowing everything's going to be
OK,'' he said. ``He's like my mother-away-from-home (showing me)
everything's going to be all right if you just do your job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always so cool and calm that you can just look to him and
get some calmness yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that poise and collectiveness, along with a strong,
accurate arm, that has helped No. 3 OSU to a 10-1 season and a
second straight Sugar Bowl berth and earned Germaine Big Ten
Offensive Player of the Year honors and a spot in the OSU record
book.
</P>
<P>
   His four consecutive 300-yard passing games are a school record
as are his seven in a season and eight in a career. His 55 career
touchdown passes are just two shy of Bobby Hoying's school record.
And he needs just 162 yards and three completions to surpass
Hoying's season records in each of those categories.
</P>
<P>
   As his collegiate career comes to an end, Germaine frequently
says he'd like to be remembered for more than orchestrating OSU's
winning touchdown drive _ and tossing the winning pass _ in the
Buckeyes' 1997 Rose Bowl victory. But in the next breath, the
quarterback also says he considers his MVP Rose Bowl trophy his
most coveted individual prize.
</P>
<P>
   He's admittedly disappointed he didn't realize his dream of
playing in the Jan. 4 national championship Fiesta Bowl in his home
state of Arizona. A 28-24 loss to Michigan State on Nov. 7, one of
Germaine's poorest games of the year (16-of-34, 239 yards, one
interception), prevented that.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 23-year-old quarterback just wants to finish his
college career with a victory over Texas A&AMP;M on Friday. After that,
he hopes there's a spot for him in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sure like to play'' in the pros, Germaine said.
``Hopefully I've proven this year and in the previous years that
I'm capable of doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   As for anyone who meets him and thinks he might not be able to
hack the NFL, Germaine says don't judge a book by its cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first impression people get from me is, `He's a shy guy, a
quiet guy. He's not a leader,' '' Germaine said. ``That's the exact
opposite of what I am. I'm a leader by example. I want to win as
much or more than the other guy.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
