<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, December 30, 1998 are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ (Eds: This is the first of weekly columns by
Atlanta Constitution editorial writer Marilyn Geewax on issues
raised by the coming of 2000. The column will move every Monday.)
Thursday night, when you start the 10-9-8-etc. ritual and pop the
champagne, yell and kiss everyone, it may be the last fun New
Year's Eve party you'll have for a long time. At least that is the
advice of some experts working on the computer problem commonly
called the Y2K bug. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Let's see how many ways we can find that this is
a really bad idea: Israel's Labor Party has hired James Carville as
a political consultant. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for
Cox Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Saddam Hussein is a bad guy. We certainly
think so. We like to think the Iraqi people also think so. But do
they? (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ One day my son said to me:
``You and Dad were my security and home was my haven. I never had
to carry a key and be alone. Whether it sounded like it or not, I
really appreciated having parents. It was the ultimate security.''
And as far as I'm concerned, that's the ultimate compliment. Guess
I'll quit griping. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
