<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Wednesday, December 30, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BRIEFS _ A compilation of health briefs from the past
week. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   BET-SMILEY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tavis Smiley loves to talk.
And talk. And talk. And talk. ``I've always been a very precocious,
people-loving kid. I've always enjoyed running my mouth.'' Now he
gets paid _ reportedly more than $1 million a year _ to run it.
Smiley, 34, is the host of Black Entertainment Television's BET
Tonight with Tavis Smiley, a live, call-in talk show in The Larry
King Live mold. We visit with the host. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DRUMMER-COLLIER _ DAYTON, Ohio _ After World War II, Joe Collier
had a career that included stints with the Count Basie band and
Dizzy Gillespie. When he rattles off some of America's music
legends, they are the names of people he knew and worked with.
Singer Lena Horne gave him his first big break, he said. She heard
him play drums when she was appearing at a USO show during the war.
``When I got out of the Air Force she hired me with her band. I
spent about a year travelling with her. I met some of the greats.
Man, that was the beginning of a beautiful musical career for me.''
Today, Collier is in poor health, but his spirits were lifted
recently, thanks to a longtime friend and a little music. (Huffman,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' profiles Jesse
``The Body or the Mind'' Ventura. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ I have heard from a number of people who regard
a little school as a potential improver of our educational system.
They are all people who, like me, happened to have attended one-
and two-room schools before consolidation hit the land. (Sibley,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEYQUEST _ ORLANDO, Fla. _ Tired of playing with that talking
Furby already? Check out another fur ball's first big venture into
high-tech entertainment: DisneyQuest, a five-story,
100,000-square-foot mall of interactive games. DisneyQuest is not
your father's video game ghetto. (Lomartire, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROLLER-DERBY _ It's simple. Pick a team, then scream while it
scrambles around a banked track on skates, shoving away opponents
with hands, elbows and well-placed knees. Each person lapped is a
point. It's wrestling on wheels. It's ``RollerJam,'' and the
creator of this new show is hoping roller derby will catch on
again. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE _ Studies show that teachers, even those who think they
are aware of sex role stereotypes, still accidentally encourage
intellectual development in boys more so than they do in girls.
Standing in the middle of the very large, very pink Barbie
department, no one can blame the girls for not protesting. By that
time they've been brainwashed by Barbie. (Bour, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HALFTIME _ Ever wonder who puts together those halftime shows
during bowl games? Patricia Antista is a choreographer for such
events, and her resume even includes the Super Bowl. She has a gym
in Duluth, Ga. where performers practice. (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MILBRATS-INTERNET _ Constant relocations make it hard for
military brats to maintain friendships. But the Internet is helping
many former brats reconnect with old friends and reminisce about
the days when they shopped at the p.x. and went to the post school.
(Lee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-1999 _ Ten things to look forward to in the region in
1999. ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
