<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9968 &Cx1f; sci-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIKING-BLOOD-NYTSF &LR;      12-29 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIKING-BLOOD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD OF THE VIKINGS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative Nirdi Relis at (212) 499-3333; fax
(212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: FOUR COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight
delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) at NO EXTRA
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT KUNZIG  
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   In middle life Kari came home. The Icelanders welcomed the
prodigal; their leaders gave him their support. So did a Swiss
pharmaceutical firm, which pledged $200 million to the company Kari
started. He said it would study the genes of his countrymen and
find the secrets of many diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Iceland is not so different from other places. It has a
McDonald's in local decor. It has shop windows filled with baggy
pants, skateboards and elevator sneakers. It has people walking
down the streets with cell phones pressed to their ears. It also
has a biotechnology company, the one Kari Stefansson started,
called deCODE Genetics.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Iceland also remains beautifully different, empty and
strange. It was all but devoid of mammals, let alone human beings,
until 874, when the first settlers arrived from Norway. By 1800
there were only 45,000 or so Icelanders, and they were barely
surviving.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty isolated the them. Icelanders today are virtually all
descended from a few thousand people who arrived in the ninth and
10th centuries. That feature makes them of great interest to
geneticists.
</P>
<P>
   In an island nation, tracing family connections even
astonishingly far back into the past is not hard _ and deCODE has
set about doing it once and for all. No more than 625,000 souls
have ever dwelled on Iceland. The deCODE genealogy now includes
560,000 of them, their names and relations.
</P>
<P>
   Kari believes it will encompass 600,000 names in another year or
two and that nearly all the missing ones will date from before
1700.
</P>
<P>
   Medical records for other Icelanders exist back to 1915, when
the country's National Health Service was formed. In the Icelandic
system, people with specific diseases are funneled into specialized
treatment centers, which makes them easy to find. When Kari and his
colleagues decide to study a particular disease, they simply call
the appropriate specialists and quickly assemble a list of everyone
in Iceland with that affliction.
</P>
<P>
   Then deCODE's robotic PCR machines and DNA sequencers and
white-coated young technicians go to work. For each patient, they
scan the entire genome _ all his or her DNA _ for markers that are
identical in most people with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   On Iceland, even unrelated people with the same disease often
have the exact same mutation. The patients who have it are not
completely unrelated, of course; they all must have inherited it
from the same founder, probably from one of the original settlers.
And the importance is this: Two otherwise unrelated Icelanders who
inherit a mutation from a common ancestor 50 generations back will
share a much smaller chunk of DNA than, say, two first cousins who
inherit a mutated gene from their common grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   With each generation, chromosomes are cut to pieces and the
pieces are shuffled; Over time, the pieces that can be traced
intact to any particular ancestor get smaller and smaller.
</P>
<P>
   By studying the DNA of unrelated or distantly related
Icelanders, deCODE can quickly zero in on a much smaller region
around the disease gene. To find the disease mutation, deCODE
workers still have to sequence that region step-by-step _ but now
they are analyzing a sequence of only 100,000 to 200,000 bases
instead of 5 to 10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kari first conceived deCODE in 1996, he has enjoyed good
support. Last year, he and his colleagues pinpointed the locus of a
gene _ not the gene itself _ for a fairly common disorder which
causes involuntary shaking of the hands, arms and head, especially
in elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, Jeff Gulcher, who runs the lab at deCODE, said
they had narrowed the search for a multiple sclerosis gene down to
a DNA region comprising three to five genes, which they were now
sequencing.
</P>
<P>
   In between, business boomed. Last February, Kari signed a deal
with Hoffman-La Roche, under which the Swiss pharmaceutical firm
will pay deCODE more than $200 million over five years to identify
genes for 12 specific diseases. The agreement gives Roche the right
to develop diagnostic tests and drugs based on the genes deCODE
discovers. It also gives all Icelanders free access to those drugs
and tests.
</P>
<P>
   What deCODE got from the deal is its lab full of gleaming
machinery and a huge staff expansion, which is expected to soon
number 200. Still, he probably would not have had problems with
other Icelandic researchers if it had not been for his database
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Kari's idea is to combine the deCODE genealogy of all Icelanders
with a crude genotype _ the marker map _ of all Icelanders, or of
as many as will agree to give blood. This is, of course, precisely
what deCODE is already doing in searching for disease genes. The
difference here is that Kari wants to include all Icelanders, the
healthy along with the sick.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have raised several objections. The first is that a
centralized medical database would threaten the privacy of
patients. The idea of all that information being collected in one
place and placed under the control of a private company makes some
people deeply wary.
</P>
<P>
   Another criticism of the database is that it is just Kari's
attempt to monopolize genetic research on Iceland. Among other
things, the database would constitute all the spadework that would
ever need to be done to launch any genetic study in Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   To make the database happen, Kari needs a law authorizing its
creation and especially giving deCODE some sort of exclusive
commercial rights to it. Such a bill, rewritten, is currently
before the Althing, the Icelandic Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymity of the database is to be guaranteed by an
independent committee, paid for by deCODE. And academic geneticists
would be allowed access to the new database _ provided that their
research does not undermine the commercial interests of deCODE. The
bill would grant deCODE a monopoly on commercial exploitation of
the database for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Iceland would get a couple of hundred good jobs. The
government would also get full access to the database, and the
country's medical records facilities would be standardized,
modernized and computerized at deCODE's expense.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill would not require deCODE to share with Icelanders
any of the profits it might make off their medical and genetic
histories _ or any money it might make from a public offering of
its stock.
</P>
<P>
   All he has ever wanted, Kari Stefansson explains, is to do good
science and to do good by Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about the isolation of the nation over 1,100
years, and if you think about all the natural disasters, all this
misery over the centuries _ we are so fortunate that we are a
company in a position to turn the consequences of that into value
for this nation. Into the creation of new knowledge for the entire
world. You could argue that it was an attempt to seek some poetic
justice for the misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's my spin on it. I'm not sure that everyone else
would agree.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robert Kunzig is Discover's European editor who is based in
France.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC; 
