<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Dec. 29, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-AG (Sacramento _ Democrat Bill Lockyer, California's
attorney general-elect, has a list of priorities that bear little
resemblance to those set by his Republican predecessor, Dan
Lungren, during his two terms. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-MOTHER-OBIT (San Antonio) _ Within a week of learning her
son would share the cover of Time as one of the magazine's Men of
the Year, Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's mother, Vannie Mae
Starr, 91, died of cardiovascular disease in her tiny home here
where she had raised him and two other children. By LISA SANDBURG.
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGE-SF (San Francisco) _ Despite opposition from mayors on
both sides of the San Francisco Bay and the threat of lawsuits,
California's State Transportation Department is pressing plans to
place the eastern span of the Bay Bridge north of the current
structure. The decision all but assures a legal fight over the $1.5
billion plan and a delay in construction. By VENISE WAGNER.
</P>
<P>
   PEN-PALS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Marsha White of the Albany area and
Rajendra Sukhtankar of Poona, India, have been corresponding since
they were teen-agers. After 35 years of letters, they are meeting
for the first time in India. By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FERTILITY-DONORS (Albany, N.Y.) _ As more couples seek options
in their quest for parenthood, clinics across the country are
competing for young women to donate their eggs. Some large
infertility clinics in New York City and New Jersey have engaged in
bidding wars, paying as much as $5,000 to recruit willing donors.
By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN-COMFORTER (Albany, N.Y.) _ A good night's sleep can easily
be interrupted by frosty weather if it leaves you shivering in bed.
Short of a two- or three-dog night (when it's so cold that you let
the pets provide extra warmth), nothing can beat the insulation
power of a down comforter. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE-OFFICER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Nothing makes Chris Cuttita
feel more romantic than a wedding. Through an unusual state law,
Cuttita is doing more than witnessing couples celebrating their
wedding day: She's tying the matrimonial knot for them. Cuttita is
a marriage officer _ a position every local government can fill but
few do. By KENNETH C. CROWE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-JEWS (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ It took a lot of chutzpah for
Stan Mack to attempt to consolidate 4,000 years of Jewish history
into a 265-page book and of all things, in cartoons. But that is
exactly what Mack, 62, set out to do in his new book, ``The Story
of the Jews: A 4,000-Year Adventure.'' By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   STREETCAR (San Francisco) _ If you must see Andre Previn's
opera, ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' be sure of one thing: You will
never encounter it sung better than on the PBS ``Great
Performances'' telecast Wednesday night. By ALLAN ULRICH.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-ACTION (San Francisco) _ We talk to the lawyer who
inspired the film ``A Civil Action'' and get the story behind the
movie. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   DANIEL-DEFOE (San Francisco) _ Hundreds of anonymous
18th-century articles and letters have been attributed to the famed
writer Daniel Defoe, author of ``Robinson Crusoe.'' But did he
really write all of them? To find out, literary experts are
analyzing the disputed texts with a computer, and their work is
being discussed at the Modern Language Association of America
conference here. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ The Asian contagion has hit the San
Francisco Bay area right in the exports. According to a report
released by the Bay Area Council, local exports plunged 18 percent
in the third quarter of this year compared with the same period
last year. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ELLISON (San Francisco) _ Sailing novice and software titan
Larry Ellison cruised to victory in Australia's deadly
Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race but said if it had been his first race
he'd never sail again. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   MARIUCCI-49ERS (San Francisco) _ Steve Mariucci picked a
ruthless occupation, and a ruthless organization picked Mariucci.
The 49ers jettisoned Joe Montana and Ronnie Lott, so why not the
young head coach? On Mariucci's watch, they have surrendered their
domain, the NFC West, and lost two straight to Green Bay. By GWEN
KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Young people know everything.
Middle-aged people suspect everything. But too many old people
believe anything, and ripoff artists know that. Fully a fifth of
the population is now composed of senior citizens, and every year
fraudulent telemarketers take them for as much as $30 billion. By
DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The City Council of Davis,
Calif., the bicycle helmet and political correctness capital of the
world (sorry, Berkeley), has decided to retroactively punish a dead
man because of his moral failures. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
