<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME RATING SYSTEM STILL GIVES GREEN LIGHT TO GORE
</HEADLINE>
  By PAMELA MENDELS  
 c.1998 CyberTimes 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While supporters and critics of the electronic game industry
agree that the voluntary rating system used for video and computer
games generally works well, a new report suggests that some
publishers may be undermining the ratings, by marketing games
featuring gore and violence to children barely out of their Sesame
Street years.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict became apparent this month (December), after the
release of the fourth annual ``Video and Computer Game Report
Card'' issued by a media watchdog group, the Minneapolis-based
National Institute on Media and the Family. The report was unveiled
at a news conference with Sen. Joseph Lieberman, a Connecticut
Democrat, who helped push for the industry to adopt its voluntary
rating system in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the report was timed for the onset of the busy
holiday game-buying season; overall, the industry is expected to
record about $6 billion in sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a combination of telephone interviews with parents,
visits to game retail and rental outlets and inspections of about
90 games, the report card offered word of some positive
developments for parents concerned about games that emphasize
violence and offensive themes, finding that the rating system is
generally working well.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings appeared on virtually all the video and computer game
boxes examined for the report, and the researchers generally agreed
with the ratings assigned to the games -- seven categories ranging
from ``early childhood'' to content suitable for ``adults only.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the report found that the ratings have not proved
altogether successful in keeping children away from graphic
content.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the report indicated that too few parents know
about or use the ratings. A national telephone survey of 529
parents conducted this summer by the National Institute on Media
and the Family found that only about 40 percent routinely checked a
game's rating when making a purchase. Another problem, the group
found, is that few retailers have policies in place to discourage
children from buying games rated for the older crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the report charged that a small group of game makers
and distributors is marketing games to a younger-than-appropriate
age group. ``We are not claiming it's widespread, but there are
examples and we are asking the industry to take a look at it,''
said David Walsh, president of the National Institute on Media and
the Family.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited several examples of inappropriate marketing,
among them an advertisement for a game called Resident Evil 2 in
the magazine Sports Illustrated for Kids. The game, made by Capcom
Entertainment, carries an ``M'' rating, indicating it is
appropriate for those age 17 and above.
</P>
<P>
   But the advertisement in Sports Illustrated for Kids was for a
toned-down version of the game made by a different company, Tiger
Electronics Ltd., and adapted for hand-held units. This version
carries a ``T,'' rating, meaning it is suitable for those 13 and
older, said Sandra M. Schneider, vice president of Tiger
Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated for Kids, meanwhile, is aimed at 8- to
14-year-olds, and about half of its readership is older than 12,
said Tracey Vogt, a spokeswoman for the company. Magazine officials
saw little that was inappropriate in the advertisement itself and
felt the product was targeted at a good portion of the
publication's readership.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh found those arguments unconvincing, suggesting that many
parents would not distinguish between the various versions of the
game. He also said he is concerned that the advertisement could
whet the appetite of the magazine's younger readers for the more
violent version of the game. ``They use products that would gain
the attention of kids to sell products that are not supposed to be
sold to kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But industry representatives insist that matters are not as
simple as presented in the study, and that game marketing is
generally appropriately targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Lowenstein, president of the Interactive Digital
Software Association, which represents 41 major game publishers,
said that it is impossible for publishers ``to create an airtight
system'' to prevent children from ever being exposed to advertising
for games aimed at an older market.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein stressed that he is not defending some of the
advertisements in the industry, which prominently highlight the
goriest aspects of violent games. Nonetheless, he says there are
other brakes on children's access to arguably inappropriate
material that the report card fails to consider.
</P>
<P>
   One is that increasingly, the players themselves are older, and
that computer games are now often played by adults, not just young
boys. Another, he said, is that buyers of the items are usually
adults, because few children have the $50 or so available to buy
the games.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh remains skeptical and says it is children, in many cases,
who buy the games. His assessment of this year's report is that it
contains both good news and bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been progress in a lot of areas, and there are some
concerns in others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   National Institute on Media and the Family Computer Game Report
Card: http://www.mediaandthefamily.org/
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Pamela Mendels, a Manhattan-based writer, covers education,
government, censorship and civil rights issues for CyberTimes.)
</P>
