<HEADER>
A0048 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AU-PAIR-LIFEBEAT-NYTS     12-29 1534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AU-PAIR-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO OUR FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
  By TODD PITOCK 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, as the infamous British nanny case made front-page
news, my wife and I began looking for childcare. Despite the
negative press, choosing an au pair seemed like the best option for
our family. If nothing else, a year of living with a stranger would
be an adventure for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   What we found, adventure aside, was that much could be learned
from our relationship with our au pair. I came to this conclusion
one Saturday when, a little past noon, my 2-year-old son threw a
major fit. He lay on the floor, outraged and bereft, his face
hidden in his arms. I knelt beside him and offered lunch, milk and
the $23 I had in my pocket. ``You know, Jeremy,'' I sighed, ``this
isn't what I had in mind for our afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a voice from above called out to me: ``Offer him a
cheese stick!''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, I thought, heavenly advice. Soon, there was peace in our
house.
</P>
<P>
   The voice belonged to our German caregiver, Kathrin (Ka-treen).
It was simultaneously disconcerting and reassuring to think that in
eight months, she'd acquired a better sense of how to handle
Jeremy's tantrums than I had.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Toni, was in graduate school when Jeremy was born, and
we found ourselves in a common predicament over childcare. Our
4-year-old daughter, Elyse, was in preschool Monday through Friday,
but we needed a full day's supervision for Jeremy and occasional
evenings for both kids. Cost was an issue, as was flexibility. Our
schedules shifted according to my unpredictable project deadlines
and the demands of Toni's academic workload.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, we wanted nurturing, consistent, one-on-one care
for Jeremy, in our house, from a caregiver whom we could train and
supervise. In our experience with daycare, which we'd used
part-time for a few months, the staff turnover rate was high, and
we wanted Jeremy to have more stability.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, we opted for an au pair, a young foreign woman from
one of six U.S. government-regulated agencies, who would live with
us for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Toni and I were scrupulous about finding the right person. We
chose an agency that asked detailed questions on its application
about the au pair's background and interests. We made up our own
questions, too, already knowing the answers we wanted, to make sure
the candidate was a solid match.
</P>
<P>
   Then we placed our overseas call to interview 19-year-old
Kathrin, the prospective au pair with whom we'd been matched by the
agency. In the conversation, we posed ``what if'' scenarios to test
Kathrin's responses on various childcare issues. Toni asked how
Kathrin's parents felt about her going abroad for a year. Hearing
they were worried (they were) would indicate that she came from a
nurturing family.
</P>
<P>
   As a final question, Toni inquired, ``How should children be
disciplined?'' ``According to the parents' beliefs.'' Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Kathrin's arrival, six weeks before Toni's fall
semester began, allowed us time to observe her with the kids and
gave her a chance to model our parenting style. During the first
days, we discussed expectations on both sides. Elyse was excited by
the prospect of having a ``big sister,'' and Jeremy instantly took
to our new helper.
</P>
<P>
   But the challenges were immediately apparent. The only room
available for her was the one right next to ours. Suddenly, our
personal space constricted. The house became somewhat more formal.
No more flopping in front of the TV set in my favorite ragged
pajamas. But that was implicit in the choice of having live-in
help. We all adjusted. I learned to wear a robe.
</P>
<P>
   The language barrier was greater than we'd anticipated. Toni,
who is a South African immigrant, and I had both lived in
non-English speaking countries and understood how overwhelming it
is to have words coming at you like freeway traffic, so we did our
best to speak slowly. Kathrin, determined to learn, studied her
palm-size German-English dictionary every night. Her discipline
paid off, and within weeks, she improved markedly.
</P>
<P>
   The children were the main issue. After the initial excitement
wore off, Elyse resisted the alien authority figure in ``her''
house. The result was erratic emotions, from love to hate,
sometimes within a bewildering stretch of 10 minutes. Kathrin, an
experienced daytime baby sitter but here clearly out of her depth,
was confused, irritated and unequipped. She compared Elyse with
Jeremy, generally an easygoing 16-month-old, and decided that Elyse
was ``difficult.'' When we explained that Jeremy was simply
younger, that Elyse had also been pliant at his age and was still a
happy 4-year-old, Kathrin did not look completely convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Toni and I began to hold weekly family meetings to discuss what
was working and what wasn't. Here, Elyse and Kathrin expressed
themselves gently but directly. Elyse needed to know that she could
articulate her feelings. Otherwise, they'd turn into tears of rage,
which in turn would provoke Kathrin. Given a chance to speak up,
Elyse felt her power restored.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Kathrin grew into her role. She continued to favor
Jeremy, though not at the expense of Elyse. Because Elyse was in
school, Kathrin spent more time with our son. She also came to know
him at an earlier stage of his life, learned the rhythms of his
moods as he developed, and moved in sync with them.
</P>
<P>
   Kathrin's relationship with the kids, Toni, and me was hard to
pin down. Kathrin was not quite family, but she wasn't just an
employee, either. One of the most challenging aspects of living
with Kathrin was when she was off duty. Sometimes she seemed like a
mature young woman who was nearly our contemporary; other times she
was like a teenager thrusting us into a stage of parenthood for
which we weren't ready.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of instances, such as a series of successive late
nights that had her falling down on the job, required that Kathrin
and I have a ``chat.'' Thereafter, we agreed to a midnight curfew
on workdays. We could also see that she needed more time off, and
we agreed to give her alternate weekends. It was a case of
enlightened self-interest. This way, we could ask her to put in
longer hours on days when our schedules got particularly hectic.
</P>
<P>
   Kathrin was clever and innovative when it came to playing with
the kids. I arrived home one afternoon to discover she'd turned the
entire basement into an indoor playground. An old blanket and two
cardboard boxes were transformed into a bedouin-style tent, and
Jeremy's cars and trains formed a little transport system
underneath, much to his delight. Not only did Kathrin seem to enjoy
playing with the kids, she knew how to do it at their level.
</P>
<P>
   As Kathrin's yearlong stay drew to a close, she said she had no
regrets. ``I learned a lot,'' she told me, ``But if I had total
choice, I would rather be an exchange student than an an pair.''
</P>
<P>
   That's understandable. Critics of the au pair program point this
out as its quintessential flaw. When the host family is looking for
childcare and the au pair is looking for an American adventure,
such mismatched expectations can lead to unhappy pairings.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Kathrin's departure, Toni and I decided not to apply
immediately for another au pair. We didn't want to bring someone
into the children's lives, only to replace the relationship on a
yearly basis. We also had the luxury of time. Toni had finished her
graduate studies and was pregnant again, so she would be at home.
</P>
<P>
   We talked with our children about Kathrin's leaving. We drew
maps and pictures, explaining where she would be going. Jeremy, not
quite 2 1/2, needed the preparation. When he heard the word
leaving, he reflexively offered to go along for the ride, for fear
of being left behind. This was one ride, we explained, he couldn't
go on. Although sad, he brightened somewhat when Toni reassured him
that neither she nor I would be leaving.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that Kathrin's absence was harder for Elyse, who
had overcome her early resistance and grown attached to her
caregiver. A few outbursts prompted us to discuss Kathrin's
departure, talking with Elyse about how it made her feel. Slowly,
we all adjusted to life as it was before having an au pair.
</P>
<P>
   After Kathrin left, the house assumed its former dimensions. The
robe returned to the closet, and I once again flopped, pajama-clad,
in front of Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time Toni and I missed the extra help, and we
were so far out of the baby-sitting loop that we didn't know where
to begin. Kathrin herself had been part of our life for a year,
sharing everything from dinnertime discussions to family outings.
It was only natural, then, that for a while, we all had a sense
that someone was missing.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Free-lancer Todd Pitock writes for the Washington Post,
Hemispheres and several other publications.) &LR;
</P>
