<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-29 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THEFT OF RESPECT AND DIGNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Young people know everything. Middle-aged people
suspect everything. But too many old people believe anything, and
rip-off artists know that.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they can prey so effectively on the elderly. Con
specialists know that older folks came of age in a gentler time,
before the world overflowed with grifters and scammers bent on
separating them from their money.
</P>
<P>
   Roger's mother found that out the hard way. I won't give you her
full name, because I don't want to embarrass her. I won't give you
Roger's full name, either, because then somebody could figure out
his mother's identity.
</P>
<P>
   But I offer this story as a cautionary tale of our times, both
for guys like Roger and people like his mother, too. Always
remember that trust is like love _ to be given of sparingly and
only with great care.
</P>
<P>
   Roger is a commercial real estate developer. He works all up and
down the East Coast. He grew up on a farm near Albany. His mother
is a widow in her 80s, a delightful lady and not without some
business experience of her own. But she had this coin collection
she'd put together over the years, and not long ago she was
approached by some coin dealers from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   This collection of yours is worth a fortune, they assured her.
Let us handle its sale for you, and we'll make you rich. And
Roger's mother went along with them.
</P>
<P>
   Through a long, complicated scheme, the coin dealers managed to
separate her from her collection and from a rather large sum of
money. By the time Roger found out about it, the coin dealers were
nowhere to be found. He hired private detectives to gather evidence
and turned that evidence over to federal authorities. At least one
of these con artists had a criminal record, Roger has learned _ a
little bit of background that the guy had neglected to mention to
Roger's mother.
</P>
<P>
   The feds have reassured Roger that they'll eventually get these
people, although he's struck by what seems to him to be a rather
startling lack of outrage on their part. He supposes that's because
this sort of thing is so common now.
</P>
<P>
   Fully a fifth of the population is now composed of senior
citizens, more of them than ever with a little money they've
managed to set aside, and every year fraudulent telemarketers alone
take them for as much as $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What Roger can't figure out is how people can do things like
this, especially on so enormous a scale. How can human beings prey
so heartlessly on helpless old people, he wonders? And how can so
many other supposedly decent people take it all so much in their
stride?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we're allowing to happen to ourselves,'' he said the
other day. ``People are just too busy to think about it, I suppose
... The culture has just turned itself on its head. Good has been
redefined as bad. Bad has been redefined as cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, you know, you try to ground your kids and keep yourself
between the lines. And you look at what goes on around you, and you
say, `Gosh, how many people are paying attention?' What's the world
going to be like in another 20 years?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I know,'' I said. ``I see a lot more of it than most
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really disappointing,'' Roger said. ``Years ago, the
measure of a man or woman was your integrity. That was what you
lived by and what you were known by. Now that's gone. Now it's all
what works, what feels good. And it can all be rationalized pretty
easily ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You really wonder when the wake-up call is going to be and how
people will respond.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
