<HEADLINE>
POPULAR DONOR EGG PROGRAMS RAISE SLEW OF ETHICAL QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Wanted: healthy young women with eggs and time to
spare. In exchange, you can earn thousands of dollars from
infertile couples trying to have a baby of their own.
</P>
<P>
   As more couples seek options in their quest for parenthood,
clinics across the country are competing for young women to donate
their eggs. Some large infertility clinics in New York City and New
Jersey have even engaged in bidding wars, paying as much as $5,000
to recruit willing donors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the growing interest in donor egg programs is rejuvenating
the debate surrounding assisted reproduction technologies.
Physicians also worry about turning human eggs into a commercial
commodity, and the potential for exploiting financially strapped
young women looking to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely something that we're looking at,'' said Dr.
Jeanne Linden, director of the New York Blood and Tissue Resources
Program, a which regulates the licensing of ovum donor programs in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The number of babies born from donor eggs skyrocketed from 112
in 1989 to 1,743 in 1995, the most recent year data were available
from the American Society for Reproductive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who would say donor egg is ethically on the
brink,'' said Dr. Peter Horvath, the medical director at Albany IVF
Fertility and Gynecology, which pays donors $2,000. It is one of 17
programs in New York to recruit donors and harvest eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the concern focuses on payments and the medical risks
involved to the donor eggs. Donating eggs is more complex than
donating sperm, when men are generally paid $100 for their
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like going into the Red Cross and donating blood,''
said Dr. John Balint, director of the Center for Medical Ethics at
the Albany Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   Although laws in New York forbid the sale of human tissue, it is
acceptable to compensate donors for their time and inconvenience,
Linden said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society for Reproductive Medicine's voluntary
guidelines say that egg donors ``may be reimbursed for the direct
and indirect expenses associated with their participation, and may
be compensated for their inconvenience, time, discomfort and risk
undertaken.''
</P>
<P>
   To donate eggs, a woman has to inject herself with fertility
drugs for seven to 10 days to cause the ovaries to swell. During
that time, she must have frequent blood samples and sonograms to
assess the growth and development of the follicles, or clusters of
eggs in her ovaries.
</P>
<P>
   When the eggs are ready to harvest, the donor is given
anesthetics so that a physician can insert a needle and remove the
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more of a time commitment than some people are
anticipating,'' said Paula Taggart, the ovum donor coordinator at
Albany IVF.
</P>
<P>
   Taggart is looking only for non-smoking women under the age of
32 who have medical insurance. Infertile couples aren't interested
in women who are taking anti-depressants or who have a family
history of genetic disease. Older women pose a problem because
``any women over the age of 35, the quantity and quality of eggs
start to diminish,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the clinic has approved two people to donate eggs.
Prospective donors must undergo a series of medical tests ruling
out problems such as HIV and hepatitis. Finally, only those donors
who pass a psychological screening will be put on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Most potential donors never make it past the first phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting donors is very challenging,'' Taggart said.
</P>
<P>
   There are potential complications of donating. Some women have
died from overstimulation of their ovaries. Others have had their
ovaries collapse, potentially affecting their own fertility. And
because many of the potent fertility drugs are still new, the
medical community is still uncertain of any long-term risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal for a woman to be an egg donor,'' Horvath
said. ``There are medical risks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians believe donor eggs raise too many questions for
both women who give them and the recipients, many of whom are in
their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   At Albany IVF, physicians have agreed only to use donor eggs in
women up to age 48 because of sticky questions surrounding the
artificial extension of motherhood. Some children have been born to
women in their 60s using donor eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no standards anywhere and the issue comes up, `Is it
fair for a child to be born to someone old enough to be their
grandmother?''' Balint said.
</P>
<P>
   There are also legal issues. How much information should donors
and recipients be given about one another? And what are the rights
of a child born from a donor egg to access pertinent genetic
information in the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a right or wrong about how you do
this,'' Balint said. ``There are a whole bunch of things out there
we have yet to resolve and that's what concerns me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has no doubt what advice he'd give his daughter if she
ever contemplated becoming a donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would discourage her because there are so many unknowns,''
he said. ``I don't think a well-off person with a good job would be
tempted to do this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
