A0130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     12-29 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOM FOR SIX MORE IN A CROWDED HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ballot has to be mailed by midnight Thursday. It has been
staring at me for several weeks. Now it's time.
</P>
<P>
   Casting a vote for Baseball's Hall of Fame is about the coolest
thing we get to do here in the newspaper's Toy Department. The
privilege goes to those who have been card-carrying members of the
Baseball Writers Association of America for at least 10 consecutive
seasons. Voting on Cooperstown credentials is not something I take
lightly. Sadly, I do a lot more research on this ballot than on the
one that confronts me on the first Tuesday of most Novembers.
</P>
<P>
   This year we have a lofty list of new candidates. There are
several worthy leftovers from previous seasons, but the new
eligibles ensure that there's going to be quite a crowd on the
platform in Cooperstown next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The top tier of new nominees (players who've been retired for
exactly five seasons) includes George Brett, Nolan Ryan, Robin
Yount, Carlton Fisk, and Dale Murphy. Other new names on the ballot
are Mike Boddicker, John Candelaria, Charlie Leibrandt, Frank
Tanana, and Mike Witt, but none of them are worthy of serious Hall
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   It's stunning to find five new names with such impressive
resumes. This ballot is to Hall voters what the 1983 NFL drart
(John Elway, Dan Marino, Jim Kelly, Tony Eason, Ken O'Brien, Todd
Blackledge) was to quarterback connoisseurs.
</P>
<P>
   --Brett is an automatic. Top shelf, no dust. You could tell he
was a Hall of Famer just by watching him take batting practice. In
Boston we remember him in his early days as the kid brother of a
lefty who pitched for the '67 Red Sox (Kemer Brett). George was the
goods from Day One. His flirtation with .400 in 1980 (he finished
at .390) stands as his signature season, but 3,154 hits, a lifetime
average of .305, an MVP, and his sheer competitiveness make him a
Hall of Famer. He is the only player in big league history with
3,000 hits, 300 homers, 600 doubles, 100 triples, and 200 stolen
bases.
</P>
<P>
   --Ryan. Not as easy as it looks. His lifetime winning percentage
(.523) is cheesy, and his only championship came when he was an
erratic kid with the 1969 Mets. Early in his career, Ryan was
something of a freak show, always capable of a no-hitter but an
inconsistent winner. He shed the Dominique Wilkins image in his
golden years and sails into the Hall on the strength of 5,714
strikeouts, 324 wins, and seven no-hitters (the last one coming
when he was 44). We may never see another 45-year-old power
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   --Yount. He gets this vote thanks to 3,142 hits, two MVP awards,
and his mastery of two of the sport's toughest positions (shortstop
and center field), but he was never feared like Tony Oliva, Orlando
Cepeda, or Jim Rice _ none of whom are in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   --Fisk. This is torture. New Hampshire's fortunate son caught
more games and hit more homers than any catcher in history. The
problem is, Fisk's numbers are only marginally better than Gary
Carter's and it seems no one wants Carter in Cooperstown. Carter
won three Gold Gloves to Fisk's one, and won a World Series, which
Fisk did not. Here, we can only fall back on the time-tested remark
by Supreme Court Justice Potter Stewart regarding pornography: ``I
know it when I see it.'' So it goes with Fisk. He always looked
like a Hall of Famer and his 1975 homer helped rescue baseball from
oblivion. Catcher Carlton gets the vote, and here's hoping he opts
for a Red Sox cap on his plaque.
</P>
<P>
   --Murphy. No. See Carter explanation above. He's a two-time MVP
who hit 398 homers. He's unfairly penalized for playing on bad
teams, but his lifetime average of .265 is too low for a Hall of
Fame outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Players must get at least 5 percent of the overall vote to stay
on the ballot, and they stay on for 15 years before their names are
turned over to the Veterans Committee. A candidate must be named on
75 percent of the ballots cast to be inducted into the Hall. Of the
holdover candidates from last year's ballot, the best are Rice and
Luis Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   I vote for Rice, but it's not easy. A ballplayer's cooperation
with the media should have no bearing on one's ballot, and I often
think I vote for Rice just to make sure I'm not accused of letting
his surliness color my vote. His candidacy is marginal, but he
should be getting more votes than he's been getting. Rice hit .298
with 382 homers in 16 seasons, but those of us who saw him every
day know that he was a dominant slugger of his time. This cannot be
said of Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   This is Tiant's 12th year on the ballot and he's not going to
make it, even though he derserves it. Put his numbers up against
Catfish Hunter and Don Drysdale and you see that Luis deserves to
join them in Cooperstown. Tiant was also a better big-game pitcher
than Jim Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. My ballot is mailed with votes for six players (10 is
the maximum allowed). And there is no vote for wonderful players
like Murphy, Carter, Bert Blyleven, Tony Perez, Steve Garvey, Dave
Parker, Bruce Sutter, Dwight Evans, Keith Hernandez, Tommy John,
Jim Kaat, Mickey Lolich, Minnie Minoso, and Tanana. Let the
arguments begin.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
