<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-FLYNT-2TAKES-BO     12-29 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-FLYNT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGUE PORN KING FLYNT PLAYS DIRTY IN DC 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Ever since his $1 million bounty on
philandering pols unearthed career-ending dirt on House
Speaker-elect Robert Livingston, Larry Flynt has been at ground
zero of Washington's toxic sex scandal. Every columnist with 80
lines to fill invokes his name. The New York Times editorializes
against his ``sleaze empire.'' Ollie North depicts Democrats as the
party of Larry Flynt. Author Gay Talese calls him ``a great truth
seeker.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Flynt Publications empire _ in a black foreboding
building guarded by a statue of John Wayne on horseback _ the phone
lines are buzzing. There are more tips about more politicians who
allegedly sweated up the sheets at the no-tell motel.
</P>
<P>
   Just down the hallway on the 10th floor, the 56-year-old Flynt
presides over this chaos in his garishly appointed office. (The
decor is Fellini-meets-Caesar's Palace. Flynt spent about $2
million to decorate his executive offices with all manner of
statuary and baubles.) Chain-smoking cigars, bedecked in shiny
jewelry, and surrounded by copies of his gynecologically graphic
Hustler magazine, Flynt looks more like a Mafia don than a media
dean. Requiring a wheelchair since he was shot 20 years ago during
a Georgia obscenity trial, his voice is slowed and slurred, and an
occasional twinge ripples through his body.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt is no stranger to the limelight, having been lionized in
Milos Forman's acclaimed 1996 film ``The People Vs. Larry Flynt.''
But he is savoring center stage in Monicagate. Forget about perjury
or obstruction of justice, he growls. This scandal ``still gets
back to the basic issue of sex.'' And if sex is the battlefield,
the pornographer is armed. In addition to Livingston, Flynt says
his investigators have come up with the goods on about a dozen sex
sinners in Washington, all but one of them Republican. And he's
getting ready to dish the dirt on what he sees as Bill Clinton's
hypocritical tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   What a perversely fitting close to a year in which the
foundations of government are threatened by the exchange of bodily
fluids, when semen stains and cigar sex antics make headlines, and
when the independent counsel's report reads like the Penthouse
letters page. Amid the slime of our civic life, the most feared
journalist in America is not Bob Woodward, not Michael Isikoff, not
even Matt Drudge. It is a jailbird porn king one month away from
the start of another obscenity trial for peddling prurience in his
Cincinnati Hustler store.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of ironies about the whole political
situation, not the least of which is that Larry Flynt is the man
right now that everyone is looking to for news of their political
leaders,'' says his longtime friend and attorney, Alan Isaacman.
``It's absolutely amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Flynt seems to harbor few delusions of grandeur.
People call him ``just a `smut peddler,' '' he says, a smile
playing at his lips. ``But I demand that they call me `Mister smut
peddler' because I've earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smut is my vocation,'' he brags. ``Politics is my hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My reason for getting involved was that I saw the polls
showing a majority of the people were against impeachment,'' says
Flynt. ``There was a lot of apathy. I ran that ad in The Washington
Post because I wanted to expose the hypocrisy that existed in
Washington.'' (It's not that he's squeamish about the Lewinsky
episode. In a recent issue, Hustler published a raunchy photo
spread showing how presidential DNA could have ended up on the blue
dress.)
</P>
<P>
   So on Oct. 4, at a cost of $85,000 for a full-page Post ad,
Flynt offered up to $1 million ``if you can provide documentary
evidence of illicit sexual relations with a Congressman, Senator or
member of the executive or judiciary branches.'' The more than
2,000 responses were ultimately whittled down to about a dozen by
Flynt's investigative reporters and a mysterious firm that he says
is staffed by former FBI and CIA operatives.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was the first to fall, but Flynt says the
``investigations are all ongoing and I'd say a dozen (cases) look
very good.'' They include, by his count, one Democrat , one
high-ranking Republican government official, one Republican
senator. The balance are GOP House members.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Livingston sort of upstaged us,'' by resigning before
Hustler could publish, Flynt is rethinking his ``outing'' strategy.
Because the magazine's lead time is several months, his options
include posting the names on his Internet site, publishing a
special issue, and maybe even calling a press conference to
identify some of the offenders. ``I think it's important to get out
what we've got prior to the Senate making its decision,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Flynt has posted this kind of bounty.
In the 1970s when Democratic Congressman Wayne Hayes was fooling
around with his staffer, Elizabeth Ray, and Democratic House Ways
and Means chairman Wilbur Mills was engaged in escapades with
stripper Fanne Foxe, he offered $25,000 for evidence of similar
follies _ with minimal results.
</P>
<P>
   He even tried his hand at elective politics. Running as a
Republican because ``I was wealthy, white, pornographic, and I've
been shot because of what I believed in,'' he launched a whimsical
1984 presidential bid based on a platform of eliminating venereal
disease and sexual ignorance. It ended when he went to prison for
failing to reveal the source of a tape he'd acquired that became a
central element of the John DeLorean drug case.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt makes no secret of his political loyalties. ``I love
Clinton,'' he says. ``I voted for him in '92. I voted for him in
'96. Sure the guy had an affair and he lied about it. . . . But how
much punishment should he receive?'' Of Lewinsky, he says
dismissively, ``she's a snitch,'' not bothering to ponder the irony
of the snitches who've responded to his reward.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt's opinion of independent counsel Kenneth Starr was summed
up in a letter he wrote to Starr after the release of the Starr
report. ``You have broken historic ground in disseminating
pornographic materials to a broader and more diverse community of
Americans,'' he wrote. ``Given your exemplary work, I would like to
enter into negotiations with you regarding full-time employment for
Hustler magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Burress, president of the Cincinnati-based Citizens for
Community Values, which is battling Flynt over his Hustler store,
thinks the pornographer is harming himself with his current
crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that filth and dirt (and) adultery have not
been accepted by this nation yet,'' says Burress. ``Larry Flynt is
doing more to hurt his cause than help his cause.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
