A0135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-29 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYE-BYE BUGBEARS, YOU'RE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's that stock-taking, resolution-making time of year again, a
good moment for the grammatically inclined to catch up on some
long-running usage disputes. Every reader, of course, has a
collection of language bugbears (much nicer animals than those
yappy pet peeves, but still, they can drain your mental energy);
these few, plucked from the year's mail, have been among the most
contentious. Here's how things stand as the new year approaches.
</P>
<P>
   --Healthy skepticism. Eat a healthful diet and you'll be
healthy, we were taught, and several readers _ most recently
Dorothy Osborn of Wenham and Andy Malkasian of Billerica _ have
complained about the increasing use of healthy for healthful. But
as my favorite usage gurus note (and the Oxford English Dictionary
citations show), healthy has also meant ``conducive to health'' for
more than 400 years; the distinction wasn't invented till 1811,
says Merriam-Webster's usage guide. If you observe it, ``you are
absolutely correct, and in the minority. If you ignore the
distinction you are absolutely correct, and in the majority.'' So
cross that problem off your list, and here's to your health!
</P>
<P>
   --Hopefully, resignedly. The use of hopefully as a ``sentence
adverb'' _ ``Hopefully, the hurricane will go out to sea'' _ has
inflamed opposition since it spread in the '60s, but it continues
to make headway, despite the feelings of correspondents like Edward
Carbonaro of Franconia, N.H. Similar sentence adverbs
(``Mercifully, he felt no pain'') are not strictly analogous to
hopefully, the critics object, but subtle matters of parsing can't
stop a crowd determined to have its way with a word. And even those
of us brought up to shun hopefully can admit its usefulness;
William Safire, the New York Times word man, defended it nearly two
decades ago. The new Oxford University Press usage guide calls
hopefully a ``skunked'' word _ one tainted by controversy _ but its
bad odor is fading fast, especially among the young. Regrettably or
not, hopefully will be with us for a while.
</P>
<P>
   --Growing pains. Some readers are alarmed by the spread of the
transitive grow beyond its agricultural domain. Growing corn and
tomatoes is all very well, say Alan Rechel of Belmont and Tom
Halsted of Manchester, but when did growing a business and growing
the economy become part of the language? I shared their pain when I
first saw grow used this way (in Inc. magazine, 20 years ago), but
I haven't found any good arguments against it, aside from the taint
of jargon _ and that will fade with time and use. After all, if you
can grow a beard or a crystal, why not a business? In fact, this
sense existed long ago, according to the OED, which gives an
example (here modernized) from 1481: ``When David had reigned seven
years in Hebron, he grew and amended much this city.'' So let's
look on the bright side: We're not gaining a neologism, we're
reclaiming a bit of our linguistic heritage.
</P>
<P>
   --Begging to differ. Readers who know what beg the question
really means _ to argue in a way that assumes the very thing in
dispute _ are an articulate but tiny minority. Most people now use
it to mean ``pose the question,'' and since the language of formal
logic is not widely used, there's nothing to slow the
transformation. But if you'd rather not annoy those few informed
readers or listeners, be careful with beg the question. You're
about as likely to win the lottery as to find yourself using it
correctly.
</P>
<P>
   --Pronounced dead. Two classic pronunciation battles seem all
but decided, and as usual, the majority rules. Short-lived _ which
Jim Daley of Colchester, Vt., Dana Whittemore of Wakefield, and I
pronounce to rhyme with strived _ is more and more often rhymed
with sieved. The argument for the long-i short-lived is that the
word is formed from the noun life, not the verb live, but our
fellow citizens seem immune to our reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   --Then there's forte, one's specialty or strength; the purist
side has argued for making it one syllable, like the French word
it's based on, not two syllables like the Italian adverb forte.
Problem is, the French word is not forte but fort, with a silent t.
And if we've already changed the spelling and pronunciation, why
stick at syllabification? I'll stick with FORT, one syllable, if
forced to say the word, but Merriam-Webster's countenances all
options: ``Since there is no etymologically respectable
pronunciation available for this word, we might as well select one
that feels natural.'' And at the moment, for-tay seems to be the
people's choice.
</P>
<P>
   And now, a proposed resolution. For 1999, let's abandon the old,
familiar usage topics _ teach your bugbears to sit! and stay! _ and
come up with a fresh list of issues. To the handful above, after
decades of disputation, it's time to say hail and farewell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
