 ART ADV.: A photo with BRAILLE-PRESS is being transmitted to NYT
Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WRGRACE-TOXIC (Woburn, Mass.) _ Until the early 1970s, W.R.
Grace dumped toxics into a ditch, never imagining they might reach
public water supplies. That carelessness cast W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. as a
villain in one of the most famous environmental trials in US
history. By Scott Allen. 1750 words. (a and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   WRGRACE-TRUTH (Undated) -- A comparison of the movie and what
really happened in the Woburn case. By Scott Allen. 750 words. (a
and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   WHISTLEBLOWER-SUES (Fort Worth, Texas) _ George Robertson has
filed a new suit in an attempt to claim part of the money he says
the government recovered from his tip that Bell Helicopter padded
its defense contract bills. By Curtis Wilkie. 1225 words.
</P>
<P>
   WIDEMAN-CASE (Pittsburgh) _ Robert Wideman is in prison,
convicted of murdering a fellow thief 23 years ago. Now he has won
a new trial by arguing that the victim died from medical
incompetence, a claim that has enraged the runner's family and
inflamed public opinion. By Mitchell Zuckoff. 1450 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
