<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THIS VIEW, WHY GO ANYWHERE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STAN GROSSFELD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ I'm going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried to redeem my frequent-flier miles but the islands I'm
interested in are booked until summer. I've carried the baby on the
shuttle and seen the businessman glare at us as though we were
personally siphoning off their 401(k)s. Were they born at age 42
with cell phones embedded in their palms?
</P>
<P>
   I have made my bed in Quincy and I'm lying in it looking out the
window, over the tops of houses. There, seven miles away out to sea
is the blinking beacon that is the last manned lighthouse in
America. Boston Light.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Garland had it right when she recited that famous phrase,
``There's no place like home.'' Every morning I open one eye, watch
the sunrise, and go back to sleep. It is a beautiful thing. Boston
Light is an exclamation point in the sea and the last marker before
the Old World. It never shuts off and it never disappoints.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, Boston Light is serenaded by incoming aircraft
to Logan. The jets are all lined up one minute apart. Passengers
are being told to shut off their electronic devices and return
their seats to the upright, knees-into-the-guy-in-front-of-you
position. When the plane lands, everyone will jump up, elbows out,
and maneuver into the aisle in a scene reminiscent of the
long-forgotten National Basketball Association. And then they will
wait until they are older than John Glenn. Then some poor soul's
luggage will wind up in Bosnia and not Boston and the cab driver
will have his seat set way back and his two-way radio set on Voice
of Pakistan. It won't be me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the great thing about Boston Light. You can't get
there. There's no public docking, and except for four trips by the
Friends of Boston Harbor in the warm months, the general public is
shut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coast Guard wants to make this place more accesible,''
said Scott Stanton, 67th keeper of the light. The public is invited
during daylight hours. ``Kayakers come all the time,'' said
Stanton. The 76-step lighthouse with stunning views of Boston is
open, but the residence is closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like is that in 1716 they were doing the same
thing we are doing now,'' said Stanton. Unfortunately, the first
two lightkeepers drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: For all the hype about Boston Harbor and the
islands, things have been disappointing. Let's start with the
Federal courthouse. Criminals and lawyers are the last three groups
that deserve a room with a view. Why can't we appreciate a good
thing? Harborlights was a great place to go to a waterfront
concert; it was the Hub's answer to the Sydney Opera House. So they
forced it to move.
</P>
<P>
   Spectacle Island was supposed to be a landscaped park years ago,
but grass grows there as well as hair grows on Opie's head. Then
you have Moon Island, the gateway to Long Island and the first
island in the Boston Harbor Island chain accessible by car. What's
there? A police firing range, where every day sounds like Chinese
New Year. Take your best shot.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Things, of course, could be worse. My esteemed colleague and
friend Charles Sennott recently journeyed to Baghdad to cover
Desert Fox. He brought his own sterilized needle because the Iraqis
were drawing blood at the border. I'm not going there.
</P>
<P>
   Nor am I going to those fancy resorts in Bermuda. I went there
at this time one year to relax and learn how to play golf. After
swinging as if I was trying to hit home runs for two hours, I
started having back spasms and started turning blue.
</P>
<P>
   As I doubled over in pain, my wife called for a doctor. But
instead, a man with a walkie talkie came running into the room. I
couldn't straighten up to see his face but I could read his tag.
``Loss prevention,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Light is majestic. Commissioned by Washington and
destined to be manned forever, thanks to Senator Edward Kennedy, it
brings light in the darkness and is reportedly haunted by spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to turn on the light and I saw someone up in the
tower,'' said Stanton, who along with an assistant lives on the
island. ``So I went back into the house and there was my partner
sitting on the couch. I said, `Weren't you up in the tower?' and he
said `No.' Now I'm not saying it was a ghost, but there was nobody
else on that island.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Light is also, for our young readers, the all-time
greatest backdrop to go ``parking.''
</P>
<P>
   (Go to Hull and travel east until you get to the cemetery and
then drive up to the upper level just below Fort Revere. From
there, you can see a sweeping view of the coastline. Boston Light
and Graves Light line up perfectly amid splashing whites and dark
sea blues. But don't look for me there. I'm going nowhere.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
