<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0143 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-SUES-BO     12-29 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-SUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SETBACKS, `WHISTLE-BLOWER' CONTINUES LONELY TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Other than $25,000 in expenses and a series
of setbacks in court, George Robertson has little to show for his
long, lonely struggle against two giants, his former employer, Bell
Helicopter, and the US government.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson is persistent. Last month, acting as his own
lawyer, the self-styled whistle-blower filed a new lawsuit in an
attempt to claim part of the money he says the government recovered
as a result of his tip that Bell padded its bills on defense
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman handling the case for Bell, a division of
Providence-based Textron Inc., did not return a telephone call
requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's one-man campaign against Bell, one of the largest
employers in metropolitan Tarrant County, and the Defense
Department bureaucracy is a case study in the world of
whistle-blowers, a term used for renegade employees who report
wrongdoing they perceive in their workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, 55, has instituted several unsuccessful actions since
he was fired by Bell nearly seven years ago. ``Sometimes my wife
calls me obsessed,'' he said. ``But I keep doing it because I don't
have any choice, because I don't have any job.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been unable to find another position because Bell
blacklisted him in the defense industry. He has been sustained over
the years, he said, by a family inheritance and a savings account
he built up through an overseas job with another defense
contractor. His wife has taken a part-time job, and Robertson said
he has been reduced to working at a car wash several days a week.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he won an $85,000 judgment against Bell only to have
the jury verdict overturned by a federal judge three months later.
He was chastised by another federal judge for filing ``frivolous''
litigation and had subsequent suits thrown out of court. Both Bell
and the Department of Defense have rebuffed his efforts to obtain
documents relevant to the case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Robertson pushes on.
</P>
<P>
   He had been employed by Bell for six years as a contractor
administrator involved in a multimillion-dollar program to upgrade
aging Army helicopters when he lost his job on Valentine's Day
1992. Robertson contends he was dismissed because he warned a
civilian Army contracting officer not to agree to Bell's demand for
more than $1 million in cost overruns on the helicopter project. He
said Bell used an unreliable accounting system to falsify charges.
</P>
<P>
   Bell contended, at the time, that Robertson was a victim of
economic cutbacks. In a letter of recommendation, a Bell vice
president called him ``a very dependable employee,'' and added,
``through no fault of his own, George has been caught in the middle
of a downsizing of our entire organization.'' Later, when Robertson
challenged the move, the company said he had been laid off because
his job performance ratings were low.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said that in late 1990, he first advised an Army
representative to disregard $1.6 million in bills from Bell because
there was not proper verification for the work in the accounting
system. When a supervisor, Alvin Leavell, instructed Robertson to
write a letter demanding payment from the Army, Robertson said, he
refused.
</P>
<P>
   He said Leavell also became skeptical about the billing and was
soon transferred to another department. ``Leavell told me they
would never fire him because he was black, but he warned me, `Watch
your back,' '' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   After he was fired, Robertson said he had difficulty finding an
attorney to represent him. ``A lot of lawyers said, `We're not
going against Bell because nobody ever wins against them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He finally found an attorney who handled the case on a
contingency-fee basis and sued Bell. After a five-day trial in
April 1993, a jury awarded Robertson $85,000. His base salary had
been $52,500 a year, he said, and fringe benefits pushed it to
$80,000.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that judicial experts say is uncommon but within the
rule of law, US District Judge Eldon Mahon threw out the verdict,
saying the ``jury's findings were clearly based solely on prejudice
or speculation and not on the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson still is indignant and says that Mahon distorted his
position. ``I wanted to appeal, but I couldn't find a lawyer
willing to say the judge lied,'' he said in an interview at his
home in a middle-class Fort Worth subdivision. So Robertson
appealed, himself, without success at several levels.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Robertson filed a separate suit against Bell on
behalf of the United States, accusing the company of overcharging
the government in connection with the helicopter maintenance work.
The case was quickly pitched out by US District Judge John McBryde
of Fort Worth, who rebuked Robertson in open court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's tragic that a company can be put to the expense
Bell has been put to and the taxpayers can be caused to incur as
much as the taxpayers have incurred because of the conduct of Mr.
Robertson in this case,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   (In September, in an unrelated decision, a panel of federal
judges sanctioned McBryde for ``intemperate, abusive, and
intimidating'' court behavior and barred him from receiving new
cases for up to a year.)
</P>
<P>
   Falling back on the Freedom of Information Act, Robertson
obtained several interesting documents from the Defense Department.
One was a letter, dated March 29, 1994, from the Army to Bell
offices in Fort Worth informing the company: ``You are indebted to
the United States government in the amount of $769,006 . . . for
unsubstantiated charges to the Army Helicopter Improvement
Program.''
</P>
<P>
   Another batch of material included minutes from a meeting of
Defense Department officials. The document took note of a Justice
Department determination in the Bell case: ``If any of Robertson's
allegations result in administrative settlement, Robertson is
entitled to . . . share.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he is convinced the Defense Department moved
against Bell because of his reports. He learned, through another
Freedom of Information filing, that the Defense Department
eventually settled with Bell for $125,000. Although his suit on
behalf of the government was dismissed, Robertson believes he is
entitled to a percentage of the money recovered by the Defense
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the department rejected him flatly. Moreover,
wrote Ellie G. Bomar, assistant counsel for the Defense Logistic
Agency in Dallas, ``I do not believe any further discussions
between us would be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson refused to take no for an answer. He has now made the
United States a defendant in a federal court complaint in which he
is asking for $31,250.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong,'' he said of his treatment at the hands of Bell
and the bureaucracy. ``The government won't do anything. You can't
get anywhere; it's just unbelievable. But I'm still working on
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
