<HEADER>
A0150 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-29 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUST ME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spectacle of the National Basketball Association on the
verge of canceling a season over its inability to share out $2
billion among 29 owners and 400 players is disgusting. The deadline
is said to be Jan. 7. If negotiations fail, it will be the first
time an entire sports major league season has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   It will be on the owner's heads.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the players are exceedingly well paid. The issues are
complex. The owners are asking for a major overhaul of the system.
</P>
<P>
   But they refuse to open their books.
</P>
<P>
   Sports page reporters have been carrying the story, and well.
They are in close contact with Patrick Ewing, New York Knicks
superstar from Cambridge, who has risen to the presidency of the
players' union; Commissioner David Stern; and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The aspect that lifts the story out of the sports pages is the
league's negoiating stance. The owners want to roll back players'
share of revenues to 53 percent from the current level of roughly
57 percent and adopt rules that would apportion players' shares
quite differently from the present way.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even in the privacy of negotiations, the NBA has made no
concrete financial case for the massive rebalancing that it seeks.
Trust me, they say. We're hurting.
</P>
<P>
   Only one team in the league _ the Boston Celtics _ is publicly
owned and therefore compelled by law to disclose audited financial
statements. All the rest rely in varying degrees on privacy and
complicated relationships among related enterprises _ owned arenas,
concession business, naming rights and so on _ to mask their total
return on investment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, bargainers for the players (and
reporters who follow the issue) are reduced to making the kinds of
educated guesses with which Kreliminologists track the performance
of the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Zimbalist, a Smith College professor, an expert on
professional athletics who consults to the NBA players'
association, went through such an exercise last month. He noted
that players had received relatively detailed information from the
owners about the 1996-97 season and concluded then that possibly 4
teams in the league suffered negative cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he said, revenues had soared. Eight teams had signed
deals to build new arenas _ including all four of the 1996-97
loss-making teams. But owners shared only ``cursory and largely
meaningless'' financial data from last year's season. (The NBA
Monday failed to return a telephone call.)
</P>
<P>
   So the owners want to vote themselves a raise at the expense of
the players. And why not? Star players have been wracking up
tremendous contracts. The Chicago Bulls signed Michael Jordan for a
single year at $33 million; David Robinson collected $12.4 million
last year from the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Zimbalist calculated (conservatively, he said) that
the average NBA team showed around a $3 million profit last year,
rising to around $16.5 million by 2002 under the new TV contract.
With 14 coaches earning more than even the highest paid football
coaches in the National Football League _ and a few earning as much
a $8 million _ no wonder the owners are feeling poor.
</P>
<P>
   Or so you might think.
</P>
<P>
   It's when you look at franchise values that the magnitude of
team owners' compensation becomes clear. Expansion fees were $32.5
million in 1988; they were $128 million in 1994, Zimbalist says.
Eighty percent of the New Jersey Nets changed hands last month for
$150 million. Whatever the multiple, at those prices no owner
should be complaining about his take-home pay!
</P>
<P>
   So now one of the greatest marketing successes of the last
quarter century is in danger _ because of its owners' greed.
``Trust me,'' after all, is just another way to say, ``Nuts to
you!''
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
