<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEN-PALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO INDIA WITH LOVE: PEN PALS MEET AFTER 35 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENANDS, N.Y _ Thirty-five years ago, Marsha White was flipping
through Look magazine when she spotted the following advertisement:
``Would you like to exchange magazines with a person in another
country?''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? recalled White, who was 14 at the time. Always looking
for new things to try, she once answered an ad seeking people to
peddle Christmas cards. Later, she was even a backup go-go dancer
one night when Otis Redding played a concert in Annapolis, Md.,
near her hometown of Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   White was forever adventurous, but she never suspected the short
letter she sent 16-year-old Rajendra Sukhtankar in Poona, India,
would lead to a 35-year correspondence and _ most recently _ an
eight-day trip around the world.
</P>
<P>
   White met her long-distance pen pal for the very first time in
November when, as a 50th birthday present, her husband Charles gave
her a plane ticket. The couple live in the Albany suburb of
Menands.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of 35 years, Marsha White and Rajendra
Sukhtankar exchanged many letters. They wrote frequently at first,
focusing mostly on how vastly their cultures differed. ``What are
sweat shirts?'' he wanted to know. ``What is bowling?''
</P>
<P>
   She answered his questions and wrote about parties, dances and
boyfriends. He told her about Hinduism, his studies and his
parents' search for a suitable wife for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family was pretty conservative,'' Marsha White recalled.
``His parents were arranging a marriage for him, while I had a new
boyfriend every week. He just couldn't understand that. I was so
American.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, one or the other would speculate about whether they
would have the opportunity to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am serious when I say that we may meet some day,''
Sukhtankar wrote in a letter dated May 31, 1966. ``Strong longings
bring about miracles in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the topics in their letters gradually shifted
from school and youthful pursuits to work and family. He married,
moved to New Bombay, opened a pharmacy and had a son.
</P>
<P>
   She worked in insurance, relocated several times with her
husband and had three girls.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes months would pass without Sukhtankar and White writing
a word to each other. But then the odd Christmas or New Year's card
would arrive with updated news and photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made sure to write at least once a year,'' Marsha White
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Charles D. White turned 50 in 1992, his wife organized a
surprise birthday party and arranged for his parents and many of
his high school friends to attend. As Marsha White's 50th
approached this year _ Nov. 28 _ her husband was racking his brains
for a present that would equal the party she had thrown him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tough act to follow,'' White said of his wife, who is
famous among friends for going out of her way to make people happy.
``But then I thought of Rajendra, and I knew a trip to meet him
would be the perfect gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsha White called her pen pal in India to tell him of her
impending trip. Sukhtankar and his wife, Ejeeta, responded
immediately with a recent photo so she would recognize them at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   After months of preparation and careful purchase of gifts _
perfume, New York souvenirs and some of those sweat shirts she told
him about 30 years ago _ White left Nov. 24 for her 17-hour flight
to India. She was nervous enough to take one of the tranquilizers
the doctor had given her. But when she finally arrived and spotted
her friend in the crowd, laden with bouquets of flowers, all of
White's anxiety dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There he was, grinning ear-to-ear and waving my picture in the
air,'' White recalled. ``I was so excited. I started crying. We hit
it off right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached in New Bombay last week, Sukhtankar said meeting his pen
pal was so exciting, so moving, that he was at a loss for words to
describe the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was so wonderful,'' he said. ``Seeing her ... It was a
feeling I cannot express.''
</P>
<P>
   White spent her week taking in the sights, smells, sounds and
tastes of New Bombay. Members of Sukhtankar's family took turns
chauffeuring her from place to place. They even threw her a
birthday party, to which she wore a purple sari and had henna
decorations painted on her palms.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like the queen of India for those eight days,'' said
Charles White, who received a call from Marsha every day while she
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   It took White several days to recover from her travels, but she
is already dreaming of her next visit to India. She would like to
return in 10 years, she said, and take her husband with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experiencing the culture was wonderful,'' White said. ``They
made me feel so special. If health and money allow it, I'd love to
go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
