<HEADLINE>
BERMUDA IS A GREAT PLACE TO VISIT RIGHT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Only an hour and 50 minutes' flight away, there is this other
world. It bans billboards. It bans neon signs. And, dare I say it,
McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   The destination is Bermuda, and the speaker is Bermuda's new
minister of tourism, David Allen. Allen, who took office in
November, after a historic election that saw a new government for
the first time in 40 years. Right now, he said, ``there is a
feeling of rebirth and renewal that is positively contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   With the beginning of the new year, Allen promises that hearing
more about Bermuda and its uniqueness. ``We have a rich and vibrant
culture that spans 400 years. Visitors come back to Bermuda for the
people _ a unique amalgam of African slaves, English settlers,
native Americans, Irish, and Portuguese.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen knows what he speaks about. He's a travel writer by
profession and still maintains membership in the Society of
American Travel Writers.
</P>
<P>
   He's also quick to point out that now is a good time to visit
the island. The weather is springlike, in the low 70s; and there's
plenty to do, from golf, tennis, and walking to cultural
activities. It's a place to relax or have an active vacation, and
there are some great travel packages starting at $389 that include
air fare accommodations and some extras.
</P>
<P>
   Bermuda recently was cited as one of the Top 10 Islands in the
world by Conde Nast Traveler in the magazine's 11th annual readers'
choice awards poll, and in September, Travel &AMP; Leisure magazine
named Bermuda the ``Best Island'' in the Caribbean, Bermuda and
Bahamas category.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is time to take a new look at Bermuda. For more
information, call 800-BERMUDA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Winter: 1775
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winter. What was it like in Williamsburg, Va., In 1775? From
Jan. 4 to March 13, visitors to Colonial Williamsburg can discover
what it was like to live during those times. While daily life in
the Virginia capital appeared normal, beneath the surface sprouted
the seeds of unrest that would soon bear the fruit of revolution.
Visitors will meet with tradespeople and hear of arms stockpiling
and concerns about sources of materials. At the governor's home,
concerns are expressed about conflicts between the royal
authorities and colonists. And at the Tenant House, visitors meet
Rachel Whitaker, who is bedridden with the flu and hears the local
gossip from friends. For more information, call 800-HISTORY.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A note of caution
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airplane travelers should be wary of taking the hormone
melatonin too often for jet lag, according the to the Travel
Medicine Service at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston.
Available over the counter in drugstores as a food supplement,
melatonin has become a popular pill for combating sleepiness,
fatigue, and decreased mental alertness resulting from jet lag.
``Research indicates that melatonin is effective for short-term
treatment of jet lag, but we don't know yet whether long-term use
is safe,'' said Dr. Clifford Dacson, a Baylor physician. Baylor
recommends seeing your doctor for recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seniors' deal
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``49 and Holding'' package at the Orlando-area Holiday Inn
Hotel &AMP; Suites Main Gate East is being extended for the year 1999.
The package for guests 50 and older offers a room rate of $49 a
night along with a number of amenities. Seniors traveling with
grandchildren also will find that the kids stay and eat free, and
there is a state-licensed Camp Holiday program on the premises for
children 3-12. For information, call 800-FON-KIDS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Take-off' package
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A good deal for those heading to Logan International Airport is
the Hilton Boston Back Bay hotel's Sleep/Park/Fly package at $205.
The package offers a room for two, early check in, seven days'
parking in the hotel's on-site garage, a $30 airport taxi credit, a
discount on dinner at Boodles and the shops at the Prudential, and
more. The hotel, across from the Prudential Center, just opened 66
new Executive King rooms, each with wall-to-wall windows or a
balcony. The hotel also offers other packages from $139 a night.
For information, call 800-874-0663.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seal watch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every March, some 250,000 harp seals enter Canada's Gulf of St.
Lawrence to bear their young on the vast floating ice floes just
west of the Magdalen Islands. In 1987, Canada announced a ban on
the commercial hunting of the seals, and now the International Fund
for Animal Welfare, along with Natural Habitat Adventures, is
creating a tourist industry to boost the local economy and ensure
that there is never a need to reinstate the hunt. The tours, which
offer an up-close encounter with the seal pups, are only offered
for three weeks of the year between Feb. 28 and March 20. The five-
or six-day tours begin at $1,795 and include a helicopter flight to
the seal herds, guide services, hotel accommodations, and air fare
between Halifax and the Magdalen Islands. For information, call
Natural Habitat Adventures in Colorado at 800-543-8917.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Down under deal
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may be winter here, but its summer down under. In Australia's
Queensland, where the Great Barrier Reef is found, the combination
of good exchange rates and market competition have created some of
the best values in years for Americans. ``If you've ever thought
about taking a snowbird vacation to Australia, this is the year to
act,'' said Jonathon Day, regional director for the Queenslands
Travel &AMP; Tourism Corp. ``This season more than ever, the
extended-stay vacation is truly a buyer's market.'' Beginning Jan.
17, a month's stay begins at $2,749, including air fare from the
West Coast, accommodations, and more. Call 800-DOWNUNDER for a free
Australia Travel Planning Kit, or to speak with an Australian
travel counselor, call 805-775-2000, or visit www.qttc.com.au.
</P>
