<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO ROCKED BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPNTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The musician was besieged by admirers. Some wanted an autograph,
others hoped to touch him, and still others sought the ultimate
trophy: a lock of his jet-black hair. Meanwhile, a massive crowd
was cheering and screaming, waiting for his concert to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis ``the King'' Presley in Las Vegas? No, Johann ``the Waltz
King'' Strauss in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   As we head into 1999 _ the year in which Vienna will mark the
centennial of Strauss's death with many special events _ let's look
back at the Waltz King's memorable visit to Boston in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss, who had a fanatical following in America, was made an
offer he couldn't refuse: $100,000 _ the most ever paid a musician
at the time _ plus all travel expenses for himself, his wife, and
his servants, to conduct at a celebration called the World Peace
Jubilee. The event was trumpeted as ``the biggest concert of all
time in the biggest hall in the world, with the largest orchestra
and largest choir.'' Quite an inducement, but Strauss had the
jitters nonetheless. ``What if your Indians massacre me?'' he asked
the organizer, a flamboyant Irish-born entrepreneur named Patrick
Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   A huge hall had been built, with a platform for 20,000
performers and an auditorium holding more than 100,000 listeners.
The site was in St. James Park, where the Copley Plaza hotel now
stands. There were so many orchestras and choirs that 100 assistant
conductors were needed. The star, who had been improbably nicknamed
Electric Strauss for the occasion, described it this way: ``Imagine
my situation, in front of one hundred thousand wildly enthusiastic
Americans. There I stood on the highest platform. . . . Suddenly
there is a cannon shot _ a subtle hint for us twenty thousand to
begin `The Blue Danube.' I give a sign. . . . And now there begins
a terrific racket which I won't forget for as long as I live.''
</P>
<P>
   The concert was a huge success, as were three smaller ones
Strauss conducted in New York a few days afterward. Everyone was
thrilled, but perhaps none more so than the people who bought those
snippets of the Waltz King's hair. Good thing they didn't know that
his valet, Stephan, had clipped them from a black Newfoundland dog
and sold them as the real thing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of the ``Blue Danube'': Grand Circle Travel, which
specializes in vacations for those 50 and over, offers a 12-day
``Blue Danube'' cruise-tour that winds past medieval castles, Old
World villages, and the rolling vineyards of Austria, Hungary,
Slovakia, and Germany on dates from May through October. What's
more, the stylish river ships include new ones custom-built for
Grand Circle Travel. Rates start at $2,095. For more information,
call 800-955-1034 or visit www.gct.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking some more of the ``Blue Danube'': Every Dec. 31, at
the stroke of midnight, the ``Blue Danube'' is played on radios all
over Austria. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: The city of Tallin is the chief port for which
country? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: ``Floribbean'' is the name of a popular and tasty kind
of Florida cooking that mixes Latin and Southern influences.
Dishes, served at many restaurants, can range from plantains with
grilled fish to watermelon salsa. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``She travels grubbiest who travels light.'' _ Erma
Bombeck. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And the winner is: British Airways has been named the top airline
for inflight entertainment in 1998, according to the World Airline
Entertainment Association. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: White vinegar is a considerate traveling companion.
Travel Holiday reports that it works miracles removing stains from
juice, red wine, and coffee. It also improves a weak travel iron;
dampen creases with the vinegar before you press. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Happy birthday, Osiris: Birthday celebrations began with the
Egyptians, about 3000 BC. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oh say can you sing: The national anthem of Greece has 158 verses. &QL; 
 &QL; 
They're everywhere! If you think there are a lot of motorscooters
in Florence, Italy, you're right. There are a quarter-million of
them _ an average of two per family. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Honeymoon aloha: Hawaii is the most romantic honeymoon spot,
according to a survey by Modern Bride magazine. The runners-up, in
descending order, are Tahiti, Italy, France, Jamaica, St. Lucia,
Bermuda, Fiji, Greece and Bali. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: David Ames of North Weymouth takes issue with our
referring to ``Jingle Bells'' as a Christmas ditty. He writes:
``The words . . . state quite explicitly: `What fun it is to ride
and sing a sleighing song tonight.' Now, how much sleighing gets
done before Christmas, and how much after Christmas? If you live in
any of the right places, you can sing a sleighing song straight
through until March.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Estonia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
