<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SHOULDN'T PIN THEIR HOPES ON BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Earl Weaver used to have an expression about
injured players. When you asked about one, he'd always say the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with the living,'' the former Baltimore Orioles manager
would growl in that raspy voice of his that was a product of too
many Chesterfields or whatever it was he was smoking.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Pete Carroll should take the same approach with Drew
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has given the Patriots nothing but good service this
season and for all of his six years in uniform. He has played
better than any quarterback they ever had and more courageously
than most, missing only four of a possible 95 games in his career.
That is a number topped only by Green Bay's Brett Favre over the
same time span, and who is a tougher character than the Packers'
feisty quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   This season Bledsoe went over the top in the courage-under-fire
category after breaking his right index finger in two places
against the Miami Dolphins five weeks ago. He continued to play
that night, throwing the winning touchdown pass as time was running
out, and played against Buffalo and Pittsburgh, taking his team to
two more wins despite having to throw with one of the most
important fingers a quarterback has causing him increasing problems
and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Finally that finger gave out in St. Louis, five days after
doctors had inserted two pins inside it to stabilize the
deteriorating joint. Bledsoe left the field with the pins out of
place early in the game, came back with a new wrap around it, and
went a dismal 5 for 17 down the stretch when he shouldn't have been
playing at all. He has sat out since.
</P>
<P>
   But after Scott Zolak's dismal 14-for-31 passing performance
against the New York Jets on Sunday, and with a playoff game
looming with Jacksonville this weekend, there is again a hue and
cry for Bledsoe to play.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is coming both from within the organization and outside
it to reinsert him in the lineup, but Carroll should ignore that
and do what a good cornerman does when his fighter has had enough.
Do not put Bledsoe in the position of having to decide his own fate
because the fighter always will choose to fight even when there's
no fight left in him.
</P>
<P>
   In such a circumstance, the good cornerman protects his fighter
from further pain and personal humiliation and makes the decision
himself that the fight is over. For this week, at least, it should
be that way for Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Although he would never say it, Bledsoe is not yet able to play,
at least not the way he can when he's anywhere near his best. If a
healthy Zolak isn't good enough to beat the unhealthy Jaguars, so
be it. Life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe is not the answer this time and he should be protected
from his own instincts, which always will be to play rather than
watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the doctors clear me to play, I'll play,'' Bledsoe said
Monday. ``That's the same thing I've said all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe acknowledged there is external pressure mounting for him
to return but insisted, ``The pressure that's out there, none of
that stuff matters. I'm not going to play because, you know,
there's pressure on me to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the fans want me to play or the team wants me to play,
none of that stuff matters. If I play, it's because I want to play
and because I love to play the game. If I can play I'll play. It's
as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely Bledsoe will, as he has done in the past. But this time
Carroll must ignore that pressure from wherever it's coming _ even
if it's emanating from the owner's box _ and use his best judgment.
If he does, he will decide that Weaver is right and deal with the
living and that means Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   To do otherwise is to court disaster for his own regime
long-term and for his team's chances short-term in a winnable
playoff game, because Bledsoe's finger remains sore by his own
admission and is not anywhere near healed. The pins that were
moving in St. Louis won't take long to begin a new trek in
Jacksonville, and when they do, what do the Patriots do then?
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, Bledsoe has not practiced in well over a
month and would require most of the snaps this week to get ready
for the Jaguars, thereby limiting Zolak's chances to prepare
adequately even though in all likelihood he would be pressed into
action at some point.
</P>
<P>
   As Carroll conceded Monday, ``It's really unlikely he can pull
this off. The doctors have not been real favorable, and if he can't
get his preparation time, what can we expect out of him?
</P>
<P>
   ``We could ask for some miracle, but he already did pull off
maybe a couple of those. Maybe he's used them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly unlikely the guy is going to be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Come Wedneday, Carroll should downgrade Bledsoe's status from
highly unlikely to out. He should tell the fans and the
organization that there will be no puff of smoke from the chimney
Sunday. Foxborough is not Lourdes. No medical miracles will occur
there. Drew Bledsoe is out and Scott Zolak is in and that is that.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the way it should be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
