<HEADLINE>
OUT OF RHYTHM, MIAMI IS NO SOUND MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The feeling was equal parts shock, disbelief, and
rage. Maybe Jimmy Johnson could dial up Pete Carroll and empathize
about their respective maulings on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was fuming after the Dolphins' MIA performance against
the Falcons, a 38-16 pummeling in a game in which Miami had
everything to gain and Atlanta had absolutely nothing on the line.
(Sound familiar?) Not even the consolation of having a home playoff
game Saturday against Buffalo eliminated the sting and
embarrassment for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   No one really should have been surprised by the result. Atlanta
is a terrific team, is unbeaten at home, and was the logical
favorite against a Dolphins club that is 3-5 on the road. But it
was the totality of the conquest and the utter demolition of a
supposedly strong defense that had to open eyes and cause jaws to
drop.
</P>
<P>
   No team had done to Miami what Atlanta did. The Dolphins entered
the game allowing a shade fewer than 16 points a game, the best in
the NFL. The Falcons had 21 in the first eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Atlanta overwhelmed the Dolphins with big plays.
The first play from scrimmage went for 62 yards and a touchdown,
and only one Miami player, Terrell Buckley, had even a chance to
make a tackle. He seemed uninterested in doing so, setting the tone
for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' fourth play from scrimmage went for 53 yards,
leading to another touchdown. There also was a 35-yard touchdown
pass and a 36-yard touchdown run. That's four plays of 35 yards or
more, all either resulting in a touchdown or leading to a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you give up big plays like that,'' Buckley said, ``it's
tough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Miami was hit hard by the loss of Jason Taylor, its
lightning-fast lineman and second-leading sacker (nine for 37
yards) who broke his collarbone in the first quarter. But that
didn't begin to address the sheer feeling of helplessness on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had allowed as many as 30 points just once all year and
was coming off an inspired performance against the Super Bowl
champion Broncos the previous Monday. The Dolphins are 1-5 when
they allow more than 20 points; 36 was a Krakatoan explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hasn't happened to us that way since the Jacksonville
game,'' said linebacker Zach Thomas, referring to a 28-21 loss Oct.
12. ``I guess we weren't ready. But I am going to stay positive,
look at things realistically. If we had won this game and lost next
weekend, it wouldn't really matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins didn't deserve any breaks from this one, but they
got one because the Patriots were similarly inept in New Jersey.
Thus, Miami was given a home game, and that could be huge because
the Dolphins are tough at Pro Player Stadium (an oxymoron if they
play the way they did Sunday) and are building on that as well as
forgetting the finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is nice to have a home game,'' Dan Marino said
unconvincingly, ``but it would have been a whole lot nicer to have
won and go into the playoffs with some momentum. We better play
better against Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, that should not take much. Offensively, they have
perked up over the past several weeks, averaging 24 points over the
last five games. That's normally plenty when the team shows up to
play. If they can't do that Saturday, then Sunday's fiasco was a
perfect epitaph for their season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
