<SLUG> BC-FBN-FLUTIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCITEMENT BEGINS TO BUILD FOR FLUTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ He has played in bowl games, in Grey Cup games. He
has won MVP honors and been called ``magical'' as many times as
most quarterbacks who are under 6 feet and attempt to play in the
NFL have been called ``undersized.''
</P>
<P>
   But what Doug Flutie has never done is start an NFL playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon in Miami, Flutie will get that chance. To say
that he is revved up is to understate his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game,'' Flutie said with a wry grin Sunday afternoon
following a 45-33 win by the Buffalo Bills over the New Orleans
Saints at the Superdome. ``Just like a lot of other games that I've
played in.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, who was a spectator in the regular-season finale _
though not by choice _ paused, and then his face broke into a wider
grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time of year you live for as a player,'' he went
on. ``It's single elimination. Every game counts. If you lose,
you're done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills are not done, largely because of Flutie. Signed last
January at age 35, he was coming back into the NFL for some sort of
last-hurrah effort to prove that he could be more than a legend in
college, more than a multiple MVP in the wide-open Canadian
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie hardly had had time to try on a pair of shoulder pads
when the Bills signed another quarterback, Rob Johnson, to a
five-year, $25 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Johnson earning 10 times as much as Flutie _ who
agreed to a barebones contract of $250,000 laced with incentives _
but he was 11 years younger and clearly the quarterback of the
future for the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   But injuries happen in the NFL, and by the sixth game of the
year, Johnson was on the injured list with broken ribs. Flutie had
the chance for his 15 minutes of NFL fame.
</P>
<P>
   Now Flutie is still going strong, and so are the Bills, who went
from an 0-3 start to a 10-6 finish and look like they can add to
that.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the other quarterback who is talking about his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my role,'' said Johnson, who played for the first time
in three months against the Saints, throwing for three touchdowns
and running for another while Flutie stood and watched, nursing a
sore leg. ``For now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. For now, Flutie is the Bills' starting quarterback, and
he wants to savor every moment. Which is why he fidgeted most of
the day while the game was going on in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' he said. ``I've almost never been hurt. I was
hurt once in the USFL and once in the CFL. I'm just not used to not
playing. I always play. That's what's fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most frustrating thing in the world. You want to
play. That's what you do. You play football. You dress up, you
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could have played, Flutie gave one of those ``you
gotta be kidding me'' looks before coming back with a quiet
response: ``Sure. The leg hurts a little, but it's no big deal. I
played with a lot worse injuries than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie sees the playoffs as the ``second season'' that everyone
talks about.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one sense, it's not any different than in the past for
me,'' said Flutie, who has a new contract for next season that will
pay him in the neighborhood of $3 million, even though there is no
guarantee that he will be the starter. ``We're on the road in the
playoffs. The only thing that will be missing will be the cold
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   He can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're off to the next stage now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, as usual, Doug Flutie will be center stage when it counts
the most.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
