<HEADLINE>
THE HIKE IS FUN, AND SO IS THE HUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH A. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are looking for real adventure in the White Mountains,
visit one of the Appalachian Mountain Club huts.
</P>
<P>
   The huts are well-equipped, have great food and funny hosts. You
have to hike from two to five hours to get to them. The hikes are
not that hard, but not that easy. There are rocks, roots, hills,
and streams in the path. I would not recommend taking anyone under
age 6.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest hut to get to is Lonesome Lake, a 1.75-mile hike.
This hike is the best for beginners. But my personal favorite is
Mizpah Springs Hut, a 2.5-mile hike that is a little harder than
Lonesome Lake but just as fun.
</P>
<P>
   After you have finished the hike, you will probably want to go
inside and buy a hot drink, such as coffee, tea, or hot cocoa. You
will be assigned to a bunk where you will be sleeping. You will
unpack, do some exploring, and probably sit at one of the long
tables and engage in a quiet activity. While you are doing all
this, the ``croo'' (the hosts, and that's how they spell it) will
be making a huge, delicious dinner with many courses and dessert.
At 6 on the dot, a croo member will ring a huge bell and the entire
croo (five or six people) will yell, ``Dinner!''
</P>
<P>
   Soon platters of hearty food will be set in front of you. After
you have eaten, some people will go to their bunks to prepare
themselves for bed and the darkness (it seems to get dark very
early because there is no electricity up there). Others will stay
downstairs and talk, play cards or a board game, or read a book
about the hut's past. (The hut supplies these things.) On some
nights after dinner, there is ``Nature Bingo'' or another quiet
game. The winner usually gets a candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you will probably go to your bunk and get in bed.
Flashlights out is around 9 p.m. The propane lights go out then,
too.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 a.m., a croo member will come yelling through the
hallways, ``Time to get up, folks! Breakfast at 7!'' A breakfast of
oatmeal and maybe French toast or waffles or pancakes will be
served. While you are eating, the croo members will put on a funny
skit about how to fold your blankets correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you will pack up and begin your hike down the mountain.
After you have concluded your hike, you will collapse in your car
and drive home thinking about your wonderful trip in the White
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information, write to the Appalachian Mountain Club,
PO Box 298, Gorham, NH 03518, call 603-466-2727, or, on the Web,
visit www.outdoors.org)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
