<HEADLINE>
PEI LOBSTER SUPPER _ IN SUM: YUM! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're unlovely to look at but delightful to dine upon. They're
lobsters, and nowhere is a lobster feast sweeter than on pretty
Prince Edward Island.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout summer and much of spring and fall on this Atlantic
Canada province, lobster suppers are a staple in church and
community halls and in restaurants dedicated chiefly to the cause
of the crustacean. The suppers, it seems, are as much a part of the
island as its stunning red soil and endless fields in many shades
of green.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot more than lobster is involved. There are the multitude
of scrumptious side dishes, of course. But there's the knowledge
you're participating in a tradition that dates back 40 years when
the first such supper was held to raise money for rural youngsters.
And there's the air of friendliness that's ever-present.
</P>
<P>
   So come along. Tie on a plastic bib and enjoy a dinner that even
impresses New Englanders who are used to good lobster. This one's
at Fisherman's Wharf in North Rustico.
</P>
<P>
   Even before sitting down, you're impressed by the informality
and conviviality _ the laughter and the chatting. You're also
impressed by the 60-foot salad and dessert bar and by the knowledge
that the restaurant's lobster pound can hold 45,000 pounds of the
crustaceans at a time. (That's a lot, but then again island
lobstermen haul in some 20 million pounds a year.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot or cold?'' your waitress asks. She's not referring to your
disposition, though. She's merely asking how you want your lobster
served. Some diners are surprised to learn that cold is the
preferred style among islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Now's the time to accumulate some side dishes, not the least of
which are Island Blue mussels, sweet and sand-free because they're
cultivated on the sides of underwater ropes. Add to that a cup of
chowder, a tasty Prince Edward Island potato _ another product the
island is famous for _ rolls, and a frosty beverage and . . . ahhh.
</P>
<P>
   Now dig into that pound-or-more lobster, secure in the knowledge
that you're being no louder or messier than your dining companions
as you crack the claws or dip the meaty tail into melted butter.
Gourmets will relish the tomalley, or liver, but not everyone is a
gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   For those who still have room, try a slice of homemade pie or
cake or a scoop or two of ice cream to go with your coffee. Then
relax and digest while pondering the fact that hundreds and
hundreds of people are having similar meals in such places as St.
Ann's near Cavendish, St. Margaret's near Naufrage Harbour, and the
original venue, New Glasgow Lobster Suppers. The cost of the feast
at current exchange rates: about $18-$20 US.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few months before it's time for the suppers to be
held again, but to paraphrase a lyric from ``The Fantasticks'':
Deep in December, it's nice to remember the fantastic taste of a
lobster supper on Prince Edward Island.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Prince Edward Island, call 888-PEI-PLAY
(888-734-7529).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
