</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A NAME ON EMILY'S LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So it ends up that Emily Rooney thinks I'm dull, a revelation
likely to inspire two questions in anyone who knows me or has read
anything I've written _ the first being: Why waste time stating the
obvious? And the second: Who's Emily Rooney?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer to question two is, she's the highly-acclaimed
former news director at Channel 5 TV in Boston who went on to land
the prestigious post as executive producer for ABC-TV's ``World
News Tonight,'' only to leave of someone else's volition seven
months later. Now she's the host of the nightly Channel 2 show
``Greater Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   To the first question, I can only ask, me, dull? Well, I never.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about me. Let's talk about Emily Rooney talking about
me. It must have been a week ago Friday when she made this comment
on the air. I happened to miss it because I was readjusting the
shoe trees in my wingtips, something I like to do every week or so,
usually just before I fire up the old CB radio and read my own
whacky brand of open-road poetry to long haul truckers fighting off
the ravages of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   I got a tape, though, and in between Animal Kingdom reruns, I
plugged it into the VCR, and there she was, Emily Rooney, calling
me dull, not just once, but a few times, and not just any kind of
dull, but ``exceedingly dull.'' Boston advertising executive and
``Greater Boston'' commentator John Carroll _ henceforth known as
the highly respected John Carroll _ had just done his own somewhat
flattering critique of myself and new columnist colleague Adrian
Walker. I'd be embarrassed to write here what he said, but call me
if you'd like the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes Emily. ``Dull is another word that comes to mind,''
she says, flashing that finishing school smile of hers. After the
other panelists hemmed and hawed that maybe passing judgment on the
first few columns was a trifle unfair, she added, ``I do think that
these were exceedingly dull.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that made me wonder. So I contemplated calling my
ex-wife, a woman of considerable bluntness, which partially
explains the prefix ex. But I realized what she would have told me:
``On your best day you're dull. You aspire to be dull. You give the
word dull a bad name . . .'' Click. So instead I could have called
my mother, but suddenly it occurred to me she doesn't take my calls
anymore. I wonder why. My boss? Well, everyone in here is on
vacation but me, mostly because I don't have anyplace to go.
</P>
<P>
   I did think about taking a few days off this week to learn how
to shape linen napkins into swans and other animals, like the
waiters did on that Big Red Boat cruise to nowhere I was on a few
years back, figuring it would be an enchanting trick to perform at
a party sometime, should I ever get invited to one.
</P>
<P>
   But no. Here I am, trying to figure out how not to be dull. For
that, maybe I should look to Emily Rooney. She's so smart, maybe
she can help.
</P>
<P>
   First off, I come to find out she's the daughter of that lovable
curmudgeon Andy Rooney of 60 Minutes. That's exciting. But I'm not
entirely convinced that having an accomplished or famous relative
can insulate anyone from dullness.
</P>
<P>
   Then I learn that Emily herself was reviewed by the Globe and
Herald in January 1997, back when ``Greater Boston'' first appeared
on the air. The reviews were a little less flattering than they
might have been. But what was truly interesting was Emily's
response. In an interview with the Improper Bostonian, she lashed
out at Herald TV columnist Monica Collins, a first-rate critic, for
her physique and psychology, accusing her of being jealous of
``people who are more attractive and slimmer than she is.'' And in
a letter faxed to Collins, Emily wrote, ``Meanwhile, with my
anxiety level at a maximum over the past six months, I've dropped
12 pounds. And you?''
</P>
<P>
   Oh my. That's certainly not dull. Maybe that explains why Emily
still seemed to be fuming that night she called me dull. She
seethed, ``Nobody's ever revisited this show after almost two years
on the air, after they blew us out of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK. I think I get it. I should lash out. I should be brutal,
vicious even, and the more personal, the better. If I'm
embarrassing myself and my newspaper, that's alright; anything in
the name of not being dull. So how's this: Hey Emily, murder
fugitives can hide out on the guest panel of ``Greater Boston''
without fear of being seen. Hey Emily, maybe the highly respected
John Carroll should be the host.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the hell with it. It's the holidays. And Emily's a smart
woman. Maybe the proper thing is to just thank her for her counsel
and say that one of these nights, I hope to put my CB poetry aside
in time to catch her enlightening show.
</P>
<P>
   (Brian McGrory is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
