<HEADER>
A0189 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ELGAR-BOS &LR;      12-29 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ELGAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLETING ELGAR'S WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In 1934 Edward Elgar, mortally ill, asked his friend William
Reed to burn the sketches for the Third Symphony the composer knew
he would not live to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Reed did not comply with Elgar's request. Instead he reproduced
a substantial number of the sketches in his memoir, ``Elgar As I
Knew Him,'' published a year after the composer's death. The actual
sketches went into the British Library, with a stern prohibition
against any attempt to alter or complete them.
</P>
<P>
   But now Elgar estate has withdrawn its objections, and the
British composer Anthony Payne has completed this last work. Payne
describes the Third Symphony as an ``elaboration'' of Elgar's
sketches. Now the new work the old master seems poised to enter the
international repertory. 62 performances have been taken place or
been scheduled since the premiere by Andrew Davis and the BBC
Symphony last year; a recording has appeared on the NMC label. NMC
has also issued a very interesting supplementary disc containing a
lecture about the work by Payne illustrated by performances of
nearly all the material in the sketches so that the listener can
understand exactly what he had to do to complete the work _ what
Elgar left and what Payne made of it. The lecture is also quite
candid; Payne admits there are bits of music in the sketches he
couldn't find a place for _ although Elgar himself would certainly
not have used up every notation in the sketches. We cannot know for
sure what Elgar would have done, but it is certain that Payne has
done something noble and thoroughly Elgarian _ Payne knows his
Elgar, which means he has to spring some surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Payne was in this country last month for the American premiere
by the Philadelphia Orchestra, and he spoke by phone about this
unusual and somewhat controversial project.
</P>
<P>
   Elgar, who had written little of importance after the death of
his wife in 1920, was urged to compose a Third Symphony by his
friend George Bernard Shaw, who had a hand in persuading the BBC to
commission the work. Elgar worked vigorously on the piece, drawing
ideas and thematic materials from earlier uncompleted or
diversionary works (an oratorio called ``The Last Judgment,'' never
completed; incidental music to a play by Laurence Binyon,
``Arthur'') as was his usual custom. There is reason to believe
that much of the symphony was substantially worked out in Elgar's
head, and he would storm through parts of it at the piano, with
Reed tagging along on the violin; he would urge Reed to ``play his
heart out.'' Among the helpful materials in the sketches are the
violin parts Elgar wrote out for Reed, and on the lecture CD
violinist Robert Gibbs plays on Reed's own instrument to the
accompaniment of David Owen Norris's piano. But Elgar didn't get
all of the symphony written down, and what he did write out is not
always clear, or in order _ parts of the sketches form a kind of
jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Payne was originally drawn to the sketches by Reed's book; he
prepared a BBC lecture on the sketches, and even arrived at a
provisional completion of the slow movement before the Elgar family
said they could not violate the composer's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowly, however'' Paye says, ``they changed their minds as we
got to know each other. At every point in the process they were
very courteous; they were sorry to refuse permission. In the end,
the family bit the bullet because of the copyright situation. By
2005 Elgar will be in the public domain, and anybody can do
anything he wants to with the music. Rather than let anything
unfortunate happen, they preferred to give me permission _ it was
that rather than any `higher good' or `giving Elgar's last thoughts
to the world' that motivated them. The family has come in for
attack; they have been accused of `feeding off the rotten corpse of
Elgar.' But they're putting all the money from the Third Symphony
into a scholarship for a young composer; nobody is going to grow
rich on the dead body of the great man.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne says that one great lesson of the Third Symphony is ``that
it gives the lie to the received opinion that the old boy was dried
up creatively. There's an entirely new tone of voice in this
symphony, and people have been astonished by it. Some of them have
even said they thought it was coming from me. But what atonished
them was absolutely what Elgar wrote out in full score, the first
20 bars or so _ a section that proved a jolly useful platform for
me to work from. It's a new Elgar and the opening of the symphony
sounds like a piece from the 1930s _ it sounds a bit like
Hindemith, but you can hear that it's by Elgar.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been a growing fascination in recent years with
finishing works left incomplete by their creators. Familiar legal
and moral arguments have been made against this. Some contemporary
composers also object because the process deflects attention from
really new work _ it is giving us new old repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with that part of the argument,'' Payne says,
``although it involves arguing against what i've done. As a
composer, I think one of the sicknesses of our age is obsession
with the past. One thing that has come out of that is writing
pieces about other pieces, music with quotation marks around it.
There's something a bit sick about that instead of writing music
from the gut, music about feeling and emotion. Now of course I've
gone and done it myself _ but I'm not going to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who was born in 1936, has produced a considerable
catalogue of high-quality music. He is married to the British
new-music soprano Jane Manning, who has appeared on several
occasions with the Boston Musica Viva; Richard Pittman and BMV have
also performed works by Payne. The composer welcomes any additional
attention the Elgar elaboration will bring to his own compositions.
``People are saying `Now we must have another look at Payne's
music.' Whether or not this attention will lead in the near future
to all that much more activity on my behalf, I can't say, but it
has helped people think that I belong to the tradition of English
music. To marry the English romantics to the continental
avant-garde _ that's my role in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne says the process of completing the Elgar Third is quite
different from the effort several musicians have brought to
Mahler's 10th Symphony, which was alos left unfinished. ``The
Mahler 10th presents a totally different problem. The continuity is
all there, but the textures are extremely sparse. In the Elgar
Third it's the other way round _ the sketches are more complete
texturally, but you have to place them together like the pieces of
a puzzle. And I had to do more actual composing; I had to write the
last 2/3 of the finale myself. But after hearing the work all these
times, I have no second thoughts _ I really think I've nailed it.
I'm pleased with it, and would never change any of it. That's it.
If another 20 pages of sketches were to turn up, I think I'd be
tempted to burn them. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Response to the Elgar Third has been fervent and emotional;
Elgar is a composer whose music means much to his countrymen.
``People do love their Elgar, and they have been very touchingly
grateful for this effort. Andrew Davis leapt in the air and shouted
`Yes!' the first time I showed him the completed score, and since
then it's become one of his favorite pieces. It is such a physical
piece that musicians like playing it. Another good thing is that
it's not as difficult as the First and Second Symphonies; amateur
orchestras and youth orchestras can get round it and do a moving
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne says he feels his life has been changed by his work on the
sketches. ``I've very proud of having done this for Elgar, who is
one of my spiritual father figures. We have been able to look at
this music in a book for years. It's wonderful that people can now
hear this music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
