<HEADER>
A0191 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWN-COMFORTER-HNS &LR;      12-29 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWN-COMFORTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET DOWN TO BASICS FOR A GOOD NIGHT'S SLEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A good night's sleep can easily be interrupted by
cold, frosty weather if it leaves you shivering in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Short of a two- or three-dog night (when it's so cold that you
let the pets repose with you for extra warmth), one of the best
insulators is a down comforter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A healthy sleeping environment is a cool one at around 65,''
said Rob Hayes, general merchandise manager for Coming Home, the
bed and bath division of Lands' End in Dodgeville, Wis. ``This cuts
down on bacteria that survive in warm, moist conditions. Therefore
you should have a proper covering to keep you warm and
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may be under the misconception that a comforter
has to be heavy to keep you warm, but it doesn't,'' Hayes said.
``On the contrary, down comforters can be very light because of
their down insulation and not give you that bogged-down feeling
that you get with several layers of blankets, yet keep you even
toastier.''
</P>
<P>
   These puffy clouds of insulation are filled with the down found
along the breast of white, mature farm-raised ducks and geese. The
goose down plumules (each cluster made up of thousands of tiny
feathery fibers radiating from a central point), are larger,
loftier and stronger than duck down. The more down clusters and the
fewer the feathers, the better the down. (Down is for insulation,
feathers are for flight.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Down comforters are made from white goose down, gray goose and
duck down,'' said Nancy Koltes, president of the retail division of
Scandia Down in New York. ``It's the type of down used that affects
the comforter's weight and cost, like the difference between a
Rolls-Royce and an inexpensive compact car.''
</P>
<P>
   Duck down may simply be called down, but only goose down can be
labeled goose down, Hayes said. A top-quality down comforter will
have at least 80 percent of its fill (amount of space gauged in
cubic inches that the down can fill) from whole down clusters,
which will be listed on the sewn-on tag.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, a product can contain as little as 20 percent to be
labeled as down.
</P>
<P>
   According to Coming Home and other manufacturers, the very
finest down has a fill power of 750 cubic inches per ounce, and the
lowest is around 300 per ounce. Down products with a count of 500
or more are considered worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less than 400 fill power adds weight without adding
much warming ability.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers state the fill power on the label. The higher the
number, the warmer the comforter, which in turn requires less down,
making for a lighter comforter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When buying off-the-shelf in department stores, the consumer
often buys a down comforter that's warmer than they need,'' Koltes
said. ``Therefore, it's important to know all you can about down
before buying a comforter or seek the advice of an experienced
reputable bedding company, so that you get a comforter that will
perform the way you need it to. The most luxurious down comforters
are the lightest.''
</P>
<P>
   But you have to know what kind of down you are buying. For
instance, according to Koltes, an all-season comforter will not
have a high fill power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the soft fluff of these clusters that insulates by
trapping warm air from your body,'' Hayes said. ``Down also
breathes, unlike a synthetic comforter, allowing moisture to wick
out and keep your body cooler as the temperature goes up.
Therefore, a lightweight down comforter would afford perfect
comfort in a warm climate.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to meet government standards, all down is cleaned,
sanitized and sorted by weight before being used in comforters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody allergic to dirt or other animal protein should use
caution when using a down comforter, or depending on the severity
of their allergies, not use one at all,'' said Mary Brasler,
director of programs for the Asthma and Allergy Foundation of
America in Washington, D.C. ``If you have a comforter, you should
encase it in a hypo-allergenic dust-mite-proof casing that gets
washed on a regular basis in water 130 or hotter.''
</P>
<P>
   A down comforter is an investment, so you can expect to pay more
for a goose down comforter than those constructed of cotton and/or
synthetic blends, which are also not as warm as down, lack a lot of
loft and tend to mat down in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
