<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-FLYNT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     12-29 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-FLYNT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BEVERLY HILLS, Calif.: ... his cause.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But what exactly is Larry Flynt's cause? Ask him if he is
investigating GOP sexcapades because he is a Clinton partisan, a
shameless self-promoter, or a lampooner of the mainstream media's
tabloid tendencies, and he says simply: ``all of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very complicated guy,'' says Hustler executive editor
Allan MacDonell. ``He's not someone who has only one motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Born into numbing Appalachian poverty, Flynt is certainly driven
by a love of lucre. Aside from his magazine empire, which includes
a number of ``adult titles'' and dozens of more mainstream
publications, he owns several Hustler stores and will soon open a
gaming parlor in Gardena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkable display of chutzpah, Flynt recently asked
Cincinnati Reds owner Marge Schott if she would sell him the ball
club. ``I was as serious as a heart attack,'' says Flynt. The way
he tells it, Flynt asked his friend, Atlanta Braves owner Ted
Turner, to sound out baseball commissioner Bud Selig on that
possiblity. ``No way you'd be approved,'' was the answer. Still
Flynt continues to insist that ``I could have put the deal
together.''
</P>
<P>
   It also seems likely that Flynt's mucking around in Washington
scandal can only help his bottom line. ``Huckster is your word,''
says Isaacman of Flynt's P. T. Barnumesque qualities. ``He is a
very, very savvy marketing genius. He can take a situation and see
how to market it, how to promote it.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Flynt also enjoys seeing the mainstream media squirm
as they come to grips with his emerging role in a scandal they
helped foment. He is still bitter that ``the media never gave me
the recognition'' he says he deserved for winning a landmark 1988
Supreme Court case, beating a suit the Rev. Jerry Falwell filed
after Hustler parodied the idea of the Moral Majority leader having
sex with his mother in an outhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is driven by economics,'' Flynt says, ``and I want
to vomit when I hear some of the grand old men of journalism step
to the podium talking about integrity. . . . The media is a
monster. It's out of control. It's profit driven.''
</P>
<P>
   On this score, he has some reluctant allies. ``I think what he's
doing is very, very disturbing _ to offer a bounty on the private
lives of public people,'' says media critic Jon Katz. But this
focus on private behavior ``is really something that the serious
media has started,'' adds Katz. ``Flynt is making an ironic
statement about journalism. He has always basically existed to
puncture hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is indisputable is that Flynt is drawn to the subject of
sex like a moth to a flame. In casual conversation, he mentions his
idea to tear down the John Wayne statue in front of his building
and replace it with a fountain in the shape of male genitalia. His
March Hustler issue, yet to hit the stands, banners the nude photos
``of radio's tightest prude.'' In a coup that parlays the hypocrisy
issue with celebrity skin, Flynt has procured dirty pics of radio
moralizer Dr. Laura Schlessinger that originally appeared on the
Internet. He is pleased, but quick to insist that Dr. Laura will
not have the drawing power of Hustler's famous 1975 nude Jackie
Onassis paparazzi photos that helped put it on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt explains that he could actually increase his company's
value by de-emphasizing his dirty magazines (the only ads they
attract are the 900-number ``hot cheap sex talk'' variety), but he
then extinguishes the thought.
</P>
<P>
   He says the quarter-century-old Hustler, with a purported
circulation of about 1 million, ``is my baby. That's where I got my
start. . . . I'm not looking for respectablility.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Flynt will return to Cincinnati _ where he was
initially convicted of pandering obscenity 21 years ago _ to stand
trial on similar charges. ``That was the only major city in America
where (Hustler) wasn't being sold,'' says Flynt. So a little over a
year ago, he opened a Hustler store there. Now, he faces the
prospect of jail time. ``I always felt that if something is not
worth going to jail for, it's not worth very much,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to figure out why a middle-aged, affluent Flynt would
still go to the wall for the right to disseminate smut in one
Midwestern city is tricky business. ``I have a lot of compassion
for Larry Flynt and I feel sorry for him,'' says Burress. ``I think
what motivates Larry Flynt is hate. I think the man has a deep hate
for women.'' In a famous 1997 New York Times op-ed piece, Gloria
Steinem agreed, assailing Hustler for subjecting women to
``degradations from bestiality to sexual slavery. . . . Let's be
clear: A pornographer is not a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier Globe story, writer Camille Paglia saw Flynt as a
raw truth teller. ``If he's a hero, it's in that he forces people
to confront their own buried snobbery about the South and
working-class culture,'' she said. ``I'm always complaining about
white upper-class bias. It's almost easier for people to defend
(Penthouse publisher Bob) Guccione or (Playboy's Hugh) Hefner than
to defend Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynt himself is most at ease when he speaks of marketing sex to
the masses. ``Ever since the Victorian era, the rich and privileged
have always hid their leather-bound edition of pornography,'' he
says. ``Now the elite can no longer control information. Down
through history, people were controlled by controlling
information.''
</P>
<P>
   On this subject, Flynt's slow and halting speech patterns
suddenly smooth out and the words flow in an easy, effortless
stream. Whatever he really is _ hero or scum, misogynist or
free-speech crusader, vapid voyeur or hater of hypocrisy _ Larry
Flynt clearly sees himself as a warrior on a sexual battlefield
where there is never any cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Flynt contemplates how he will detonate his sexual bombshells
about Washington pols (Hustler's MacDonell wants to call it ``The
Flynt Report'' in honor of the Starr report), it's worth noting
that he's enjoyed his 15 minutes of fame on numerous occasions. The
obscenity trials, the shooting that paralyzed him, the Falwell
lawsuit, and Forman's biopic all elevated him from the world of
close-up crotch shots into the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a stunning Washington scandal has afforded him another
opportunity to play mind games with our confused public morality,
conjuring up the line in ``The People Vs. Larry Flynt'' that Flynt
uttered upon returning to work after major surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pervert is back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
