<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dragonfly: NASA and the Crisis Aboard Mir'' by Bryan Burrough
(HarperCollins,$26.95). A gripping account of the near-catastrophe
on the joint Russian-American space mission. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I Will Bear Witness: A Diary of the Nazi Years, 1933-1941'' by
Victor Klemperer (Random House, $29.95). The extraordinary record
of a German Jew who lived and wrote through a nightmare. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Amsterdam'' by Ian McEwan (Doubleday, $21). Two Englishmen are
brought together by the death of a lover they shared. Winner of the
1998 Booker Prize. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love of a Good Woman'' by Alice Munro (Knopf, $24). Eight
new stories by the Canadian master of the form. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hours'' by Michael Cunningham (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$22). A lovely triumph, both a re-imagining of the story of
Virginia Woolf's modernist classic ``Mrs. Dalloway'' and an homage
to the original. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0197 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWELLS-BOOKS-SPI &LR;      12-29 2375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWELLS-BOOKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND'S FAMED BEHEMOTH OF BOOKSTORES KEEPS GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The two weddings were fine, one with 15 folks
in the Rose Room amid the books on cooking, the other in the Purple
Room with 50 people beside the histories. But then came the recent
e-mail from someone who wanted to mark another life passage at
Powell's Books.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to have his ashes interred in the bookstore. It was a
place he loved during his lifetime, so why not just stay there
forever? Call it the eternal bookstore browse.
</P>
<P>
   The request did have its logic. Powell's, probably the largest
bookstore in the United States and maybe the world, bills itself as
the ``City of Books.'' And this Northwest institution boasts many
features of a city, being open 365 days a year, purveying food for
the stomach and the intellect, requiring a map to navigate its real
estate, having its codes and legends.
</P>
<P>
   So even though the man's request to be interred at Powell's was
declined, it does indicate how the people of Portland and elsewhere
feel about this wondrous fiefdom of bookdom.
</P>
<P>
   As Julie Mancini, executive director of Portland Arts &AMP;
Lectures, has often said, ``If there's a new edition of the Bible,
people expect God to be at Powell's to sign books.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Joanna Rose, who worked at the store for 12 years before
leaving recently, ``People just love Powell's. When people come in,
they exhibit a real sense of ownership and treat it more like a
library than a store. People feel `this is our bookstore' and that
makes them so proud.''
</P>
<P>
   They will soon have even more of Powell's to love, honor and
cherish.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition will begin in a few weeks on the northwest portion of
the store, which will be replaced by what is jokingly referred to
as ``Powell's Tower 2000.'' This four-story addition will increase
the size of the 43,000-square-foot store by almost 60 percent and
allow it to have 1 million volumes under one roof, as well as new
sites for its popular author readings and its overcrowded rare-book
room.
</P>
<P>
   This major expansion is happening during the dreariest of days
for independent booksellers. They keep losing so much market share
to the big-bucks chain superstores and Internet purveyors that many
independents are imperiled (including Seattle's Elliott Bay Book
Co.) and many others have been forced to close (including three in
downtown Portland).
</P>
<P>
   Michael Powell, the 58-year-old owner of Powell's, has this
explanation for the expansion: ``We're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Powell's has become a behemoth by dashing convention.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's was started in 1971 by a retired painting contractor _
Michael's father, Walter _ who did not know better. So he mixed
paperbacks and hardbacks on the same shelves in his used bookstore,
which grew prodigiously as the store bought more and more books
from customers.
</P>
<P>
   He later decided to put new books on the same shelves. Powell's
now boasts editions of ``Moby Dick'' ranging from a used paperback
at $1.95 to an American first edition at $12,000 (the store's most
expensive book), with dozens of editions in-between.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Powell is only honoring that why-not spirit with
Powell's expansion. And despite joking about being crazy, this
unassuming but outspoken figure allows that there are practical
reasons for expanding the ultimate superstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're maxed out in our space and have more inventory to expose
to our customers,'' Powell says. ``Besides, we're selling more
books on the Internet, so we could either put more books in
warehouses or the shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   As Miriam Sontz, City of Books manager, adds: ``We could stand
pat, or we could do something daring.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's hardly looks like a place to foment such daring. The
City of Books sprawls over an entire Portland city block
(two-thirds the size of a Seattle block), a collection of
industrial-grade buildings that once housed a Rambler dealership
and a car-repair shop on the section of West Burnside that was
Portland's original auto row.
</P>
<P>
   The store's atmosphere is utilitarian, more warehouse than
living room, with concrete floors, wooden bookshelves, nooks and
crannies on many levels. The mammoth emporium is divided into seven
color-coded rooms, with 122 sections and 4,000 subsections,
alphabetized by author.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that staffers refer to the entrance area of
Powell's as ``the duh zone,'' since many of Powell's 3,000 daily
visitors (including many tourists) seem dumbstruck about how to
proceed any farther. They stop in their tracks, stare at overhead
signage, scratch their heads before finally heading to the
information desk.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the info ``donut'' sits Shelley Brennan, who
uses her six years at Powell's to answer a dizzying array of
inquiries: A book to translate Bosnian and Croatian? A cash
machine? A new translation of ``The Odyssey?'' The restrooms? Books
with photos of fireplaces? Jewish calendars? Maps of the Oregon
Coast?
</P>
<P>
   The cheerful Brennan directs most customers without pause,
usually sending them on their way with copies of Powell's free
full-color map, which unfolds to 17 by 22 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan alternates work at the ``donut'' with work in the
dictionary section, her great love of books evident in what she
does, as it is with many of Powell's 220 main-store employees, an
educated and eclectic corps of laid-back bibliophiles in rough-hewn
attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with the colleague who once said that `Powell's is the
best dead-end job in Portland,''' Brennan relates. ``There's a
level of comfort and civility in this store. People seek refuge
here, interesting people. Something keeps us here, even though it
is difficult to make ends meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Salaries, which start near minimum wage, remain a sticking point
with employees at this bookstore that has long prided itself on its
progressive employment practices and its liberal political
activism. A yearlong petition drive to join the Longshoreman's
Union is now quietly under way at Powell's, much to the chagrin of
Powell and managers who consider it ``a mistake,'' especially in
perilous times for bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its plans to expand, despite its robust annual sales of
more than $30 million, despite its stock far beyond any Barnes &AMP;
Noble or Borders, despite its six smaller stores in Portland, this
is not Fortress Powell, at least according to the man whose name is
on the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've felt the impact of chain stores in our new book sales,''
Powell says. ``At best, they're flat. ... These are depressing
times. With every new Barnes &AMP; Noble that's built, there's more
redividing of the pie. Not many independent stores can survive
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's survival is built on used books, which keep increasing
in sales and now account for half of the store's take. Used books
have higher profit margins and usually incur no shipping charges,
although Powell's does buy the entire stock of closing bookstores
around the country. And its vast store of used books means Powell's
often has books found almost nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   This is the source of many legends surrounding Powell's, tales
that sometimes seem apocryphal but often come from well-known
writers.
</P>
<P>
   Biographer Doris Kearns Goodwin found Abraham Lincoln books in
Powell's that she had not seen in Cambridge, Mass. British writer
Doris Lessing found several books at Powell's that she had sought
for years.
</P>
<P>
   And a skeptical Carlos Fuentes came to Powell's, located in an
American city that ranks 30th in population, with a test list of
five fiendishly obscure titles seldom found on any bookstore
shelves. The widely traveled Mexican writer had found only two
bookstores in the world with two of the titles. Powell's had four.
</P>
<P>
   The key players in Powell's phenomenal selection are its 30
used-book buyers, who take turns at the long counter by the front
door and pronounce their verdict on the stacks of books brought in
by hopeful sellers. Some 5,000 books are bought every day, but many
are rejected, often to the disappointment of those who have lugged
them in.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's used-book buyers, who train for at least two years,
have a computer for backup, as well as price guides for used and
rare books. But, as veteran buyer Allen B. Lloyd says, the best
reference is his head. So he quickly accepts and rejects books,
with sellers receiving one-third of Powell's sale price in cash, or
20 percent more in store credit.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd loves books and his job. ``What else are you going to do
with a B.A. in English?'' he says. ``This can be intellectually
stimulating and it's not flipping burgers.''
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old buyer does his business with a brisk efficiency,
partly because of how many books he evaluates, but also because he
would rather not hear sad stories behind the selling of books.
</P>
<P>
   Although buyers pride themselves on their knowledge, a rare book
will sometimes be bought for far less than its value. Then buyers
try to find the seller and pay the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The same effort is made when something is left inside a book. A
scrapbook behind the buyers' counter contains the book leavings of
sellers who were never located. It is a sometimes hilarious,
sometimes bittersweet repository of lost memories.
</P>
<P>
   The scrapbook includes: a bowling clinic diploma, a karaoke
request form, the number for dial-a-prayer, a prom photo, a torn $5
bill, an 8-by-10 glossy of Oliver North, a photo of a nude man, a
photo of a Little League team, a photo of a nude woman, the
handwritten goals of a seventh grader.
</P>
<P>
   The scrapbook is hardly the only expression of quirky at
Powell's, a store that seems intent on elevating quirky to Olympian
heights.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Books frequently resounds with semi-intelligible
announcements over its loudspeakers. A support beam displays the
autographs of visiting science-fiction authors. A tiny poster in
the fiction section urges, ``Save a tree! Buy a used book!'' A
display of Powell's souvenirs looks to have been last dusted a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to what manager Sontz refers to as Powell's
``funk factor,'' one more cornerstone of its appeal to legions of
loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Copra is one such customer, a bearded bicycle mechanic in
overalls who could easily be the quintessential counterculture
Oregonian. The 51-year-old Portland man takes great pride in not
having owned a car since 1966 and has no computer either. He makes
his pilgrimmages to Powell's by bus and searches for gems by
favorite authors J.G. Ballard, Thomas Hardy and Christopher
Isherwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I might want, I'll find it at Powell's,'' Copra
emphasizes. ``A bookstore can never be too big _ there's just
something about bigness. And I don't want some bookstore guy in a
vest asking if he can help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's legion of loyal customers extends far beyond Oregon,
especially since the arrival of the Internet. Powell's has had a
Web site _ www.powells.com _ since 1993 and its business there has
grown markedly since 1996 when the store's entire inventory of 1
million-plus books was put online, requiring 13 months of tedious
work.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's no-nonsense Web site now generates annual revenues of
more than $3 million. A new building across the street will house
its burgeoning Internet operation. And Powell's inventory is so
huge that it often supplies the virtual business that bills itself
as ``Earth's Biggest Bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Amazon.com provides considerable revenue for
Powell's, which sends books to the Internet retailer's Seattle
distribution center for shipment under its own mailing label. Some
might see this as trading with the enemy, but not Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to build alliances that are mutually beneficial,'' he
explains. ``Amazon has so much marketing money behind them, which
we do not. Customers who want our books cheaper than (through)
Amazon, can buy direct from us. If people are avid readers, they'll
find us sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, a Portland native and now a member of the city's
establishment, brings the same matter-of-factness to the store's
high-profile activism. Powell's has been in the forefront of
support for the literary arts in Portland, the first business to
fund the Portland Arts &AMP; Lectures series (precursor to its Seattle
namesake), as well as aiding school libraries.
</P>
<P>
   In an annual November promotion, Powell's donates 10 percent of
a sale when a customer mentions ``it's for the schools.'' That
raised $57,000 to purchase library books for Portland and Beaverton
schools in 1997 and $70,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even more visible has been Powell's contributions to defeat
Oregon initiatives to curtail gay rights or tighten obscenity laws.
The store's staff-developed mission and values statement includes
support for such causes, but Powell's goes far beyond mouthing
expected platitudes. It was the first Oregon business to oppose the
1992 anti-gay rights initiative, at risk of offending some
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people who said they would never shop here again
and people who said they would never shop anywhere else, but I take
it all with a grain of salt,'' Powell says. ``I don't go looking
for these fights, but people come to me. I believe being a
bookseller carries a burden of supporting the First Amendment and
other causes, such as racial diversity and gay rights. Our
intelligent and active staff continues to challenge us.''
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge is making Powell's better. It may seem like
book nirvana to many customers, but those who work there know it
must continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things I'd like to change around here,''
stresses Sontz, 48, a shrewd businesswoman who started in the
remainder department and advanced through the ranks. ``How to be
larger and more customer-friendly _ that's my life story here.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell has his own ideas of what to improve. The store is open
daily from 9 a.m. to 11 p.m., but he wonders if 14 hours is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer 8 a.m.,'' he states.
</P>
<P>
   Sontz responds in mock horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael sees 25 people out front when we open at 9 a.m., so he
thinks we should open at 8,'' she says. ``I've held him off on that
for a decade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
