<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-YEAR-RULES-NYTSF &LR;      12-29 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-YEAR-RULES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. GROUCH'S RULES FOR 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Forget about my New Year's resolutions, let's talk about what
you can do in 1999 to improve the quality of my life.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not you specifically. You're a smart and sensible person,
anyone can see that. That you're reading this very newspaper shows
you to be an individual of taste and class. Congratulations on
being a quality individual.
</P>
<P>
   It's the other guy we have to worry about. The other gal too.
They're the ones who don't know how to behave in public; they're
the ones who annoy us with their rude, stupid, ignorant,
thoughtless behavior.
</P>
<P>
   As the always-pixiesh and ever-delightful Meg Ryan once told me
after we had fun mocking some other people, ``They're all so flawed
and we're so perfect!'' (All right, all right _ I resolve in 1999
to hold the gratuitous celebrity name-dropping to three per month.
Well, four.)
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but it's still the holiday season, so let's give the oafs a
break, OK? Let's assume they know not what they do, and they're
just in need of a little guidance, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll come up with a list of words and deeds that constitute
unacceptable behavior, and you can clip the column and quietly slip
it to someone who will appreciate being set straight.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few questions that should never be asked of anyone _ not your
best friend, not your sister, not your children:
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you put on weight?''
</P>
<P>
   ``So how much are you making these days?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When are you guys going to get married?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When are you guys going to have a baby?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, did you ever sleep with her (him, it)?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How come you rent, why don't you buy a place?''
</P>
<P>
   And why is it that you should never ask these questions? BECAUSE
IT'S NONE OF YOUR BUSINESS.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the baby question. Maybe someone has a medical
problem that precludes a pregnancy; perhaps one partner in the
relationship wants children and the other doesn't. It could be that
the couple's been trying to have a child for three years, with no
success; there might be a miscarriage or two you don't know about.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answer is, it's between the two of them.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, if you see someone from your distant past, it's
really bad form to walk up say, ``You don't remember me, do you?''
It puts the other person on the defensive and makes for an awkward
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever someone says, ``You don't remember me, do you?'' I
reply, ``Of course I do, and I'm wondering why you're not obeying
the restraining order.''
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About that gum-cracking: Unless you're playing shortstop for a
Little League team, it makes you look and sound like a surprise
guest on the ``Springer'' show, OK?
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a long line behind you at the cashier, who is ringing up
$147 in merchandise. Hint: Now is a good time to reach into the big
bottomless purse and fish out the checkbook or the credit card or
the little zippered pouch where you keep your cash tucked away.
Don't wait until the items are bagged to start digging around for
your method of payment! It's not as if you should be taken by
surprise when they ask you to actually pay for the items.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You're waiting for an elevator. When the doors open, should you:
</P>
<P>
   A. Bullrush right in, thus creating a human traffic jam with
those who are trying to exit the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   B. Stand back and wait for the elevator to empty before
entering.
</P>
<P>
   If you answered B., excellent. Your brain is indeed functioning.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of mechanized transportation, the top of the escalator
is not _ repeat, IS NOT _ a good place to stand while you consider
your next move.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   See those people up there on the big silver screen? They're
called actors, and they've been paid a lot of money to recite
dialogue written by professional wordsmiths. Trust me: What you've
got to say is not more interesting to me than what they've got to
say, even if it's a Joe Pesci comedy. So really, shut up.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so you enjoy whistling loudly at work, eh? That's great,
because you'll never have to wonder if people are calling you a
rude simpleton behind your back. They are!
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Others dream of a 1999 where nations can live in harmony, and
the little children of the world always have food to eat and a roof
over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   I'd settle for a place where those who engage in the above
activities would give it a rest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
