<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRGRACE-TRUTH-BOS &LR;      12-29 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRGRACE-TRUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER, RESIDENTS SEE TRUTH IN FILM'S PORTRAYAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f cocoding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get a few facts straight about the new movie, ``A Civil
Action.'' Jan Schlichtmann's Porsche was not as cool-looking as the
one in the movie, and his office was on Broad Street, not tony
Charles Street at the foot of Beacon Hill. He doesn't look like
John Travolta, either.
</P>
<P>
   But Schlichtmann, the flamboyant lawyer portrayed by Travolta
who battled two major corporations over their role in poisoning
wells in Woburn, believes that ``A Civil Action'' is true on a
deeper level. It captures both the warlike atmosphere of his
lawsuit and the futility of counting on courts to provide justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were moments in the film . . . in which I felt the
emotions of that time,'' said Schlichtmann, who spent his law firm
into bankruptcy hoping for a big verdict against Beatrice Foods and
W. R. Grace &AMP; Co. ``I found myself really convulsed by the humor
and the irony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Civil Action,'' which has its local premiere at Boston's
Wang Theatre on Jan. 6, tells the story of the bitter 1986 lawsuit
over the leukemia deaths of five children and one adult that family
members believed were caused by chemicals from Grace and Beatrice.
Far from winning a big verdict, Schlichtmann finally settled for $8
million from Grace and no admission of guilt by either firm.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of Steven Zaillian, who won an Oscar for his
screenplay of ``Schindler's List,'' the moviemakers were concerned
with making a fair and realistic movie, bringing lawyers for both
sides to the set for advice and asking a federal lawyer for old
photos of her office to help recreate the mid-1980s offices of the
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann is particularly impressed with how realistic the
characters seem. Travolta plays him as a luxury-loving, obsessed
attorney whose singlemindedness makes the lawsuit possible but then
undermines efforts to win a favorable settlement.
</P>
<P>
   And Schlichtmann doesn't disagree with the portrayal. ``Woburn
long ago put me in a position to be examined by many people from
many different angles. I'm used to it,'' he said. ``What I'm
impressed by is the integrity of the retelling.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Civil Action,'' based on the best-selling book of the
same name, is most concerned with the lawyers, employing the
environmental disaster as a backdrop against which Travolta and
Robert Duvall, as Beatrice's attorney Jerome Facher, fight their
legal grudge match.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, nonlawyers _ the parents of the dead children,
neighborhood activists, and even the well-meaning government
regulators _ have a limited role, although their collective
efforts, spread over years and hundreds of meetings, finally
cleaned up Woburn's water.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Robbins, who initiated the Woburn lawsuit after her
9-year-old son died of leukemia, isn't even represented in the
movie, and one poignant line is spoken by another parent, Anne
Anderson, played by Kathleen Quinlan. In real life, Robbins had
said she would sit in the left-hand corner of the courtroom,
because as he lay dying her son promised to meet her in the
left-hand corner of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset when I saw it coming out of her mouth. . . . It
feels like they really stole part of my life away,'' said Robbins,
who, like many former plaintiffs who attended a private screening
last week, felt the movie was too short.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also simplifies a complicated pollution history to
keep the focus on Beatrice and Grace. In reality, the wells on the
Aberjona River were surrounded by industries that likely
contributed to the 56 chemicals found in the wells, which Woburn's
engineers cautioned against digging in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woburn is really the beginning of our industrial history. It
embodies the mistakes of individuals and government agencies and
industries, who, for many years, behaved very irresponsibly,'' said
Gretchen Latowsky, former director of For A Cleaner Environment,
which watchdogged the Woburn cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann says that the movie underscores one of the most
important lessons he learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was perpetuating the very evil that I was railing against,''
he said, looking back on the more than $10 million the adversaries
spent in legal combat. ``When we fight with each other over the
truth, we do not honor the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
