<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRGRACE-TOXIC-BOS &LR;      12-29 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRGRACE-TOXIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE BRINGS TOXIC TRAGEDY   BACK TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOBURN, Mass. _ Employees jokingly called the ditch behind the
W. R. Grace plant the ``swimming pool,'' though only a fool would
swim there. Until the early 1970s, workers dumped cleaning
solvents, paint, and other wastes into or near the ditch, never
imagining that the poisons might reach public water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   That carelessness cast W. R. Grace &AMP; Co. as a villain in one of
the most famous environmental trials in US history, pitting its
high-priced attorneys against parents who believed that their
children had been killed by Grace chemicals in their tap water. To
this day, the company denies that it poisoned Woburn wells, but it
paid the parents and their lawyers $8 million to end the legal
ordeal in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Now, like a recurring nightmare, a new movie, ``A Civil
Action,'' reintroduces America to a history that Grace officials
have been trying to live down. The film, starring John Travolta as
the driven lawyer representing the Woburn parents, opened in New
York City on Christmas, accompanied by the advance publicity and
critical praise that may foreshadow a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie omits Grace's much-improved environmental
record since 1986, ``A Civil Action'' offers a powerful lens
through which to view how the environmental movement has
transformed American industry since the 1980s. Grace pollutes far
less than it once did, but, like many companies, it is still
haunted by the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think that they are very guilty and responsible for
everything that happened, even though Grace is trying to say they
didn't do it,'' said Woburn plaintiff Donna Robbins, whose
9-year-old son, Carl Robbins III, died of leukemia in 1981. ``I
don't know how they can go around saying they weren't
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Woburn case was never clear-cut, which is why only
a risk-taking lawyer like Travolta's character, Jan Schlichtmann,
would handle the parents' costly lawsuit, driving his law firm into
bankruptcy in the process. Grace's stainless-steel equipment plant
was just one of many industries huddled around wells G and H, the
farthest away of five companies that the US Environmental
Protection Agency later held legally responsible for cleaning up
the pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Even Schlichtmann does not believe that Grace's chemical dumping
was remarkable for industry in the years before states and the
federal government passed tough laws on hazardous waste disposal.
In fact, some of the discharges may have been legal at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were more the rule than the exception, in the sense that
they had a lot of things in their past that were ugly. There were
many companies that suffer from the same kind of an ugly past,''
Schlichtmann said.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike other companies near wells G and H, Grace, along
with Beatrice Foods, had ``deep pockets,'' making it a good target
for a lawsuit aimed at recovering large amounts of money. Adding to
Grace's troubles, a conscience-stricken employee revealed the
company's secret dumping practices during preparation for the
trial, indirectly leading to a $10,000 criminal fine against Grace
by the Environmental Protection Agency. In the end, the jury let
Beatrice off, but found that Grace had contributed to the
contamination of the two wells.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Woburn case cemented Grace's image as one of
the nation's top polluters, along with Monsanto of Times Beach,
Mo., and Hooker Chemical of Love Canal in New York. In
Massachusetts alone, Grace was called to account for several other
environmental messes, from toxic chemical lagoons in Cambridge to
the plants in Acton that contaminated 40 percent of the town's
water supply. Meanwhile, thousands of people nationwide were
joining lawsuits charging that asbestos-containing insulation made
by Grace had made them sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They continually do things that once again reinforce the
notion . . . that at times the chemical industry is callous and
acts with disregard for communities,'' Boston University management
professor John Mahon said in describing Grace to the Boston Herald
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   W. R. Grace officials insist they were never as bad as they
seemed to be; for instance, they were the first company around the
wells to test the ground water for contamination. But company
officials admit that they made serious errors in Woburn that turned
the community and government agencies against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made mistakes in addressing the concerns of the community
and government agencies, and we realized that it was up to us to
demonstrate our commitment to addressing these concerns,'' said
Mark Stoler, Grace's director of environment, health, and safety
and a junior lawyer for the company at the time of the Woburn
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Today, W. R. Grace, based in Boca Raton, Fla., barely resembles
the ``mega-corporation'' that Schlichtmann battles in ``A Civil
Action.'' Once a far-flung conglomerate with businesses ranging
from restaurants to pipelines to cruise ships, the empire built by
J. Peter Grace ran into falling profits in the 1980s, prompting
managers to sell off or close three-quarters of the firm's
businesses, leaving a company focused on specialty chemicals such
as cement additives and can sealants.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Grace's employment has plummeted, from 3,000
at the time of the Woburn suit to 538, as the controversial plant
on Washington Street in Woburn closed and the company facilities in
Acton were bulldozed.
</P>
<P>
   Grace has shrunk in other important ways, as well, reducing its
toxic chemical releases by two-thirds from 1991 to 1995, according
to the Investor Responsibility Research Center, while slashing by
three-quarters both the environmental fines it must pay and its
overall waste generation.
</P>
<P>
   The Investor Responsibility Research Center, a Washington,
D.C.-based organization that evaluates corporations for socially
conscious investors, now ranks W. R. Grace as tops among US
specialty chemical companies for following environmental laws. Dan
Kennedy, a reporter for the weekly Boston Phoenix who covered the
trial for the Woburn Daily Times, described Grace as ``one of
Woburn's model corporate citizens'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But the road to ``model corporate citizen'' has been neither
smooth nor easy, reflecting a company caught in a riptide of
changing standards. Grace had never faced an environmental lawsuit
before the Woburn case, despite decades of polluting activities,
such as chemical disposal, mining, radioactive contamination, and
asbestos manufacturing. Until 1987, Grace didn't even have a chief
environmental official.
</P>
<P>
   When the company finally created an Office of Environmental
Policy, they brought in a man to run it who was contemptuous of the
EPA. ``If the FAA were like the EPA, all the planes would crash,''
Hugh L. Carey, hired as Grace's environment director in 1987, told
the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Grace has been named a responsible party at 32 Superfund
hazardous waste cleanups across the country, from Woburn to
Lansing, Mich., where the company is part of a cleanup of an old
manufacturing waste pit.
</P>
<P>
   That's almost twice the specialty chemical industry average,
according to the IRRC, and Grace has spent $126 million to clean up
old environmental hazards since 1995 alone.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Grace has paid half a billion dollars to settle
lawsuits over its asbestos-containing insulation, and by the end of
1997 the company faced 96,000 claims of bodily injury from the
insulation, which Grace stopped selling in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Stoler argues that the high number of waste sites partly
reflects the buying and selling of subsidiaries during Grace's
conglomerate years, which made the company owner of waste sites
that it never contaminated. For example, Grace has spent more than
$1 million investigating possible jet-fuel leaks at the
Massachusetts Military Reservation from a pipeline the company
briefly owned after it had already been shut down.
</P>
<P>
   But Grace's record also reflects decades of sloppy
waste-handling practices, some of which are just coming to light
today. For example, Grace is only now conducting a full search for
asbestos at its Cambridge property and an abutting playing field,
up to 80 years after the contamination began. In New Jersey,
meanwhile, Grace has agreed to resume cleanup of radioactive waste
at a site the company had believed was cleaned up more than 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And other messes are the subject of dispute. John Morgan of
Winchester has sued Grace, as well as three trucking companies, for
what he says is toxic waste dumping in front of his Rock Avenue
house in 1982, a charge the company vehemently denies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, activists and government officials who have worked with
Grace at waste sites over the years say they have detected a
profound shift in company attitudes, from defensive and difficult
in the 1980s to helpful and even forward-looking today.
</P>
<P>
   In Acton, where nine Grace waste lagoons and two landfills had
contaminated public wells and the company dragged its feet on the
cleanup for years, the company finally apologized for its conduct
in 1989 and took a more aggressive approach to cleanup in the early
1990s. Activists say the change reflected the intervention of top
Grace environmental officials, eager to speed the cleanup process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accomplished more in three years than we had in the
previous 12,'' said Edmond Benoit, who supervised the Acton cleanup
for the state Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   In Woburn, Grace went from mounting a $7 million legal defense
against the Woburn parents' lawsuit to installing a water treatment
system that was more effective and more costly than the EPA
required.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime observers say the changes reflect the fact the
sprawling corporation is slowly getting the message that
environmental protection is important, particularly when the highly
regarded Stoler took charge of the firm's environmental affairs in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   But, as long as Grace is cleaning up its past, some people still
feel at risk. Russ Bromfield of Cambridge, who lives near the area
Grace is studying for asbestos contamination, has been unimpressed
with company efforts to show sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view them more as the enemy,'' Bromfield said. ``They
haven't done anything to show me they have positive intentions in
the neighborhood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
