<HEADER>
A0209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-29 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX' TV DEAL CAN ONLY BE SCRAMBLED BY INCLUSION OF DUNN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing is ever simple with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Since last season ended: They lost their best player. They
raised ticket prices. They evicted sidewalk vendors, only to
reinstate them after a push by the local government.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder what else the Red Sox brass can do before the
end of the year to annoy their long-suffering fans.
</P>
<P>
   Yup, you guessed it.
</P>
<P>
   Screw up their television deal.
</P>
<P>
   For the last six months, the Red Sox have negotiated with two
media heavyweights, Fox Sports and Barry Diller's USA Network. They
talked with Channel 68, the station that carried the team's
over-the-air games the last three seasons. They even talked with
Kevin Dunn, who doesn't have any money or his own television
station.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who is close to signing a deal?
</P>
<P>
   If you picked Dunn, consider yourself Red Sox executive
material.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn and his partner, former CBS president Gene Jankowski,
offered the Red Sox $10.1 million to air 75 games next season.
Because the two don't have their own station, they apparently
reached an agreement with Channel 56 to carry the games in Boston
and are trying to secure similar deals in other large New England
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we're going to get the deal done,'' Channel 56
general manager Leslie Glenn proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   That was last week, and Glenn predicted that things would be
finalized Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't, and more than likely, they won't be, largely
because of one big reason: money. Dunn and Jankowski don't have
enough, and most potential backers are reluctant to make up the
difference because of an even bigger reason: The Red Sox are a
losing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a good, hard look at the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunn deal comes out to about $135,000 per game. Add another
$25,000 for production and the cost is $160,000. Each game has
about 60 30-second advertising spots. Channel 56 gets 10-12 of
them. That leaves Dunn with, say, 50 spots to break even or make
money. To do that, he must get at least $3,200 per spot.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem. Channel 68 had a hard time getting $2,000
for a spot. On New England Sports Network, the premium cable
channel, owned in part by the Red Sox, that carries the other half
of the team's schedule, ad spots sell for about $1,400.
</P>
<P>
   It's not impossible to jack up the price, but it's pretty tough,
especially considering the number of media outlets selling time
during Red Sox games and the demographics of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, NESN, Channel 68, and, to a limited extent, Fox
(eight games) sent sales forces to the Boston marketplace to place
ads. If Dunn's deal goes through, that would add his sales force,
plus the one at Channel 56.
</P>
<P>
   With that level of competition, the price goes down, not up.
Further eroding the value of advertising spots is the demographic
of the Red Sox audience, which tends to be older. That is not
necessarily a bad thing, but advertisers prefer 18- to 49-year-old
males, not the 50-plus crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 68, for instance, had great ratings last season and
still lost millions. And the team made the playoffs and actually
won a game.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume that Dunn and Jankowski are extremely smooth
talkers and are able to get $2,500 per 30-second spot. That would
mean $125,000 per game, which would put them $35,000 in the hole
per game. Multiply that by 75, and that hole is now $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Financial backers are not usually generous sorts, especially
when the borrower factors lottery winnings into the repayment plan.
The money men are probably using a more realistic number for the
30-second spots, something like $1,800. That would leave Dunn and
Jankowski $70,000 in the hole after each game, and a staggering
$5.2 million in debt at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox apparently don't care what happens to Dunn and
Jankowski. Or whether such media hotbeds as Manchester, N.H., or
Portland, Maine, can make up the difference between the rights fee
and the shortage of Boston advertising dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox CEO John Harrington knows the numbers. He knows the
television rights for the ne'er-do-well team are worth about $8.5
million a year, $9 million tops. Can't blame the man for trying to
squeeze every penny that he can.
</P>
<P>
   Securing advertising is not the Red Sox' problem. They want that
$10.1 million. Or at least a guaranteed letter of credit, which so
far hasn't come.
</P>
<P>
   They really wanted $14 million per year. Channel 68 had the
chance to renew its contract for that amount but declined.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing about forgetting history. Three years ago, the Red
Sox had another deal on the table. It was worth about $14 million a
year. At the last minute, the deal fell through. Dunn was heading
that deal, too, and, three years later, he still doesn't have
enough money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0210 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      12-29 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHARLES KURALT'S AMERICAN MOMENTS &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Peter Freundlich (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $22)
</P>
<P>
   ``Moments'' is the right word. That's all we get here _ they
come close to being sound bytes, and that was never Kuralt's style.
These were the last projects he worked on before he died, and he
was uncomfortable with them. The proposal was that he would create
90-second moments to be distributed to independent television
stations. At first he refused, saying 90 seconds wasn't enough time
to do anything worthwhile. Writer-producer Freundlich persuaded him
to try. All 117 of the pieces that they wrote and produced are
included here, in a book of 255 pages. Kuralt visits a kazoo
factory, a flagmaker, a basket weaver, a shoemaker, a man who
carves whirligigs, the caretaker for the Statue of Liberty (here
Kuralt was beaten soundly by David Isay, who profiled the same man,
Charlie DeLeo, for National Public Radio and published a wonderful
essay about him in his book, ``Holding On''). It helps if you
imagine Kuralt's voice reading these little pieces, but it's not
enough to make them seem substantive. They are too brief, too
prescribed, and they'll make you miss what Kuralt was in his good
days. With a foreword by Charles Osgood. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EX LIBRIS: CONFESSIONS OF A COMMON READER &QL; 
 &UR; Anne Fadiman (FSG, $16)
</P>
<P>
   When Anne Fadiman and her husband finally got around to
consolidating their libraries (they had lived together for six
years and had been married for five, but her books had remained at
the northern end of their loft, his at the southern), they engaged
in negotiations that in seriousness and tenacity resembled the
Mideast peace talks. He was a ``lumper,'' whose books were
unorganized and charmingly kept, some vertical, some horizontal,
some actually (begin itals) behind (end itals)others. Fadiman kept
her books ``balkanized by nationality and subject matter'' and
proposed that in their consolidation they arrange English
literature chronologically but American literature alphabetically
by author (their American collection was mostly 20th century, and
``chronological distinctions would require Talmudic
hairsplitting''). That she spends eight pages talking about the
details of this literary conversion is a measure of how
self-conscious she is when it comes to her reading habits. Hardly
the common reader described by Virginia Woolf, Fadiman is beguiled
by the physical presence of books, the feel of them, the memory of
them, the milestones they are in our lives. She also loves her part
in it, the (begin itals) show (end itals) of reading. Is she being
pretentious when she tells us that she once left a book store with
19 pounds of books, and that she knows this because she weighed
them when she got home? It doesn't matter. These essays (first
published in ``Civilization'' magazine) are self-absorbed, but
dumbfoundingly readable. If you're zealous about books, give them a
try. All you'll want is equal time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WE INTERRUPT THIS BROADCAST &QL; 
 &UR; Joe Garner (Sourcebooks, $45)
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was a good idea. Garner pairs text and photographs of
some of the momentous events of this century with two CDs that
bring you radio and television announcements of each. The audio
footage is tremendously effective, as when back-to-back we hear an
early, sketchy announcement that President Kennedy has been shot, a
later report that the bullet struck him in the head and, finally,
an emotional Walter Cronkite's announcement that Kennedy has died.
We also hear Lyndon Johnson decline a re-election bid, Robert
Kennedy's last words to a reporter before he was shot, the gunfire
that killed four students at Kent State University, Richard Nixon
resigning the presidency, the announcement of John Lennon's death,
the riots that followed the Rodney King verdict, a bomb exploding
in front of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City,
the first reports of Princess Diana's death and other chilling
moments that many of us remember all too well. Each is preceded by
a tedious, overly dramatic narration by television newsman Bill
Kurtis that almost sours the whole package. Are the broadcasts
worth waiting through the unnecessary buildup? Yes. Cronkite
contributes a foreword to the text. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FOR THE LOVE OF THE GAME: MY STORY &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Jordan (Crown, $50)
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing Phoenix and Charles Barkley in the 1993 finals was
like playing against your little brother and knowing you're
well-equipped. Your little brother might beat you one or two out of
seven, but you know he's going to get beat in the end. The Suns
didn't know how to win. They knew how to compete, but they didn't
know how to win. There is a difference.'' You have just read one of
the few passages in this book that does not contain the word ``I.''
Most paragraphs _ and they're not long paragraphs _ are riddled
with it. Even if you are starved for basketball, even if the ``I''
in question is the greatest player of all time, it wears on you
after a while. The text in this Michaelfest is accompanied by
countless photographs of Jordan in all of his evolutionary stages:
Michael with hair, Michael in a succession of Nikes, Michael in
silhouette, in a suit, in Bill Cartwright's face. And later,
Michael in his mansion, in his baseball uniform, in the grips of
the flu during the 1997 finals. Sound like your thing? We'll say
only one thing more: Not once is he as pretty on paper as he is
moving through the air. &QL; 
(Reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
