A0214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TROLLOPE-BOS &LR;      12-29 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TROLLOPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WOMB OF LITERATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
FANNY TROLLOPE 
The Life and Adventures of a Clever Woman 
By Pamela Neville-Sington 
Viking,. 416 pp., $29.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony Trollope's publishers deliberately omitted his first
name from the cover of his first novel, hoping buyers would assume
the book had been written by his best-selling mother, Fanny. A
century and a half later, we still read the works of Anthony
Trollope, one of the great novelists of the Victorian era _ but who
remembers Fanny?
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Neville-Sington's ``Fanny Trollope: The Life and
Adventures of a Clever Woman'' is a lively biography of an
extraordinary woman, a writer who deserves to be remembered in her
own right and not just as Anthony's mother. Her life was as
eventful and dramatic as any of her 35 novels or six travel books.
Neville-Sington's meticulously researched biography tells Fanny's
story with the energy, humor, and joie de vivre that characterized
her subject's life and work.
</P>
<P>
   Fanny Milton was born into the social milieu Jane Austen
immortalized in her novels. She was four years younger than Austen;
their fathers were rectors in the same Hampshire deanery. Fanny was
educated at home and encouraged to read widely, the classics as
well as popular novels of the day (``It is good for us to read
trash occasionally,'' she wrote late in life).
</P>
<P>
   At 30, she married the senior Anthony Trollope, an
Oxford-educated barrister, a difficult man who probably suffered
from emotional or mental illness. The marriage was tolerable, at
first. But he was hopelessly inept at managing money, and they were
always in financial difficulties. After the death from tuberculosis
of their 11-year old son, Arthur, in 1824, his anger increased, his
dark moods worsened. Fanny mourned her son deeply and withdrew. The
marriage began to come apart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1827, Fanny took an extraordinary step for a woman of her
class in the Victorian era: She set off for America with three of
her five remaining children, Henry, 16, Cecilia, 11, and Emily, 9.
Tom, 17, and Anthony, 12, were left behind to finish their
educations. Her reasons for leaving England were partly financial:
The Trollopes were deeply in debt. The journey also offered her the
opportunity to live apart from her increasingly bad-tempered
husband without the social stigma of a formal separation. She also
had fallen under the spell of the charismatic social reformer
Frances Wright, who had established in the backwoods of Tennessee a
community called Nashoba to educate slaves in preparation for their
eventual emancipation.
</P>
<P>
   The journey was difficult, Nashoba was a complete failure,
Frances Wright turned out to be a crank. Fanny and the children
settled in Cincinnati, where she hatched one money-making scheme
after another. Cincinnati, nicknamed ``Porkopolis'' because of the
number of pigs who met their end in local slaughterhouses, was a
booming community, the fastest-growing city in America at the time.
Its citizens were avid for culture, which Fanny tried to provide by
producing amateur theatricals and establishing a wax museum, among
other ventures. Unfortunately, her most ambitious project, a lavish
and eccentric social/ &QC; 
entertainment center called the Cincinnati Bazaar, was a disaster.
Fanny begged and borrowed money to return to England.
</P>
<P>
   At age 53, bankrupt, desperate to support her family, Fanny
launched a writing career. Her first book, ``Domestic Manners of
the Americans,'' a gossipy, critical, humorous account of her
travels, was an immediate sensation on both sides of the Atlantic,
though not for the same reason. British readers relished Fanny's
portrait of their boorish, benighted, bigoted American cousins.
American readers wanted to hang her, but they bought her book, and
they talked and argued about it, and about her, for years.
</P>
<P>
   Fanny went from success to success, writing novels, romances,
travel books. Misfortune dogged her personal life. Three more of
her children succumbed to tuberculosis. Only Anthony and Tom
survived her. Four of her grandchildren died of the same disease.
Her husband's disposition worsened. She found a refuge in her work;
for 24 years her writing pace never flagged. She began working at
4:30 every morning, so she could be done with her day's writing
before the rest of her family awoke. She was 77 when her last book,
``Fashionable Life; or Paris and London'' was published, in 1856.
She died at 83.
</P>
<P>
   Neville-Sington took her subtitle from one of Fanny's later
novels, ``The Life and Adventures of a Clever Woman,'' but the word
``clever'' barely begins to descibe her subject. Fanny emerges from
these pages as amazingly resourceful, tough, courageous, ambitious,
good-hearted, good-humored, loving, likable, wonderful company. She
never cared for fashion; her manners were sometimes rough. Her
independent spirit was far from the Victorian ideal of womanhood.
She was a woman ahead of her time, in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Most of her books were meant to amuse, but she also tackled
controversial subjects. She wrote the first anti-slavery novel,
``The Life and Adventures of Jonathan Jefferson Whitlaw'' (1836),
as well as a novel about the wretched lives of England's working
poor, ``The Life and Adventures of Michael Armstrong, the Factory
Boy'' (1840).
</P>
<P>
   Fanny made no apologies for writing for the masses. Some critics
sniffed at her books and called them vulgar, but she was popular
with readers. Neville-Sington notes numerous similarities between
Fanny's work and that of her son. Each possessed a lively wit and a
keen eye for human foibles. They mined the same literary ground,
and many of the same experiences. Neville-Sington's research
reveals that the son freely borrowed characters and plots from the
mother, though he never acknowledged it.
</P>
<P>
   Neville-Sington believes Anthony Trollope was to blame, in part
at least, for the decline of his mother's popularity as an author.
In his own ``An Autobiography'' _ published in 1883, 20 years after
his mother's death _ Trollope condemned her novels in harsh, almost
spiteful terms. Neville-Sington writes, ``Mrs. Trollope's novels
suddenly ceased to be published. Anthony had, in effect, buried his
mother's literary reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony's resentment of his mother is probably understandable,
for a number of reasons. Neville-Sington suggests that he may never
have gotten over his anger and disappointment at being left behind
when Fanny traveled to America. He also complained that she didn't
encourage him in his writing, though Neville-Sington presents
evidence to the contrary. But perhaps no amount of maternal
encouragement could have satisfied the shy, insecure Anthony.
Neville-Sington speculates that the main reason behind his
mean-spirited treatment of her may have been her reputation as a
``coarse'' and ``vulgar'' writer of popular fiction. Anthony
aspired to, and achieved, greater things. He may have wanted to
distance himself from her.
</P>
<P>
   Neville-Sington writes that without his mother's example and
support, Anthony might never have been able to launch his literary
career in the first place. She believes he paid tribute to her in
his own way: ``Although in his memoirs Anthony could not bring
himself to be as generous to his mother as perhaps he ought to have
been, he honors her with the innumerable strong-willed and
brave-hearted women who appear in his fiction. I like to think that
one of Anthony's best-loved creations, Glencora Palliser, is a
conscious and deliberate portrait of his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
