<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Dec. 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ Iraq's vice president says his country
is challenging no-flight zones by flying its own warplanes there.
By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   Other Iraq as needed.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS (Phnom Penh) _ Meeting with both foreign and
Cambodian reporters, the two top Khmer Rouge defectors apologize
for mass killings of the Pol Pot era, but ask Cambodians to ``let
bygones be bygones.'' By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Strasbourg) _ The launch of a new currency, the euro, on
Friday represents the single most important change on the Continent
since the end of the Cold War. In getting to this point, 11
European nations have for the first time adopted a common economic
policy that has reined in public spending, reduced debt and tamed
inflation. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ China says it has sent two more
dissidents to labor camps, two U.S.-based dissidents who sneaked
back into the China.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-MILITARY (Jakarta) _ Armed forces chief says military
will stay out of next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments on impeachment: Republican
House managers meet to plan strategy for their Senate role; other
developments. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   Other impeachment as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-SOUTH (Dateline to kum, Ga.) _ In last month's election,
Rep. Sanford D. Bishop Jr., a moderate black Democrat, won
re-election convincingly in a rural, conservative district where
nearly two-thirds of the voters are white. Many black politicians
have managed to attract white support in urban, New South areas
like Atlanta. But Bishop's electoral success demonstrates that even
in the most rural and impoverished districts, a significant number
of white Southerners no longer view race as an absolute obstacle to
voting for a black politician who shares their thinking, votes
their interests and hauls home plenty of pork. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-SHOOTING (Riverside, Calif.) _ The police chief here
promised a full investigation after officers killed a 19-year-old
woman by firing at least 27 bullets as she sat locked in a car with
a flat tire. By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-BOMB (Oklahoma City) _ Grand jurors investigating
accusations of a wider conspiracy in the Oklahoma City bombing are
nearly ready to issue their report, the judge overseeing the case
said today. By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DEBT (London) _ Russia is expected to again default on
some of its foreign debt. Debt holders expect Russia to miss a
payment on bonds that were issued in late 1997 to restructure debt
inherited from the Soviet Union. On Aug. 17, Russia defaulted on
what is now about $10 billion in domestic debt; at issue now is a
request Russia made last month to creditors that they accept new
bonds in lieu of a $362 million cash interest payment on its
principal notes. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-CARS (Undated) _ Gasoline prices have plunged and sales of
sport utility vehicles are soaring, yet many of the world's biggest
auto makers have made the seemingly unconventional decision to
introduce new models of small cars in the United States in the
coming months. The interest in small cars reflects a shift in how
auto makers look at small cars. Disappearing are the economy boxes.
In their place will be more expensive models that look and perform
like short versions of mid-size cars. The new small cars will also
have almost as much interior room as mid-size cars, thanks to
higher roofs. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly business travel column.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RATES (Tokyo) _ Japanese banks will raise mortgage rates
as much as 0.85 percentage point, more bad news for the nation's
consumers. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was off 16
points, or 0.2 percent, and the Nasdaq index was down 13 points, or
0.6 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 1 percent in Tokyo and 0.6
percent in Hong Kong. They fell 0.1 percent in Frankfurt but rose
0.9 percent in London. Stocks were down 3 percent in Brazil and 0.3
percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond was
down 3/32 point, with the yield at 5.16 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
