<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-COLETTE-BOS &LR;      12-29 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COLETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLETTE: MYTH AND NAUGHTY INUENDO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
CREATING COLETTE 
Volume I: From Ingenue to Libertine, 1873-1913 
By Claude Francis and Fernande Gontier 
Steerforth Press, 367 pp., illustrated, $32 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the end of her exuberant life, the writer the world would
come to celebrate as Colette once remarked, ``They have of me an
old stereotype image.'' Were such words uttered by anyone else, the
comment could be regarded as the lament of someone branded by a
youthful indiscretion or a rueful reflection on a stubborn
impression that forever obscured the truth.
</P>
<P>
   But coming from the woman born Sidonie-Gabrielle Colette, it is
hard to imagine her making such a statement without a sly, telling
twinkle in her eye. Whatever perception the public holds of the
famed French writer is an image carefully cultivated and crafted by
Colette herself. By the time of her death at age 81 in 1954,
Colette was more icon than woman, swaddled in grand myth and
naughty innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   And she probably wouldn't have wanted it any other way. Hers was
a life lived full, a great hungry thing greedy to experience
everything the world had to offer. A renaissance woman, she made
her name as a writer of such novels as ``Gigi,'' later made into a
1958 musical starring Leslie Caron, Maurice Chevalier, and his
signature song, ``Thank Heaven for Little Girls.'' Her ``Claudine''
novels sparked a social revolution that redefined attitudes and
social expression. But she is perhaps best remembered for her
myriad love affairs with both men and women, and her free-thinking,
convention-be-damned style that made Paris burn. A woman who all
but created the jet-set lifestyle of mad parties and holy
indulgence, Colette was what Madonna thinks she is.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder then that such a life could not be contained
within a single book. ``Creating Colette: From Ingenue to
Libertine, 1973-1913,'' details the first 40 years of Colette's
life, and if this first volume is any indication, this may well
become the definitive biography of the woman who seemed to live a
life-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   Authors Claude Francis and Fernande Gontier have also tackled
biographies of Simone de Beauvoir and Marcel Proust. But they have
met their greatest challenge in Colette, and perform a masterful
job of sifting through the myths and deconstructing the fictions,
many of which Colette perpetuated. Conversely, they also give
credence to some of her claims, especially regarding her heritage.
</P>
<P>
   For most of her life, and in fact even in death, many have
dismissed Colette's contention that she had black Caribbean
ancestors. Some have accused the nonbelievers of racism, but given
Colette's ability to spin colorful tales of half-truths, it is more
likely that some simply took anything she said with a grain of
salt. As the authors write, ``A genius at self-promotion, Colette
had become the mythical figure she and a collective act of faith
had created.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was merit in her assertions of mixed heritage. Francis
and Gontier trace Colette's lineage to 1792, and her
great-grandfather Robert Landois, a wealthy mulatto from
Martinique. There is also a four-page appendix dealing solely with
Landois, and how documentation of Colette's heritage became
obscured. Even more attention is paid to Colette's mother, Adele
Eugenie Sidonie ``Sido'' Landois, who shaped her daughter's liberal
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Colette was born Jan. 28, 1873, and for someone who so enjoyed
the world, she took her own sweet time coming into it. Sido was in
labor for three days, and her daughter was born ``all blue and
silent.'' According to Colette, it was ``my own self-determination
and sheer will which started my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sido and her husband, Captain Jules-Joseph Colette, a war hero
who lost a leg fighting with Napoleon, imbued their daughter with
an early appreciation of the finer things; she was barely 3 the
first time she tasted wine. She would later write: ``Daintily, I
drained the best of my father's cellar goblet by goblet.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Colette married her first husband, Henry
Gauthier-Villars, a writer who would both help and hinder her
literary aspirations, she was already immersed in a life of free
love and sexual experimentation. She thought of herself as
``unisexual,'' and possesser of ``the extraordinary soul of an
intelligent man and of a passionate woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis and Gontier take great pains to highlight Colette's
reputation as a writer who excelled as an essayist as well as a
novelist. It is valid to do so since, in 1954, Colette became the
first female French writer awarded a state funeral. But it is the
life of the woman _ unbridled, risk-taking, and liberated _ that
resonates and provides a delicious, vicarious thrill for us in
these far more cautious, conservative times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colette not only wrote but openly lived according to her
beliefs,'' her biograpers write. `` . . . Colette, for 81 years,
six months, and six days, feasted on life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
