<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-JANE-BOS &LR;      12-29 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JANE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING A FRIEND, GAINING PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE EVOLUTION OF JANE 
By Cathleen Schine 
Houghton Mifflin, 210 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title of Cathleen Schine's perceptive comedy of manners,
``The Evolution of Jane,'' might lead one to expect the central
character to undergo a profound change over the course of the
story. The evolution Jane experiences is a subtle one, a slight but
crucial mutation, as understated as Schine's style.
</P>
<P>
   At 25, Jane Barlow is a self-obsessed young woman, recently
divorced, who sets off to tour the Galapagos Islands. The trip is
her mother's idea. She thinks Jane needs to ``go abroad'' in order
to heal. Jane doesn't feel wounded by her divorce. She's happier
without her husband. What's really eating at Jane is the loss of
her best friend, her cousin Martha. Jane has spent 10 years
mourning the dissolution of their friendship, wondering what went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever lost a friend?'' the novel begins. ``It is the
saddest and most baffling experience. No one sympathizes, unless
the friend dies, which she did not. I lost my best friend many
years ago. She had been my best friend for a decade, for more than
half my childhood, and then she evaporated, as though she had never
really existed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Off Jane goes to the Galapagos, a destination she's dreamed of
visiting since girlhood, when her fascination with Charles Darwin
began: ``Whenever I hear his name, to this day, I experience a
sudden alertness, as if my own name has been spoken.'' Jane muses
on the concept of species. What is a species? Who decides? Why are
some species more successful than others?
</P>
<P>
   Like the central characters in Schine's previous books,
``Rameau's Niece'' and ``The Love Letter,'' Jane probes the Big
Philosophical Questions and complains (some might say whines) about
life's problems. Schine's heroines are all-too-human, self-doubting
and self-deluding, and sympathetic. We can laugh at them, and at
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   When Jane arrives in Baltra, one of the Galapagos Islands, she
finds Martha holding a sign with the name of her tour group. Now a
naturalist, Martha has a job with the Ecuadorian parks service,
leading tours. She will be Jane's ``Galapagos hostess.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha is friendly to Jane, but doesn't want to talk about their
past. Jane trails around after Martha, drinking in her knowledge of
Galapagos flora and fauna, all the while wondering what happened
between them to sever their friendship. They had been more than
friends, more than cousins, more like twins, so close they seemed
to be two halves of a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to ask Martha . . . why she stopped being my friend.
I wanted to ask her if she would be my friend again. Of course I
could do neither. One has one's pride. Anyway, how could she
explain the end of something that itself had no explanation? `What
is the evolutionary reason for friendship?' I said to her. `Good
 &UR; morning &LR;  to you too, Jane,' she said, laughing. `And evolution
doesn't have reasons. It's opportunistic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jane, in her obsessive way, recalls the details of their
friendship, searching for clues, for possible offenses on her part
that might explain Martha's disappearance from her life. She mulls
over their family history, examining a mysterious feud between
Martha's parents and her own. What was it about? Could it explain
Martha's rejection of her?
</P>
<P>
   Darwin's transcendent ideas about evolutionary change are
everywhere in ``The Evolution of Jane.'' Jane tries to use
Darwinian concepts to explain the nature and meaning of friendship.
She runs her ideas by her roommate, Gloria, who tells her that she
sees Martha as a vestigial organ to Jane. Jane says: ``Martha is
not a vestigial organ. . . . I think of Martha as a sort of echt
friend. . . . The model on which all other friends must be based.
And so this entire shipload of strangers has partaken of her
essence.''
</P>
<P>
   That shipload of strangers, Jane's fellow tourists, includes a
number of first-rate eccentrics, characters who may seem a bit
over-contrived, except to readers who've been on group tours.
Schine makes evocative and interesting use of her story's setting,
the starkly beautiful home of the giant tortoise and the
blue-footed booby, among many rare species.
</P>
<P>
   Jane's persistent intellectual probing can't, of course, lead
her to the evolutionary reason for friendship, ``this oddest of all
organisms.'' But it gives her a fresh appreciation of Darwin's
wisdom and, more important, it leads her to understand the nature
of her friendship with Martha, and to self-understanding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
