<HEADER>
A0222 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR &LR;      12-29 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSBOOKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS, UNLIKE TOYS, DON'T BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whew! Having survived Christmas, parents now face the challenge
of finding something wholesome for the kids to do when the new toys
break, batteries run down or boredom sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Try a book or two. Here are some of the standouts among recent
releases. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ONE, TWO, SKIP A FEW! FIRST NUMBER RHYMES &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Roberta Arenson (Barefoot Books, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   Arizona artist Arenson uses collages and watercolors to
illustrate 20 counting rhymes familiar to several generations:
``There were 10 in the bed, And the little one said: `Roll over,
roll over;' '' ``Four little fishes swimming out to sea, One met a
shark! And then there were three.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids enjoy reciting the rhymes and might even pick up some
counting tips. The pictures, which have a folk art quality to them,
feature children of all races, not to mention frogs, elephants,
chicks, cows and monkeys. For ages 2-5. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT IF THE ZEBRAS LOST THEIR STRIPES? &QL; 
 &UR; John Reitano; illustrated by William Haines (Paulist Press, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   What would happen if zebras suddenly split into two types: all
black or all white? Would they still be friends? Would they live in
separate zebra lands? Would their children play together?
</P>
<P>
   This parable about prejudice is charmingly written and
delightfully illustrated. Reitano's simple narrative is easy to
read, without being preachy. Haines' vivid pictures of jungle
animals are active and bold.
</P>
<P>
   Sure to spark discussion, this volume is a worthy addition to
classroom and home libraries. For ages 4-6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SPOT'S BEDTIME STORYBOOK &QL; 
 &UR; Eric Hill (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $12.99)
</P>
<P>
   The ever-popular Spot, a favorite character of early readers, is
featured in this 10-story collection. Stories include ``Spot's
Windy Day,'' ``Spot in the Snow,'' ``Spot at the Fair,'' and
``Sweet Dreams, Spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The puppy appeals to young children because his day goes a lot
like theirs. He's got a Mom who warns him not to get muddy when he
goes out to play because she just finished cleaning the house, a
Grandpa who is sporting enough to ride bumper cars, and two close
friends, Helen and Tom, a hippo and an alligator.
</P>
<P>
   Strong, primary colors carry the illustrations. The text is
written in short, declarative sentences with lots of dialogue. For
ages 4-6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CARIBBEAN DREAM &QL; 
 &UR; Rachel Isadora (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $15.99)
</P>
<P>
   Take a trip to an island in the West Indies, where children run,
splash, fish, dance and sing in the tropics. Isadora, a
professional ballerina turned children's writer and illustrator,
has won awards for previous works. Her realistic, warm watercolors
capture joyful play, with an exotic Caribbean twist. For ages 4-6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BASKETBALL BUDDIES &QL; 
 &UR; Jean and Dan Marzollo; illustrated by True Kelley (Scholastic,
$3.50)
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic's ``Hello Reader!'' selections help kids hone their
reading skills by focusing on subjects of interest to them. The
inexpensive paperback series has grade-level guidelines to help
adults make selections.
</P>
<P>
   In this piece, ``Too Tall Paul'' is teased about his height by
other kids, and he feels like all feet on the basketball court. But
he keeps practicing, and learns how to use his height as an asset.
On the day of the big game _ guess who saves the day? For ages
5-7. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE WAITING PLACE &QL; 
 &UR; Marc Sutherland (Abrams, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Dr. Seuss book ``Oh, The Places You'll Go!,'' in
which the sticky ``waiting place'' immobilizes people who are just,
well, waiting for something to happen? How about Maurice Sendak's
``Where the Wild Things Are,'' about a recalcitrant boy whose
flight of fancy takes him beyond the confines of his room? Put them
together and you have this imaginative tale.
</P>
<P>
   A young boy who can't fall asleep entertains himself by
imagining a series of adventures: marching with soldiers of the
Queen of England; playing chess with a gryphon and floating on
slippery seas with Vikings. The story is told in an appealing
rhyme, and the intricate charcoal illustrations are unusual,
bordering on bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland, a land surveyor and forester, says the moral of the
book is: ``If for some reason you find yourself in an unpleasant
situation, dream of better places and then go make them real.'' For
ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MY TOWN &QL; 
 &UR; William Wegman (Hyperion, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   Wegman's hilarious weimaraners, popularized on ``Sesame
Street,'' spoof every schoolchild's challenge: searching for an
original book report topic. ``Chip'' dons the garb of several
occupations, appearing as a potter, school crossing guard,
construction worker and grocery clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting weimaraner characters like the school librarian, town
doctor and local barber offer Chip help along the way. Just as he
nears panic, Chip realizes that his report doesn't have to be in
writing. A photo essay about the town folks is just the ticket! Get
ready for giggles. For ages 4-8. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FINDING OUT ABOUT WHALES &QL; 
 &UR; Elin Kelsey (Owl Books, $9.95)
</P>
<P>
   Beluga whales are such expert mimics they can even repeat bird
calls. Some male killer whales live with their moms their whole
lives. Blue whales are the largest animals in the world, exceeding
the size of a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Fun facts about the world's most awe-inspiring creatures fill
this paperback, the first volume in the new ``Science Explorers''
series that not only tells what we know but how we know it.
Scientists and researchers explain their findings about various
species of whales, which are shown in dramatic pictures. A great
pick for budding marine biologists and undersea explorers. For ages
8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE SOUL: THE FAMILY STORYBOOK COLLECTION &QL; 
 &UR; Lisa McCourt; illustrated by Pat Grant Porter (Health
Communications,
 &UR; $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Nobody does schmalz like the ``Chicken Soup'' folks. This
collection assembles the best of the best for kids: ``The Goodness
Gorillas,'' ``The Best Night Out With Dad'' and ``The Never
Forgotten Doll.'' The themes show how kindness turns a school bully
into a friend, generosity seals a friendship, and thoughtfulness
brightens an elderly woman's birthday. Action-packed illustrations
capture the emotions that bring the points home. For ages 8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE CHILDREN'S BOOK OF AMERICA &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by William J. Bennett; illustrated by Michael Hague (Simon &AMP;
 &UR; Schuster, $21)
</P>
<P>
   From the pilgrims to Neil Armstrong, America's heroes are
celebrated in 17 stories, songs, poems and folk tales. Bennett, a
former cabinet officer, based his selections on stories that show
how perseverance, ingenuity, hard work and compassion shaped
American history and its character.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King's dream, Paul Bunyan's ox, and young Abe
Lincoln's love of books are chronicled. Interspersed are songs and
verses, among them ``America the Beautiful,'' ``I Hear America
Singing,'' and ``Home on the Range.'' Beautiful realistic
illustrations and top-quality production make this large-format
treasury a keepsake volume about Americana. For ages 8-12. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Reach correspondent Beverly Medlyn at bevmedlyn(at)aol.com, via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
