<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-RADIO-BOS &LR;      12-29 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-RADIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE LAST PURVEYOR OF `GREAT AMERICAN SONGBOOK' BIDS FAREWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 700,000 listeners of New York radio station WQEW-AM are
about to experience their own version of The Decline and Fall of
Western Civilization. Anyone not abreast of the station's current
circumstance will receive a jolt to the senses when he or she tunes
this week expecting to hear a selection from the Great American
Songbook and instead encounters something known as Disney Radio.
</P>
<P>
   WQEW, 1560 on the AM dial, bills itself, and rightly so, as
``The Home of American Popular Standards.'' This is where the great
treasure trove of popular songs that represent, in the opinion of
many, America's ``classical music'' are heard around the clock.
This is not some treacly ``Music of Your Life'' station. What one
hears on WQEW is, to borrow a phrase, the good turtle soup, not
merely the mock.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the format has been under assault for the past three
decades, but it has been firmly established in New York, first on
the legendary WNEW and, since 1992, on WQEW. But come midnight
Monday (Dec. 28), in the city where so much of this music was
written and first performed, in America's entertainment capital, in
the ``New York, New York'' of Sinatra, his voice will no longer be
heard. Disney has paid the station's owner, The New York Times, a
staggering $40 million for an eight-year lease in order to replace
Sinatra with Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)No Tony Bennett. No Mel Torme. No Joe Williams.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   And no Jonathan Schwartz, who, more than anyone else, is the
public face of the station and the music in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is a tragedy filled with joy,'' sighs Schwartz. ``WQEW
was a joy.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)No Irving Berlin. No Cole Porter. No Richard Rodgers. No
George Gershwin.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   When WQEW changes its format, the most prominent casualties will
be Schwartz's ``Sinatra Saturday Show,'' which is the Granada to
all those Asbury Parks on other stations, and his incomparable
five-hour Sunday show, which has served as a loving tutorial for
his enraptured listeners without interruption since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the capital of American music, to lose this show is
obscene,'' declares local music critic James Isaacs, himself a
much-missed presence on our own airwaves. ``There is no show in
America that mixes classic American pop standards with show music,
jazz, contemporary music, and even classical music from the
perspective of someone who knows all about the music and
performers, and who is a published novelist and short-story
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)No Judy Garland. No Ella Fitzgerald. No Billie Holiday.
No Sarah Vaughan.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   What is so utterly frustrating about all this to those whom it
will most affect is that WQEW is not a sick station. In a recent
book, WQEW placed a healthy 19th out of 70 stations in overall
listenership. There remains an audience for this music.
</P>
<P>
   But it's strictly business. ``If someone offered me $40 million
for this station,'' says Schwartz, ``I'd certainly take it.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)No Fred Astaire. No Billy Eckstine. No Louis Armstrong.
No Bing Crosby.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, who has financial backers, is actively engaged in
seeking another spot on the dial for this cherished American art
form. Meanwhile, he has become affiliated with Lincoln Center,
where he has put together upcoming tributes to composers Harold
Arlen in February, and Richard Rodgersin March. With the benefit of
just one newspaper ad, each sold out in seven hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my experience with music, ballet and theatre,'' says
Nat Levanthal, president of Lincoln Center, ``I have never seen
such an immediate reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, someone in New York wishes to hear American treasures
Barbara Cook and Maureen McGovern swap choruses of Arlen companion
pieces ``Hooray For Love'' and ``Down With Love.'' Clearly, someone
in New York is interested in spending a few hours being entertained
by the music of geniuses such as Arlen and Rodgers, whose 27th-best
melody would represent someone else's career masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)No Lorenz Hart. No Ira Gershwin. No Oscar Hammerstein II.
No Johnny Mercer.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The effect of losing WQEW will be catastrophic for performers,
since this station is nothing less than the home office for what
is, arguably, America's most enduring artistic creation. ``This
station has served me and my records very well,'' says guitarist
and singer John Pizzarelli. ``They have been playing me, not once a
week, but several times a day since 1983. I just did six weeks in
Las Vegas, and once or twice a night someone would come up to me
and say, `I hear you on Jonathan all the time.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And it is not just old people. Thanks to this station, the
music is being kept alive for people under 40. This is not a dead
art form. People are out there doing it, making a living from it. I
am living proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Ron Della Chiesa introduced Rebecca Parris to an
approving New England audience via his irreplaceable ``Music
America'' program on WGBH-FM, so, too, has Schwartz created
audiences for a number of deserving performers, including the
gifted Pizzarelli and a talented singer named Nancy LaMott, whose
career he championed on the air before her untimely death nearly
two years ago. A radio station can be a powerful vehicle for
entertainment good, and the ultimate winners are, of course, the
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing WQEW would be devastating,'' agrees Cook. ``This is one
of the ways those of us in the cabaret field get new fans and new
listeners. Someone will hear something and say, `Who's that? What's
that song?' Where will this music be heard now? What am I going to
listen to? This is all hard to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)No ``Oklahoma.'' No ``Guys And Dolls.'' No ``My Fair
Lady.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   This is the music of our century. It is the music that carried
America through two world wars, the music that was the seed of an
entity known as American musical theater, the music that inspired
thousands of brilliant composers, lyricists, and singers who, when
the history of this century is recorded, may very well represent
the most valuable and appreciated of all American exports.
</P>
<P>
   No ``Cheek To Cheek.'' No ``Lady Is a Tramp.'' No ``Night Aand
Day.'' No ``All The Things You Are.''
</P>
<P>
   One week from Monday (Jan. 4, 199) there will be a spot on the
radio dial in our most influential city for news, a spot for
business, a spot for sports, a spot for talk, a spot for classical,
a spot for country, and a spot for straight jazz, a spot for scores
of ethnic groups, a spot for Elvis, a spot for Wu-Tang Clan and
many spots for Bare Naked Ladies, but there will be no spot for
Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a preview of what's in store for us after the
millenium, the 21st is shaping up to be a bad century.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
