A0229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-BJT-COX     12-29 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-BJT-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM ADVISORY
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: NEWS, FEATURE, RELIGION EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   Here are budget lines for the first installment of the Cox
Millennium package on the 2000th anniversary of Christianity. It is
running in two parts, the first on Sunday, Dec. 27, the second on
Saturday, Jan. 2. CoxNet will produce a full-page layout for each
of these two parts:
</P>
<P>
   This package is for Sunday, Dec. 27: MOVED LAST WEEK
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-OVERVIEW _ Almost 2,000 years ago, a man named Jesus
was born and the world changed forever. The impact of Jesus echoes
through the millennia. It has profoundly changed the way people
view God, the world and each other. Over the next two weeks, and
the coming year, Cox Newspapers will take a look at Jesus, focusing
on the spread of Christianity, first in and around its homeland in
the Mideast, later through Europe and the Americas, and ultimatley
around the world. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CHRISTIANS _ JERUSALEM _ Despite their urban settings
and the politics that engulfs them 2000 years later, the sites
where Christ was born, lived and died are still powerful ``faith
strengtheners'' for millions of Christians world wide. Visits to
the region by Christians _ and they constitute about 75 percent of
Israel's 2.3 million annual tourists _ remind them that Jesus was
human and the ideals he practiced can be practiced by others. The
physical sites still make Jesus' story real. Christian
denominations have picked their favorite spots. Catholics come to
Jerusalem's Old City, where they often rent wooden crosses and walk
the supposed path Jesus took with his cross. Traditional
Protestants gravitate toward the Church of the Nativity and
Evangelicals head for prayer nearby in the Shepherd's Fields.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service) 35.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-SCENES _ JERUSALEM _ Short vignettes from the places
where Jesus was born, lived and died, focusing on what they look
like today, what visitors think of them and how they fit into
today's political, social landscape. (Kaplow, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday, Jan. 2: MOVED TODAY
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-FUTURE _ BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ There is a new trend
in this old city. For about a year, Christians have been putting
crosses, usually lit electrically, on their homes and shops. It is
largely seen as a sign of a population that is free, but is a
minority and feels insecure. Christians are a divided minority. In
Israel, Arab Christians benefit from a healthier economy and some
even serve in the Israeli army. In Palestinian areas, they face a
military occupation and a stagnant economy _ driving many to
emigrate to the United States. But, 2000 years after it was founded
here, it would be a mistake to predict Christianity's demise in the
Holy Land. (Kaplow, Cox News Service) 25.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-SYRIAC _ JERUSALEM _ Two thousand years later, you
can still
</P>
<P>
   hear the language. About 3,000 Syriac Christians cling to their
lifestyle in the walled city of Jerusalem and still practice
religion in Aramaic, the language of Christ. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service) 20.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-AMERICA _ Two thousand years after Jesus's birth, the
relationship between his native people, the Jews, and his
followers, the Christians, is complex. Some evangelical Christians
are Zionists, believing that the Temple in Jerusalem must be
rebuilt so that Jesus can come again. But some of these same people
think they must proselytize the Jews. A look at American Christian
attitudes toward Israel and its people. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 30.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MILLENNIUM COVERAGE:
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, Jan. 3: MOVING WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MILLENNIUM _ C'mon, you're not going to usher in the new
millenium by popping the top on a Pink Champale and staring at Dick
Clark on the TV, are you? This once-in-a-lifetime event demands a
once-in-a-lifetime celebration, whether it's frolicking with a
million pagans in the California desert or sipping Dom Perignon in
your own private Times Square hotel, yours for the low rental price
of $3 million. We've spanned the globe, or at least plowed through
a mountain of brochures, to bring you the wackiest, weirdest, most
daring and most extravagant millennium parties. Call it Y2K _ 2 the
extreme. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
