<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANITIZING A CITY, A STREET AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The City Council of Davis, California, the
bicycle helmet and political correctness capital of the world
(sorry, Berkeley), has decided to retroactively punish a dead man
because of his moral failures.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis City Council voted to change the name of Sutter Place
to Shasta Way because a retired history professor told them that
famed California pioneer John A. Sutter was ``an immoral man, a
sexual predator, a rapist and an enslaver of native Californians.''
</P>
<P>
   A biographer of Sutter, Richard Dillon, said that the
Swiss-German settler of the Sacramento Valley may have consorted
with women other than his wife (probably not an indictable offense
in a college town like Davis), but said Sutter was not a rapist, a
sexual predator or an enslaver of Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Sutter's virtues or vices, the City Council of
Davis has made a great advance in government _ one that the
Republican Party could follow.
</P>
<P>
   It now can judge the morality or immorality of the dead, and the
dead can't sue or hire spinmeisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the years before the discovery of gold, (Sutter) was
perhaps the most important and most colorful character in
California,'' wrote Erwin Goode in ``California Place Names.''
</P>
<P>
   After the discovery of gold, California was inundated by
colorful characters, many of them immoral by somebody's standards,
and now immortalized on street signs.
</P>
<P>
   Street-sign purification, and punishing the dead, are mighty
tasks.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans adopted the Davis strategy of punishing
immoral dead persons, they could wait to impeach President Clinton
after he dies, when the odds of the comeback kid coming back are
much smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Impeach a dead president? The Republicans are making it up as
they go along, anyway. Also, they keep saying Clinton is dead, and
it keeps turning out he isn't. They should wait for the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators on the left have been trying to nail Thomas
Jefferson on morals charges for years. They finally got him with
DNA evidence, and they didn't even have a blue dress.
</P>
<P>
   Now a family in Chicago has renewed hope of proving it's
descended from an affair between George Washington and one of his
slaves, named Venus. If this family manages to make its case, just
think. Using the Davis precedent, we can rename Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Mudville might be more fitting, regardless of whom the father of
our country fathered.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of the Davis action for San Francisco are even
more staggering than they are for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   For years the Board of Supervisors has been condemning the
living for their immorality. They usually direct their resolutions
at dictatorships other than the one in San Francisco, though.
</P>
<P>
   Now they can pass condemnatory resolutions locally. San
Francisco has a huge population of the immoral dead, especially by
the supes' standards of immorality.
</P>
<P>
   Kearny and Stockton streets would be gone, as would Sloat
Boulevard, because they're named for officers who took part in the
immoral Mexican War.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter Street would get a nice Native American name like Shasta,
of course. Shasta was a tribe, not a soda, incidentally. Forget
anything named Funston _ this was the general in command during the
Earthquake and Fire, but there's also the matter of the imperialist
Spanish-American War, in which he played a role.
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac could lose his alley because he hated anti-war
protesters and was in denial about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus Avenue? Sorry, you'll be drinking your Columbian on
Indigenous People's Street. You can be darn sure Broadway would be
something else, too.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is famous for street-name fights, like the long
battle over Cesar Chavez Street. That was a tough one. It would be
easier to bring morals charges against forgotten people on street
signs.
</P>
<P>
   You know how it is in the new West. All you have to do is make
an accusation, and the next thing you know, the guy's name isn't
hanging from a lamppost anymore.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, who was the city of Davis named for? Perhaps the
Davis City Council should look into this. The city was named for
Jerome Davis, a rancher in the 1850s who owned 400 acres of land,
where he grew wheat and oats, had orchards and vineyards and grazed
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   If the evidence shows that Jerome Davis slaughtered and ate
those cattle, the Davis City Council could be pressured by its
large animal-rights constituency to change the name of its own
city.
</P>
<P>
   How about Bicycletia?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
