<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
APES-MOVIES (Los Angeles) _ In Disney's new film ``Mighty Joe
Young,'' Charlize Theron snuggles in the big furry arms of the
giant doe-eyed Joe and sings him a lullaby. This tender scene is
just another example of Hollywood's continuing love affair with our
nearest biological relatives _ the great apes. By Jon Gerun. 
. 
HILO-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``I once set out to kill someone,''
says a grim-faced young man in the opening moments of the
strikingly beautiful new cowboy movie ``The Hi-Lo Country.'' The
line establishes a sort of western noir tone from the outset, but
the movie actually has a lot more to offer. 3 Stars. By Glenn
Whipp. 
. 
HILARY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Those nutty musical geniuses. So
egocentric, so demanding, so weird. Good thing they tend to suffer
from severe medical imbalances. Otherwise, how could we sympathize
with them through a whole movie? ``Hilary and Jackie'' is the
latest in the ``Shine''-inspired line of films about oddball
classical musicians. 3 stars. By Bob Strauss 
. 
AFFLICTION-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Nick Nolte has played so many
raging losers in his career that you'd think he'd have exhausted
his insight into the condition long ago. ``Affliction'' suggests
that the pit of despair Nolte draws from is bottomless. 3 stars. By
Bob Strauss. 
. 
PARADISE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ You'd think that word would be out
on the motel grapevine about Mel and Sid. Every time this
pharmaceutical Bonnie and Clyde checks into a place in ``Another
Day in Paradise,'' somebody seems to wind up dead either by shotgun
or overdose. 3 stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
TALKIN-RADIO (Los Angeles) _ At its most essential, radio is a
timekeeper _ a device for entertainment but also for marking time.
Funny how so many radio folk forget that tiny fact in the current
blizzard of multi-million-dollar takeover deals, high-priced
syndication efforts and ever-expanding egos. By Fred Shuster. 
. 

