<HEADER>
A0282 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARADISE-REVIEW-LADN     12-29 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADISE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH `PARADISE,' NO NEED TO THINK TWICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You'd think that word would be out on the motel
grapevine about Mel and Sid. Every time this pharmaceutical Bonnie
and Clyde checks into a place in ``Another Day in Paradise,''
somebody seems to wind up dead either by shotgun or overdose. And
these guys never hang around long enough to pay the carpet-cleaning
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Mel (James Woods) is a petty thief who thinks of himself as some
kind of highwayman philosopher. Sid (Melanie Griffith) is his
beautiful junkie accomplice, handy with a needle and a firearm.
``Another Day in Paradise'' is about what happens when this wayward
couple decides to take a couple of kids (and since this movie is
directed by Larry Clark, you know what kind of ``Kids'' we're
talking about) on the road with them for a spree of heists, drug
deals and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Day in Paradise'' demonstrates Clark's maturation as a
visceral filmmaker, someone with the courage of his convictions,
which, in this case, means showing a world populated by people with
a complete lack of convictions. In the end, this film amounts to
little more than just another junkie-thugs-on-the-run movie (and
one starring Woods doing yet another variation on his tough-guy
routine), but it's a well-made one with some snappy performances,
crackling confrontations and a down-and-dirty Stax soul soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The movie opens with a bracing, nickel-and-dime (literally)
robbery as emaciated teen-age Bobby (Vincent Kartheiser) breaks
into a community college and shakes down a couple of vending
machines for a weighty bag of coins. The job doesn't quite go off
as planned, though, and soon Bobby is dragging his skeletal frame
(and the change) back to his squalid flat, bruised, battered and
hemorrhaging.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby lives with his gaunt girlfriend, Rosie (Natasha Gregson
Wagner), and Danny, another drugged-out youth. With the teens'
spindly, heroin-chic look, the place could well double as the
setting of a Calvin Klein perfume advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   To get Bobby back on his feet, Rosie calls Danny's uncle, Mel,
who arrives bearing bandages and syringes. Bobby, in a daze, asks
Mel if he's a doctor. ``Yeah, I'm a doctor, kid,'' Mel answers.
``I'm a doctor shooting you up with heroin.'' Soon Bobby is well
enough to sit up in bed and watch the snowy interference on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Mel sees something in Bobby and proposes they go into business
together. Soon, Bobby and Rosie, Mel and Sid are cruising America's
highways and byways in Mel's magnificent Coupe de Ville, stealing,
shooting up and making new friends. (There's a particularly
riveting episode involving a group of thugs called Hitler's
Henchmen.)
</P>
<P>
   It isn't surprising that Bobby and Rosie start seeing Mel and
Sid as role models, especially given what we learn of Bobby's
abusive father through a brief flashback. But it's just as
inevitable given the source material (Eddie Little's book) and
Clark's penchant for realism that this is one dysfunctional family
that isn't going to live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   Woods could play this gun-toting jerk in his sleep, and while
Griffith, too, isn't exactly breaking new ground, it is nice to see
her flexing her acting muscles in a smart, tough role. The kids
(Kartheiser and Gregson Wagner) cover the most emotional ground,
and they cover it well.
</P>
<P>
   Clark fills the rest of the movie with an array of weird
characters, including James Otis as a gun-selling minister who will
cast out Satan while handing over a Saturday night special. To
quote one of the soundtrack's many gritty grooves, he's ``some kind
of wonderful,'' as is the movie in its own perversely unpleasant
way. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
