<HEADER>
A0287 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFLICTION-REVIEW-LAD     12-29 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFLICTION-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AFFLICTION' CHILLS TO THE BONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nick Nolte has played so many raging losers in his
career that you'd think he'd have exhausted his insight into the
condition long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affliction'' suggests that the pit of despair Nolte draws from
is bottomless. A summing-up of everything this distinctive,
distinctly American actor is about, ``Affliction'' is the kind of
dark, bone-chilling showcase that comes around once in a career, if
at all.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just Nolte's show. James Coburn also does his best
work ever in the film. These two performances should not be missed
by anyone who cares about acting or cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Those who only go to the movies for enjoyment, however, will
want to steer wide of this relentlessly bleak exercise. For the
second time in a row, the most depressing movie of the year has
been adapted from a Russell Banks novel set in a snowbound northern
hamlet with no hope of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Last year it was Atom Egoyan's dead children special ``The Sweet
Hereafter.'' This one's by Paul Schrader, a writer (``Taxi
Driver,'' ``Raging Bull'') and director (``American Gigolo,''
``Mishima,'' ``Light Sleeper'') hardly known for a cheery view of
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Painful as it is, however, ``Affliction'' proves a better fit
for Schrader's downbeat sensibility than ``Hereafter'' was for
Egoyan's. It's Schrader's most perfectly realized directing effort
since his first, the uncharacteristically humorous ``Blue Collar.''
</P>
<P>
   But as good as the directing is here, the film's bleeding soul
lies in Nolte's towering wreck of a performance. He's Wade
Whitehouse, officially the police chief of little Lawford, N.H.,
but actually the errand boy of the town's only successful
businessman (Holmes Osborne).
</P>
<P>
   Just as well; Wade's never been able to handle real
responsibility. Unhappily divorced and abhorred by his preteen
daughter, he tries to be an affable guy but is always too late, too
stoned, too loud, too delusional and/or too rough for anything he
attempts to do.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows Wade through a particularly rough patch of
winter. He decides to sue for custody of his unwilling offspring,
gets it in his head that a hunting accident was actually a murder
plot between his only real friend (Jim True) and his resented
employer, and he can't quite marshal the proper attention toward
his waitress girlfriend Margie (Sissy Spacek). Throbbing through
all of this, like a reminder of the gaping wound where his
self-esteem should be, is the mother of all toothaches.
</P>
<P>
   Though hardly equipped to fumble through these converging,
immediate crises, Wade must confront the big, basic one. His
father, Glen (Coburn), the alcoholic sadist who made Wade the mess
he is, has let his wife freeze to death in their isolated
farmhouse. Now Wade and his brother (Willem Dafoe) who got away
must confront the vicious monster on the intimate battlefield
they've avoided their whole lives.
</P>
<P>
   Something, inevitably awful, has to give.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Who'll Stop the Rain'' through ``The Prince of Tides,''
``Cape Fear,'' ``Q&AMP;A,'' ``Mother Night,'' ``U-Turn'' and the
current ``The Thin Red Line,'' Nolte has excelled at portraying
extreme psychic stress. But none of those roles had quite the
completely lived-in quality he brings to Wade Whitehouse.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Coburn serves up a frighteningly sustained act of
cruelty. He leaves no doubt about what drove his son to such
lifelong ruin. Indeed, the major question one asks upon leaving the
scorched emotional snowscape of ``Affliction'' is how Wade managed
to maintain, however tenuously, for as long as he did. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
