<SLUG> BC-SF-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN WOES CRIMP EXPORTS ON WEST COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Exports from the San Francisco Bay area plunged
18 percent in the third quarter, signaling the region's
vulnerability to the economic troubles in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area Council, which conducted the quarterly study, said
the region was particularly vulnerable because it is about twice as
dependent on exports for economic growth than other parts of the
country, in part because of its concentration of manufacturers
producing high-tech goods.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the area's exports are shipped to East Asia,
where economies also rely heavily on the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Financial specialists said while they had not seen a percentage
drop this great since the recession of the early 1990s, export
levels and the area's overall economy remained relatively healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of years have been phenomenal (in terms of)
growth in the Bay area. The economy of the Bay area is now growing
at what we've seen historically,'' said Joe Nation, editor of the
Bay Area Economic Pulse, published by the Bay Area Council, a San
Francisco-based public policy institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is how much more financial turmoil we should see
overseas,'' he said. ``Unless we have a complete collapse in Asia,
which I think is unlikely, we've probably seen the worst in terms
of the drop in exports.''
</P>
<P>
   Other specialists had less confidence in the ability of the
struggling Asian countries to recover anytime soon, especially
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan is the linchpin to the entire East Asian regional
economy. Until Japan shows signs of real improvement, the outlook
for East Asia remains a bit downbeat,'' said Rob Valletta, a senior
economist for the Federal Reserve Bank in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Valletta, citing statistics from the Massachusetts Institute for
Social and Economic Research, said California exports to East Asia
fell 20.6 percent in the first nine months of 1998 compared to same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Arredondo, assistant secretary at the state Trade and
Commerce Department, said the estimates of Japan's debt range from
the conservative $500 billion to as high as $1.5 trillion. In
contrast, he said, the savings and loan scandal in the United
States added up to a comparatively modest $160 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But helping to offset the Asian turmoil, California's exports to
Latin America and Europe have been strong, Arredondo said. The
introduction of the euro next month and computer upgrades to
correct the year 2000 problem have helped create demand for
technology-related exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time ever in European economies, banks will be
able to talk to each other electronically,'' Arredondo said. ``The
know-how to do that is coming from California.''
</P>
<P>
   Exports to Western Europe, Canada and Mexico account for about
40 percent of California's total exports, according to the Federal
Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Gavin Tritt, assistant coordinator for economics at the San
Francisco-based Asia Foundation, said some Asian countries, such as
South Korea and Thailand, have already shown signs of an upturn. He
admitted the size of those economies pales in comparison to
Japan's, but said the improvements show that financial reforms are
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should start seeing a strengthening in the region towards
the end of 1999,'' he predicted. ``China has been riding this
through without a significant contraction. And we're seeing a
number of countries doing pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area Council's report, which was released Monday, shows
that employment remained healthy. Unemployment for the region in
September rose slightly to 3.8 percent from 3.7 in September 1997,
but was still well below the state average of 6.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
