   &UR; WHEELS: &LR;  Chevrolet's Tracker may be slow to grow, which is not
a bad thing, but it is developing rather quickly, thanks to
membership in the high-volume, highly competitive arena of small
sport-utilities.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC: How do you know when you need new brakes?
What is that squealing noise when stopping or the chirping noises
while still on the move? Those are just two of the questions you
should know the answers to when the subject turns to brakes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY: &LR;  MILLENNIUM BUG: With the Millennium Bug's
sting only a year away, businesses and governments haven't
completed the expensive task of fixing computer systems nationwide,
and experts can't rule out major disruptions from the software
glitch. Horror stories abound. Some activists fear that elevators
will trap riders, electricity and water won't flow to homes, mass
transportation systems will be halted and airplane pilots will be
unable to communicate with air traffic controllers. Most experts
say that such scenarios are wildly exaggerated, but there are
likely to be some disruptions in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REACTION: Worried citizens mobilize in preparation of
computer problems in new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOW TO PREPARE LIST: A list of issues that consumers
should be aware of in connection with the Year 2000 (Y2K) computer
problem.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WEB TOP 10: At the end of the year, people love top-10
lists. For the Web, 1998 was quite a year. Here's one Internet
user's personal Top 10 Web sites of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: The holiday season is a good time to reflect
on high-tech magic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR; :Throughout the novel-writing process, Guy Johnson's
mother, the celebrated poet and writer Maya Angelou, encouraged him
to continue. The efforts pay off in ``Standing at the Scratch
Line,'' a piece of fiction focusing on men of his grandfather's
generation. ``This is not a story she would have written because
she works from a woman's perspective, but she values difference.
She has never wanted me to be anything other than who I am,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: For a century now, the Times has been
American publishing's herald and arbiter, pronouncing with
magisterial authority on the work of Henry James and Don DeLillo
and an astonishing gallery in between. Some do the job with equal
dedication and others, on occasion, with greater wit. But none does
it as thoroughly, week after week, year after year.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEWS: ``The First Time.'' Leave it to pop icon Cher to
not let the weight of soulful reflection hold her back. She has
dragged out all her photo albums and all her best stories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEWS: ``T.C. Boyle Stories.''This book throws a rope
around Boyle's four previous collections as well as catching seven
new stories that haven't been published in book form. This near-700
page reconsideration of the man's short fiction pretty much tells
us what we already knew about him: For all his writing talents, his
audacity and abundant comedic gifts, Tom Boyle isn't terribly
comfortable yet in the company of sympathetic characters or complex
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR; : The answer to America's drug problem may lie
somewhere in the roots of an obscure plant that grows wild in
African rain forests. That is, if only scientists could read and
follow the directions the plant seems to be giving them. But after
several million dollars' worth of federally funded research,
efforts to understand the plant and the properties of a compound
squeezed from its cells have foundered on a tangle of lawsuits and
conflicting scientific results.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ENDANGERED MANATEES: For centuries, manatees have migrated
north along the Florida coast in the summer and returned south in
the winter. But the proliferation of power plants, with their
warm-water outflows, has thrown off the sea mammals' migration
times. As a result, the slow-moving manatees are at a heightened
risk for thermal shock and death from cold water.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOLIDAY MEALS: It's not necessarily the family and friends
that make you feel so good during holiday celebrations. It could be
the food. Holiday meals are a particularly strong concoction of
stimulants, sedatives and chemical aphrodisiacs.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: Infertility treatments are becoming easier
to take and more popular, and multiple births are becoming more
common, doctors say. But their frequency doesn't diminish their
danger.
</P>
