 PageExpress budget for the week of Dec. 28, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call John
Gardner, pagination consultant for The New York Times Syndicate, at
917-224-4381 or e-mail him at pages &LR; nytsyn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m.
Tuesday, Dec. 29.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: &LR;  (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., Dec.
31) The celebrations that will mark the beginning of the year 2000
are actually acknowledging an anniversary of the birth of Jesus of
Nazareth. Christians believe that through the birth of Jesus
Christ, God became human. Whether or not he was God incarnate,
Jesus changed the world. His impact on history, politics and
culture over the past 2000 years cannot be understated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PILGRIMAGE OF FAITH: Undeterred by the grime and urban
chaos of Jerusalem, believers are deeply moved by their visit to
Jesus' homeland.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TIMELINE: Graphic showing a look at events from 40 B.C.
through 44 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT: (Available by 2 p.m., Wed., Dec. 30) Politics has
made the spectacle of human behavior very distasteful in recent
days, and though none of it should be ignored, some of it must be
put at a distance for at least some of the time. So it's easy to
escape into the world of animal fables and animation, gazing at old
MGM and Warner Bros. cartoons on cable television, following
nightly episodes of ``The Simpsons,'' watching ``Babe'' on video
and then going to the theater to see the sequel, ``Babe: Pig in the
City.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR FILE: Some actors are known for their voices, their
hair, their comic timing or their muscled bodies. Alfre Woodard
should be known for her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: CHATTANOOGA, TENN.: &LR;  Like fences, bridges make good
neighbors. That's especially true of the Walnut Street Bridge over
the Tennessee River. The pedestrian span between Chattanooga 's
Market Street and Veterans Bridges links the chic Bluff View Art
District on the south bank and still-developing-but-definitely-cool
Frazier Avenue on the North Shore. Though quite different in
character, these artsy enclaves are two of the hippest
neighborhoods in this vibrant metropolis that has rejuvenated its
once-derelict downtown and has more to offer visitors with each
year.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CHATTANOOGA DINING: A guide on where to eat when visiting
downtown Chattanooga.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: If you're planning a ski trip, head for the
Rockies. According to Conde Nast Traveler's poll of the top 50 ski
resorts in North America, Colorado was declared the favorite
destination among experienced skiers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MILLENNIUM TRAVEL: The night of Dec. 31, 1999, is still
more than a year away, but movers and shakers in the travel
industry have been hard at work preparing for what many of them
