<HEADER>
A0325 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-STREETCAR-HNS &LR;      12-29 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STREETCAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS AIRING AN UNDERWHELMING `STREETCAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALLAN ULRICH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you must see Andre Previn's opera, ``A
Streetcar Named Desire,'' be sure of one thing: You will never
encounter it sung better than on the PBS ``Great Performances''
telecast Wednesday night (check local listings).
</P>
<P>
   You can rest easy, too, that the version on the tube, taped
during the second, third and fourth performances at the War
Memorial Opera House last September with the composer in the pit,
provides a more cogent and balanced souvenir of this San Francisco
Opera commission than what one encountered at the Sept. 19 world
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   The project represents a considerable act of faith on the part
of PolyGram Classics, which released the performance on three
compact discs last week (Deutsche Grammophon 289 459 366; the
commercial video will follow).
</P>
<P>
   There's also no doubt that the Tennessee Williams-inspired opera
(Philip Littell's libretto is drawn almost completely from the
play) has become a career milestone for soprano Renee Fleming,
whose Blanche DuBois lends the opera its only shred of emotional
depth.
</P>
<P>
   What else is there to recommend? Kirk Browning's TV direction
focuses Colin Graham's original Opera House staging, and the San
Francisco Opera has found another opportunity to reach an
international audience, though the announcer's hyping of the
1999-2000 season is a tad aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Then, however, we must deal with the opera itself, and the news
isn't so good. The premiere was reviled by most of the 140 critics
who attended, not because they had it in for neophyte opera
composer Previn, who commands enormous respect, but because the
failings of the opera are so evident.
</P>
<P>
   On television, those blemishes emerge with even more force than
in the theater. Previn writes in a neo-Straussian idiom that wears
you out with its rampant prettiness long before the three hours
have elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Only Blanche and her hapless suitor, Mitch (a definitive
performance by tenor Anthony Dean Griffey), are even minimally
characterized. The brutish, but terrifyingly perceptive Stanley
Kowalski (baritone Rodney Gilfry) is not even assigned an aria.
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental problem is that Previn simply lacked the gift to
translate Williams' tragedy to the lyric stage. He sets the
libretto, but never transcends it.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' text is so suffused with poetry that it's a bit
painful to experience Previn's respectful attempt to find a place
for lyrical expansion. Blanche's ``I Want Magic'' and her
distracted monolog, ``I Can Smell the Sea Air,'' are all you get
for sitting through three hours of undeveloped melodic cells and
bland orchestral commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Again, one is amazed at how little Previn avails himself of the
ensemble form. Rarely do you hear two voices raised simultaneously;
why delve into opera at all if you ignore what opera does best? The
composer has an obligation to convince us that his source is in
need of music.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, what seemed overblown in the Opera House appears
natural on the tube. Fleming wisely dropped her ludicrous Old South
accent after opening night. Gilfry, whose larynx seemed less
lubricated than his pectorals at the premiere, is in better voice.
Soprano Elizabeth Futral's conflicted Stella remains the major
discovery of the production, and although the cast's diction is
superior, subtitles are a boon.
</P>
<P>
   However, the burning issue hasn't gone away. Why, on the eve of
the 21st century, would opera General Director Lotfi Mansouri
commission an opera that is so 19th century in its format and
orientation?
</P>
<P>
   This ``Streetcar Named Desire'' also raises an issue about
imposing subjects on composers. Has any great opera ever been
written without the composer choosing his own text? We shall see
what happens in 1999, when the Lyric Opera of Chicago unveils
William Bolcom's ``A View From the Bridge'' (based on Arthur
Miller's play) in September and the Met premieres John Harbison's
``The Great Gatsby'' in December.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes are high in both cases, but these _ let's face it _ are
the projects that receive the publicity, the recording contracts
and the TV exposure. Yet in their reliance on an assigned source,
these same works may be telling us that opera remains a subservient
species of artistic endeavor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1506EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      12-29 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Wednesday, Dec.
30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MONTEREY-WINES (Undated) _ For California winemaking in the late
'70s, if Napa and Sonoma were the diplomatic equivalents of Paris
and London, Monterey was considered Bucharest. When mentioned at
all, Monterey was slammed for producing cabernets that tasted a lot
like the local asparagus. But for 20 years Dan Lee has been in the
thick of things as the region's growers and winemakers, after
ripping out the cabernet vines and replacing them with chardonnay
and pinot noir, have pushed Monterey into serious contention as a
producer of top-quality, exciting wines, with the best yet to come.
By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Proust had his madeleine. For
me, the catalyst was seared foie gras with pomegranate seeds and a
spicy pear and pepper chutney. Proust's little cake sent him on a
journey back in time, but my savory plate made me contemplate the
future. And it looks very promising. When this epiphany occurred I
was sitting in Tabla just after it opened. What intrigued me was
the fact that the ingredients went together in a way that seemed
completely natural. Looking around, I realized that everything
about the restaurant felt natural. Only a week old, Tabla seemed to
have been open for years. A momentous change has occurred as the
booming economy has bolstered chefs' and restaurateurs' confidence
to a whole new level. American restaurants have finally come of
age. By Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-TRENDS (Undated) _ As exhilarating as the fast-moving
food world can be, over the past few years, it has felt more like a
car speeding out of control. Trends have bombarded us from all
directions; cookbook sections in bookstores have grown into
complex, multicolored labyrinths; restaurant dishes have become
feats to deconstruct, both physically and sensually. Even home
cooking, which so often evolves out of restaurant cooking, has
become muddled. Now, just as chefs tossed aside overwrought French
cuisine to revel in the simplicity of nouvelle cuisine, many
contemporary cooks are pulling away from fusion cooking and
free-wheeling experimentation and heading in an entirely new
direction _ toward simplicity. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-POULTRY (Undated) _ The USDA lifts its ban on imports of
raw poultry from France, a boon for connoisseurs of foie gras; now
we'll get it from geese, not just ducks. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   PANKO (Undated) _ The Japanese bread crumbs taking the food
world by white storm. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The column: a basic wine library. By Frank
J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ A short wine review.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: easy osso buco. By Mark
Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: roast pork with fennel,
quince and apples. By Alfred Portale.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRACEUTICAL-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ A look at the brave new
world of nutraceuticals, or food products pumped up with everything
from echinacea to cholesterol-fighting wood pulp. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food and dining. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH-BAYLEY _ (Oxford, England) _ Iris Murdoch, the
celebrated author of 26 rigorously intellectual novels, stood
uncertainly in the doorway of her living room, her face frozen in
the blank expression that is a sure badge of Alzheimer's disease.
It was only when she saw her husband, the critic, professor and
novelist John Bayley, that a flicker of comprehension sparked in
her eyes. But it was gone, as quickly as it came. Bayley talks
about his 40 years Murdoch, and his new memoir, ``Elegy for Iris,''
due out in January. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   AFFLICTION-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Affliction'': Paul
