<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-ACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER WHO INSPIRED `CIVIL ACTION' LEARNS NEW TAKE ON LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the new movie ``A Civil Action,'' John
Travolta, in the role of a flashy Boston personal injury lawyer,
makes a momentous decision to take a difficult environmental case
as he overlooks a polluted river outside Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta is on his way back to Boston after meeting with
distraught parents who believe the town's drinking water has
poisoned their children.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't going to take the case, but as he steps gingerly over
multicolored tannery dregs spilling into the river, he sees factory
signs of two giant corporations with deep pockets. He thinks he can
do good and make money.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the film, which is based on a true story, he has
quit law and gone nearly nuts. He's lost his black Porsche, house
and furniture as well as a spot on Boston's Top 10 Eligible
Bachelors List. He has $14 in the bank and a portable radio after
spending more than $2 million of his and his partners' money over
four years on environmental studies, medical tests, depositions and
a four-month trial.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the real-life lawyer on whom a book and now the film are
based said he would do it all differently.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Schlichtmann, 47, after bankruptcy and a near breakdown, is
again taking environmental cases, but he's trying to win justice
for his clients outside the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Woburn experience has taught me so much. It's changed me
as a human being and a lawyer. I'm approaching the world so
differently. Woburn taught me we have to figure this out
together,'' Schlichtmann said in recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann, who acted as legal consultant for the movie, is
representing 60 families in the little town of Tom's River, N.J.,
in a case similar to the one in Woburn. In this instance, he
believes people are dying from brain and blood cancers caused by
hazardous waste from Union Carbide and Ciba-Gigy. Instead of suing
the giant corporations, though, Schlichtmann is negotiating with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's easy. It's very challenging and difficult,
but there's no alternative. It's a recognition that the legal
system is not helpful in solving our problems. Our legal system
encourages behavior that is destructive. The first casualty is the
truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Touchstone Pictures film is based on the 1995 book by New
Yorker staff member Jonathan Harr, who won the National Book
Critics Circle award for nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Readers praise Harr for painstaking reporting and spellbinding
writing that turned an intricate legal case of the 1980s into a
thrilling drama of Schlichtmann's battle on behalf of eight Woburn
families. ``A Civil Action'' was on the New York Times bestseller
list for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Zaillian, scriptwriter of ``Schindler's List,'' has
written and directed the film. Producers are Scott Rudin, Robert
Redford and Rachel Pfeffer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With John Travolta playing Schlichtmann and Robert Duvall taking
the role of his cunning opponent, an attorney for Beatrice Foods,
the film also tells a compelling environmental tale.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann's business associates are played by William H. Macy
(``Fargo''), Tony Shalhoub and Zeljko Ivanbeck. Kathy Bates takes
an uncredited role as a bankruptcy judge who can't understand how
Schlichtmann could lose it all by the end of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   John Lithgow plays Warren Skinner, the judge who Schlichtmann
believes is out to get him. Stephen Fry, of PBS ``Jeeves'' fame,
portrays the scientist leading the environmental studies. Kathleen
Quinlan plays Anne Anderson, the mother who spearheads the parents'
fight to win retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting close up, the camera records high-spending
Schlichtmann's Boston life of fancy cars, luxurious offices and
expensive clothes as his young firm starts winning big personal
injury settlements.
</P>
<P>
   When the Woburn case takes over in the early 1980s, however, he
spends millions of dollars and four years preparing for the trial
while visiting the grieving families of eight leukemia victims.
</P>
<P>
   The parents tell tragic stories: a 2-year-old dying in his
father's arms while parked near a highway exit on an emergency trip
to the hospital, a dying boy telling his mother he had arranged to
meet her ``in the back left-hand corner of heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   As mother Anne Anderson explains to Schlichtmann when he first
goes to Woburn, ``We don't want money. We want an apology.'' From
whom?, Schlichtmann asks. ``We don't know,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann finds the two businesses _ Beatrice Foods and W.R.
Grace _ that he believes dumped TCE, the solvent trichloroethylene,
and other chemicals into Woburn's water supply. Since the owners
won't talk, he looks for the workers, many of them living in Woburn
with their children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's best performances comes from James Gandolfini,
who plays Al Love, the father of eight children. Employed by the
tannery, a subsidiary of Beatrice Foods, he tells Schlichtmann that
barrels of toxic waste were pushed into pits. Others tell of a
waste pond jokingly called the ``swimming pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Duvall, in the role of wise, wily Boston attorney Jerome Facher,
tries to blame bacon, peanut butter, gasoline, Teflon pans, silver
fillings and tampons for the leukemia cluster.
</P>
<P>
   In most drinking water contamination cases, the plaintiffs must
meet a high proof test. They must show that a company's pollution
got to the water supply and that the water caused the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the Woburn case, the judge posed a set of questions to the
six jurors after the trial had gone on for four months in 1986.
Schlichtmann had to convince the jurors that the companies'
chemical waste got to the wells by a certain month and year. If
not, Schlichtmann wasn't allowed to present the compelling evidence
of the children's leukemia. The jurors decided that W.R. Grace had
tainted the wells but that Beatrice Foods had not.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann was crushed. He had planned to use the settlement
money from one of the corporations to finance the next stage of the
trial against the other. What he got instead was an $8 million
settlement from W.R. Grace, which equaled about $450,000 per
family, and nothing from Beatrice Foods. (At one point, he had
asked for $410 million.)
</P>
<P>
   He spent three years trying to win an appeal, but he was denied
all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichtmann, by then ready to give up law, turned all his files
over to the Environmental Protection Agency, which had been
dragging its feet on the case. In 1989, he borrowed enough money to
move to Hawaii. He stayed for a couple years, at one point nearly
swimming out to sea in desperation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the EPA ordered a $70 million cleanup by W.R. Grace,
Beatrice Foods and some other companies. It was the largest such
cleanup in New England's history.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney indicted W.R. Grace for lying in its
statements to the EPA. W.R. Grace pleaded guilty to two counts and
paid a maximum fine. The companies closed the two plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
