<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-4TAKES-     12-29 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-4 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S CRUSADE FOR THE POOR OF THE SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Three photos are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Eds.: Wil is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE ROCK, Va. _ A man who lives atop a mountain here communes
with the dead. He swears they've told him _ the dead that is _ to
rid America of its poor.
</P>
<P>
   So he travels rural roads, into towns that don't show up on
maps, into towns you've never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he'll be driving, down through the Georgia pines,
across that endless Mississippi Delta, and he'll feel his body get
to aching, he'll feel the sleep climbing up into his eyes, he'll
wish he were twenty years younger. But he just keeps going. Rolling
toward the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Once, right here in Virginia, he drove the car into a ditch.
Asleep at the wheel. Three weeks later he was up, rolling again.
Trying not to think about the busted ribs, the broken hand, or the
dark things the doctor had said about his heart. The dead _ slave
ancestors buried in a plot 30 feet from his front door here _ won't
let him be. ``I can feel them,'' the man says.
</P>
<P>
   Old Harris Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Old William Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Old Emma Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Little Emma Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Little Emma was Emma Ray's namesake and daughter. Poor thing:
she died in infancy.
</P>
<P>
   The world hardly knows the man on the mountain, though he may
have done as much to lift the hearts and raise the sights of the
Southern black poor as any man alive.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Donald Anderson. He's an intellectual. He's kind and
generous. He's also vain _ and, with his wobbly cowboy walk, lofty
manner, and green eyes, something of a curiosity to almost everyone
he meets.
</P>
<P>
   But if he can be absent minded about the small things, Anderson
is a demon about the big picture: Poor folk will rise. And from
that dream has grown an organization _ inspired by the resolute
localism of the British House of Commons and the ideals of Thomas
Jefferson _ that, for thirty years, has been quietly bringing true
grass-roots democracy to rural communities across America's South.
</P>
<P>
   He calls it The Assembly _ a network of mini-parliaments, formed
of 50 citizens each, that is built anew in every town Anderson
enters, that first shadows and then dislodges the traditional
government structure. He works in the tradition of other ground-up
community organizers, but his targets are among the toughest, and
his methods and passion uniquely and entirely his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, everywhere he went, it seemed, folk tugged at
his elbow, dropped words into his ears, told him he couldn't
sweet-talk his way into rural communities as an outsider and
organize them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it forty-one times,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For thirty years, in unknown places, in misbegotten towns.
</P>
<P>
   There he stands, in the homes of poor folk, shaking hands that
have lifted contaminated well water that very morning, telling men
who have trouble with the alphabet that they can sidle right up to
Thomas Jefferson and his beliefs and make something large of
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He's seen barely literate souls, men and women, transformed into
leaders. In some counties whole political structures have been
upended, turned around, set loose in new directions.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments, too, when his whole vision gets reduced to
the simplicity of goodwill _ a warm coat found and draped around
the shoulders of a woman living in a shack the cold wind owns.
</P>
<P>
   In all, his assemblies have brought $20 million in development
to the rural South, but he hasn't been feted at one testimonial
dinner. He hasn't had one medal draped around his neck. He seems
not to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he cares about is a roof over his head,'' says Wyche
Fowler, the former US Senator from Georgia whose friendship with
Anderson dates back 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now Anderson _ whose National Community Development Organization
has previously concentrated on the American South _ is moving
north. He wants to reopen the debate about the crumbling cities of
America. The other week he was in Cleveland. Then Washington, D.C.,
where his organization is headquartered. Washington might well be
the nation's largest think tank, where, day in and day out, the
problems seem to outfox the thinkers. There he was, under the roof
of an urban church, eyes gleaming, telling mothers and fathers who
live on a street where crime has started to creep badly to hold on,
telling drug addicts that Thomas Jefferson is getting ready to
march into their lives.
</P>
<P>
   He's been on this road before. He was there in the Sixties, when
there was footstomping and rage on behalf of the poor. But then the
political climate changed, the rage quieted. A lot of the marchers
went home.
</P>
<P>
   As for Donald Anderson, he kept dreaming. Then he came down off
the mountain, tossing off the highclass dreams his own parents held
for him _ breaking their hearts without meaning to _ and swearing
to cure a nation of what ails it, rumbling against time as the dead
men and women who sleep near him _ ``the folks in the back yard,''
he calls them _ kept whispering, driving him. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seeds of hope &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to slip into rural communities, where the citizens
were often distant and disconnected from one another. He planned to
organize in groups of 50. Each group would elect officers and
representatives. Collectively, an Assembly would be drawn from the
group representatives. The Assembly itself would agree on one
problem _ sewers, schools, housing _ and attack it with unity and
vigor.
</P>
<P>
   It was early 1968 and Donald Anderson was looking for someplace
to test his vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin told me about Surry,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   That Martin.
</P>
<P>
   They'd met in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   An impoverished old Virginia farming town, Surry had long been a
place where blacks outnumbered whites, yet a black had never held
elective office. In 1959 public school officials _ with the state's
blessing _ boarded up the schools in nearby Prince Edward County
rather than integrate. The move ignited ``massive resistance''
across the state to integrated public education. In Surry whites
pulled their children out of the schools. All-white private
academies flourished.
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson reached Surry, he met Walter Hardy, C.C. Pettaway,
and Thaddeus Lane. Three black men. Three poor men.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy and Pettaway had risen to become community leaders. Hardy,
who had worked as a gardener and a chauffeur for a well-to-do white
family, was working at a packing plant. Lane was scuffling as a
small farmer. Pettaway got by on welding work.
</P>
<P>
   Three common men. Donald Anderson saw royalty in them. But they
were suspicious of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought I was a communist,'' remembers Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came here as a surprise to us,'' says Walter Hardy. ``Came
here with a white secretary. That was a no-no in this area. We
didn't know if he was fly-by-night or what. He came here with a
set-up we had never heard of, talking about the British House of
Commons.''
</P>
<P>
   Three men, and not a one without scars.
</P>
<P>
   For years C.C. Pettaway had been quiet as stone. Then they let
the schools go to ruin rather than integrate. He had children, and
they needed to learn, to grip schoolbooks. When the schools finally
reopened, whites didn't return. Somehow a lot of the public
education money got siphoned off into those all-white private
academies. Quiet no more, Pettaway went to court and sued.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet, too, until he couldn't stay away from the restaurant any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the ``Whites Only'' sign finally came down at the
Surry House Restaurant, C.C. Pettaway ambled inside. He ordered a
steak. He waited a long time, but it finally came. He sat there,
joyful as a man at a feast. It wasn't the steak, which was actually
a bloody mess when he knew good and well he had ordered it
well-done. It was just knowing it was his.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1522EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-29 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 EAGLE ROCK, Va.: ... it was his.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardy's awakening began when he entered the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I had a country until I went to the Army,'' says
Hardy. ``White officer said to me, `This is your country too.'
Being from little ole Surry, I didn't realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Lane and Pettaway and Hardy wanted to do things,
dreamed of doing things. But even with blacks a clear majority in
Surry, they couldn't crack the ranks of office holders. Truth be
told, they'd never raised a loud voice. They thought Surry would
always be Surry.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Donald Anderson. This stranger to Surry spelled out
his vision in detail, and before long infant hope was born of his
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what they want,'' Anderson says. ``They want jobs
for their community. They want better housing. They want recreation
to take the youths off the street. What they want is a better
society.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went in Surry: every month, an Assembly meeting. And every
month, another little community feud stamped out in favor of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' explains Walter Hardy, ``you talk about peanuts
and corn at the same time. But with the Assembly, you weren't
allowed to talk about peanuts until you got the problem of the corn
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   After three years, in 1971, the Surry Assembly announced a slate
of candidates to run for board of supervisors. Surry had never had
a black on its five-member board of supervisors, and now three men
_ common men _ were running. And all three won.
</P>
<P>
   In time, too, Thaddeus Lane, an unschooled farmer, a man who
remembers paying a $1.50 poll tax to cast his first vote years ago,
would win election as county treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A minor rebellion,'' Donald Anderson called it.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy and the other black board supervisors had no experience
with power. ``We finally knew we had to stop criticizing,'' says
Hardy. ``We had to govern.''
</P>
<P>
   So they brought in experts to offer them technical advice. They
applied for and received foundation funds to help them attack
county poverty. They brought in a doctor. They got funds to build a
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The Surry schools were in scary shape. Most of the white
children had been pulled out, and even many rural black kids stayed
away, their parents fearing violence. But in time, propelled by
priorities set in the local Assembly, the Surry school system
revolutionized itself. Good teachers came and stayed. An all-black
school system began to integrate itself as whites poured back into
the system. Surry High School went from last in the state in test
scores to the top third on national standardized tests. Today, 95
percent of Surry graduates go on to further their educations.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Williams is principal of Surry High. If he could work 40
hours a day, he would. It's the kids; they elevate him. He'll see a
knot of kids coming down the hall toward him and it's like
something warm and righteous flowing into him. He'll start
backslapping. He'll start complimenting. He'll start goading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Mr. Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Mr. Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this boy here could be brilliant,'' Mr. Williams says,
pulling a kid toward him. ``Gotta stay on him though. Gotta stay on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some mornings Frank Williams will be sitting in his office and
the phone rings and it's Don Anderson on the other end. He's coming
into Surry, now. He forgot to call yesterday to make an
appointment, and he's sorry. But he's on the way and he's got some
think tank folks with him and a congressman and a corporate
executive and he can't wait to show them the school, to show them
the classrooms, to share the latest news of the latest test scores
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just say, `OK, Don, anything for you,' '' says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Anderson, whooshing into the building, quick
hellos to Frank Williams and others, then bolting down the hallway
with his visitors, pointing out kids, poking his head in
classrooms, interrupting the classrooms with his giddiness, talking
in that stop-and-go-like fashion of his _ ``Well, uh, hi, uh, well,
uh, isn't this beautiful!'' Kids getting a good education. It fills
him like helium. Then he's turning, galloping toward the exit
because he's running late for his next appointment. And there's
Frank Williams, standing in the middle of the hallway, smiling,
shaking his head, one eye on the backside of the vanishing Anderson
and the other eye on the kids coming toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first glance you don't know how to take the brother,''
Williams says of Anderson. ``But once you understand where he wants
to go, the man becomes a giant . . . In the old days we had a
saying. `That brother's been touched.' Don's been touched. You
don't know why.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`He had an epiphany' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man who would change the lot of America's poor and
disfranchised has never known a day of poverty in his life. ``We
had cars during the Depression,'' Donald Anderson says, twin
touches of pride and arrogance in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   He was born 66 years ago in Pittsburgh, into a family of Negroes
who walked with arched backs, who flaunted their college degrees.
``We did not hobnob with the humdrum,'' as Anderson puts it.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Celeste, was a teacher, his father, Russell, a
biologist enamored of microscopes, bugs, and genetics.
</P>
<P>
   An aunt was a psychologist. An uncle had an advanced genetics
degree. Another aunt, Helen Baker, would become the first black
woman to attend the University of Maryland law school.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Uncle Sylvester Anderson, who didn't have
credentials to flaunt, but who taught young Donald another kind of
lesson. Sylvester was a river rat in Virginia, where the family's
lineage began. An old black man who beat the last march of slavery,
but who heard enough stories to pass along. Donald Anderson would
sit across from Uncle Sylvester and just stare. His uncle seemed
ancient to him. It was Uncle Sylvester who saved money to buy land
on a mountaintop in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   So Donald Anderson's childhood, wrapped as it was in the
travails of black America, was nevertheless rich in example and in
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Like the one Helen Baker taught him. Diagnosed with a rare form
of cancer as she was about to enter law school, she was given a
year by her doctors. She was blessed with 20 more. On her deathbed
she turned to her nephew, Donald, and with a clarity that was
fairly stunning, summoned up words that would stick with him: ``I
knew that every day I woke could be my last. That meant this
minute, this hour . . . was the most important one. Therefore,
whoever is standing in front of me is king of the world, if kings
are important.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's father was, he says, ``a brilliant man.'' Also
something of an intellectual pioneer in a race-divided land. He
lectured widely overseas and in his own land, though he knew, when
in America, to travel with a blanket and sheet. Jim Crow didn't
make exceptions for the exceptional, and often Russell Anderson
would wind up bundled up outside.
</P>
<P>
   By 1943 the Anderson family had relocated to Washington so
Russell Anderson could begin a medical internship at Freedman's
Hospital (now Howard University Hospital).
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, heady minds were rolling in and out of the
Anderson home. Mordecai Johnson, the influential president of
Howard University, would visit. So would Howard Thurman, the
renowned minister. Young Donald Anderson heard their echoes, saw
their footprints.
</P>
<P>
   But the boy, even with sisters and a brother, a mother and
father, grew lonely. ``Whenever we moved onto a street, all the
`best friends' were already taken,'' he remembers.
</P>
<P>
   The friends he did find were between the hardcovers of books.
His sisters and brother would be outside playing, and Donald would
be upstairs, reading, aloud: Victor Hugo, Edgar Allan Poe,
Alexandre Dumas and, above all, Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
