<HEADLINE>
FUNERAL FOR KENNETH STARR'S MOTHER SET FOR WEDNESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA SANDBERG  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Vannie Mae Starr, the mother of Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr, will be buried Wednesday in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Starr, 91, died Sunday within a week of learning that her
son and President Clinton would share the cover of Time Magazine as
its Men of the Year. Her body was discovered by her housekeeper in
the tiny white home where she had raised Kenneth and two other
children, a family member said.
</P>
<P>
   She died of arteriosclerotic cardiovascular disease, according
to the Bexar County Medical Examiner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was doing beautifully right up until the end,'' Kenneth
Starr's older brother, Jerry Starr, said by phone from his late
mother's house. ``We feel very blessed she didn't suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Starr said he believed his mother had died suddenly
because she did not activate an emergency communication device,
called a ``lifeline button,'' that she wore around her neck.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his famous brother had each spoken to their
mother by telephone just hours before her death. Kenneth Starr
received the news on Sunday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The independent prosecutor's investigation of Clinton became the
basis of the House vote Dec. 19 to impeach the president, the first
time such a vote was taken since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Vannie Mae Starr had steadfastly avoided the glare of the media.
But in a rare interview last week, she told the San Antonio
Express-News that her son had called her hours after the House
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation never touched on Clinton, Monica Lewinsky or
impeachment, she said. ``He doesn't talk about business,'' she
explained. ``He said he was tired and he was going to bed early.''
</P>
<P>
   The Starr family lived in Thalia in north Texas when Kenneth was
a child before moving to Centerville and then to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Starr, who continued to live in a blue-collar part of San
Antonio until her death, in September described her son as ``just
an ordinary guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A visitation for Mrs. Starr was held Tuesday at Mission Park
Funeral Chapels South, and burial is set for 2 p.m. Wednesday at
the Starr Cemetery in Elkhart, Texas, according to an obituary
notice supplied by the funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Mahan, an informal go-between for the news media and
Starr's mother, said she would remember her as ``very sweet, very
thoughtful and very eager to have her son shielded from any
publicity that was unpleasant or unfavorable. She was certainly a
devoted mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahan, 81, was Kenneth Starr's English and journalism teacher at
Sam Houston High School here in the early 1960s. She had
volunteered to speak to the media for Vannie Mae Starr, knowing she
didn't like the spotlight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
