<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON TO PONDER THE BIG QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, 1998 is down to its last dry, raspy breath and if we're
lucky we'll usher in 1999 just a couple of days from now. That's
really exciting, isn't it? For most people, this is a time of
expectation, looking forward toward a new horizon and new
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it's more a time of reflection and introspection. What
have I learned this year? Who can I help with that knowledge? And
how do you clean a harmonica?
</P>
<P>
   I like harmonicas. A blues band without a harmonica is like Al
Gore without a tie. Sure, I could go into this new millennium
without knowing how to properly clean a harmonica, but it's going
to bug me until I find out.
</P>
<P>
   These and other really shallow thoughts occupied my mind during
Christmas dinner as I gorged myself on turkey and impeachment
cobbler. Meanwhile, Aunt Lois and Uncle Johnny had a heated debate
over whether cows have feelings. They grew up on a farm and,
therefore, care passionately about these things. Being a city girl,
I could not contribute anything of substance to their dispute but I
did refrain from eating any of the sliced beef just in case Aunt
Lois was right.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, lack of firsthand knowledge usually doesn't stop me
from joining a discussion, but I was rather tired on Christmas Day.
We had driven quite a distance the day before to visit some friends
and as usual, the trip left me exhausted. I don't know why I get so
tired on these forays because my husband always drives and I always
fall asleep within 30 minutes of leaving home. He doesn't
understand why I can stay awake long enough to make it to north
Dallas, 45 minutes away, but I can't stay awake for the first hour
of a four-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple. I don't like short naps. On a long drive, I know I
have time to take a long nap and then comb my hair and freshen my
makeup. I can't do all of that in 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he doesn't talk to me. He just stares at the road and
hums along with the radio. Maybe he's humming me to sleep. Besides,
if you've ever driven north, south, east, or west of any Texas
town, you know that there is absolutely nothing to look at for
miles upon miles except for those sensitive cows.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I survived the trip despite my restless rest and,
although I enjoy sharing holidays with family and friends, I wasn't
all that sad when Aunt Lois retrieved her calf, Esther, from the
garage and bid us farewell. Like dominoes, the rest of the
relations fell out the door behind her.
</P>
<P>
   As they drove out of sight, either Aunt Lois or Esther yelled,
``Happy Moo Year!'' Back in the house, someone had thoughtfully
left us a gift on the dining room table. It was a very pretty but
obviously used harmonica. I smiled and put it in the dishwasher
next to the casserole dish. Don't you just love getting great
things for free?
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy your new year.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
