<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RIND ON THE BRIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What are the ingredients of the white rind on Brie cheese,
and is it edible?
</P>
<P>
   A. The rind of a Brie _ and any other soft-ripened cheese _ is
where the unripened cheese meets the bacteria that make it the food
we all know. Brie is aged with the help of friendly bacteria called
Penicillium candidum, which attach themselves to the rind of a soft
cheese and encourage it to age from the outside in.
</P>
<P>
   Brie came into contact with these bacteria naturally in the air
of the Brie region of France. But today, most Bries are treated
with a manufactured liquid form of Penicillium candidum. The rinds
are perfectly edible, but some people prefer to cut them off.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food and cooking can be sent to Food Chain, The
Dining Section, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York NY
10036-3959, or e-mailed to dining(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
