<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSMAN NEEDS NO ASSITANCE BY STOPPARD FOR IMMORTALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not only my opinion that Tom Stoppard is Britain's
foremost playwright of these times, possibly the best of the
century's second half, and surely above any current American
dramatist.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of his career _ or at least from
``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' which established him,
still in his 20s, in 1966 _ it has been evident that Stoppard has
an abiding interest in literature, and a quite literary
sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jumpers,'' in ``Travesties,'' in ``The Real Inspector
Hound,'' in ``The Real Thing'' and other Stoppard staples, literary
allusions abound, and the plays are themselves mirrors of respected
literary themes.
</P>
<P>
   After a spasm of down time, Tom Stoppard is with us again, with
a drama whose West End success is likely to be duplicated on
Broadway. The play is ``The Invention of Love'' and surely it is as
``literary'' as any theater piece ever may be.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is hell for the most part, and the central figure is
one who goes there _ Alfred Edward Housman, the scholar-poet,
perhaps the best-known classicist of modern time. Other literary
figures _ Oscar Wilde, John Ruskin _ penetrate Stoppard's drama,
and the flashback device gives us acquaintance with lesser-known
persons of importance in Housman's life.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among these is Moses Jackson, the object of Housman's
unrequited love. Jackson's marriage to a woman Housman also knew
has been pegged by his biographers as the pivotal event in the
poet's rather gloomy life. Nobody really knows, but Housman is
figured an inactive homosexual, damned in his own mind if he would,
and damned if he wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I heard someone say that Stoppard's play is calculated
to rehabilitate Housman, for whom a return to popularity may be
expected. Oh, the irony! I was reminded of Walt Disney's
exclamation, during production of the animated ``Fantasia,'' that
``This is going to make Beethoven!''
</P>
<P>
   A.E. Housman requires no rehabilitation whatever. Although he
has never been considered a ``major'' poet, his popularity holds
steady through the passing decades, and he remains one of the most
memorized and quoted poets in our language.
</P>
<P>
   His is the voice of loss, of controlled despair. Sadness
underscores even his loveliest lyrics. Mortality is ever lurking in
his verse; and although Housman tells us that ``Life, to be sure,
is nothing much to lose,'' we are left believing that the specter
of mortality hounded him throughout his adult life.
</P>
<P>
   A life so strange. Born into comfortable circumstances in 1859,
Housman was a precocious child and early poet, but he discarded the
pastime when he entered Oxford, where he met Moses Jackson. Housman
was an outstanding student who mysteriously (deliberately?) failed
his finals, and for 10 years thereafter was an obscure clerk in the
London patent office.
</P>
<P>
   When he secured at last a professorship (in Latin) at London
University, he began composing poetry again; and in 1896 published,
at his own expense, ``A Shropshire Lad,'' 63 short rhyming poems in
traditional metric schemes. These ironic and tragic creations
eventually caught on, became the top-selling single book of English
verse ``of all time,'' and never fell from favor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Housman published no more poetry until the oddly titled
``Last Poems'' was issued in 1922, 14 years before his death and
midway through a long tenure as the most distinguished professor at
Cambridge. ``More Poems'' appeared in 1936, the year of Housman's
death, and the entire body of his published work fills one small
volume.
</P>
<P>
   Housman composed his poems in a longhand as rigid as his verse,
in notebooks I have been privileged to hold and behold in the
Seymour Adelman collection at Bryn Mawr College. If Tom Stoppard
hasn't been to Bryn Mawr, he should go there for the altogether
awesome experience of communion with Alfred Housman himself.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
