<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-OFFICER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRIAGE OFFICERS FIND JOY IN TYING THE KNOT FOR OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KENNETH C. CROWE II  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALFMOON, N.Y. _ Nothing makes Chris Cuttita feel more romantic
than a wedding. When she became a court clerk, she was sure she
would see many people united by the town's judge.
</P>
<P>
   But through an unusual state law, Cuttita is doing more than
witnessing couples celebrating their wedding day: She's tying the
matrimonial knot for them.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttita is a marriage officer _ a position every town, city and
village government in New York can fill but few do because
performing marriage ceremonies is traditionally the province of
mayors, judges and justices of the peace. But a handful of
municipalities choose to appoint marriage officers to act in
reserve. Their only function is to marry people.
</P>
<P>
   It's such an unusual and rarely made appointment that no state
agency keeps track of how many there are in New York. The Secretary
of State's office, which works with local governments, keeps no
records on this appointed job title, which are unpaid positions.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the marriage is performed within the boundaries of
Halfmoon, located in upstate New York's Saratoga County, Cuttita is
doing something that ship captains are not allowed to do under
state law: she's marrying couples as long as they have their
license. Ship captains may marry couples while at sea, but their
jurisdiction ceases as soon as they hit land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the best part of my job,'' Cuttita said. ``I'm a
classic romantic. I've been doing it for six years for a lot of
family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In Halfmoon, Cuttita will on occasion do a ceremony twice. The
first time in town hall for the couple, the second time recreating
the ceremony for the guests.
</P>
<P>
   Doing what the bride and groom want seems to be a selling point
for marriage officers. That's what Peter Tulin, the Saratoga
Springs city attorney, has done the five times he has served as a
marriage officer.
</P>
<P>
   Tulin has performed weddings in which a dog took part, prompted
a nervous groom to help him remember his forgotten vows and recited
poetry when the ceremony was running shorter than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it because I was honored and touched. I was flattered
that people want me involved in one of the most important parts of
their lives,'' Tulin said. ``Some of the people I knew personally
or through relatives. By the time of the weddings I knew the
couples well.''
</P>
<P>
   Grafton Town Clerk Suzanne Putnam discovered that performing
marriages allowed her to make ``a wonderful gift'' to her brother
Joseph Sciacco and his wife, Patricia. She married them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
