   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Since President Clinton was impeached by
the House ten days ago, the airwaves have filled with senatorial
speculation about a speedy trial and perhaps even a pre-emptive
censure deal. But below the level of generality, the speculators do
not agree on just how a trial should be conducted, or what a
workable censure deal would be. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-SOUTH (Dateline to kum, Ga.) _ In last month's election,
Rep. Sanford D. Bishop Jr., a moderate black Democrat, won
re-election convincingly in a rural, conservative district where
nearly two-thirds of the voters are white. Many black politicians
have managed to attract white support in urban, New South areas
like Atlanta. But Bishop's electoral success demonstrates that even
in the most rural and impoverished districts, a significant number
of white Southerners no longer view race as an absolute obstacle to
voting for a black politician who shares their thinking, votes
their interests and hauls home plenty of pork. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (With move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH-BAYLEY _ (Oxford, England) _ Iris Murdoch, the
celebrated author of 26 rigorously intellectual novels, stood
uncertainly in the doorway of her living room, her face frozen in
the blank expression that is a sure badge of Alzheimer's disease.
It was only when she saw her husband, the critic, professor and
novelist John Bayley, that a flicker of comprehension sparked in
her eyes. But it was gone, as quickly as it came. Bayley talks
about his 40 years with Murdoch, and his new memoir, ``Elegy for
Iris,'' due out in January. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
</TEXT>
