<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL PROMISES `THOROUGH' INVESTIGATION OF OLYMPIC CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``s'' categories)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell
promised a ``prompt and thorough'' investigation Tuesday into
charges that bribes helped Salt Lake City win the 2002 Winter
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen last week by the United States Olympic Committee to chair
a special commission to investigate the claims, Mitchell met for
the first time Tuesday morning with the four other members of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic games hold a special place in the hearts of
Americans, indeed people around the world, and it is up to us to
make sure the selection process for cities lives up to the ideals
of fairness and honesty,'' he said at a news conference here after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who is co-chairman of the USOC's ethics committee,
said the investigation will focus on the circumstances surrounding
the selection of Salt Lake City by the International Olympic
Committee (IOC). He added that the panel also will make
recommendations on how to improve the bidding process to ensure
``it is fair and above reproach.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said the commission will file its report with the USOC
by Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be a prompt and thorough investigation,'' said
Mitchell, a longtime Democratic senator from Maine who brokered the
Irish peace talks earlier this year. Mitchell has been mentioned as
a possible mediator in President Clinton's attempt to avoid a
Senate vote to remove him from office in the wake of the House vote
Dec. 19 to impeach him on charges of perjury and obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC investigation will focus on scholarships and athletic
training given to relatives of IOC members under a $400,000 program
of humanitarian aid from 1991 to 1998 and whether those
scholarships were used to buy IOC votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City Olympic Committee has acknowledged that it
paid nearly $400,000 in scholarships to 13 people, six of whom were
relatives of IOC members before the city was selected for the
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is expected to look into two internships given
to the son of Swaziland IOC member David Sibandze by the city of
Salt Lake in 1993 and 1994, while the city was bidding for the 2002
Winter Olympics. Sibandze's son, Sibusiso, also received bachelor's
and master's degrees from the University of Utah in the mid-1990s,
but it is not known whether he was one of the six relatives of IOC
members who got the scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Three other probes of the allegations are under way.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department announced last week that it had begun an
investigation and that a prosecutor from its criminal division had
been sent to Salt Lake City. The International Olympic Committee
also has started an investigation, which is expected to conclude by
Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Salt Lake City Organizing Committee is conducting
an internal investigation and plans to issue a report on its
findings Feb. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said that Tuesday's meeting helped the five commission
members set the process that will be used to conduct the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the USOC special commission are Donald Fehr,
executive director and general counsel of the Major League Baseball
Players Association; Kenneth Duberstein, former chief of staff to
President Ronald Reagan; Roberta Cooper Ramo, a former president of
the American Bar Association, and Jeff Benz, an at-large member of
the USOC Athletes' advisory council.
</P>
<P>
   International Olympic Committee officials also have promised to
investigate questionable gifts and scholarships given to committee
members by cities in previous Olympic bids.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those gifts and scholarships also involve Swaziland IOC
member David Sibandze. In 1985, his son, Sibusiso, received a
three-month scholarship offer to a Swedish university, while Falun,
Sweden, was bidding to become host of the 1992 Winter Olympics.
That honor, however, eventually went to Albertville, France.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Australian newspapers have reported that a daughter
of David Sibandze obtained a job at a catering institute in Sydney
with the help of the president of the Australian Olympic Committee
during the bid process for the 2000 Summer Olympics.
</P>
</TEXT>
