<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Primitivo Salento Cantele 1995, Italy. About $10. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Just to uncomplicate things a bit, primitivo is the grape,
Salento is the region in southeastern Italy where it is grown, and
Cantele is the name of the family who grow it. For a while,
primitivo was a prime suspect in the mystery surrounding the origin
of the zinfandel grape. But then someone came along with a Croatian
grape that seemed even closer. Scientists now say it is unlikely
that either grape can claim parenthood. In any event, the
resemblance of this full, sturdy red to zinfandel is unmistakable.
Like a suspiciously high number of our California zinfandels, this
primitivo comes from vines 35 to 40 years old, which accounts for
its intensity. At $10, it is a good buy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1639EST &QL; 
