<SLUG> BC-DANIEL-DEFOE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMICS ARGUE MERITS OF TECHNOLOGY IN THE IVORY TOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hundreds of anonymous 18th-century articles and
letters have been attributed to the famed writer Daniel Defoe,
author of the adventure story ``Robinson Crusoe.''
</P>
<P>
   But did he really write all of them? To find out, literary
experts are using computers to analyze the disputed texts.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of many topics discussed this week at the San
Francisco conference of the Modern Language Association of America,
one of the biggest scholarly organizations in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, literary scholars, English professors, French
teachers, linguistic theorists and other devotees of the printed
word have packed the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Few of them resemble tweedy profs. Rather, these hip new members
of the intelligentsia are holding panel discussions analyzing
language, imagery and symbolism in ways unimaginable a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   They are talking about the deeper meanings of videotaped
pornography and the growth of feminism on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the conference has been devoted to erudite discussions
not about printed books but, rather, about its supposed competitors
_ computing, television and the Internet. Ironically, many
conferees are discovering that these potential competitors can be
allies.
</P>
<P>
   The use of computers to study Defoe's writings was discussed
Monday in a session entitled ``Computer Methods in the Study of
Literature and Theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Professor Joseph Rudman of the Carnegie Mellon University in
Pittsburgh detailed his and other scholars' efforts to use
computers to identify anonymous writings as Defoe's. The computer
scans texts for Defoe's literary fingerprints _ for example,
sentences of certain lengths.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee that everyone will agree on the computer's
conclusions. Rudman noted that one scholar who uses a computer to
analyze Defoe texts has gotten into a ``slightly heated'' dispute
with a traditional scholar who doesn't rely on computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the computer, the task (of analyzing Defoe) is very
difficult,'' Rudman said. ``Without the computer, the task is next
to impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
