<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR FOOD IN A WORLD OF CUISINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As exhilarating as the fast-moving food world can be,
over the last few years it has felt to me increasingly like a car
careering out of control. Cooking trends have bombarded us from all
directions, cookbook sections in bookstores have grown into
multicolored labyrinths, restaurant dishes have become ordeals to
deconstruct _ both physically and sensually. And many home cooks
have followed these trends into the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   I remember going to a dinner party that included dishes from
nearly every continent. I left dazed and confused. It was just too
much.
</P>
<P>
   In response to this overload, I started retreating.
</P>
<P>
   At home, I find I'm now cooking straightforward traditional
dishes. When I go out, I gravitate toward restaurants like
Etats-Unis, Il Buco and Le Bernardin, whose chefs understand
restraint and simplicity. I have cravings for the clean, honest
flavors of sushi.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not alone. I have noticed a growing number of home cooks,
chefs and cookbook authors who seem to share my sentiment. In the
same way that many food professionals two decades ago tossed aside
overwrought French cooking to revel in the purity of nouvelle
cuisine, many are now pulling away from fusion cooking and
free-wheeling experimentation and heading for an entirely new ideal
_ simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   This growing respect for the pure and uncomplicated is looking
like an engine for a whole new movement in cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was inevitable,'' said Rozanne Gold, a food consultant and
cookbook author in Brooklyn who is known for her pared-down
approach to food. ``My feeling was we needed that kind of antidote
to the fussiness of the food in the '80s. Chefs could no longer
compete with the number of ingredients in a dish or how high it was
on a plate.''
</P>
<P>
   As with many shifts in the food world, this one was born in the
restaurant kitchen. A couple of years ago, a few chefs began
forgoing garnishes, cutting down on the number of ingredients and
focusing on techniques that coaxed the essential flavors from the
foods they used. The results are spare in appearance and impeccable
in flavor. Most important, they are easy for the palate to
comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   For chefs once absorbed by the idea of cooking with a
multiplicity of components, this has been an about-face. ``When we
used to do desserts at Montrachet,'' said Bill Yosses, who is now
the pastry chef at Bouley Bakery, ``our idea was contrast and
juxtapose. The big catchword was marriage of flavors, and who could
marry the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is who can marry the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we opened up Bouley Bakery,'' Yosses said, ``I thought it
would be great to focus on a more direct and powerful experience on
the plate. I wanted to limit what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, his acclaimed desserts can be as simple as a
supercreamy rice pudding or a rich chocolate tart. The ``zinger,''
as Yosses calls it, is not candied orange peel on the side of the
plate or a chocolate fork poking into the dessert, but the
intensity of flavor in the dessert itself. Chocolate is what makes
the chocolate tart memorable.
</P>
<P>
   And it is probably no coincidence that I can still recall a
decadent brioche pudding I had there three months ago, while all
those fusion feasts have become a blur.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Colicchio, the chef at Gramercy Tavern, has also done a bit
of nipping and tucking in his cooking in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for me, anyway, it's a question of maturity,'' he
said. ``The older I get, I think less is more.'' Instead of adding
elements to a plate, he has started taking them off. Items like
``roasted farm chicken in consomme with black truffle'' at Gramercy
Tavern may seem blunt when compared with the grocery lists on many
restaurant menus.
</P>
<P>
   But what the chef is really telling diners is that they are
getting a perfectly roasted, high-quality chicken with two
accompaniments they can make sense of.
</P>
<P>
   It takes courage, though, to serve such unadorned food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people spend a lot of money in restaurants,'' said David
Rosengarten, the host of the ``Taste'' program on the Food Network,
``and it's easier to see the evidence of the money they've spent in
froufrou on the plate _ swirls, complexity, multiple garnishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Diners in search of those circuses may find themselves outraged
by chefs like Laurent Gras of Peacock Alley, who has served a slab
of pristine salmon on a white plate with zero garnishes and a gravy
boat of sauce bearnaise on the side, or an entree with all of two
ingredients: sea bass and salsify batons. These may seem
excessively spare, but we depend on chefs to take risks and shape
the way we eat.
</P>
<P>
   The changes they are making in their kitchens are starting to
trickle down to home cooks, not just through inspiration, but by
way of their cookbooks as well. Tomes with recipes that call for
foie gras and quail eggs and take three days to prepare are being
challenged by books by top chefs that are surprisingly accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Le Bernardin Cookbook: Four-Star Simplicity'' (Doubleday,
1998) by Eric Ripert and Maguy Le Coze: As long as you have a good
fish store nearby, you can count on achieving the pure, powerful
flavors of Ripert's cooking with little effort.
</P>
<P>
   More mainstream cookbooks are also responding to home cooks'
desire for clarity. Ms. Gold's books ``Recipes 1-2-3'' (Viking,
1996) and ``Recipes 1-2-3 Menu Cookbook'' (Little, Brown, 1998),
for instance, make the stripped-down approach even stricter by
limiting recipes to three ingredients or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Simplifying what we eat and how we cook is being done in other
ways, too. Some cookbook authors have taken a more definitive
approach, answering a question that plagues all home cooks: Which
is the best recipe for a well-known dish? They are moving away from
presenting their version, or a version, and are declaring the
version.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many cookbooks in almost any given area that
there is confusion on the part of consumers as to which is the most
authentic, authoritative voice,'' said Jennifer Josephy, a cookbook
editor at Little, Brown &AMP; Co. ``They don't want to try five
different recipes and see which is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, cooks want one recipe that they know is going to
be great. It needn't be something original: They want a basic
repertory of things that really shine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
