<HEADER>
A0475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-3RD &LR;  &UR; TA     12-29 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 EAGLE ROCK, Va.: ... all, Shakespeare.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young Donald told himself that the great minds of the world
didn't see color. He believed that if he offered the world his
colorblind gifts, then the world would toss colorblind appreciation
back at him. His aunt Helen told him he possessed ``a beautiful
naivete.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1949 Donald Anderson boarded a bus _ had to walk to the back
and take his seat _ for Ann Arbor and enrolled at the University of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   What few black kids there were on the Ann Arbor campus tended to
knot together. It gave them a sense of security. Donald Anderson
kept his distance. He didn't want to be grouped with any particular
clique. Some blacks thought him strange.
</P>
<P>
   During his senior year Anderson was talking to a professor about
transportation economics, which fascinated him. He was thinking of
graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't teach transportation economics right in America,''
the professor told Anderson. ``You should go to to London and study
at the London School of Economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson smiled. Such beautiful instruction, he thought, such
colorblind guidance.
</P>
<P>
   London would have to wait until Anderson finished a two-year
Army stint, but when he set foot in the ancient city in 1955, he
swooned. He made his first friends there, and of course there was
the Bard _ the Old Vic was right across the road from the London
School of Economics.
</P>
<P>
   After London he returned to Ann Arbor to attend the University
of Michigan Law School. By 1960 he would hold two degrees from
Michigan and one from the London School of Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Academically, he was loaded. He waited for the offers to come in
from the blue-chip law firms. None came. He found a job in
Pittsburgh, clerking for a judge. But he soon grew bored.
</P>
<P>
   Someone mentioned the name Adam Clayton Powell Jr., the New York
congressman, and told Anderson that Powell was always looking for
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson sent a query letter to Powell. He was invited in for an
interview. Maxine Dargans, Powell's chief clerk, knew the applicant
was white _ the rich credentials, America 1962 _ and she raised her
head with the arrival of every white man into the office. Donald
Anderson arrived. The revelation was too rich. Powell hired him on
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of 1962 was a wonderful time to be in Washington,
and downright intoxicating to be on Powell's staff. After having
languished in Congress for years, Powell was now chairman of both
education and labor committees.
</P>
<P>
   Following Kennedy's death, the anti-poverty machine roared.
There were momentous victories. But there were troubles. Powell was
investigated for overspending committee funds and for refusing to
settle a slander lawsuit from a woman in Harlem. In 1966 Powell was
refused his seat. He would return to Congress in 1968, but minus
the power. His last term in office, 1968-1970, was sad: humming
gospel tunes, missing votes, sick with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Anderson left Washington. Like so many, he had first been
dazzled, then disillusioned. He'd always thought politicians had
too much power over poverty programs. He started dreaming. About
Thomas Jefferson, about the British Parliamentary system, fashioned
to respect order and process. He started dreaming about all the
poor faces he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an epiphany,'' recalls Wyche Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson told his parents. They listened, but didn't hear. But
when they heard, they were aghast. Russell Anderson didn't sleep
outside so his son could gallivant around the country, some sort of
savior for the poor. Celeste Anderson's treasured son couldn't
vanish into a web of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   He needed seed money. He looked across the Virginia countryside.
A lot of folk looked at him and rolled their eyes, closed their
doors. But a Virginia farmer who had made a mark in local politics
listened _ and helped. ``A most unusual Christian,'' is how
Anderson describes Edwin Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in race relations,'' says Lynch,
now a retired Virginia landowner. ``He wasn't happy with the
federal government,'' Lynch recalls about Anderson. ``He thought he
had a system that could work better.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has taken his Assembly into North Carolina and South
Carolina. He's glided into Alabama. He's convinced those whose
faith had lapsed in small towns in Georgia to pull out chairs and
invite him to sit down and listen.
</P>
<P>
   His reception, however, can vary from place to place.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he'd walk into a room and it wouldn't be long before
he'd realize that his critics were already there, were, in fact,
the very people sitting around the table awaiting his pitch _ some
with white faces, some with black faces. He'd start pulling out the
forms, the Assembly literature. He'd start talking about C.C.
Pettaway, about the Surry school district and the high test scores
of the children. Those around the table would listen. They'd nod.
And then the inquisition would begin. They'd want to know what it
was he was really selling. They'd want to know what political
office he was after. They'd want to know just where he would be
when the drought came, because he sounded like a farm-belt
evangelist, promising rain, and they didn't believe in rain
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson couldn't understand why everyone didn't see the wonder,
the beauty of it all _ communities full of rural folk who had
started rumbling. He knew some mighty fine poetry, and yet, he
couldn't find the words to properly explain the joy on C.C.
Pettaway's face when Pettaway saw his community rise up _ without a
rifle shot being fired as had happened in so many other Southern
rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   His dream has, at times, bumped headlong into reality _ money
has often been short. But then last year Donald Anderson caught a
second wind. Some new foundation money flowed in. He got that
little beautific smile on his face again. He told his staff, now up
to 14 full-timers, it was time to turn north, to take on urban
American and the very symbol of urban disarray: the nation's
capital. And also time to burrow to the very bottom of the South,
to that one place that has long befuddled anti-poverty workers and
haunted him and the family of slaves he sleeps near every night. He
told himself that it was time to go to Mississippi because if he
couldn't make peace with Mississippi, he wondered if he could keep
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippi is a lot like Virginia was 30 years ago,'' Donald
Anderson says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Different, sure enough' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claude King is Don Anderson's man in Mississippi, and Don
Anderson's man in Mississippi is two hours into a drive, zooming
out from Jackson into the delta, going to meet some Assembly folks.
</P>
<P>
   King's been around Mississippi for years. Before Mississippi he
rolled around other parts of the South, doing anti-poverty work,
holding on until the money ran out, packing up when a program
folded.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Claude King's feet are covered in lizard cowboy
boots. His tummy's a huge and wide thing. ``Maann
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKING-TRENDS-2NDTAK     12-29 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-TRENDS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: really shine.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she was writing ``The Perfect Recipe'' (Houghton Mifflin,
1998), Pam Anderson tested dozens of variations of dishes like
macaroni and cheese, chicken pot pie and lobster salad until she
developed recipes she considered the very best. Her recipes will
not change your life, but the book gives you confidence that they
will work and you will not be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Anderson's recipes are of the down-home variety,
the techniques are not always conventional. For macaroni and
cheese, for instance, she calls for stirring the mixture every five
minutes while it is baking. This, she says, gives it the ideal
balance of lightness and creaminess _ a detail that is missing from
most macaroni and cheese recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Rosengarten's latest book, ``Taste'' (Random House, 1998), takes
a similar tack as he explores an eclectic mix of traditional and
trendy dishes from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In a section on moussaka, he lays out the problems he has found
with most versions and highlights the ``criteria for quality'' to
help the reader tell a good one from a bad one. Then he offers a
recipe he calls ``the lightest, least oily, least tomatoey, most
eggplanty, most refined moussaka that you've ever tasted.'' Isn't
that just what you want as you plan a dinner party? Rosengarten
writes with bravado, but he certainly persuaded me to try his
recipe. And it delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Home cooking is also influenced by food magazines. And even they
are devoting energy to sorting the glut of information in the food
world.
</P>
<P>
   You can read a new spirit in the definitive cover lines. ``True
Bagels,'' offered the November issue of Saveur; ``Perfect Beef
Tenderloin,'' promised Cook's Illustrated for November-December.
Instead of ``unforgettable'' and ``festive,'' the lures are now
``authentic,'' ``perfect'' and ``best.''
</P>
<P>
   In many magazines, the recipes themselves are moving toward
restraint. A recent Cook's Illustrated, for instance, did not claim
that ``the best lemon bars'' had a revolutionary twist or culinary
acrobatics: They simply promised to be traditional lemon bars from
a perfected recipe. Readers were made to feel they could trust it.
</P>
<P>
   So what do all these signs mean? That chefs are maturing and
that cookbooks and magazines are offering more substance and less
fluff? I hope so.
</P>
<P>
   Will chefs who fail to prune their creativity fall off the map?
Will cookbooks that lack authority sit on the shelves? Will the
food world ever be one cohesive, organized unit? Certainly not.
Cooking is an art, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems clear that among the forward-looking, the brash,
over-the-top '90s style of cooking may be simmering down. And a
pared-down approach to cooking and eating does seem a logical
progression.
</P>
<P>
   And I, for one, am ready to embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED GARLIC FLAN
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Recipes 1-2-3 Menu Cookbook,'' by Rozanne Gold
(Little, Brown &AMP; Co., 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   2 large heads elephant garlic
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Wrap garlic in foil and place on
a baking sheet. Bake for 1 hour. Allow to cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. Lower oven temperature to 350 degrees. Cut garlic heads in
half, exposing cloves. Squeeze pulp from skins. Place in a food
processor and puree until a smooth paste is formed. Add cream,
eggs, salt and white pepper. Process again until smooth; do not
overprocess, or the cream will thicken.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bring a tea kettle of water to a boil. Ladle custard into 6
custard cups or ramekins. Place cups in a deep baking pan. Pour
boiling water into the pan two-thirds of the way up the sides of
the cups.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place baking pan in oven. Bake until custard is set, 35 to 40
minutes; do not overcook. Remove cups from the water bath, and
allow to sit for 5 minutes. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Flan may be baked early in the day before it is to be
served, and refrigerated in the baking molds. To reheat, place in
the hot-water bath, cover with foil, and place in a preheated oven
at 400 degrees for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST MACARONI AND CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Perfect Recipe,'' by Pam Anderson (Houghton
Mifflin, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh bread crumbs from French or Italian bread
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt, plus a pinch
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons melted butter, plus 4 tablespoons butter at room
temperature
</P>
<P>
   { pound elbow macaroni
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces evaporated milk, heated until warm
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon hot red-pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard, dissolved in 1 teaspoon water
</P>
<P>
   10 to 12 ounces mild cheddar cheese, grated.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place a 1{-quart heatproof dish,
such as a souffle pan, in oven to warm.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small baking pan, combine bread crumbs, a pinch of salt
and the melted butter. Mix well and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large pot, bring 8 cups of water to a boil. Add 1{
teaspoons of salt and the macaroni. Cook until almost tender but
still a little firm to the bite. Drain and transfer to preheated
dish. Stir in remaining 4 tablespoons of butter.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a small bowl, combine eggs, 1 cup of the evaporated milk,
the pepper sauce, { teaspoon salt, the black pepper and the mustard
mixture. Mix well. Pour egg mixture over macaroni. Add } of the
cheese, and stir until thoroughly combined and cheese starts to
melt.
</P>
<P>
   5. Place dish of macaroni and cheese in the oven, and bake for 5
minutes. Remove dish from oven and add about half of the remaining
evaporated milk, and half of the remaining cheese. Stir well, and
return pan to oven. Bake 5 minutes longer, remove pan from oven,
and stir thoroughly. If mixture does not look moist and creamy, add
a little more of the milk and cheese. Return to oven for an
additional 20 minutes, removing pan from oven halfway through to
stir in remaining evaporated milk and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   6. While macaroni is baking, add pan of bread crumbs to oven.
Bake until bread crumbs are toasted and golden brown, 10 to 15
minutes. Remove from oven and set aside. When macaroni has baked,
sprinkle surface with toasted bread crumbs, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
