<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLISON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE'S ELLISON WINS DEADLY RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sailing novice and Silicon Valley software titan
Larry Ellison cruised to victory in Australia's deadly
Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race but said if it had been his first race
he'd never sail again.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities recovered the bodies of four sailors and gave up
hope Tuesday of finding two others after a monstrous storm
decimated the race with 90-mph winds and 35-foot swells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sailing right through the eye of a hurricane,''
Ellison, owner and skipper of the 78-foot yacht Sayonara, said at a
somber post-race news conference in Hobart.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, CEO of Redwood City-based Oracle Corp., escaped heavy
winds and seas that sank or crippled 59 of the 115 boats entered in
the race _ the worst tragedy in the contest's 54-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was my first race, I would not have gone back to
sea,'' Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   With media tycoon Rupert Murdoch's son Lachlan on board,
Sayonara crossed the line Tuesday, several hours ahead of defending
champion Brindabella, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to pay tribute to families who lost sailors who
were in this race, and our prayers go out to the search crews and
the people who are still in the water,'' Ellison said when Sayonara
was officially declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Sayonara, which rode a southwesterly wind change
to finish at close to 10 knots, finished about five hours outside
the 1996 race record of the Morning Glory.
</P>
<P>
   It was a low-key victory with few spectator boats in Hobart to
greet the Sayonara after massive storms on Sunday devastated the
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's gale raked the fleet of 115 competing in the
630-nautical-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   The storms sent 27 Australian Navy ships scouring the seas for
survivors after the first call of ``Mayday! Mayday! Mayday!'' came
over shipboard radios Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Two Australian sailors were killed when their 40-foot boat,
Business Post Naiad, capsized 60 miles off the New South Wales town
of Merimbula: skipper Bruce Guy and crew member Phil Skeggs. Guy
had an apparent heart attack during one of the boat's two rollovers
and Skeggs drowned when he was unable to release his safety
harness.
</P>
<P>
   Their bodies were left on the abandoned boat by the other
crewmen, but attempts were being made to recover them as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Three crew members from the stricken Winston Churchill _ Jim
Lawler, Mike Bannister and John Dean, all from Sydney _ were washed
out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Six other crewmen were rescued, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the bodies recovered are believed to be those of Winston
Churchill crewmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things got extremely dangerous,'' Ellison said in Hobart.
``Guys were knocked down time and time again and kept getting up
and kept getting back to work to do what was needed to be done to
keep the boat in one piece and keep all of us alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind made sounds I have never heard before,'' Ellison
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the sailors were injured _ with broken bones, dislocated
shoulders, cuts on the face and hands _ from being struck by broken
rigging or tossed upside down when their boats capsized.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison's former sailing tutor, San Francisco Yacht Club skipper
Paul Cayard, expressed praise, sadness and sharp criticism for the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough race every year,'' said Cayard, who skippered the
54-foot yacht Jubilation through the 1987 Sydney-to-Hobart race.
``This year, obviously, they've had a really bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said 50-knot southerly winds cutting across opposing heavy
currents during the opening days of the race created some of yacht
racing's most hazardous seas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that every year,'' said Cayard, skipper of
AmericaOne, the St. Francis Yacht Club's entry at the 1999 New
Zealand challenge for the prestigious America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard was particularly saddened to hear of the loss of fellow
yacht racer Glyn Charles, who was washed off the Sword of Orion
yacht Sunday night and presumed drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Australian rescue officials on Tuesday called off the search for
Charles, still missing along with one of the Winston Churchill's
crew members after storms overwhelmed the race on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really sad thing,'' said Cayard. ``But it's something
that you have to learn to accept when you're in this line of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard said he wasn't surprised to learn of Ellison's victory in
the 80-foot Sayonara, a custom-designed racing yacht.
</P>
<P>
   The average size of a boat in the race is 40 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest boat in the fleet,'' said Cayard. ``It's like
a 500-horsepower car beating a 200-horsepower car.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard said Ellison's crew also gave him an edge in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done `round-the-world races,'' said Cayard. ``They
know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard helped Ellison first learn about sailing when the
software mogul bought the Sayonara in 1995 and skippered the boat
during several trans-oceanic races.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's big for a beginner,'' said Cayard. ``But he can afford
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does Ellison rate as a sailor?
</P>
<P>
   Cayard said he always tries to tread a fine line between running
a boat and letting the well-to-do owners ``feel like they're in
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, Cayard said, was ``somewhere in the middle'' between
boat owners who want to run things immediately, and those who are
shy about taking the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't overbearing,'' said Cayard. ``Now he's knowledgeable
and involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cayard was critical of some racers in this year's Australian
race, saying the desire for speed is edging out the safety factor
in sailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is most of the fleet is not prepared to encounter
(Sydney-to-Hobart) conditions,'' said Cayard. ``Most are built like
Formula One racers, to go around the buoys during a day race. It's
very typical. And we were all asking for something like this to
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
