<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECTING PRIVACY IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As 1998 winds to a close (finally!), many in the
online world are sounding an alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern: privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Web continues to grow, reaching into the lives of millions
of people, becoming a part of everyday life and emerging as a
trusted medium of communication _ everything from simple e-mail to
delicate financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, that's good. The more people online, the more
useful the Web becomes. And the more people embrace computers and
online communication, the more benefits we all enjoy _ everything
from secure online banking to lively forums on our favorite topics.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the booming online economy has sparked a mad
dash for cash _ money to be earned from anybody and everybody who
goes online. And the money can be made whether or not you've given
a Web site your Visa card number.
</P>
<P>
   How? By selling your information _ your age, your browsing
habits, the advertisements you choose to click on, your hometown
and any other tidbit Web sites can glean from you as your
electronic path crosses their contest entry forms and other tricks
they use to get you to enter personal data.
</P>
<P>
   Online ``cookies,'' nuggets of information Web sites store on
your hard drive, remain as useful to the individual surfer as to
the originating Web site. But cookies, combined with ``data
mining,'' the ability of highly technical software tools to dive
into oceans of seemingly unrelated data and emerge with trends that
can be used to make money, are making the information brokering
business a lucrative one.
</P>
<P>
   Millions, if not billions, of dollars are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   All this has renewed interest and concern over online privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites make money by luring as many people as possible
through their electronic doors.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web sites, especially heavy-hitters such as Yahoo! or
America Online, try to convince the surfing public to begin each
online venture using specific online ``portals,'' or home pages.
They do this by offering free e-mail and the ability to customize
the portal to suit individual desires when it comes to news, sports
and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Once surfers have entered all of their information into the
appropriate online form, they are treated to a more personalized
and somewhat friendlier online experience.
</P>
<P>
   But what's to keep the Web site that just collected all that
data from turning around and selling it?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Although many major Web sites have taken great pains to protect
the privacy of their users, many others continue to operate with
little or no regard to individual privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wired News'' recently concluded that despite repeated warnings
from federal regulators, the online community has done a poor job
regulating itself when it comes to protecting the privacy of
individual users.
</P>
<P>
   In a Dec. 22 perspective piece, James Glave of ``Wired News''
indicated that federally imposed consumer privacy protection laws
might be the answer:
</P>
<P>
   `` `Trust us,'' say the Internet lobbyists fighting such laws
under the self-regulation lobby,'' Glave wrote. ``But why should
you? You have no more control over information kept about you than
you did a year and a half ago, when leaders of the Web first stood
up in Federal Trade Commission hearings and argued against laws
that would empower end users.''
</P>
<P>
   The dawning of 1999 may, in fact, bring some type of federal
regulation of online privacy unless self-regulating efforts, such
as TrustE, an industry coalition that hands out ``privacy seals of
approval'' to deserving Web sites, are able to make some
significant headway.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, individual users can do a few things to protect
themselves:
</P>
<P>
   - When using Web sites that require personal information, first
look and see whether they have a posted policy on privacy. If they
do, read it. Make sure you don't need to check a box somewhere or
send someone e-mail to keep them from selling your data. If they
don't have a privacy policy, take your business somewhere else!
</P>
<P>
   - Even if a Web site offers a great privacy policy, think twice
before filling out contest entry forms or other methods of online
registration. Do you really value what you will get in return for
giving up your personal data?
</P>
<P>
   - When faced with an online registration form of any sort, don't
just blindly fill in all the blanks. Often, only certain fields are
required, such as your e-mail address. Many other fields, such as
your annual household income, your age, etc., could be optional.
You can protect some of your privacy by not filling in the optional
fields.
</P>
<P>
   - Like to participate in online forums? No problem with that.
But be cautious about the personal facts you sprinkle throughout
your missives. Messages posted to public forums take on lives of
their own, and personal details you've revealed can be collected
and used by anybody.
</P>
<P>
   - Read more about online privacy and, if you oversee a Web site,
develop your own privacy policy by visiting TrustE's Web site at
www.truste.org/ or the Web site of the Online Privacy Alliance at
www.privacyalliance.org/.
</P>
<P>
   - Want to become more active in protecting online privacy? Check
out the Privacy Watchdog, a new Web site and service created by the
Center for Democracy and Technology. The site, at
watchdog.cdt.org/, is aimed at halting the abuse of online cookies.
It encourages individual Web surfers to participate by rating Web
sites of their choice when it comes to privacy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOME SERVER NEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regular readers of this column know that I like to rant about
the need for home networks _ systems linked to a home server that
can run electronic appliances throughout the home.
</P>
<P>
   Pieces of such home networks exist, but I've yet to see anybody
get serious about making it work in a cost-effective and realistic
fashion. We need, for example, computer terminals designed for the
space where they are to be used, like small, easily cleaned models
for the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as though 1999 will bring us closer to that reality.
</P>
<P>
   First off, industry insiders say the coming year will see the
first products released that meet the so-called ``HAVI'' standards.
HAVI, which stands for Home Audio Video Interoperability, allows
companies to make devices that all can ``talk'' to each other.
</P>
<P>
   A simple example of HAVI's usefulness: You download the latest
album from your favorite musical group from a Web site, but instead
of just saving it to your computer's hard drive, you pass it on for
immediate use to the stereo in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, Matsushita, Hitachi, Toshiba, Sharp, Thompson and Philips
are expected to release the first HAVI devices over the next 12
months. Whether they'll be cheap enough to purchase, I'm not sure.
But this is a step in the right direction!
</P>
<P>
   Another home server development: CEOs are beginning to speak
openly about the home server market and the fact that the
development of such a market will play a key role in maintaining
strong sales of PCs.
</P>
<P>
   This news has surfaced from a variety of sources, including
``Fortune'' magazine's David Kirkpatrick, who managed to speak to
five CEOs at the recent COMDEX computer trade show in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway CEO Ted Waitt and Sony Electronics President Teruaki
Aoki both told Kirkpatrick that home PCs would become servers
capable of running a variety of appliances throughout the home.
</P>
<P>
   Aoki went so far as to say that the home server concept is one
of the reasons Sony entered the PC business.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see where the home server idea stands
come this time next year.  &QL; 
THIS WEEK'S DOSE OF HUMOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I remember back in my school days reading books about
``pioneers.'' Typically, these were folks who did things like
crossing America in covered wagons 150 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Internet and the fast pace of computers, we are
now seeing the word ``pioneer'' used with a bit more abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: A recent press release from the public relations
staff behind iPrint.com, an online print shop at www.iprint.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``iPrint.com pioneered the concept of the online print shop back
in early 1997,'' the press release stated.
</P>
<P>
   Good god! Early 1997? That was a loooong time ago! Was Arizona
even a state back then?
</P>
<P>
   Ha!
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's it for this week (and 1998)! Happy computing, and
have a great New Year! &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
