<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-MICROSOFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLIND GRADUATE STEPS INTO MICROSOFT'S WORLD  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Loren Mikola is asking friends with good fashion sense
to put little tags on his clothes so he won't look goofy on on his
first day of work at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   He's also brushing up on his cooking skills because, at the age
of 24, he's moving out of his parents' Glendale, Ariz., house.
</P>
<P>
   He'll also have to learn to navigate the public bus system in
Microsoft's hometown of Redmond, Wash., because it's probably best
he doesn't drive.
</P>
<P>
   Mikola is blind but has managed to use Braille books and quick
wits to graduate with honors from Arizona State University College
of Business in Tempe, Ariz., and land a $44,000 job with the
nation's leading software firm.
</P>
<P>
   His family members cheered earlier this month as he received his
bachelor's degree in computer information systems.
</P>
<P>
   When Mikola initiated his job search in August, he feared the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought I would have a difficult time finding a job
because no matter what everybody says there's discrimination out
there,'' Mikola said. ``So I really feel fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mikola began handing out resumes during on-campus job fairs,
he only stopped at Microsoft's booth because his friend did. He
even told the representative that he wasn't interested in leaving
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   So Mikola was surprised when Microsoft requested an interview.
When they met, the recruiter only asked two questions. One was,
``how would you design a toaster?''
</P>
<P>
   Mikola was even more surprised when Bill Gates' company flew him
to Redmond where he sat through five hours of interviews. They
asked, ``how would you design a stapler?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought they'd give me an offer,'' Mikola said.
</P>
<P>
   But they did.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it's not that un usual for them to hire people
with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft looks for people that are smart and that's our first
priority,'' spokeswoman Beth Brainard said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Mikola is ``an incredible asset'' because he can offer his
perspective on whether Microsoft's products to assist the blind
work well, Brainard said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikola also received a competitive offer from Andersen
Consulting. The job involved extensive travel and overtime, factors
that led him to turn them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what it means for me to have an offer from
them, too, because they were able to make me an offer and look past
my disability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Going to Redmond won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   But, Mikola is up to the task, armed with a can-do attitude his
family has impressed upon him for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was born, to me, he could see. And that's how I raised
him,'' said his mother, Judy Peabody.
</P>
<P>
   Since boyhood, Mikola has gone fishing, camping and to the
movies just like his siblings.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-pound stripped bass he caught while on a fishing trip hangs
on his bedroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   He attended regular public schools where he also took special
classes to learn Braille. He graduated valedictorian from his high
school in Michigan, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   He attended a junior college in a suburb of Detroit until his
family moved to Glendale, in part so that Mikola could begin
studying at ASU in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his first unassisted day on ASU's sprawling, crowded
campus, Mikola laughs and shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   He missed his turns and got lost among the university's 50,000
hurried students.
</P>
<P>
   In time he learned to make his way.
</P>
<P>
   Accounting Professor Paul Steinbart remembers Mikola as a
bright, friendly student who was quick to offer an answer in class.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from preparing tests early so that Mikola could take them
orally, Steinbart made few accommodations for Mikola.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really almost forgot that he was blind,'' Steinbart said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikola uses a handful of tools that help him live a relatively
normal life. He has a cane, uses a tape recorder rather than taking
notes in class and has textbooks made into Braille.
</P>
<P>
   At home he has a Braille terminal attached to his computer. Its
a long rectangular board with pins that gently raise up to
translate the words on the monitor into Braille. Also, he has a
speech synthesizer that can read the words on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   He's loved computers ever first started playing on them at age
14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like seeing people and technology working together,'' he
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rebecca Rolwing can be reached at rebecca.rolwing(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
