<HEADER>
A0546 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-29 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDING A CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only one more year to go and we can wrap up an
astonishingly tumultuous, revolutionary century with a whimper, a
bang, a cheer or a sigh of relief, depending on the point of view.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens in 1999, the 20th century has already
recorded two world wars; the Vietnam war; the start of the nuclear
age; the exploration of space; massive industrialization;
inventions that have transformed communications, transportation and
everyday life; the emancipation of women; the rise of civil rights;
unprecedented prosperity as well as a crushing Depression, and a
steadily spreading cynicism about national leaders and
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon's resignation to avoid House impeachment and
President Clinton's impeachment trial in the Senate are political
milestones with inevitable psychological impact. But they are not
as profoundly important in the course of human events as the great
shifts of philosophy, politics, technology and power that have
taken place.
</P>
<P>
   It may turn out that 1999 is merely a leftover year to kill,
unimportant in the grand scheme of things. Perhaps it will be the
equivalent of my grandmother sitting on her farmhouse porch
watching the corn grow. But who knows?
</P>
<P>
   One hundred years ago, in 1899, not a lot occurred to indicate
what a dramatically different era was ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The first magnetic recording of sound only hinted at the
potential for world-wide communication. Theodore Dreiser published
his first novel, Sister Carrie, about a disgraced woman with a will
to survive. It was not a critical or commercial success but later
came to be viewed as capturing the emerging spiritual emptiness in
a materialistic society.
</P>
<P>
   The big political event of 1899 did not seem so significant at
the time. President William McKinley's vice president, Garret
Hobart, died, thus leaving a vacancy for McKinley to fill when he
ran for re-election in 1900. The popular governor of New York and
hero of the Spanish-American war, Theodore Roosevelt, was easily
nominated as Hobart's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   When a newly re-elected McKinley was assassinated by an
anarchist in 1901, Roosevelt was propelled into the White House,
where he became one of our most respected presidents. As the first
chief executive in tune with the changing times, Roosevelt battled
corporate monopolies, demanded conservation of American parkland
and fought for new consumer protections like the Food and Drug Act
and employers' liability laws.
</P>
<P>
   There may be few clues to the next century from the 12 months of
1999 as well.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will be in a holding pattern, doing little. The Clinton
impeachment drama will consume the White House and Senate until a
trial is completed or detoured into a censure path. After that,
exhaustion and the political calendar will take over. Congressional
maneuvering for re-election in a polarized atmosphere will prevent
substantive action on anything.
</P>
<P>
   As for the House, it is now so tarnished as partisan and
unreasoning that, like Humpty Dumpty, it cannot be put together in
its present shape. New political eggs, fresh from the 2000
election, will be required before it can function usefully again.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of this century, forget progress on Social Security
and Medicare financing. Forget education reform. Forget campaign
finance reform. Not even re-naming an airport for the Virgin Mary
could win approval before the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   This year is also likely to be as clueless about international
relations in the next century as 1899 was about the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Already we have gone from the Cold War terror of nuclear
disaster to an era of harassment by minor rogue nations that cannot
compete with our global power but can generate chaos, brutalize
their neighbors and threaten American lives. Where this leads us
depends on the ability of evil forces to carry out their sinister
intentions, the diplomatic skills and wisdom of the peaceful
international community and the growing strength or weakness of
democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of Iraq and the continuing tensions there represent
a dangerous situation but not necessarily a permanent one. The
Middle East is a muddle as always, but progress has been made
against incredible political odds and the process continues. The
Soviet Union is kaput, a ruin of its former self. The seeds of
trouble are there but with luck and care they need not germinate.
</P>
<P>
   The new year will be a transitional period, cleaning up the
Clinton crisis and preparing for the presidential election that
will dominate the first year of the next century. Will we get lucky
and pick another Teddy Roosevelt? Let us hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
