<SLUG> BC-MARIUCCI-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARWINIAN DAYS GONE FOR FRANCHISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Steve Mariucci picked a ruthless occupation, and
a ruthless organization picked Mariucci. The 49ers jettisoned Joe
Montana and Ronnie Lott, so why not the young head coach?
</P>
<P>
   He is 25-7 in two regular seasons, and anywhere else, he would
be invulnerable. But Mariucci coaches the 49ers, and on his watch,
they have surrendered their domain, the NFC West, and lost two
straight to Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   This still shouldn't be enough to put him in harm's way, but
George Seifert reached the 1996 NFC title game with a badly damaged
Steve Young and was ushered out the door the minute the season
ended. This is the way the 49ers do business, the way they treat
family. So why not Mariucci?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the scenario,'' said Jerry Rice, cutting through the
niceties. ``I've been in the league 14 years, and there are
questions about me, right? It's a business, and I'm learning. I'm
learning fast. Ain't no guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   But the business has changed for the 49ers. For years, Darwinian
principles favored them. They could get rid of anybody, because
they were bigger than any one player or one coach. They could
hemorrhage talent and turn around to find someone else happy to
open a vein on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams had to worry about whether they could afford to lose
a star, whether they could land a great new head coach. They
couldn't afford to be ruthless.
</P>
<P>
   So why not, at long last, the 49ers?
</P>
<P>
   Who says they can afford to dump a talented young coach on the
assumption that something or someone better is waiting for them?
</P>
<P>
   The rampant speculation around these parts says that Mike
Holmgren will be courted by the Niners if his Packers beat
Mariucci's squad in this weekend's playoff game. Mariucci's stock
will take a dive, and he will be expendable, even with three years
left on his contract. Or so the reasoning goes.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody really knows what the 49ers, as an organization, want
to do. Maybe they don't, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have anything but rumors?'' Steve Young asked, when
questioned about Mariucci's alleged predicament.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, all we have are hints. The biggest one is that
Mariucci was approached about a contract extension in early October
and that the deal never got done.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that the club's confidence in its young coach
wavered as the penalties piled up, as Atlanta rode higher and
higher, as the sacks kept coming and the pitiful teams that once
bowed to the 49ers at kickoff struck for early leads?
</P>
<P>
   That's possible, but the inability to complete an extension
discredits the 49ers' front office more than it does Mariucci. With
three years left on his old deal, the only legitimate reason to
offer a new one was a desire for clarity, to center the club in the
absence of a president, general manager and owner. To make that
move, to aim for clarity, the Niners needed to be clear themselves,
certain that they had the coach that they wanted for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   They slipped a rug under Mariucci, and then it got pulled out.
By him? By them? It doesn't matter. The Niners should never have
let it happen. It reveals them to be either vacillating or
ineffectual, neither of which is remotely related to ruthless.
</P>
<P>
   The presumption behind the Holmgren rumors is that the Packers
coach can have his pick of jobs after the season. He wants to be a
coach and general manager, and the 49ers happen to have an opening
in the GM's spot. But even if the Niners were willing to sweep
aside Mariucci to create room for Holmgren, who says that San
Francisco would be his first choice?
</P>
<P>
   He is a native of the city, and that could be inducement. But
what reason does he have to believe that the 49ers, in their
current predicament, can foster greatness for much longer?
</P>
<P>
   Will Eddie DeBartolo, whenever he returns from his Cajun-fried
exile, still have pockets deep enough to a) pay Mariucci's contract
off, b) spend the millions in salary it would take to lure a
Holmgren here and c) assure that the next general manager has
enough payroll money to continue tooling around the salary cap?
</P>
<P>
   On purely football terms, Carolina may have a better job to
offer. So might Seattle, with Paul Allen's millions. In those
towns, the resources are fairly predictable and extremely generous,
while the expectations are lower. A coach with a 12-4 record
wouldn't be asked to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   Here, there is an aging roster and a pending salary-cap
nightmare, not to mention a front office with tumbleweeds blowing
through it.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, Mariucci may have more leverage than
the 49ers. If, somehow, he is in jeopardy, he should know that a
job will turn up quickly. Cleveland would surely make a play for
him if the 49ers went the ruthless route.
</P>
<P>
   If the Niners win this weekend, and their chances look good from
here, this whole issue could be moot. Then again, it could be moot
now. Nobody knows, because there is really nobody to ask.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, there was always someone with an answer, even if it
was just another round of slippery comments from Carmen Policy.
Now, all is silent. They don't do business the same way anymore.
They've lost too much in the last year, maybe even the ability to
be ruthless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
