<SLUG> BC-BAY-BRIDGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES CRITICIZE PLAN FOR NEW BAY BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The state Transportation Department faces almost
certain legal challenges as it moves ahead with a plan to replace a
heavily used bridge that was badly damaged in a 1989 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The department, known as Caltrans, is moving forward with plans
to place the eastern span of the Bay Bridge north of the current
structure, a design that the Metropolitan Transportation Commission
recommended in June.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Mulligan, program manager of the Toll Bridge Program, said
Caltrans was bracing for lawsuits and expected that many would be
filed in June, when the choice is expected to be finalized.
However, he said, a delay in construction seemed unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every large project we do gets sued,'' Mulligan said. ``The
question is how often and by whom. We can't satisfy all the
competing interests on this issue. We'll proceed with our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans made its announcement Monday, rejecting five
alternatives. The bridge is expected to cost $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans has begun design of the northern alignment of the
bridge, drilling in various areas across the San Francisco Bay to
determine seismic responses on the Bay floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motivation, why we're not sitting on our hands, is we live
in a seismic zone. ... It's prudent to proceed as expeditiously as
possible,'' Mulligan said.
</P>
<P>
   The upper deck of the eastern span collapsed during the 1989
Loma Prieta earthquake. That quake registered 7.1 on the Richter
scale and killed 63 people in the Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown was said to be disappointed with Caltrans'
decision, a spokesman said. The Brown administration favors a span
that would be constructed on the southern side of the existing
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as though Caltrans is buying themselves a lawsuit,''
said Ron Vinson, the mayor's spokesman. ``San Francisco will
continue to fight for an environmentally friendly southern
alignment. We will continue to work with the city of Oakland, the
Port of Oakland, the Federal Highway Administration, the Coast
Guard, Navy and other entities to develop a consensus for moving
forward with the southern alignment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Port of Oakland and East Bay Regional Park District
oppose a southern alignment because it would cut into property they
use.
</P>
<P>
   If there are no delays, Caltrans plans to begin construction of
the new eastern span in 2000 and complete it in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   As designed, the single-tower suspension bridge would be
positioned to cut into the northeastern edge of Yerba Buena Island
that San Francisco hopes to redevelop once the Navy releases the
property to the city. The design calls for five lanes in each
direction, two 20-foot shoulders and a 15-foot-wide bicycle and
pedestrian path.
</P>
<P>
   After approving a northern alignment two years ago, Brown
changed his position when he realized that the new span and ramps
would wreak havoc with the redevelopment plans for the island. He
has since proposed a span south of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors of Alameda, Albany, Berkeley, Emeryville, Oakland and
Piedmont have pushed the transportation officials to consider a
more elegant design than the proposed single-tower suspension. They
say the 7,800-foot skyway leading to the suspension bridge, which
traverses shallow water, is unattractive.
</P>
<P>
   The design being pushed by Caltrans also doesn't include rail
service, which voters in November said they preferred. Caltrans
argues that the project has financial constraints and that
additional amenities, such as rail service, would not fit in the
budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
