<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-PROBE _ WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. George Mitchell and
other members of the special commission probing allegations of
improprieties related to how Salt Lake City won the bid to host the
2002 Winter Olympics will discuss their investigation. Other
members include former Reagan Chief of Staff Ken Duberstein and
Donald Fehr, executive director of the Major League Baseball
Players Association. All will attend Tuesday's news conference.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (s) sports, (i) international and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GA-SC-ALA-LOTTERY _ ATLANTA _ South Carolina Gov.-elect Jim
Hodges meets with outgoing Georgia Gov. Zell Miller today to
discuss the lottery and education. Miller will hold a news
conferenc0e after the meeting. Miller met last week with Alabama
Gov.-elect Don Siegleman on the same topic. All three were elected
promising a lottery for education, and the others are asking Miller
for advice. Miller, for his part, is asking the other two how much
revenue they expect to take from residents who currently cross
state lines to play Georgia's lottery. (Mantius, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   STONEMOUNTAIN-FEES _ ATLANTA _ Stone Mountain's governing board
balks at raising the entrance fee from $6 a car to $7, yearly fee
from $25 to $30. Board members delay vote, saying $6.50 is more in
line with inflation. Vote postponed until January. Board asking
Silver Dollar City, the private company now running the park, to
justify the increase. (Torpy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-PRIVATEPRISON-LAPSES _ ATLANTA _ Little more than a month
after the first private prison opened in Georgia, state inspectors
found security lapses, sloppy record-keeping and dirt during two
inspections of the D. Ray James State Prison, which Cornell
Corrections Inc. operates in Charlton County. According to reports
from state Department of Corrections monitors after inspections at
the Cornell prison on Nov. 18-19 and again on Dec. 9, the private
prison guards were not keeping track of inmates as they moved
around the prison. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-ED _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Does talking about safer sex encourage
teens to have sex? Some say it does. Others, including some of
those who preach abstinence, acknowledge that some teens are
sexually active and need to hear the message of safer sex. The Ohio
Department of Education is weighing arguments on all sides in the
HIV education debate as the department develops a model health and
physical education program. The model is a collection of goals
students should be able to reach for each grade level. Among those
goals are learning about reproduction and ways to prevent sexually
transmitted diseases. (Hulsey, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
