<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0644 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MITCH-FOREST-HNS &LR;      12-29 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-FOREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFORESTATION ADDED TO MITCH DEVASTATION, ENVIRONMENTALISTS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA ESPERANZA, Honduras _ Juan Benito Palma scans the deep sea of
mud, rocks and uprooted trees that now fills what was once a green,
tranquil valley near the mouth of the Choluteca River on Honduras'
Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   He takes a break from chopping wood and, straightening his back,
sweeps a hand toward the low range of mountains a half-mile across
the rubble. Once this was all watermelon fields, he says. Over
there were pastures for goats and cattle. The tallest, prettiest
trees used to shade the riverbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was beautiful,'' Palma says, grimacing at the pile of
debris that rises higher than a standing man and wider than a dozen
football fields laid end to end. ``Now look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like all of Honduras has been brought here,'' he says.
``The flood carried everything down.``
</P>
<P>
   The flood was caused by Hurricane Mitch, which worked its way
across this bedeviled land in late October. The storm killed at
least 5,600 people in Honduras, damaged or destroyed the homes of a
million more and left some 8,000 still missing here, according to
the government.
</P>
<P>
   The storm also scraped away scarce topsoil, collapsed
mountainsides and gnawed at an ecosystem already frayed from
over-farming, over-logging, over-building and over-population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should serve as a lesson,'' says Edwin Mateo Molina, a
Honduran sociologist who specializes in environmental issues for
the Inter-American Development Bank. ``Everyone realizes that the
damage was magnified by the misuse of resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will happen again,'' Molina says of Mitch's accentuated
destruction, ``and will be even worse unless we look for a way to
use the land in a more responsible manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Years of logging the once-thick pines in the mountains and
clearing the rain forests in the coastal lowlands for farming meant
that there was little left to hold the soil when Mitch's deluge
came.
</P>
<P>
   Years of building makeshift houses and solid middle-class
neighborhoods along riverbanks, gullies and flood plains had
ignored the urge of water to reclaim its own balance.
</P>
<P>
   Years of chopping, building and clearing had subdued the
Honduran landscape under the weight of a burgeoning population.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after Mitch, the Honduran highlands look as if some giant
beast has swaggered through, scratching the mountainsides with
vengeful claws, sending everything tumbling into the deep valleys
and away.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, tidal surges have swept away houses. Rivers have
changed course, collapsing dikes, sweeping entire neighborhoods
from the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature is going to demand its quota,'' Molina says. ``It's not
that the rivers entered houses. Houses entered the river.``
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Nicaragua, about 100 miles south of La Esperanza,
a murderous landslide caused by Mitch's rains killed as many as
2,000 people. Environmentalists say that deforestation contributed
to the tragedy, which occurred when a mudflow at the rim of a small
volcano tumbled unhindered to the sea, burying several villages of
farmers drawn to the region years before in search of fertile
lands. Once the landslide began Oct. 30, geologists say, there was
little to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   In the mountains of south-central Honduras, 40 miles to the
north of La Esperanza, Jose Santos just smiles wearily and points
up the steep slope across the highway from his house to where his
two acres of corn once stood.
</P>
<P>
   Like many poor farmers in a country with little flat land,
Santos has had to scratch his fields into slopes whose grade would
challenge a Swiss skier. He built small dams on mountain streams to
irrigate his grain. He cut away trees to have more land to plant.
</P>
<P>
   When Mitch came, Santos says, the dam went first. And then the
few trees that were left. And then the corn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was raining day and night, night and day,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche swept across the road, which connects the capital
of Tegucigalpa with the Pacific coast, to the right and left of
Santos' house, and on down the steep valley walls to a river, which
connected to another, which swept away about a third of the town of
Pespire, 15 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good soil is all gone,'' Santos says, nodding toward the
rock-strewn soil of what's left of his runaway field. ``But we've
got to try to plant again. There is no other land around here.''
</P>
<P>
   With population growth of about 3 percent a year, among the
highest in Latin America, the number of Hondurans tripled between
1945 and 1988 and now stands at about 5.5 million. Despite decades
of immigration to the cities, nearly 60 percent of Hondurans still
live in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   As in many Latin American countries, wealthy ranchers and
farmers control the best land along river bottoms and wide valleys.
An exploding peasant population on a limited amount of tillable
land led the government in the 1970s to encourage the settlement of
the thickly forested mountains and plains of northern and eastern
Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   While it alleviated some of the population pressures in the
impoverished central and southern mountains, the resettlement to
the north also spread the country's deforestation problem.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1962 and 1990, Honduras lost nearly 20 percent of its
forests, according to a recently published study by the World
Wildlife Foundation. Deforestation continues at a pace of some
250,000 acres a year, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been made worse by the export-focused economic
policies of the past decade, which have further concentrated much
of the best land in a few wealthy hands at the expense of the poor
majority of farmers, the World Wildlife study and others argue.
</P>
<P>
   Peasants now plant corn and other crops up the sides of steep,
thinly soiled mountains along the Caribbean coast that were virgin
forests just a few decades ago. And flooding in the newly settled
areas was as bad as anywhere, Molina and other environmentalists
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ecological pressure in the countryside is worsening,''
says Rafael Diaz, president of an umbrella group of 100
nongovernmental aid agencies, many of which work in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, sustainable development and farming techniques
that do not destroy the land rank among the primary focuses of aid
efforts by foreign governments and the more than 300 aid agencies
in Honduras. So far, some aid experts say, there have been few good
results.
</P>
<P>
   But with Honduras' population expected to double, to about 12
million people, in the next 25 years, experts here say that
developing a more ecologically friendly economy is of primary
importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look for policies that won't damage the earth,''
says Oscar Fernandez, coordinator of the Honduran Red Cross' relief
effort in along the Pacific coast. ``We have to learn to live with
the land, not just on it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
