<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0647 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLYMPICS-PROBE     12-29 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-PROBE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MITCHELL PROMISES 'THOROUGH AND PROMPT' PROBE OF SALT LAKE CITY
OLYMPICS BID
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (s) sports, (i) international and
(w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Sen. George Mitchell on Tuesday promised to
direct a ``thorough and prompt'' investigation into allegations
that thousands of dollars worth of possibly illegal favors were
used to lure the 2002 Winter Games to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, named by the U.S. Olympic Committee to head a
six-person ``special commission'' to look into the charges, refused
during a press conference to rule out the possibility his group
also would ask questions about methods used a decade ago to bring
the 1996 Olympics to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But he and other members of the newly appointed commission
indicated that any questions about the Atlanta games would be for
the purpose of understanding the overall climate in which U.S.
cities compete with foreign cities for the right to host the
events.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said serving on the commission would not interfere with
his role as an advisor to President Clinton during impeachment
proceedings, which appear likely to occur at the same time the
Olympics investigation is going on.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell commission is now one of four organizations,
including the Justice Department, looking into allegations that
college scholarships, free medical service and lavish gifts were
used to get members of the International Olympic Committee to vote
in favor of Salt Lake City's bid to host the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The international committee and an independent ethics panel in
Salt Lake City also are investigating the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesman confirmed last week that federal
investigators are looking into methods used by organizers of the
Salt Lake City bid. Published reports said the probe would focus on
possible violations of federal bribery, mail fraud and tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the Mitchell commission are Bill Hybl,
president of the U.S. Olympics Committee; Donald Fehr, executive
director of the Major League Baseball Players Association; Ken
Duberstein, former chief of staff to President Ronald Reagan;
Roberta Cooper Ramo of Albuquerque, N.M., past president of the
American Bar Association, and Jeff Benz, at-large member of the
U.S. Olympic Committee athletes' advisory council.
</P>
<P>
   The only member of the commission not associated with the U.S.
Olympics Committee is Ramo. Duberstein and Mitchell already served
on the committee's ethics panel and Fehr is a member of the
committee's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the decision of whether Salt Lake City will be allowed
to continue as the host city for the 2002 Winter Games is not up to
the U.S. committee, Mitchell said he expected the games to be held
there. A spokesman for the International Olympic Committee has said
the games will not be moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do the best we can within our power and scope to
determine what the context was of these actions,'' Mitchell said,
adding that his commission also will attempt to provide
recommendations to the U.S. Olympic Committee for ``guidelines and
enforcement mechanisms'' to assure that future efforts by U.S.
cities to lure Olympic games are above reproach.
</P>
<P>
   Without subpoena powers, the inquiry will be conducted on the
basis of voluntarily-provided information from persons involved in
attracting Olympic games, he said. It is to be completed by Feb.
28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to begin by saying that we are looking at Salt
Lake City or we are looking at Atlanta,'' Mitchell said when asked
if his the commission would restrict its questions to the Utah
city's bid. ``We will do what's necessary to establish fairly the
context in which these events occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   He said at another point that ``if there were activities in the
past that were inappropriate, we want to make sure they don't occur
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   He generally avoided answering questions about the impeachment
proceedings facing Clinton but said that ``my role in this
commission will not preclude my role in the impeachment process.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, a former federal prosecutor and U.S. district judge in
Maine, was majority leader of the Senate from 1989 to1994 and
served this year as Clinton's special representatives to talks that
led to a cease-fire in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
