<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS30-C     12-29 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings for the holidays
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Lanier Islands (Ga.) _ Magical Nights of Lights, a
drive-through animated light show on the shores of Lake Lanier,
features storybook vignettes including ``Cinderella,'' ``Jack and
the Beanstalk'' and ``Wizard of Oz.'' Through Thursday.
770-932-7275.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ ``Christmas at Biltmore Estate'' through
Sunday includes day tours of the festively decorated mansion and
Candlelight Christmas Evenings (by reservation only).
1-800-211-9803 or http://www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ River Gallery in the Bluff View Art District
presents ``Winter Cordial,'' featuring the landscapes of Lawrence
Mathis and floral sculptures of glass artists Yaffa Sikorsky-Todd
and Jeffrey M. Todd. Opening Saturday. Artist reception 6:30-8:30
p.m. Jan. 8. Through Jan. 31. 423-267-7353.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis _ The annual Elvis Presley Birthday Celebration at
Graceland is Jan. 8-10. 1-800-238-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ Wilderness Wildlife Week of Nature Jan.
9-17 is an educational and entertaining program that focuses on
preserving the beauty of the Smokies with more than 80 nature
experts, nature hikes and lectures. 1-800-251-9100.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biloxi, Miss. _ The Professional Cowboy Association holds its
Championship Finals Jan. 7-10 at the Mississippi Gulf Coast
Coliseum. Parade is 6 p.m. Jan. 6. 1-888-467-4853.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ The New Orleans Museum of Art presents ``Ancient
Gold: The Wealth of the Thracians, Treasures From the Republic of
Bulgaria'' through Sunday. The exhibit features more than 200
brilliant gold and silver objects. 504-488-2631.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Athens , Ga._ The Georgia Museum of Art is the first U.S.
museum to present ``Rembrandt: Treasures From the Rembrandt House,
Amsterdam.'' The exhibition, through Jan. 10, includes 82 etchings
and two copperplates that give a thorough representation of
Rembrandt's body of work in printmaking, 1628-1659. 706-542-0487.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Louisville, Ky. _ The Speed Art Museum presents ``Rodin:
Sculpture From the Iris and B. Gerald Cantor Collection,''
featuring more than 60 large and small scale sculptures, including
``The Walking Man,'' ``The Burghers of Calais'' and ``The
Thinker.'' Through Jan. 31. 502-634-2700.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmond _ The Virginia Museum of Fine Arts presents
``Designed for Delight: Alternative Aspects of Twentieth-Century
Decorative Arts'' through Jan. 31. The exhibition includes 200
objects from the Montreal Museum of Decorative Arts representing
major stylistic movements from art nouveau and art deco to pop and
postmodernism. 804-367-0878.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charlotte _ The Mint Museum of Art presents ``Earth, Fire and
Spirit: African Pottery and Sculpture,'' an exhibit that explores
nearly 2,000 years of West African ceramic history and includes
ancient terra cotta figures as well as contemporary vessels and
sculpture. Through Feb. 14. 704-337-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ The Historic New Orleans Collection presents
``Seen and Not Heard: Facets of Childhood in 19th-Century New
Orleans'' through April. Includes vintage photographs, drawings,
prints, books, manuscripts and ephemera. 504-523-4662.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charlotte _ The Mint Museum of Art and the Afro-American
Cultural Center of Charlotte present ``Lois Mailou Jones and Her
Former Students: An American Legacy'' through Monday. The
exhibition features eight paintings by Jones, including signature
works ``Les Fetiches'' and ``Moon Masque,'' and 72 works by 38 of
her former students at Howard University. 704-337-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The Charleston Museum celebrates its 225th
birthday with the exhibition ``Queens &AMP; Commoners of Egypt's New
Kingdom'' from the British Museum. Through June 30. 360 Meeting St.
843-722-2996 or http://www.charlestonmuseum.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
