<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY30-1999-COX     12-29 1534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY30-1999-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A roundup of notable Southern happenings in '99
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Mint condition
</P>
<P>
   A former department store in downtown Charlotte will be the home
of the Mint Museum of Craft + Design. The new showcase for
international craft, an uptown branch of the 62-year-old Mint
Museum, will open Jan. 10. The 82,000-square-foot Montaldo's
Department Store was renovated by Bank of America (formerly
NationsBank) at a cost of $9.5 million. An extravagant blown glass
chandelier by Seattle glass artist Dale Chihuly will be the lobby's
centerpiece. A 40-foot glass wall by Tom Patti will dominate the
carriageway. The permanent collection display on the ground floor
will be ``Currents in Craft,'' illustrating contemporary art in
craft media. The second floor permanent collection, opening in
March, will feature craft developments of the 19th through mid-20th
century. Inaugural exhibitions opening Jan. 10 are ``The White
House Collection of American Crafts'' (through May 30) and ``Harvey
K. Littleton Reflections, 1946-1994'' (through July 4), a
retrospective of the founder of the American studio glass movement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 704-337-2000 or http://www
</P>
<P>
   .mintmuseum.com.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy islands
</P>
<P>
   Move over, Mickey. Something huge is invading your universe. The
popular Universal Studios Florida, which opened in 1990, will be
joined in May by a $2.6 billion theme park called Universal Studios
Islands of Adventure. Hyped as the ``world's most technologically
advanced theme park,'' the 110-acre complex consists of five
islands, each with its own theme: Seuss Landing, the Lost
Continent, Toon Lagoon, Jurassic Park and Marvel Super Hero Island.
Steven Spielberg is the creative consultant. The two theme parks
are part of Universal Studios Escape, which includes the
just-opened entertainment complex CityWalk; hotel resorts with more
than 5,000 rooms (the first of which will open this year); and
expanded film and television production facilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 407-363-8000 or http://www.usf.com
</P>
<P>
   High rollers in Mississippi
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone by its neighbor to the west _ namely,
Louisiana _ Biloxi, Miss., is throwing a yearlong party to
celebrate the French landing on its shores 300 years ago. Biloxi's
Tricentennial Celebration blasts off with a birthday celebration
(Feb. 13), including a re-enactment of the landing of Pierre
LeMoyne Sieur d'Iberville in 1699, and traditional Mardi Gras
festivities. The Summer Music Festival runs May through October.
The Tricentennial Jazz Band Festival is May 17-18, the
Tricentennial Fourth of July and Fireworks Celebration is on
Independence Day, of course, and the year ends with the
Tricentennial Commission's New Millennium New Year's Eve
Extravaganza. Information: 1-800-245-6943 or
http://www.biloxi300.com. And there's more big news from Biloxi:
The $600 million Beau Rivage, a development of Las Vegas' Mirage
Resorts, will open in mid-March. The resort will boast 1,780 rooms,
an 85,000-square-foot casino, a 1,550-seat showroom featuring
Cirque du Soleil's ``Alegria,'' a 30-slip marina, health spa and
salon and a Tom Fazio-designed golf course.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 228-386-7111.
</P>
<P>
   Macon's in the pink
</P>
<P>
   You could say life is just a bowl of cherries in Macon (Ga.)
during the Cherry Blossom Festival, but the truth is the Yoshino
cherry trees that grace the Middle Georgia city's streets don't
bear fruit _ edible or otherwise. The city's 230,000 trees do,
however, put on quite a show when they bloom around the third week
of March. The 17th annual festival March 19-28 features more than
500 events including parades, historic tours, sports events, arts
and crafts, a hot-air balloon fest, tours of homes, theater, a
street party, an international food fair, multicultural exhibits,
children's activities and fireworks. A '50s and '60s dance will
feature the Coasters, the Platters and the Drifters, and Bertie
Higgins and the Key Largo Band will perform at a beach party. There
also will be concerts by the Atlanta Rhythm Section, Wet Willie and
K.C. and the Sunshine Band. The 1999 theme is ``The Last Blast of
the Century ... As Good as It Gets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 912-751-7429.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Morocco
</P>
<P>
   Just follow I-20 west to get a taste of Morocco in April during
the Birmingham International Festival, which salutes a different
country each year. The highlight of the monthlong celebration is
the Moroccan Street Festival in Birmingham's Linn Park downtown
April 16-18. The family event will feature Moroccan artists
displaying their crafts, including pottery, woodcarving and
rug-weaving; authentic Moroccan music and dance under entertainment
tents throughout the park; and a simulated archaeological dig for
kids. The International Festival also presents ``Sijilmasa: An
Archaeological Exhibition'' at the Birmingham Civil Rights Museum
(April 4-25) and a daylong International Trade Forum at Energen
Plaza (April 15).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 205-252-7652.
</P>
<P>
   Laissez les bon temps rouler
</P>
<P>
   FrancoFete '99 _ a yearlong bash for the Louisiana Tricentennial
_ promises to be the biggest, longest and most extravagant party
the state has ever thrown. Every parish is celebrating the state's
culture and French heritage that began with the Acadian exile from
Nova Scotia in 1699. Statewide, more than 600 fairs, festivals and
fais-do-do will be set to a Cajun and zydeco beat and fueled by
Cajun cuisine such as boudin, crawfish, gumbo and jambalaya. Major
events include the exhibit ``Degas and New Orleans: A French
Impressionist Painter in America'' at the New Orleans Museum of Art
May 1-Aug. 31; and Congres Mondial Acadien Louisiana, a huge family
reunion in Cajun country in August.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a brochure detailing all FrancoFete events and
attractions, call 1-800-395-1939.
</P>
<P>
   Wild times in Charleston
</P>
<P>
   The 17th annual Southeastern Wildlife Exposition, the largest
wildlife art show in the country, comes to the Holy City Feb.
12-14. Featured artist Nancy Howe of Vermont will exhibit her work
and sign copies of the 1999 poster she designed at Charleston
Place. The Wildlife Show in Marion Square Park features wildlife
and nature paintings, prints, sculpture, carvings, photography,
crafts and collectibles. In addition, there will be lectures, live
animal exhibits, retriever demonstrations, a wild game cooking
contest and dining events including an oyster roast and a pig
picking. New for 1999 is the Sporting Village with hands-on
displays of products and services related to hunting and fishing.
For information or a brochure, call 843-723-1748 or e-mail
sewe(at)sewe.com. Check the Web site at http://www.sewe
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For hotel and tourism information, call the Charleston Area
Convention &AMP; Visitors Center at 1-800-868-8118.
</P>
<P>
   Honest to George
</P>
<P>
   Were the first president's dentures made of wood? Did he cut
down a cherry tree when he was a boy? Find out the answers to these
and other questions as ``George Washington: The Man Behind the
Myths'' opens Feb. 22 at the Virginia Historical Society in
Richmond. The exhibition, which is being mounted in recognition of
the bicentennial of his death, looks at his upbringing and his life
as husband, father and Virginia planter through paintings, personal
artifacts and documents. The largest collection of Washington
mementoes ever assembled, the exhibit will study his major military
and political accomplishments and encourage visitors to reconsider
what they believe to be true about ``the father of our country.''
The exhibit closes Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 804-358-4901 or http://www.vahistorical.org.
</P>
<P>
   Made in Kentucky
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Crafted: The Market _ billed as ``A Cultural Showcase
of Kentucky's Finest'' _ moves to the Kentucky Fair and Exposition
Center in Louisville on Feb. 20-21. The market offers the Bluegrass
State's best contemporary and traditional crafts, musical
recordings, books and food products for sale by more than 200
exhibitors. New this year will be two-dimensional visual art and
wood products. The event, in its 18th year, will also feature book
signings, musical entertainment, ongoing craft and food
demonstrations and children's craft activities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-888-592-7238 or
http://www.state.ky.us/agencies/crafts/crfthome.htm.
</P>
<P>
   A joyful noise in Savannah
</P>
<P>
   The city's historic squares will be alive with the sound of
music during the 10th anniversary Savannah Onstage International
Music Festival Feb. 26-March 7. Winners of prestigious
international classical and jazz competitions are featured during
the Kuhlman Concert Series in historic district churches and
synagogues, and Jazz Weekend (March 6-7) in settings on the
Savannah Riverfront and in the City Market Courtyard. The ENMARK
American Traditions Competition, which offers $27,500 in prize
money, identifies previously unrecognized young singers while
showcasing the musical heritage of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-868-3378 or http://www.savannahonstage.org.
</P>
<P>
   --Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
