<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: MADAME DE POMPADOUR'S PORTRAIT; `OCULUS' MOSAIC;
MUSIC FOR NEW YEAR'S EVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madame de Pompadour will pay her first visit to New
York next month, and in keeping with her station in life (after
all, she was the mistress of King Louis XV of France), she'll
reside in a Fifth Avenue mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course, it won't be the real Jeanne Antoinette Poisson,
Marquise de Pompadour, who was born in 1721 and died in 1764. But
it will be ``Madame de Pompadour,'' Francois-Hubert Drouais'
celebrated full-length portrait of the woman whose influence at
Versailles extended from politics to the arts.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, on loan from the National Gallery in London, will
be at the Frick Collection from Jan. 26 through April 25. The
exhibition of the portrait will be accompanied by a display of
complementary paintings from the Frick's holdings.
</P>
<P>
   To Behold
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The focus will be on the eye when Monday arrives at
the World Financial Center Winter Garden, at West Street on the
Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   Through Jan. 19, on the floor of the Winter Garden, artists led
by Kristin Jones and Andrew Ginzel, winners of the Rome Prize of
the American Academy, will be assembling ``Oculus,'' a
20-by-40-foot 800,000-piece oval glass and stone mosaic.
</P>
<P>
   Working with a Roman mosaicist, Rinaldo Pira, they intend to
create a map of New York City _ intertwined with the continents,
swirling around a central eye _ symbolizing New York as a microcosm
of the world's diverse cultures. In late January the ``Oculus'' is
to be permanently installed in the Park Place IRT subway station,
which is already decorated with hundreds of mosaic eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Musical Menus
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For those who would like the challenge of a marathon
on New Year's Eve _ albeit a rather sedentary marathon _ the 92nd
Street Y offers the complete piano concertos of Ludwig van
Beethoven, performed by the pianist Anton Kuerti and the Jupiter
Symphony, led by Jens Nygaard. The proceedings begin at 5 p.m.,
with Nos. 2, 3 and 4, break for dinner at 7 p.m. and resume at 9
with the ``Prometheus'' overture, Concerto No. 1 and finally, No.
5, the ``Emperor.'' After that comes a champagne toast to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, at Avery Fisher Hall, the three Strausses _ Johann
Sr. and Jr. and Richard _ will be on the New Year's Eve program of
Kurt Masur and the New York Philharmonic. The vocalists will be the
sopranos Deborah Voigt and Heidi Grant Murphy and the mezzo-soprano
Angelika Kirchschlager. With Beverly Sills as host, PBS will
broadcast the event as a ``Live From Lincoln Center'' attraction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
