A0669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN30-COX     12-29 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Readers recall lots of learning in little schools
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I have heard from a number of people who regard a
little school as a potential reinforcer and improver of our
educational system.
</P>
<P>
   They are all people, like me, who attended one- or two-room
schools before consolidation hit the land. It's funny that, while
praising the learning they got in small classes, they seem to
remember most the extracurricular activities that went on at the
little country schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   One man called to tell me that bringing drinking water from the
spring was the delight of boys his age. He did not dwell on the
fact that having a dozen or more children drinking from a single
dipper might not have been the best thing for their health, but he
did get a little pleasure from relating how he and his playmates
kept their teacher on her toes by putting frogs in the water
bucket.
</P>
<P>
   The schoolchildren themselves drank a lot of water just for the
excitement of fishing frogs out of the bucket, but the teacher took
it hard when a frog leaped out of the dipper and landed on the back
of her neck, sliding down under her dress.
</P>
<P>
   After that, she may have transferred to the nearest consolidated
school with automatic water fountains.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, noting that I called a shade tree in the back yard
our cafeteria at Creola, Ala., grammar school, said she grew up in
rural Georgia and remembers fried rabbit and fried squirrel,
brought from home in blue-striped jelly buckets, as the prime
goodie available to children at the school she attended in Heard
County (GA.).
</P>
<P>
   She also spoke fondly of digging a small hole on the school
grounds, lining it with brown paper, pouring cane syrup brought
from home in the hole and sopping it with a biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   Irene O. Mathews of Gay recalled her daughter's more recent
experience with a small school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building burned and they went to school in an old Army
barracks that had been moved in. Martha Simonton, 97 now and in
Molena Nursing Home, taught 60 pupils with no help. They learned
far beyond what a first-grader learns now and she had no discipline
problem. She would leave them work to do and go across the road to
give her mother her medicine. She told me when she got back, they
were all busy doing what she had told them to do. Can you imagine
that happening now? Can't they see that what they need is good
old-fashioned teachers and discipline?''
</P>
<P>
   She decried so-called ``social promotions'' and quoted a teacher
as telling her a few years ago that students were being graduated
when they couldn't read their diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   And also on the educational record of the little school is a
note from a banker who said he learned to spell in grammar school
because the Friday entertainment was a spelling match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to `spell down' all contenders. We actually
prepared for it. I practically memorized the little spelling book
we had and branched out and learned words from The Atlanta
Constitution. I regret to say that my beautiful young secretary,
who attended a bigger, better school, cannot spell anything.''
</P>
<P>
   I have great respect for the old-fashioned spelling match. A few
years ago, I attended a civic club banquet in LaGrange where part
of the entertainment was a spelling bee. You'd be surprised at how
those Rotarians could spell. I seem to recall sitting down on a
tough word like Nebuchadnezzar.
</P>
<P>
   I can blame a country school for not teaching me about that old
king of Babylon, but then the word does not come up often in the
day's work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
