<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ventura's biography runs short on charisma
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Whether you think of him as ``the Body'' or ``the
Mind'' makes no difference. What matters is that in Minnesota,
he'll soon be Jesse ``the Governor'' Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' (8 o'clock E.T.) airs another of
its classic pull-the-punches profiles of a major celebrity, this
one the life story of the hulking pro wrestler, born James Janos in
July 1951, who this year performed a perfect body slam on
Minnesota's political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Surely you've heard the gist of the tale by now. Wrestling's
Jesse ``the Body'' Ventura (who donned pink tights and boas long
before Dennis Rodman) runs for governor, transforms his image into
Jesse ``the Mind'' Ventura and flat out wins the Guv's Mansion,
besting even Hubert Humphrey's son.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story as perfect as any of pro wrestling's pay-per-view
theatrics. And one that's cool because it's real. We'd say, ``Only
in America,'' but wasn't it Italy that elected a former porn star
to Parliament?
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's bio is produced by ABC News Productions for A&AMP;E. And,
frankly, we expected more.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Arnold Schwarzenegger talking about Ventura's pivotal
death scene in 1987's cinematic testosterone play ``Predator''?
Where's WCW's Bobby ``the Brain'' Heenan talking about Ventura's
verbal prowess as a wrestling commentator?
</P>
<P>
   Too often we get the same old photos _ Ventura the Navy SEAL
with shaved head, Ventura the California Surfin' Wrestler in full
pose, Ventura the high school senior voted best physique _ shown
over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   It's really when Ventura, a one-time biker, bar bouncer and
radio host, starts venturing into politics that this bio starts to
kick butt.
</P>
<P>
   There he is as Brooklyn Park's mayor conducting council meetings
in a T-shirt. There he is at the start of Minnesota's gubernatorial
debate, winking at the camera when his name is announced. There he
is meeting with the public, shaking hands and talking issues at a
booth at the Minnesota State Fair. And there he is, nearly nude,
posing like Rodin's ``The Thinker'' in a political ad proclaiming
him ``The Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It is said he likely won the election by meeting the public face
to face and spouting a platform of less government intrusion into
everyday lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so gratifying about this is proving all the so-called
experts wrong,'' Ventura says on his election night.
</P>
<P>
   We prefer the comment about him from retired Navy SEAL Capt.
Larry Bailey: ``Put on the right path, he would excel. Allow him to
go too far the other way, he'd be a mafia don.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
