<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS NEED TO SHAKE FIRST-PERIOD BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Their style has been called stingy at times, even
stingier at others. Whatever terminology one wants to use to label
the way the Bruins play, perhaps the best description of the
tactics employed by coach Pat Burns is ``defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins have been successful, it has been because they
hold their opponents off the scoreboard for long stretches,
especially early in the game, and take advantage of errors when
they start to press. Well, at least that was the plan.
</P>
<P>
   It has gone wickedly awry in the last two games. The Bruins have
staked their foes to two and three goals, respectively, in the
first period and the results have been predictable: losses on both
fronts, in New York Saturday night to the Islanders (4-2) and to
the Capitals Monday night (5-1). The loss to Washington was the
team's third straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are halfway through a four-game road trip, and so far
their fortunes have been dismal. With Nashville on tap Wednesday
night and Dallas on deck Thursday, the journey could get even worse
if something doesn't change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our starts,'' lamented goalie Byron Dafoe, who was
peppered with 18 shots in the first period and 37 overall by
Washington. ``Our first periods have just been not strong at all.
It's been our worst period of hockey every game for the past seven
or eight games. I don't think we've held a team off the board in
the first period the last seven or eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in the year, we'd go the first half of the game
without allowing a goal. That's partly my fault. I have got to
start coming up with bigger saves and as a team we have to bear
down more.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Dafoe hasn't been playing badly. The same can't
be said for many of the forwards, who have been running around in
their own zone, looking as if they weren't sure what to do. The
defensemen have been only marginally better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit here and name a bunch of names,'' said
Burns, though when asked specifically about Sergei Samsonov, the
coach conceded that the sophomore left wing has struggled mightily
the last two times out. ``He's not alone. There is a whole cast and
crew of guys who didn't show up, old and young. Washington
outhustled us, that's all. It's as simple as that. They were first
on the puck, we were second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have been putting themselves behind the 8-ball right
off the bat. Against the Islanders, they were in a deficit just
6:57 into the game. It was worse Monday night when the Capitals
scored at the 24-second mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting the breaks right now,'' said Dafoe. ``We've
talked about getting good starts, and 24 seconds in, the thing goes
off my head and my back and in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're struggling when we're behind, 1-0, early.
It's something we have to focus on. You can't make excuses and say
we're not having good luck but we definitely aren't getting the
breaks we were earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had 18 shots and they definitely came to play. They've
been struggling and there's no reason why we would get outshot,
18-8, in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all got to take a serious look at ourselves and try to
figure out what's going on here. The games don't get any easier.
We've got to dig deep and try to salvage what we've got left of it.
Nashville is playing great and then we have back to back with
Dallas. If we play like we did (against Washington), we're going to
get absolutely spanked.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defenseman Dave Ellett said it's too tall an order to
expect a club, especially the Bruins, to rally from deficits time
and time again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, you can't win on the road by giving up two or
three goals in the first period,'' Ellett said. ``We're not a
come-from-behind team. We have to be ready from the start of the
game. We can't afford to give teams easy goals or fall behind
early. For this team to be successful, we have to be within one
goal or ahead or tied after the first. We don't make many mistakes
and we don't give up many chances but these last two games have
been totally out of our character.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was bad news on the injury front Tuesday. Chris Taylor
bruised his shoulder in practice and is questionable for Wednesday,
as is Ken Belanger, who has a sore neck. The Bruins called up
forwards Landon Wilson and Cameron Mann from Providence for the
rest of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   (Allen Lessels of the Globe Staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
