<HEADER>
A0684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-PRIVATEPRISON-LAPS     12-29 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-PRIVATEPRISON-LAPSES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspections detail 'filthy' conditions, security problems in
Georgia prison
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's first privately-run prison _ open a little
more than two months _ had lax security and ``filthy'' conditions
in some areas during two recent state inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The warden and a executive from Cornell Corrections Inc., which
opened the medium-security private prison in Folkston, Ga. in
mid-October, said they had addresses the criticisms in reports of
two inspection visits and attributed the problems to kinks in the
system of any new prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just takes time,'' said Gary Henman, Cornell vice president
for secure institutions. ``We received inmates very quickly, at our
request. We brought them in twice as fast as we originally
scheduled. It was like the horse catching up with the cart.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 500 prisoners in the D. Ray James State Prison
in Charlton County, Henman said Tuesday. The maximum number of
inmates the Legislature has committed to sending to the prison, 750
men, will be reached in mid 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Two reports _ one written after an inspection Nov. 18-19 and
another after a Dec. 9 visit _ said there were security lapses,
sloppy record-keeping and poor tracking of inmates. On some days,
officers assigned to cell blocks did not know how many inmates were
to be in the areas they were supervising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've received a commitment to make sure they are going to
start running thinks like a state prison,'' said Jennifer
Sargenson, spokeswoman for the Department of Corrections, which has
a contract with Cornell Corrections Inc. to send inmates to the D.
Ray James State Prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to be embarrassed, and they don't want to
embarrass us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Warden Lowell Hudson said he had been transferred to open a
Cornell prison in California, and insisted his move was routine,
having nothing to do with the critical report. ``I'm going to do
bigger and better things for Cornell,'' Hudson said. ``Cornell is
expanding like a son of a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of three private prisons to open in Georgia this year,
the Cornell facility was three months late taking prisoners because
of construction delays. Each day without an inmate is a day of
profits lost for the Houston-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, as well as the federal prison system and several
states, have turned to corporate America to incarcerate it's
criminals because they think it will save money. DOC claims
privately run prisons save taxpayers money. Cornell is billing
Georgia taxpayers $45.13 per inmate per day, about $13 a day less
than the cost at state-run prisons.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say concern for profit carries more weight that
concern for security, and the results can be dangerous, such as in
Ohio where five dangerous men from Washington, D.C., escaped from a
CCA prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``All decisions made inside these prisons is based on what
shareholders want,'' said Brian Dawe, director of operations for
Corrections USA, a non-profit lobby for prison guards. ``In private
prisons, the only pros are the cons. You have inexperience staff,
undertrained and undermanned. You have people sworn to protect the
bottom line instead of public safety. . . ``It's corporate welfare.
. . and no one's been minding the roost.''
</P>
<P>
   Folkston Mayor Dixie McGurn said she is not worried, even though
she was unaware of the critical report.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my knowledge, we have had no problems with the prison,''
McGurn said. ``I'm sitting here a little dumbfounded. I've not
heard any of this. But I feel like if the Department of Corrections
has come down here and their monitors have seen these problems, it
will be taken care of. If it's a major problem, I feel like we have
a right to know. But it's not like they have inmates crawling over
the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Corp. of America of Nashville also has contracts to
operate medium-security prisons in Wheeler and Coffee counties, and
those facilities have been taking about 50 inmates weekly since
Dec. 1. CCA charges $48.10 per inmate per day, and there are about
330 inmates combined in the two CCA Georgia prisons.
</P>
<P>
   The state has agreed to lease 750 beds at the two CCA prisons
and the CCI operation in Folkston, but the companies will expand
their institutions to eventually hold about 1,600 each, with the
hope that Georgia will also want to fill those cells.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, CCA, the nation's largest private prison company, has
announced plans to build a $45 million prison for more than 1,000
inmates in Telfair County even though it has no formal agreement
with Georgia to lease those spaces to the state. CCA officials and
House Appropriations Committee Chairman Terry Coleman (D-Eastman),
who represents the area, said there is an understanding with the
state, while DOC Commissioner Wayne Garner insists there have been
no negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
