<HEADER>
A0686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-COLUMN-COX     12-29 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conversion to euro fostering anxiety
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm OK, euro OK,'' reads the motto on a T-shirt distributed by
Netherlands-based banking giant ABN Amro. But a lot of people are
keeping their fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   The first swarm of euro conversions, a near-relation to the
millennium bug, will arrive Jan. 4. Many analysts believe the euro
changeover will provide an unpalatable foretaste of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   The Gartner Group, a Stamford, Conn.-based consultancy,
estimates the euro conversion will cost $150 billion to $400
billion in the European Union alone, an estimate that does not
include PCs and packaged software.
</P>
<P>
   Other estimates suggest the rest of world will spend tens of
billions on the euro.
</P>
<P>
   And not least, the changeover to the euro has diverted lots of
time and money from Y2K efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co., for example, said it will have to
convert all its information technology systems, recalculate
currency risks, modify its processes for preparing taxes, payroll
and customer records, among other things. Coke does business in all
of the countries involved in the conversion and has been preparing
for it for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're well prepared to handle the issues surrounding the
introduction of the euro,'' said spokesman Bill Hensel. ``It's
going to impact more on our bottlers and even more on our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   At the retail level, he said, stores will have to list two
prices for all products during the phase-in period, as well as
maintaining two cash drawers for both types of currency.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange rates in relation to the euro will be set at the
European Union headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, on Thursday.
There are 11 participating countries: the Netherlands, Belgium,
Luxembourg, France, Spain, Portugal, Italy, Germany, Finland,
Ireland and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain, Denmark, Sweden and Greece are members of the
European Union but not members of the European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
   After the rates are set, financial institutions will have to
scramble to adjust their software to convert a spectrum of
financial products into euros before businesses open four days
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Year 2000 problem, you simply change a date. But with
the euro, you're also dealing with a perception issue. It's akin to
people who think in inches and feet having to think in terms of
centimeters and meters,'' said Adelbert Spaan, vice president and
euro marketing manager for ABN Amro, North America in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of perceptual problems, ``you may have to add new
fields that display the euro alongside the legacy currency. An
example: You used to show deutsche marks in a given monetary field.
Now you want to show both deutsche marks and euros to familiarize
users with the relationship between the old currency and the new,''
said Jonathan Rende, product marketing manager for Mercury
Interactive in Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   For this and other reasons, the euro conversion has been
complicated and expensive. Spaan said his company, which has $400
billion in assets and offices in 72 countries, will spend more than
$350 million on the euro and far less, $175 million, on Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
