<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-TECH-STOCKS-COX     12-29 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-TECH-STOCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta-based tech companies a mixed bag for investors in '98
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Along with their national counterparts, some local
tech companies brought their investors serious money during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Those that performed well, like MindSpring Enterprises and ISS
Group, did so by aggressively increasing market share and by
operating in a hot industry, the Internet, which saw dramatically
increasing numbers of users this year.
</P>
<P>
   But sheer growth did not guarantee success, as Harbinger
discovered. The stock of the electronic commerce software firm
suffered as the company struggled to fold the companies it acquired
into its corporate mix.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MindSpring Enterprises, the southeast's largest
Internet access provider, are up 515 percent over last Dec. 30
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick W. Moran, an analyst with ING Barings, said 1998 was
the year Atlanta-based MindSpring, ``burst on the scene by
developing one of the leading ISPs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the year when not only did they get recognition
nationally by the consumer, but also by the institutional
investment community, which rewarded their shares handsomely,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said two things fueled much of MindSpring's growth: a 10
percent price hike in April by America Online, America's largest
ISP with 17 million subscribers, and MindSpring's purchase, from
AOL in October, of 180,000 subscribers. Overall, MindSpring's
subscriber base grew 150 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said 1999 will continue the battle between MindSpring,
with 700,000 subscribers, and EarthLink Network, with 1 million, to
be the nation's second largest ISP. He expects MindSpring to be
trading at $111 in 12 months. It closed Tuesday at $68.
</P>
<P>
   ISS Group, a network security software firm, went public in
March. Its shares have climbed 153 percent since.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of ISS Group are up 38 percent in the last five days,
closing Tuesday at $56.25. Barry Glasgow, an analyst with LaSalle
Street Securities, said 1999 will be a big year for ISS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 1999 is the year for security stocks,'' he said. ``Y2K
has been holding people back from making buying decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   But local tech-stock news was not all good. Premiere
Technologies was down 75 percent. The company sells communications
service devices, one of which ties Internet e-mail to voice mail
and conference calling.
</P>
<P>
   And shares of CheckFree are up 122 percent, to $21.93 3/4, since
Sept. 30, but are down 26 percent for the year. CheckFree is one of
a handful of companies hoping to make the Web the place where you
get and pay your bills.
</P>
<P>
   Harbinger, which bought 12 companies in 30 months, is down 62
percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael G. Chung, an analyst with Williams Capital Group, said
Harbinger's attempt to integrate companies it acquired led to its
sluggish 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A 41 percent drop in share price in one day, Oct. 1, led to
drastic changes. Co-founder C. Tycho Howle was brought back, 10
percent of the workforce was trimmed and half the product line was
cut. The stock, which had sunk to $4.06 Oct. 2, has since
rebounded, closing Tuesday at $8.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
