<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENTIFIC-ATLANTA-CO     12-29 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENTIFIC-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gambling on future of TV
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A lanky 58, James McDonald looks like a long distance
runner and, at least in the way he's run Scientific-Atlanta, he is.
</P>
<P>
   As president and chief executive, McDonald has pushed this
Atlanta-based maker of television equipment to chase the promise of
digital interactive TV that glimmers on a distant horizon.
</P>
<P>
   He saw this technology, although considered a risky bet by some
of his counterparts, as the company's great chance to leap ahead of
its main competitor, General Instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate to see the potential of digital technology
five years ago,'' says McDonald. ``Now everyone sees it. Given what
we've invested and built, Scientific-Atlanta has a significant
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   That lead, however, is currently in a race no one else is yet
running.
</P>
<P>
   A problem for Scientific-Atlanta in the short term is that it
accelerated hard toward such items as digital set-top boxes, such
as in its Explorer 2000 digital cable networks. They enable cable
operators to offer customers such things as digital television,
more channels, interactive on-screen TV guides and high-speed
access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta somewhat overestimated the immediate demand
for the devices when the Telecommunications Act passed in 1996. So
far, many customers are taking their time making decisions on the
timing for going all-digital. While Scientific-Atlanta probably
guessed right about the long-term need for its digital technology,
potential customers have hesitated to move that way.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the company is moving ahead smartly in the
development of digital cable network ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Explorer 2000 is shipping and already has 15 big customers,
including Atlanta-based Cox Communications. Scientific-Atlanta made
97,000 Explorer 2000 set-top boxes in the second quarter, shipping
57,000 of those.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reg Griffin, the Atlanta spokesman for MediaOne, said
his company is still testing digital boxes in Detroit and elsewhere
and has not established a firm timetable for introducing them to
the Atlanta market.
</P>
<P>
   Will Explorer 2000 pick up momentum fast enough to justify the
company's huge investment over the past six years in digital
technology? Some say it's too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``McDonald is a great visionary, but has he executed well?''
asks George Hunt, a media analyst who covers the company for
Interstate/Johnson Lane. ``That's still up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   If McDonald is worried about his strategy, he doesn't show it.
Curly-haired and slightly balding, McDonald smiles easily. He
explains the reasons behind his strategy with confidence and vigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't fight technology,'' explains McDonald. ``We knew it
was only a matter of time before the cost of digital services would
come down to the point where they become affordable to a mass
market.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald has not come by his self-assuredness easily. He is no
stranger to adversity. The native Kentuckian spent 21 years at IBM,
many of them as a troubleshooter. Later, he was president of
software maker Prime Computer as it struggled to restructure itself
in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a 35-year career in technology and have worked
through most of the kinds of jobs there are in the industry,'' says
McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   These experiences have taught McDonald that you must gamble big
to win in hi-tech businesses. He has done that on digital
television with Scientific-Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, his major competitor, General Instrument, has taken
an opposite approach. It chose to build an inexpensive set-top box
that serves cable TV's current analog systems. The strategy has
paid off big, with General Instrument selling more than two million
of those boxes. ``They've sold the heck out of them,'' says Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, says McDonald, but he hints that General Instrument
has been caught sleeping by not investing in a true digital two-way
technology like Scientific-Atlanta. He maintains that, by investing
in digital technology, his company now has a significant lead in
this important new market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're there too early or too late with a new technology,
you lose,'' says McDonald. ``Most people see things coming but
don't get the timing right.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the timing right wasn't easy for Scientific-Atlanta.
Indeed, McDonald led his company on a six-year journey through the
wilderness to reach this day. That journey began in 1992, when
Scientific-Atlanta signed up to produce the digital network that
powered Time Warner Cable's experimental two-way system in Orlando,
Fla. That system was ridiculed by critics as too expensive and
impractical. ``We got beat up bad,'' says McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   That drubbing prompted most other cable operators to kill
interactive tests of their own. McDonald, though, didn't give up
and searched for another partner in testing his digital technology.
That led to a series of trials with the cable industry's
arch-rival, the telephone companies: BellSouth, US West, PacTel and
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually the telephone companies too lost faith in two-way
digital TV technology, at least in the near term. ``They got burnt
and eventually gave up on it,'' says McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as the telephone companies cooled on digital
technology, cable rediscovered it. McDonald re-enlisted
Scientific-Atlanta as a major industry player.
</P>
<P>
   For Scientific-Atlanta, investing in digital technology has been
expensive in terms of both research and forgone earnings pumped
back into the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We carried our digital technology efforts five years without
revenue,'' says McDonald. ``Our earnings and stock would be higher
if we had not invested in digital technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta has not established a consistent profit
picture over the last decade, experienceing a loss year in 1996.
But the company has seen profits climb over the last two fiscal
years, ending in June, showing a profit of $80.8 million on
revenues of $1.2 billion in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company's stock has traded between $11.75 and
$27.93 a share, with the price hovering recently around $22.
</P>
<P>
   While he considers the company's stock undervalued, McDonald has
no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company like ours has to invest in research and
development,'' he says. ``Value for us is driven by catching a ride
on the next big wave in technology, offering the right product at
the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
