<HEADER>
A0720 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PEACH-UGA-COX     12-29 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PEACH-UGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA's Stinchcomb says goodbye to one great career, hello to
another
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Matt Stinchcomb's football career at the University of
Georgia will end sometime Thursday night, after the No. 19 Bulldogs
battle No. 12 Virginia in the Peach Bowl. When Stinchcomb walks off
the turf of the Georgia Dome, he'll leave with mixed emotions about
his four years in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some goals that weren't obtained,'' Stinchcomb
said. ``There were a lot of things that we could have done that we
didn't. I don't know if I'd call them regrets; probably
disappointments more than anything else. But there have been a lot
of surprises, as well. It's been a two-way street.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the goals that weren't fulfilled were an SEC title and
playing with his younger brother, Georgia freshman Jon Stinchcomb,
who redshirted this season after injuring his knee as a senior at
Parkview High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to play with him,'' Stinchcomb said.
``But I think redshirting him was the best decision. I hope he's
better than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a lofty goal for the younger Stinchcomb. Matt
Stinchcomb's four-year career went basically as scripted. He left
Atlanta-area Parkview High in 1995 on a path bound for NFL stardom.
Now, he leaves Georgia as a consensus All-American, the top
offensive lineman in the SEC and a probable first-round pick in
April's NFL Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb, a 6-foot-6, 291-pound native of Lilburn, Ga., also
wants to leave Athens on a winning note.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to finish the season strong,'' he said. ``We
failed to do that in the regular season, so this bowl game presents
us another opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb, who graduated with a 3.96 grade-point average,
earned a finance degree from Georgia earlier this month, taking
only 3 1/2 years to finish his studies. Stinchcomb was a two-time
Academic All-American, and this year was named one of the NCAA's
top eight student-athletes in all sports. He was awarded an $18,000
post-graduate scholarship by the National Football Foundation,
which he might use for law school.
</P>
<P>
   Stinchcomb will spend the next three months in Atlanta working
with personal trainers Chip Smith and Robby Stewart, who helped
former Bulldogs players Adam Meadows, Whit Marshall and Brandon
Tolbert improve their draft status.
</P>
<P>
   Before the NFL combine, Stinchcomb wants to improve his
upper-body strength _ he bench-presses 365 pounds _ and lower his
time in the 40-yard dash. Stinchcomb, perhaps the nation's most
fundamentally sound tackle, also is very durable; he missed the
first game of his career this season against Ole Miss with a
separated left shoulder. He is expected to be among the first
offensive tackles selected, along with UCLA's Kris Farris, a junior
who has not declared for the draft yet; Wisconsin's Aaron Gibson;
and Florida's Zach Piller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous player,'' said Georgia right tackle Chris
Terry, also expected to be an NFL draft choice. ``He's helped me
out a lot. At first, I was a little nervous about moving positions
(from defensive end to offensive tackle). I watched his technique
and noticed his work ethic. His hard work paid off for a lot of
players, especially me.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Cavaliers, Stinchcomb faces another of the nation's
top pass-rushers in Virginia defensive end Patrick Kerney.
Stinchcomb faced Tennessee's Shaun Ellis, Florida's Jevon Kearse
and Georgia Tech's Jesse Tarplin earlier this season, yet the left
tackle graded 90 percent or better in blocking in all 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stinchcomb's had a great career,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan
said. ``Virginia's going to be a big challenge for him. I think our
ability to negate Kerney is going to be a key aspect of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
