<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, Dec. 30. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GANGPOWER (Phoenix) - The failed hit against Arizona's
prison-system boss is the latest display of prison gang power
behind bars and outside. With GANGSIDE, a list of crimes directed
by prison gangs in Arizona and nationally; and GANGBIO, who they
are, what they do. By REPUBLIC STAFF. Stories will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BADAIR-PHOENIX (Phoenix) - The Phoenix area's air quality dipped to
its worst level in two years as officials issued a warning they
hope will drive more people to buses and carpools. By MARY JO
PITZL. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
INTERNET-RAPE (GILBERT, Ariz.) - A troubled 13-year-old girl from
Gilbert meets a ``19 year old'' man on the Internet who promises to
take her to a place far, far away from her unhappy life. He did, to
Tennessee, where he and his girlfriend raped the girl and held her
captive for three days. By JIM WALSH. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SABBATH-CONCERT (Phoenix) - Chris Balogh stood in the field of at
Bank One Ballpark, watching a team of erect a giant video screen in
front of the electronic scoreboard. ``It's like a big family back
here,'' said Balogh, a personal assistant to Ozzy Osbourne. ``And
everyone is very excited about the first show.'' Excitement seems
to be the key word at the ballpark these days. The buzz inside BOB
focuses on the Black Sabbath New Year's Eve show. There are a lot
of firsts associated with the concert. By RANDY CORDOVA. Story will
move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FIESTA-ECON (Phoenix) - The Fiesta Bowl contributes close to $100
million to the Arizona economy, according to an Arizona State
University economic impact study, but a professor of sports
economics questions that figure and suggests that the event is a
relatively insignificant blip on the Phoenix area's huge economy.
By PETER CORBETT. Story will move in the ``F'' and ``S''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - They are burying him in a New York cemetery as I
write this. I cannot be there, do not belong. I never met the man
in person, only through his words. All the same, I stole from him,
learned from him, owe him. I figure making good on my debt requires
at least a few hundred words.
</P>
<P>
   They will be sad words, let me say up front. Mike McAlary dying
colors newspapers a deeper shade of gray. It is always that way
when brilliance quits the game. By DAVID LEIBOWITZ. Story will move
in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Phoenix) - As 1998 winds to a close (finally!),
many in the online world are sounding an alarm. Their concern:
privacy. The Web continues to grow, reaching into the lives of
millions of people, becoming a part of everyday life and emerging
as a trusted medium of communication _ everything from simple
e-mail to delicate financial transactions. On one hand, that's
good. The more people online, the more useful the Web becomes. On
the other hand, the booming online economy has sparked a mad dash
for cash _ money to be earned from anybody and everybody who goes
online. By DAVID HOYE. Story moved in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BLIND-MICROSOFT (Phoenix) - Loren Mikola is asking friends with
good fashion sense to put little tags to his clothes so he won't
look goofy on on his first day of work at Microsoft. He's learning
how to cook because, at the age of 24, he's moving out of his
parent's house for the first time. He's also has to learn to get
around on the bus because its probably best he doesn't drive.
Mikola is blind, but has managed to use Braille books and quick
wits to graduate with honors from Arizona State University and land
a $44,000 at the nation's largest computer firm. With photo. By
REBECCA ROLWING. Story moved in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
ANNE STEPHENSON. Story moved in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KIDSBOOKS (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new books for children. By
BEVERLY MEDLYN. Story moved in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
