<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATOR-NDAME-COX     12-29 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATOR-NDAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Denson quietly makes his mark in Notre Dame record books
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Except when he's running into the line or
filling out an informational questionnaire, Autry Denson is as
modest a college football hero as they come.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a side of Denson few see, revealed within a feature
item called the Denson File in the 448-page, seems-like-50-pound
Notre Dame football brochure.
</P>
<P>
   The question: If I were making a football ``Dream Team'' the
first three players I would pick would be . . . .
</P>
<P>
   His answer: Autry Denson, Barry Sanders and Walter Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least, he didn't have to pick the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had anyone give me any grief about that,'' Denson
said with a laugh after a practice for Thursday's Gator Bowl game
against Georgia Tech. ``I didn't think anybody read those things.''
Denson quietly has been making a name for himself the past three
years at Notre Dame. He comes into the game against Tech as the
Fighting Irish's all-time leading rusher with 4,318 yards after a
third 1,000-yard season in a row.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the storied football program that has produced such
familiar names as Allen Pinkett, Vegas Ferguson and the Gipper,
George Gipp.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was a prediction few paid attention to four years
ago. When former Notre Dame coach Lou Holtz switched Denson from
cornerback to tailback after the first game of his freshman season,
Denson told reporters he wanted to become the greatest tailback in
school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could do it,'' he said. ``The only one I had to prove
anything to was myself.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the top 10 running backs on The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's Super Southern 100 in his senior year of
high school in Lauderhill, Fla., Denson has had to overcome the
cliche stigma about size relating to durability. He is 5-10, 200
pounds and his speed in the 40-yard dash ranges from 4.4 to 4.6
seconds, depending on who's holding the stopwatch.
</P>
<P>
   He says about his NFL future: ''I make no predictions, I just
hope somebody gives me the opportunity. I'd like to wait awhile
before using my degree in management information systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Davie has no reservations about Denson's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an expert on (the NFL),'' Davie said, ``but it's just
hard for me to imagine that a guy who has accomplished as much as
he has at Notre Dame would not be successful at the next level.
When you know him personally, and you're around his work ethic and
see how much pride he has, it's hard to imagine he wouldn't be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Denson's 1,176 yards in 1998 rank seven in Irish history. And
when he surpassed Pinkett for the all-time Notre Dame record with
two regular season games to play, it was Pinkett, now an investent
broker in Houston, on the telephone to offer congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just told me that it couldn't have happened to a better
person,'' Denson said. ``He just encouraged me to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But first there's the little business of dealing with Georgia
Tech on New Year's Day. He remembers the Yellow Jackets well. In
the 1997 season-opener, Denson was held to his second-lowest
rushing total that year, 71 yards, but he scored twice, including
the game-winner late in the fourth quarter, and the Irish prevailed
17-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that they played very hard, very aggressive,''
Denson said. ``Those linebackers they had last year were rough. I
think both of them are in the NFL now, too. They're rough. They
have some more good ones this year. They have a pretty good
corps.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets might be keying on Denson this time around. With
quarterback Jarious Jackson coming off a knee injury, the Irish
could choose to limit his involvement in the option offense and
turn to Denson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel any added pressure,'' Denson said. ``I just feel
I have to go out and play my game and the offensive unit has to go
out and play as a team. I don't feel there's any more burden put on
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Denson doesn't want to let his cheering section down. About
40 family members will be coming up from South Florida for the
game. ``Good thing I don't have to provide all the tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
