<HEADLINE>
AUTO INSURANCE RATES GOING UP IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the first time in five years, the average
Massachusetts driver will be paying more for car insurance next
year, although the new rate provides just a small fraction of the
15.5 percent hike sought by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Linda L. Ruthardt Tuesday set a 1999 rate that
represents a 0.7 percent hike for policy holders or about an extra
$20 million in premium payments statewide.
</P>
<P>
   While consumer advocates say she should have lowered the rate
for next year, Ruthardt defended her decision, saying it would cost
a typical driver only ``about a dime a week.'' For the motorist
paying an average $835 premium, the increase would be $5.86.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt also noted that for those car owners who buy just the
mandatory coverage, the rate represents a 3.1 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ruthardt said she based the new rate on the evidence
the industry presented at hours of hearings, the state's auto
insurers denounced her decision and predicted large underwriting
losses for the firms from their auto policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very disturbing,'' said Dan Johnston, the president of
the Automobile Insurers Bureau of Massachusetts. ``It clearly does
not provide even enough money in the system to keep the system
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said Ruthardt's decision will force insurers to pay out
about 6 percent more than they collect in auto premiums. He also
warned that it will likely spark an industry retreat from the
discount programs that have become available to Massachusetts
drivers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She expects the companies to operate in a way that for every
$100 we collect we have to pay out $106,'' Johnston said. ``That's
an underwriting loss of six percent. I have never seen a number
like that anywhere in the country in a ratemaking process.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said he would not make any further comment until he can
review the full text of the decision when it is released later this
week. In the past the industry has appealed rate decisions to the
state supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some consumer advocates claimed the industry must find
one aspect of the decision to its liking: it breaks four straight
years of rate reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privately (the industry has) to be pleased that a string of
decreases has been broken,'' said Stephen J. D'Amato, a consumer
insurance activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a consumer standpoint, it's hard to view this result as
anything but a loss for the consumers,'' said D'Amato, the former
head of the State Rating Bureau, which had recommended a 10 percent
decrease. The agency operates as a consumer advocate within the
insurance commission and makes recommendations to the commissioner
on filings by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a rare move by an insurance commissioner, Ruthardt
also leveled $9 million worth of sanctions against the industry,
money that has been factored into the rate.
</P>
<P>
   One fine, amounting to $3 million, was levied for the industry's
failure to provide information about the salaries that the
companies pay their executives. She said the industry had agreed
that the information it had turned over was inadequate. Attorney
General Scott Harshbarger, who had argued for a 12 percent rate
reduction, had called for a $100 million sanction on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Another, $6 million sanction was invoked because the industry
was unable to provide evidence that it had adhered to cost
containment programs that the commissioner had demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a message being sent: you have have to comply with
discovery orders, and you have to comply with regulations that
require evidence of cost containment programs,'' Ruthardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt rejected the insurers' request that she begin to
dismantle the system by which suburban drivers subsidize the rates
for urban drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by his office, Harshbarger said only
that he was ``disappointed'' in Ruthardt's decision not to cut the
rate, but applauded her for adopting a ``large number of my
recommendations on individual aspects of the rate case.''
</P>
<P>
   The departing attorney general, who had asked Ruthardt to recuse
herself from the case for having met with Johnston privately early
this year, said he would not make a decision whether to appeal the
decision until reading the commissioner's entire text.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
