<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE TO GET LATEST WORD ON FINGER WEDNESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Jacksonville Jaguars have one less day
to prepare for Sunday's wild-card playoff game against the
Patriots, because they played Monday night, posting a 21-3 win over
the once-proud Pittsburgh Steelers in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good part for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The bad part is that Jacksonville will be playing at home,
quarterback Mark Brunell is ready to go (though not at 100 percent,
after an ankle injury), and the Jaguars will have the momentum of a
win.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Patriots are coming off a crushing loss to the
Jets and don't know definitively who their starting quarterback
will be, though the distinct possibility is that it won't be Drew
Bledsoe, who is scheduled to get a medical evaluation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If it is thumbs-down on Bledsoe, who is still treating a
fractured finger, the Patriots will go into the playoffs with
backup Scott Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can't throw, he can't throw,'' said defensive end Willie
McGinest. ``Nothing is going to make him use his fingers better.
He'll do everything he can, but if he can't, then we'll have to get
behind people who are in there like Scott Zolak. He's a veteran guy
who's been around here for a long time. This would be a great thing
for Scott to be able to play and lead us to a win. The guys here
have faith in Scott. You can't blame him for Sunday; everybody had
a hand in that.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility being considered is to remove the pin from
Bledsoe's finger and have him try to play with a splint, as he did
before.
</P>
<P>
   The healing process is only about halfway complete, and doctors
must determine whether Bledsoe could do long-term damage if he
plays and is reinjured.
</P>
<P>
   There is pressure on Bledsoe, as the franchise player, to give
it a go, and from a team point of view, the Patriots can't think
about anything beyond the Jacksonville game _ not even a possible
matchup in Denver against the Broncos in the next round.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Zolak wasn't horrible news two weeks ago, when he led
New England to a victory over the 49ers. But it wasn't the best of
scenarios last weekend in New Jersey, when the Patriots were
outplayed in every aspect of the game in a 31-10 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' locker room is certainly mixed on whether Bledsoe
should play. Some feel he has to play if it's physically possible,
while others don't want him in there if he's not 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can't be effective with the finger as is, then there's
no point,'' said safety Lawyer Milloy. ``Drew has to know that if
he plays, he'll be able to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, players and fans remember the 26-20 win in
Jacksonville last season as the team's finest moment. The Patriots
played without Curtis Martin and Terry Glenn, and Bledsoe seized
the moment. In what many considered his best game of the season, he
completed 26 of 35 for 234 yards, with two touchdowns and no
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a game in which Bledsoe showed some spunk and
leadership, jawing with receiver Vincent Brisby for not getting
himself open while Bledsoe was running for his life. Bledsoe took
the argument to the sidelines, and Brisby responded with four
receptions for 58 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Patriots are coming off a disastrous loss and may
not have Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   How do they overcome that?
</P>
<P>
   ``The same way we overcame the St. Louis loss,'' said receiver
Shawn Jefferson. ``We just find a way. We've already forgotten
about New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you play for,'' said Milloy. ``We don't dwell on
losing games. We take the next challenge on. If we played badly, we
improve the next week. That has to be our focus.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Jets game, McGinest said, ``What game?''
</P>
<P>
   With Brunell not as mobile as he can be, it may be a game that
comes down to how well McGinest can get after him. Coming off a leg
injury, McGinest slowly made his way back into the lineup against
the Jets and expects to go all out in this one. He'll likely have
to battle the Jaguars' Tony Boselli, widely considered the best
offensive lineman in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how (Brunell's) ankle is,'' said McGinest.
``Hank (Henry Thomas) had a similar injury, and when he came back,
he wasn't moving around as well. So he may not be trying to run
around as much. They might try and design plays to sit in the
pocket and throw the ball and get away from the boots or the naked
(bootlegs) that he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know. We have to prepare for the Brunell that we
know, who runs the draw, the nakeds, and who is going to be
scrambling around.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell can be a pocket passer, and he has excellent wideouts in
Jimmy Smith and Keenan McCardell to throw to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reads defenses so well,'' said McGinest. ``We looked at old
games we've had against them in the past because we haven't seen
them this year. They have the same team they've always had except
that they've got (running back) Fred Taylor, who did a great job
for them. We have to figure out what Taylor does good or bad and
try to find a way to contain him. They have their receivers playing
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are 3-0 against Jacksonville the last three years,
with the 1996 AFC Championship game the most decisive win (20-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps that we've played them in the past and that we've
played Brunell before,'' said defensive end Chris Sullivan, who is
scheduled to return to the lineup after missing a game with a sore
knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
