<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, Dec. 30. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ A top leader of the
Khmer Rouge mutters an apology, saying he is ``sorry, very sorry''
for the suffering he caused the Cambodian people. But the leader,
Khieu Samphan, repeatedly urges Cambodians and foreigners to ``let
bygones be bygones'' regarding the deaths of more than a million
people between 1975 and 1979, when the Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia
and he was head of state. By Seth Mydans. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Since President Clinton was impeached by
the House 10 days ago, the airwaves have filled with senatorial
speculation about a speedy trial and perhaps even a pre-emptive
censure deal. But below the level of generality, the speculators do
not agree on just how a trial should be conducted, or what a
workable censure deal would be. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Strasbourg, France) _ The launch of a new currency, the
euro, on Friday represents the single most important change on the
Continent since the end of the Cold War. In getting to this point,
11 European nations have for the first time adopted a common
economic policy that has reined in public spending, reduced debt
and tamed inflation. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   A primer: 2,200 words; with graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-SOUTH _ In last month's election, Rep. Sanford D. Bishop
Jr., a moderate black Democrat, won re-election convincingly in a
rural, conservative district where nearly two-thirds of the voters
are white. Many black politicians have managed to attract white
support in urban, New South areas like Atlanta. But Bishop's
electoral success demonstrates that even in the most rural and
impoverished districts, a significant number of white Southerners
no longer view race as an absolute obstacle to voting for a black
politician who shares their thinking, votes their interests and
hauls home plenty of pork. By Kevin Sack. 2,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-YACHTRACE (Gold Coast, Australia) _ The search has
been called off for two missing sailors in the Sydney-to-Hobart
yacht race, and with four others confirmed dead, the 54th running
of the event is already the second worst disaster in modern
yacht-racing history. By Susan B. Adams and Samantha Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ Iraq defiantly vows to fly over the
large swaths of the country where the United States and its allies
bars its flights. But the Pentagon says that Iraq has not yet
provoked a military confrontation. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH-BAYLEY (Oxford, England) _ Iris Murdoch, the celebrated
author of 26 rigorously intellectual novels, stood uncertainly in
the doorway of her living room, her face frozen in the blank
expression that is a sure badge of Alzheimer's disease. It was only
when she saw her husband, the critic, professor and novelist John
Bayley, that a flicker of comprehension sparked in her eyes. But it
was gone, as quickly as it came. Bayley talks about his 40 years
with Murdoch, and his new memoir, ``Elegy for Iris,'' due out in
January. By Sarah Lyall. (MOVED)
</P>
</TEXT>
