<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CHAMP-GONE-COX     12-29 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CHAMP-GONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs' Bailey likely to enter NFL Draft
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia All-America cornerback Champ Bailey, a
6-foot-1, 180-pound junior, probably will be playing his final game
for the Bulldogs on Thursday, coach Jim Donnan said Tuesday. Bailey
is expected to enter April's NFL Draft and could be a top-five
pick, according to some NFL sources. Bailey has until Jan. 8 to
declare for the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a meeting with Champ and his mother after the bowl
game, but I would think pretty much that this is going to be his
last game,'' Donnan said. The No. 19 Bulldogs face No. 12 Virginia
in the Peach Bowl in the Georgia Dome on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the speculation all season after Bailey emerged as
the nation's top two-way threat, averaging 87 plays per game at
cornerback and wideout and on special teams. Bailey, who won the
Bronko Nagurski Award as the nation's top defensive player, had 52
tackles, three interceptions and 10 pass breakups as a senior. He
also was Georgia's top wideout, finishing with 47 catches for 744
yards and five touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some (NFL scouts) like him better on offense and as a
kick-returner,'' Donnan said. ``I would say more than likely that
he'll play corner at the next level. Guys like him are like
dinosaurs. You can't find guys that can cover like him. Look at all
the people he's covered over the last two years, and he's blanketed
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey has repeatedly said he'll wait until after the Peach Bowl
to make a decision. His mother, Elaine Bailey, is adamant about him
earning his degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after the game, I'm just going to start thinking about
it,'' Bailey said. ``Right now, we're just focusing on Virginia. I
know what's important to me. I've been able to keep (the NFL)
pushed back pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a banner year for the Bulldogs in the NFL draft.
Along with Bailey, offensive tackles Matt Stinchcomb and Chris
Terry are expected to be high draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
