<HEADER>
A0772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PEACH-UVA-COX     12-29 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PEACH-UVA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kerney is UVA's pleasant surprise
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As football odysseys go, Patrick Kerney's is as
improbable as, what, the Falcons winning the NFC West? Actually,
the Dirty Birds were a September sure thing compared to a kid who:
</P>
<P>
   Left his Pennsylvania home to play hockey at a toney Connecticut
prep school. Took up lacrosse and also played football for the Taft
School. Played final game against arch-rival Hotchkiss, before a
crowd of 50 (''And those were probably parents''). Got one football
recruiting call, from a Syracuse coach who'd dialed the wrong
number. Went to Virginia on a lacrosse scholarship and walked on
for the football team. Hoped to be a second-string defensive end by
now. Inadvertently became an All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that summer day in 1995 when he walked on in
Charlottesville, Kerney said, ''I think they were expecting some
little preppy kid they could break down in a few days and send home
crying to mama.''
</P>
<P>
   What Virginia got instead was a nonpareil pass rusher who led
the ACC in sacks (15) and tackles for lost yardage (21), became an
All-American (first-team Football Writers Assn. of America,
second-team AP) and was so hounded by agents this fall he had to
get an unlisted phone number.
</P>
<P>
   The phone calls may resume, and multiply, after Kerney concludes
his collegiate career Thursday night against Georgia in the Peach
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   How did all this happen? ''Our lacrosse staff did a heckuva job
recruiting him,'' said UVa defensive coordinator Rick Lantz.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Patrick making All-American is a great tribute to him.
Not to us,'' said Cavaliers head coach George Welsh. ''When you
come in as a walk-on, he had alot to do with it himself, working in
the weight room and on the practice field.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerney's explanation? ''Patience and perseverance, my two
favorite words,'' he said. ''I did what I was told, worked hard and
I didn't expect success overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kerney became an over-four-years(cq) sensation. Even
he's astounded, even now. ''When I look back to when I first
arrived at Virginia, this is a whole 'nother(cq) world,'' he said.
''It's certainly exceeded my expectations. It's wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet all true. All-ACC and second in the voting for ACC Defensive
Player of the Year, Kerney was all over opposing quarterbacks. He
had three sacks against both Maryland and Florida State (one ending
Chris Weinke's season). He tied UVa records for sacks and TFL's in
a season. He was one of five finalists for the Bronko Nagurski
Award that Georgia's Champ Bailey won as the nation's best
defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve in the Georgia Dome, Kerney will confront Matt
Stinchcomb, Georgia's All-American offensive left tackle from
Lilburn who hasn't allowed a sack all season. ''He's an excellent
football player,'' Stinchcomb said. ''Plays whistle to whistle.
More than anything, he finishes off the play, better than most
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerney's football career seemed finished after high school, when
he chose to play lacrosse at UVa. ''I was going to give up
football,'' said Kerney. While he was curious to see whether he
could play Division I-A football, ''I had my doubts. My goal was to
be a backup defensive end and see some action by this year.''
</P>
<P>
   What Welsh and his staff immediately saw was a relentless, swift
6-foot-5 kid. ''He showed us something,'' said Lantz. ''Showed us
he was capable of playing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerney not only made the team, he became one of five true
freshmen to play in 1995. Still a sub - but on scholarship - in
'96, he became a starter last season, a star this fall. He's now
6-foot-6, 260 pounds and a likely high NFL draft choice. All this
from a guy who once terrorized Hotchkiss and the rest of the
Founder's League. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
