<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATOR-GATECH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Edsall effect raised Tech on defense
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Randy Edsall's stay at Georgia Tech turned
out much shorter than even he anticipated. This week is his
farewell tour after a year as Tech's defensive coordinator and 17
years as an assistant coach at Syracuse, Boston College and the
Jacksonville Jaguars. After Friday's Gator Bowl, Edsall leaves to
become Connecticut's coach.
</P>
<P>
   But as he and Tech defenders look back over the season, they
realize that they accomplished a good bit in a short time and that
Edsall might have made the kind of impact that will last for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't always pretty,'' Edsall said. ``But I don't think
there was ever a time where we never played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's improvement did not show in the numbers: The Yellow
Jackets went from last in the ACC in total defense in 1997 (429
yards allowed per game) to eighth (397.6). Tech held steady at
seventh in the conference in both rushing defense and
passing-efficiency defense, same as in 1997. And scoring defense
went up from 24.2 points allowed in 1997 to 24.3 points allowed in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the story is in the nine wins, not the defensive numbers.
Tech's defense cost the Yellow Jackets wins in 1997, late in games
against Notre Dame, Virginia and Georgia; but in 1998, it was
bringing them home, against Virginia, Georgia and Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted we didn't play well against (Boston College), but
there was not one game where the defense let the team down and let
somebody else win,'' Edsall said. ``The Virginia game, yeah they
had some yards, but we made all the plays we had to make in the
second half, and we were stingy. Same thing in the Georgia game.
Right there early in the game, we give up that big play, but we
came back and played pretty darn well the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Edsall said the goals he set for the Yellow Jackets on defense
coming into the season were to play a championship season, keep
people from scoring, be a good third-down team and create
turnovers. Tech came away with a share of the ACC championship, an
NCAA record with seven fumbles returned for touchdowns and an
improvement in third-down-efficiency defense, from allowing teams
to convert 44.4 percent of the time in 1997 to 36.7 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the '97 season, Tech's defense was tight, feeling
the pressure of losing games late. Playing on defense didn't look
like much fun anymore. That's what Edsall set out to restore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to let them go,'' Edsall said. ``We tried to let them
have fun within the scheme of a defense. We didn't want to harness
them. We didn't want to put a noose on them and make them feel
restricted. We wanted to be aggressive, because I think kids enjoy
that. We knew there would be mistakes, and we coached off the
mistakes. They liked that opportunity that we gave them, having
that ability to do those things, and I think it paid off for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he won his players' respect and loyalty, which
makes this last week all the more meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's going to replace him, but I'm just glad I'm
not going to be here,'' senior defensive end Nate Stimson said. ``I
don't want to play for anyone else. Everyone is happy for him, but
a lot of people don't want him to go because we like him. His goal
is to be a head coach, and he got it, so he's got to go for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The impression Edsall hopes he leaves behind is this one: ``When
people look back on the 1998 Georgia Tech defense,'' Edsall said,
``(it) was one that played hard, never gave up, was opportunistic
and they made plays when they had to.''
</P>
<P>
   GATOR BOWL
</P>
<P>
   _ Opponents: Georgia Tech vs. Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Friday, 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Gator Bowl, Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
