<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOFTDRINK-ADS-COX     12-29 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTDRINK-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Diet drink ads turn to 'feel good'
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first new commercials for Diet Coke in nearly a
year will appear Monday, just in time to capture that perennial
army of New Year's resolution-bound dieters.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than focusing on how the world's No. 1 diet soft
drink can help consumers cut a more dashing figure, the ads suggest
Diet Coke can empower them to be their best while living life to
the fullest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live Your Life'' is the tagline, a departure from the previous
``You Are What You Drink'' and the long-running ``Just For the
Taste of It'' campaigns. The new phrase, featured in the two new
commercials and likely to be used in another half-dozen expected
later this year, was crafted after Atlanta-based Coca-Cola
interviewed 3,600 Diet Coke loyalists in nine countries about what
role the beverage plays in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The research showed that ``looking good is important, but it's a
subcomponent of feeling good,'' said Jan Hall, Diet Coke's global
brand director.
</P>
<P>
   One of the commercials, from the Portland, Ore.-based Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy agency, shows a woman preparing to use a video dating
service. As she sips a Diet Coke, she reflects on her options and
realizes she is happy with her life the way it is. The other
features a woman who lets a cute guy's car roll off a cliff so she
can offer him a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This advertising is reflective and consistent with living life
on your own terms,'' said Ian Rowden, Coca-Cola's global
advertising director. ``It's less focused on some of the shape and
calorie benefits of the brand and more on how consumers see their
life and how they react to the changes in their life.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials follow what Coca-Cola said is the best year for
its flagship diet drink since 1990. Incomplete figures show U.S.
volume rising 4 percent over 1997 and worldwide sales up about 8
percent, the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The diet beverage category has been sagging for years, but
Coca-Cola and its competitors hope to change that with a slate of
new marketing campaigns set for release in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Pepsico and No. 3 Cadbury Schweppes also will release new
advertising for their diet drinks, as well as for their
full-calorie brands.
</P>
<P>
   John Sicher, publisher of trade publication Beverage Digest,
said he's not surprised by the flurry of new campaigns _
particularly for diet soft drinks. That's because the Food and Drug
Administration recently approved two new beverage sweeteners, which
taste more like sugar, and make for a longer shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   All the beverage companies are still weighing how to take
advantage of the new sweetener options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diet segment is going to be fascinating to watch for the
next few years,'' said Sicher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be more focus and attention on the diet
sector. More focus means more growth, or more potential for
growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Diet drinks peaked in 1990, making up 29.8 percent of the U.S.
soft drink market, according to Beverage Digest. In 1997, the last
year for which figures are available, diet drinks made up just 22.9
percent of the total soft drink market. Within that diet market,
products from Coca-Cola had a 49.5 percent share compared to 32.2
percent for Pepsico's brands and 7.7 percent for Cadbury Schweppes.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico has been trying to shift the weight with its Pepsi One
brand, which has been called the first innovation in the U.S. diet
soft drink arena in more than 16 years. The one-calorie drink,
introduced in October, is the first to use a blend of aspartame and
acesulfame potassium, also known as Ace-K, one of the newly
approved sweetener options.
</P>
<P>
   A marketing blitz for Pepsi One has been under way since
October, with commercials starring actor Cuba Gooding of ``show me
the money'' fame, and it's not expected to let up anytime soon. The
company wouldn't release details about the next wave of
commercials, but it plans to spend $100 million promoting Pepsi One
over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico is among the advertisers spending an average $1.6
million per 30-second spot during the Super Bowl Jan. 31. The
company has not said which brands it plans to feature during its
air time.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts, however, expect some of the Super Bowl ads to
introduce a new Pepsi theme, ending the year-old ``Generation
Next'' campaign that hasn't been a hit with beverage chief Phil
Marineau.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which ran just one Super Bowl commercial last year
compared to several by Pepsico, isn't shelling out the cash to
advertise during the upcoming game.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes, however, is using the event to unveil a new 7
UP campaign, which will be teased to in TV commercials during the
two weeks before the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The spots will lay the groundwork for the campaign, which asks
``Are U an UN?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a play on the brand's Un-Cola trademark and a chance to
distinguish the beverage from conventional soft drinks, said Mike
McGrath, president and chief operating officer of Plano,
Texas-based Dr Pepper/Seven Up, part of London-based Cadbury
Schweppes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. division, which said it plans to spend 12 percent more
to promote its Dr Pepper and Diet Dr Pepper brands this year, was
not included in the $1.85 billion deal Coca-Cola recently announced
to buy most of Cadbury Schweppes' global beverage operations.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve new TV spots for Dr Pepper and Diet Dr Pepper begin
airing in primetime Jan. 11. The bulk of the commercials are for
Diet Dr Pepper, and revolve around the idea that some people can't
tell the difference between that drink and ``regular'' Dr Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey H. Gramig writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
