<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-SURVIVAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF OCTUPLETS TO BE RELEASED FROM HOSPITAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional trim included) 
 
By CAROL CHRISTIAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Nkem Chukwu, who gave birth to octuplets this month,
is scheduled to be released from the hospital Tuesday, while her
seven surviving babies have passed an important medical test and
are now given a 92 percent chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, 29, is still anemic but slowly gaining strength, said
Dr. Brian Kirshon, her attending physician and maternal-fetal
medicine specialist and high-risk obstetrician at St. Luke's
Episcopal Hospital in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very weak from being bedridden for such a long time,''
said Kirshon, who delivered the world's first octuplets born alive.
The first baby was born naturally Dec. 8 and the other seven by
Caesarean section Dec. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu entered St. Luke's in early October and had been confined
to bed for six weeks before the first delivery.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 21, about 18 hours after the seven babies were born, she
went back into surgery to control her abdominal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the surviving babies remained in critical but stable
condition, said Dr. Patti Savrick, a clinical assistant professor
of pediatrics at Baylor College of Medicine and the children's
primary care pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   Savrick said ultrasounds of the babies' heads Monday had yielded
``dramatic good news'' _ they had no bleeding or cysts in their
brains.
</P>
<P>
   Bleeding to the brain is probably the most reliable single
predictor of future neurological problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of neonatology service at Texas
Children's Hospital and the newborn-premature service at St.
Luke's, said that 20 percent to 25 percent of babies as small as
the Chukwu octuplets experience bleeding to the brain, which
increases the risk for long-term complications such as cerebral
palsy.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the premature infants' progress, they are likely to
stay in the hospital until their due date of about April 1, Savrick
said.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest baby, a girl named Odera who weighed only 10.3
ounces at birth, died Sunday of heart and lung failure. The
largest, a boy named Jioke, weighed 26 ounces. None is expected to
gain weight until about two weeks old, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving babies' chances for survival are now about 92
percent, Weisman said, based on the hospital's treatment of 2,500
premature infants during the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Texas Children's treats about 250 babies born between
25 and 29 weeks gestation, said Weisman.
</P>
<P>
   The seven surviving babies include five girls and two boys.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, first-born Ebuka, sixth-born Ikem and eighth-born
Gorom were on ventilators, while second-born Chidi, third-born
Echerem, fourth-born Chima and seventh-born Jioke were breathing on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   At the family's request, no photographs or videotapes of the
babies have been released to news media, hospital officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu and her husband, Iyke Louis Odobi, were born in Nigeria
and are naturalized U.S. citizens. Odobi, a respiratory therapist
in Houston, is expected to return to work by the end of the week,
Kirshon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although neither St. Luke's nor Texas Children's has solicited
gifts for the family, donations and good wishes have come from
around the world, hospital administrators said.
</P>
<P>
   Donations may be sent to the Chukwu Family Fund, St. Luke's
Episcopal Hospital, 6900 Fannin, Suite 440, Houston, Texas 77030.
For more information, call 713-791-3137 or 713-770-2196.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, said Tuesday that after
the holidays she will urge Houston-area corporations to donate such
things as a van and a larger house than the family's four-bedroom
dwelling in southwest Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
