u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SC-ALA-LOTTERY-COX     12-29 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SC-ALA-LOTTERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller offers advice on passing a lottery
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Zell Miller lent his support Tuesday to a
proposed South Carolina lottery for education, by meeting with that
state's governor-elect, Jim Hodges, to give him pointers on how to
win popular support for a state-run lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges said he planned to take Miller's advice to stress to the
public that all lottery proceeds would flow to education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take a lesson from Georgia,'' Hodges said. ``If we begin
piecemealing the lottery money, education suffers, and the lottery
suffers.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller acknowledged that a new lottery in a neighboring state
might cut money outsiders spend on the Georgia Lottery, which funds
HOPE scholarships, pre-kindergarten and school technology. But he
dismissed that as a reason for withholding his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at how many young South Carolina children will be
helped by the money,'' Miller said at a press conference after his
meeting with Hodges. He said Georgia would need to devise
attractive new games to keep its revenues up.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia doesn't have precise numbers on how much outsiders spend
on its lottery. Neither Miller or Rebecca Paul, president of the
Georgia Lottery, would speculate on how that spending would change
if neighboring states started lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way, way too early to tell,'' Paul said. ``How much they
impact us depends on how they are structured.''
</P>
<P>
   The types of games offered and commitment to advertising
influence a lottery's popularity. ``There are things they can do,''
Paul said. ``I'm sure not going to tell them what those are.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Miller met with Alabama's governor-elect, Don
Siegelman, to offer him advice on setting up an Alabama lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Both Siegelman and Hodges campaigned on the promise to imitate
Georgia's lottery, Miller's signature program.
</P>
<P>
   Both states plan statewide referendums on the issue in the year
2000. Their lotteries wouldn't begin operating before 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges said he planned to use lottery money to reduce class
sizes, establish college scholarships and fund pre-kindergarten.
``A lottery carefully crafted will help education in South
Carolina,'' Hodges said. ``We're tired of being 50th in several
(education) categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mantius writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
