A0796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STONEMOUNTAIN-FEES-CO     12-29 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STONEMOUNTAIN-FEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parking fee hike at park slowed
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Members of Stone Mountain Park's oversight committee
on Tuesday postponed a decision on a parking fee increase, saying
they want the private company that manages much of the park to
justify the hike.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Dollar City, the theme park developer that started
managing park attractions this year, wants to raise the daily
parking pass from $6 to $7 and the annual parking pass from $25 to
$30. The last increase _ from $5 to $6 _ came in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to arbitrarily increase prices based on limited
information,'' said Lonice Barrett, a member of the Stone Mountain
Memorial Association Board and commissioner of the Georgia
Department of Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   He and other board members said they received information
packages about the increase late Monday afternoon. ``I want to see
a package more reassuring to me,'' said Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   The board is scheduled to vote next month on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Paul van Leeuwen, executive vice president for Silver Dollar
City, said his company this year spent $3.3 million on park
improvements and $1.3 million at the Evergreen Conference Center
and Resort at the park. He said the added parking revenue would
finance improvements such as ``significant increases in the laser
show'' that include enhanced fireworks and a new sound and light
tower.
</P>
<P>
   He said the parking fee increases _ on about 600,000 annual
daily parking passes and 60,000 yearly passes _ would raise close
to $1 million a year, about 2 percent of the park's $45 million to
$50 million in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Dollar City has increased prices from $3.50 to $4 for
admission to the plantation, the railroad and the wildlife center
at the park. But van Leeuwen said the cost of a 10-attraction
ticket has dropped from $25 to $18.
</P>
<P>
   Under the lease agreement with the state, Silver Dollar City
pays the authority a base payment of $9.5 million annually and 3
percent of all revenues over $44 million. The state still manages
all natural areas of the park, provides police service and
maintains roads and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Torpy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
