<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POISONED-DOGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POISON KILLS NEIGHBORHOOD PETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbara Kawadler sensed something was amiss Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Crows filled the backyard of her home in Milton, Mass., although
it wasn't trash collection day. Looking out the kitchen window, she
saw one big black bird and then a second suddenly fall off their
tree perches and flop to the ground, cawing noisly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to my husband, `I think somebody is trying to poison
them,' '' Kawadler recalled. But when she turned back to the
window, the birds had vanished and she gave it no more thought.
</P>
<P>
   Before day's end, the Kawadlers' nine-year-old mixed Labrador
Retriever was barely clinging to life and their daughter's two dogs
_ a great dane and golden retriever that the Kawadlers were
babysitting while their daughter was in the hospital giving birth
to twins -- were dead.
</P>
<P>
   The three pets were victims of what police Tuesday described as
a case of serial poisoning that also had taken the lives of two
other dogs in the Pope's Pond neighborhood and possibly the life of
a puppy.
</P>
<P>
   All the dogs apparently had eaten meat laced with strychnine, a
poison used to kill rodents, after being let out in pens or yards
Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, as police expanded their search for the poisoner, news
of the killings shook the upscale neighborhood, where large yards
and ample green space have attracted many families that own dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who don't own dogs expressed shock at the cruelty of
the crimes, while pet owners vowed to keep their dogs on a short
leash. Some called on neighbors to check on the wellbeing of their
four-footed friends, while the families of the poisoned dogs
grieved.
</P>
<P>
   The Kawadlers turned over to Milton police a remnant of what
resembles a meatball, encasing a poison pellet, which their dog
Lucy had carried in to their Craig Street home from their fenced
backyard the night she fell ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrendous death they suffer,'' said Captain Robert
Fennessey, deputy director of law enforcement for the Massachusetts
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. ``They go into
violent spasms, they can't breathe and they are vomiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Fennessey said his agency usually gets 5,000 reports of animal
abuse a year, but few involve poisonings and even fewer involve
poisonings of such a large number of pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually what we find is somebody has a gripe with a neighbor
and one or two pets are involved,'' he said. ``Something like this,
which is a serial killer, there is something more.''
</P>
<P>
   And, like a movie sleuth trying to identify a serial killer by
getting inside his head, Fennessey tried to speculate about what
might motivate a dog killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could want to rid the neighborhood of dogs, so they can
do things in the night,'' he said. ``It could be just somebody who
doesn't like dogs and wants to see them suffer and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy, the Kawadlers' dog, remained in intensive care at Angell
Memorial Hospital Tuesday. She may have survived up to this point
only because she ate less of the tainted meat, which either had
been left or tossed into yards, police and the family said.
</P>
<P>
   Kawadler said the 50-pound dog has been her husband Gerald's
constant companion for nearly a decade, often nestling by his feet
beneath the desk as he worked in the family's heating and
air-conditioning business.
</P>
<P>
   The Kawadlers' son, Stuart, said his father would even take Lucy
to business conferences and record her as being present in his
minutes of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   At the office, Lucy would share a turkey pocket with the
receptionist's dog everyday for lunch, except Friday, when they
feasted on Chinese food.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a funny dog,'' Stuart said. ``I don't know what kind of
demented mind could do this. They're not just pets, they're part of
our family.
</P>
<P>
   Other families had equally strong feelings for their poisoned
pets.
</P>
<P>
   Molly, a six-year-old Labrador belonging to the Phillips family,
just around the corner from the Kawadlers, had gone on many family
vacations _ to Cape Cod, to New Hampshire, to Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends kind of expected if they invited me anywhere, Molly
was going to be there, too,'' chuckled Gary Phillips, as he fondly
recalled Molly. ``Yeah, she was a dog, but she was a great member
of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Minard Culpepper said Sheba, his family's seven-year-old German
Shephard, usually barked when she wanted to come back into the
house from the fenced yard.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, when Culpepper didn't hear anything after what
seemed like an hour Saturday evening, he went out to check on her
and found her dead, blood trickling from her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very protective dog,'' Culpepper said. ``She would
bark at strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another owner of a dog possibly poisoned by the serial killer,
Susan Derrick, lives near Curry College, about a half-mile from the
three-block area where the other families live. She said her
six-month-old golden retriever, Rusty, was timid and would not have
wandered far from her hilltop house.
</P>
<P>
   That would have meant someone would have had to come near the
house to leave the poison, since the house is set 150 feet back
from the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little more frightening to think someone would have to
come up here to do it,'' said Derrick.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty also had violent seizures before dying on the kitchen
floor. But Fennessey of the MSPCA said her body already has been
cremated, so tests could not be conducted to confirm poisoning.
Meanwhile, Barbara Kawadler's voice shuddered with sorrow as she
recalled having to tell her daughter her dogs had died only hours
after her daughter had given birth. Then it swelled with anger at
the thought her own family could no longer feel safe in their home:
The poisoned meat was placed in the yard, she noted, where her
grandchildren often play on the swing set when they visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been a child who picked it up, and if it was a
child, they would have called it homicide,'' said Kawadler.
</P>
<P>
   The MSPCA is offering a $1,000 reward and the Kawadlers $500 for
information leading to the arrest and successful prosecution of the
person or people responsible for the poisonings. People should call
the MSPCA at 1-800-628-5808 or Milton Police at 617-698-3800 with
information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
