<SLUG> BC-BLIND-SETTLEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AGENCY FOR THE BLIND AGREES TO PAY EX-WORKER $50,000 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Jamestown, N.Y.) 
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Commission for the Blind has agreed to
pay $50,000 to a former employee in Houston who said she was
harassed for her own blindness and denied aids to overcome her
disability.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Justice Department lawyers said Tuesday the settlement
resolves the first such case nationally in which it found that a
government agency discriminated against the disabled individuals it
is charged with helping.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was forged in out-of-court mediation after the
Justice Department investigation determined that the Texas agency
had violated the Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the hell my husband and I have lived for the past six
years will make things better for the people in Texas,'' Joanna
States said when reached late Tuesday at her current home in
Jamestown, N.Y. ``It's really been unreal. I had to leave Texas in
order to get a part-time job.''
</P>
<P>
   The state commission, however, continues to deny wrongdoing and
said it settled only to save the cost of a lengthy court fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say? It does look ironic. On the other hand it
wasn't true,'' said Terry Murphy, executive director of the state
commission. ``We are not an organization that goes around
discriminating against people who are blind.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, however, the agency agreed to
compensate States, formerly a secretary at the agency's Houston
office, for at least some of her losses. She left her job under
duress, she complained, after her supervisor criticized her for
using a Braille machine, a cane and a talking clock.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she works pushing a linen cart at a Christian-affiliated
hospital where she's thankful her new co-workers have let her show
them what she's capable of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what you can do in order to survive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   State's 1993 complaint of harassment and a hostile work
environment sparked the Justice Department's investigation and
findings that such practices were not isolated events within the
agency's workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation has revealed that the commission failed to
make reasonable accommodations to the known disabilities of
individuals, and that it maintains a practice of failing to provide
certain employee manuals and information in accessible formats
(such as Braille and audiotape),'' the civil rights division of the
Justice Department reported last year.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said States has agreed to the settlement. He added that
she had originally sought back salary and damages totaling
$200,000, ``so this is a lot less.''
</P>
<P>
   States said she was contacted earlier Tuesday by one of the
federal lawyers who advised her not to comment to reporters about
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've strictly been advised that I should keep my mouth shut,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another former employee, Sharon Fernandez of San Antonio,
however, said in a telephone interview that she has not decided
whether to accept the $5,000 offered for similar claims of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have contacted a lawyer,'' she said. ``There's a couple of
things in there I'm not happy with.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said she left the agency after the assistant assigned
to her refused to accommodate her blindness. She said she had sent
government lawyers ample documentation to back up that claim.
</P>
<P>
   She added that she suffers severe visual impairment in her left
eye and lost the other eye years before to illness caused by her
two-month premature birth as a twin in 1948. The babies each
weighed just barely 2 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Another San Antonio employee that federal lawyers said suffered
discrimination, Louis Larralde, had already been reinstated as a
vocational rehabilitation counselor at the time the agreement was
forged. While the Justice Department takes credit for the rehire,
Murphy said it had nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement settling the discrimination dispute requires Texas
Commission for the Blind to take several steps to prevent
discrimination of its disabled employees in the future. It also
makes clear that most of them are already in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``By implementing the agreed upon changes, the Texas Commission
for the Blind has taken a significant step towards ensuring full
and fair employment opportunities for people with vision
impairments,'' Bill Lann Lee, acting assistant attorney general for
civil rights, said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said about 80 employees, or 13 percent of the
commission's workforce, are blind or visually impaired.
</P>
<P>
   The commission agreed to make certain all employee manuals,
training materials and other printed information is provided also
in Braille, large print or on computer disc.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has designated a person to specifically handle
disability discrimination complaints under the Americans with
Disabilities Act and refer to independent mediators those cases
that aren't resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the agency must evaluate the needs of its employees in a
timely way and make sure all necessary equipment is provided. All
current and future employees must additionally be trained about the
rights and needs of people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is subject to approval by the Texas Attorney
General. Ward Tisdale, spokesman for outgoing Attorney General Dan
Morales, did not return phone calls as to whether that is likely
before Morales leaves office next month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
