<HEADLINE>
CAN ANYONE KEEP PEACE BETWEEN THE SERBS AND ALBANIANS IN KOSOVO?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Desks)   (This pithy ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS
EXCELLENT ARTICLE STANDS ALONE IN 625 WORDS; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS
1,200 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international, ``a'' domestic/general and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much for General Winter, and the stillness that for a few
frozen months, at least, was supposed to lie across the tormented
land of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, when Christians fight Muslims across the
snowy hillsides of the southern Balkans, not even Christmas can
halt the bloodshed.
</P>
