<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0838 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENAE-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-29 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENAE-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PROSECUTORS ANNOUNCE PLANS TO CALL WITNESSES IN CLINTON
TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House prosecutors announced plans Tuesday to call
witnesses _ perhaps even former presidential paramour Monica
Lewinsky _ when President Clinton's impeachment trial gets under
way in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But that strategy conflicts with the position of Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that a trial could be based solely on
the record of sworn testimony compiled by independent counsel
Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lott and several other Republicans, including
Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, cautioned lawmakers against rushing toward a
censure deal with the White House before a Senate trial begins and
the charges against Clinton are fully aired.
</P>
<P>
   Impeached by the House on perjury and obstruction of justice
charges stemming from his effort to conceal his affair with
Lewinsky, Clinton is only the second president in U.S. history to
face trial and possible removal by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging Tuesday afternoon from a closed-door strategy session,
several of the House members appointed to present the case against
Clinton to the Senate said they had agreed to summon witnesses and
not rely solely on grand jury evidence once the trial starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no show of hands. But I am anticipating, based on
everything we've discussed in there today, that there would be
witnesses, we would present witnesses. I don't think there's any
question about that,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Lewinsky might be called, Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif.,
said: ``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Other key figures, including Linda Tripp, who secretly recorded
her telephone calls with Lewinsky, Clinton confidante Vernon
Jordan, the president's personal secretary, Betty Currie, and other
key White House figures could be questioned in public.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott said a trial _ much like the House impeachment hearings
and debate _ could be held without bringing witnesses to the floor
of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are witnesses required? I don't think so,'' Lott told The
Associated Press. ``I think the record is there to be reviewed,
read, presented in a form that (House prosecutors) choose ... and I
think that would be sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott also proposed to Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., that Clinton's trial begin Jan. 7 with Chief Justice
William Rehnquist swearing senators in as jurors. The GOP leader
suggested Jan. 11 as the date for the Senate to begin hearing
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   No firm decisions were made about a timetable for beginning the
trial, the first since President Andrew Johnson was acquitted by
the Senate in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday's meeting, the 13-person, all-Republican team of
case managers was told by Illinois Rep. Henry Hyde, the chief House
prosecutor, to prepare for a full-fledged trial even though it
could be abruptly halted by a censure deal. The group plans to meet
again next week after the Senate convenes and provides guidance on
how it wants to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Senate Republican, several Senate Democrats and
White House allies have publicly advocated reaching an agreement
that would avoid a prolonged trial and result in a formal censure
or rebuke of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and Gramm said senators should vote on whether Clinton
should be removed before formally considering any censure proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm urged lawmakers to ignore ``rising calls for the Senate to
short-circuit the constitutional process'' of beginning Clinton's
trial next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the Senate has a clear, constitutional
obligation to vote on whether the president is guilty or not guilty
of the two articles of impeachment adopted by the House,'' Gramm
said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the lone Republican voice in the Senate calling for
censure of Clinton is Sen. Orrin Hatch, a Utah conservative who
sees it as ``the only option left'' since impeachment advocates are
expected to fall short of the two-thirds vote needed to convict the
president and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm disagreed. ``I strongly believe that the Senate's
commitment must be to a fair, constitutional process and not to any
given outcome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Texas Democratic Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee said a case
for censure can still be made now that influential senators have
come out in favor of the measure instead of removing the president
from office.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Jackson Lee told reporters that when the new
Congress convenes next week and the House votes to reappoint Hyde
and his team of prosecutors, Democrats should be included.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have the momentum to present a case for censure,'' said
Jackson Lee, one of four House Judiciary Committee members who
drafted a censure resolution that was rejected in committee and on
the House floor. ``I'm saying let us address the question openly
about a censure resolution. We have the right as Democrats to have
managers.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, Jackson Lee said she would be willing
to participate as one of the case managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they would hear from those who have argued for
censure,'' she said. ``It (censure) is not a deal. It is not a
cover up. It is an appropriate reprimand. It is harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter Salatheia Bryant contributed to this story &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
