<HEADER>
A0844 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATIMES-LAYOFFS-LADN     12-29 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIMES-LAYOFFS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. TIMES TO LAY OFF NEARLY 100 IN THIRD ROUND OF CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (Also moving in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
files) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned about slowing growth in advertising revenues, the Los
Angeles Times said it will eliminate nearly 100 distribution jobs
and end contracts with 50 or more free-lance delivery agents as
part of a third and apparent final round of job cuts this holiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   Ten full-time and 84-part-time jobs in the single-copy and
home-delivery distribution operations will be eliminated. Most will
be layoffs, but some are voluntary retirements, the paper announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The flagship newspaper of Los Angeles-based Times Mirror Co.
also will stop doing business with 50 of the 150 independent
newspaper delivery agencies that deliver the paper to subscribers
in Los Angeles, Orange, Ventura, Riverside and San Bernardino
counties.
</P>
<P>
   While workers in those agencies are not Times Mirror employees,
typically the bulk of a delivery agency's revenue comes from one
newspaper. A Times spokeswoman couldn't say how many people would
be affected by the decision to stop working with the 50 agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks are being done to streamline home-delivery
operations and reduce distribution costs, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The Times first announced in November that it would begin a
series of layoffs in the last weeks of the year in response to poor
advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the company has identified a total of 850 jobs _ 13
percent of the paper's work force _ to be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs began in November and will continue into the first
quarter of 1999. Most of the jobs cut were in business operations,
not the news department. Half were part-timers.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no plans for further cutbacks in 1999, ``it's
not wise to say there won't be anything,'' said Times spokeswoman
Laura Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising revenue growth at the Times has been lagging behind
the industry average, said Peter Appert, an analyst for BT Alex.
Brown in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a slowing economic engine nationally, industry ad
growth has been weakening this year, from an increase of 6.6
percent in the first quarter to 5 percent in the third quarter and
an expected 4 percent increase for the fourth quarter, Appert said.
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror said earlier it would take a $225 million charge
against earnings this year for the restructuring at the Times and
at its other papers. Tuesday's cuts were announced after the stock
market closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 2026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
