<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0846 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENTER-EURO-ENFIN-INDE     12-29 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTER-EURO-ENFIN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE SLEEP-WALKS ITS WAY INTO EUROLAND  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 1,225-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By JOHN LICHFIELD  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The owner of my favorite bar in Paris is not a
philosophical sort of man. He rarely says anything at all. The
other day he came to my table and gave a long soliloquy about the
euro (a subject dear to his heart, and pocket, since he replaced
his till and portable bankers' card machines to prepare for the
partial launch of the new currency next month).
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise, the soliloquy was not negative. Nor was it
especially positive. He was convinced, in a matter-of-fact kind of
way, that the coming of the euro was the ``real beginning of Europe
as one country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How much did any of it mean, there, in Brussels, until now?
Nothing. But money, that people understand.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that in 50 years' time, everyone in Europe would
have two nationalities and two languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, I feel Breton and French. In the future, they will feel
French or Italian or German, and at the same time, they will feel
European. Everyone will talk their own language and also English.
Except you, the English. You will always talk only English.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is right, and the Daily Telegraph is right, and the French
Euroskeptics like the former interior minister, Charles Pasqua, are
right, this week marks the beginning of the end of the nation state
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Where _ apart from in Britain _ are the forces of national
resistance? Where are the violent street demonstrations? Where are
the new European civil wars, predicted in a book serialized in The
Times a couple of years ago? Where are the legions of currency
speculators, determined to bring the whole cumbersome apparatus
down?
</P>
<P>
   The coming of the euro is the story of a whole pack of dogs
which did not bark. The recession, and uprisings, predicted as a
result of the spending cuts forced by the euro guidelines have not
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The economies of the Euroland countries, with record low
interest rates and low inflation, are resisting the turbulence in
the world economy better than most.
</P>
<P>
   The visceral opposition of the German public has evaporated. The
French public _ like the other nine euro publics _ is apathetically
enthusiastic: hugely in favor, according to the polls, but not
especially interested.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year gap between the political launch of the single
currency this week and the appearance of alien, monopoly money in
people's pockets looked like a huge hostage to fortune.
</P>
<P>
   It may turn out to have been a political masterstroke: lulling
the Europeans into a gradual acceptance of the euro, like someone
drowsing in the bath with the hot tap turned on.
</P>
<P>
   Even for someone fundamentally pro-European, it is bizarre, even
disturbing experience, to see a proud and great country like France
sleep-walking into something so elemental to its future.
</P>
<P>
   From Jan. 1, the husk of the franc will remain in French
pockets, but the franc, as an independent, national currency, as an
instrument of national economic policy, as a symbol or tool of
national sovereignty, will have ceased to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of the franc against the euro and the 10 other euro
currencies will be fixed in concrete. Decisions on interest rates
and money supply will be taken by the European Central Bank in
Frankfurt, under the chairmanship of a Dutch banker who looks like
one of the many incarnations of Dr. Who.
</P>
<P>
   Until Jan. 1, 2002, the euro will have a strange life as a
virtual currency, a plastic currency, an electronic currency. There
will be euro checkbooks (smaller than existing ones to set them
apart). There will be euro-compatible bankers' cards. But there
will be no foldable euro notes or spinnable euro coins.
</P>
<P>
   Big business in Euroland is expected to switch to making paper
and electronic transactions in Euros immediately. For the next
three years, small businesses, restaurants and shops have the
option of accepting Euros in plastic or check form _ or not, as
they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Seen from street level, the whole business looks like a bit of a
non-event. But the Paris bar owner, Charles Pasqua and the Daily
Telegraph are right.
</P>
<P>
   The coming of the single currency is a quantum leap in the
creation of a common European identity and a single European
political and economic entity (even if the f-word, federalism, is
banned now in France and Germany as much as in Britain).
</P>
<P>
   It is a quantum leap partly for the reasons the bar owner gave.
Once the euro becomes a real currency in three years' time, Europe
will become part of daily life, something palpable and meaningful
to ordinary, non-farming Europeans for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   This could, ultimately, help to create the kind of political and
democratic legitimacy which the European Union _ always a top-down,
elitist kind of notion _ has never really had. Small wonder that
the Euroskeptics loathe the idea of the euro as they do.
</P>
<P>
   But there are huge dangers also, from the pro-European
perspective. If the European economies falter or crash before the
euro becomes fully accepted, the single currency and the European
Central Bank will be easy and obvious demagogic targets.
</P>
<P>
   The single currency is a quantum leap for other reasons, which
pro-Europeans prefer to smooth over.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason why many Britons have never emotionally
accepted the EEC/EC/EU is that it was sold to them as a simple
common market, which it never really was.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Blair government, under withering Euroskeptic
fire, tends now to minimize the significance _ in terms of
sovereignty, in terms of loss of economic control _ of joining the
single currency.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the existence of a single currency is likely to force
the Euroland governments, little by little, to take many more
economic and political decisions together.
</P>
<P>
   Scope will remain for independent policies on taxation (as even
the individual U.S. states or Canadian provinces have). But the
otherwise destabilizing effect of differing national economies will
force the Euroland governments to coordinate economic policy more
and more closely.
</P>
<P>
   To this extent, the decision of the new German government to
drop the Kohl-fired opposition to such a notion is not so much a
swing to the left as a recognition of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Once that happens, the case for more direct democracy at
European level _ also inevitably a federalizing force _ would
become unanswerable.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the EU has been one of setting seemingly purely
economic targets _ the common market, the single market, the single
currency _ which turn out to be deeply political targets.
</P>
<P>
   Removing economic barriers forces the removal of political
barriers (something Baroness Thatcher failed to grasp). The coming
of the euro sets that clock ticking again, more powerfully than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. There are good economic arguments for the Euro. There is a
case for more political unity in Europe, short _ far short _ of the
arrogant, bureaucratic, federal superstate of Euroskeptic
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   But the closer you come to real lives of real people, as the
euro does, the more you need to be sure that the real people accept
what is happening in their name and why.
</P>
<P>
   The indifference with which the phantom phase of the euro will
be greeted throughout Euroland next week may baffle Euroskeptics;
it should also unsettle the pro-Europeans. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 1,225-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 2026EST &QL; 
