<SLUG> BC-BADAIR-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX-AREA AIR POLLUTION WORST IN 2 WINTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Air pollution hit its worst level in two winters
Tuesday, spurring pleas for Phoenix-area residents to curb driving
and not light wood-burning fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   That means no fireplace burning until 10 a.m. today. And
motorists should try to minimize their time behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combine your trips so you're not backtracking,'' said Steven
Peplau, air-quality manager for the Maricopa County Environmental
Services Department. ``Take a bus where you can, carpool where you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than two years since Maricopa County officials
have had to call a high-pollution advisory. And the timing couldn't
be worse.
</P>
<P>
   It comes two days before the deadline for the Valley of the Sun,
as the Phoenix area is known, to record two straight years of good
readings for carbon monoxide pollution. If that happens, Valley
officials can apply for clean-air status from the federal
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley is rated ``serious'' for carbon monoxide, as well as
for particulate and ozone pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Peplau blamed the rising bad-air levels on a spate of
post-holiday driving and folks soaking up the ambience of a roaring
fire. Throw in the relatively still weather, and conditions are
ripe for an inversion that traps polluted air close to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is wind,'' Peplau said.
</P>
<P>
   That might come Thursday, when a strong airmass is predicted to
move across the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The haze hugging the Valley in recent days is a mix of
pollutants, including carbon monoxide, which is invisible. The
color comes from the tiny bits of soot and grime caused by a
variety of sources, ranging from fireplace particles to
diesel-truck exhaust to the road dust kicked up by car tires
traveling millions of miles daily.
</P>
<P>
   To get through the end of year, extra precautions are needed to
avoid violating federal health standards for carbon-monoxide
pollution, Peplau said.
</P>
<P>
   If pollution levels can be kept at bay through the end of
Thursday, it will strengthen Valley officials' bid to have the EPA
classify the area as meeting clean-air standards.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first time since the standards were created in
the 1970 federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the designation would be more intangible than
practical. The Valley would no longer face the threat of federal
sanctions for failing to meet clean-air standards, and it could
erase one of three black marks against its air-quality ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But measures put in place over the last two decades to cut
carbon monoxide would remain in place. Those include the
vehicle-emissions test, cleaner fuels and federal mandates on
cleaner-burning automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Because carbon monoxide is created primarily by vehicle exhaust,
the pollution advisories target driving.
</P>
<P>
   But fireplaces also boost carbon monoxide, since wood and wax,
or ``fake,'' logs burn incompletely, Peplau said.
</P>
<P>
   The fireplace ban does not apply to people who have an
EPA-approved wood-burning fireplace, or alternatively fueled
fireplaces, such as those that run on natural gas or electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 444-8963 or via e-mail at
maryjo.pitzl &LR; pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
