<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      12-29 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S SEN. JOHN MCCAIN TO TAKE 1ST BIG STEP TOWARD PRESIDENTIAL
BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain today will take his first major step
towards launching a presidential campaign by filing papers to
create a presi dential exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, McCain becomes the first Republican to take such a
formal step, which allows him to begin raising the estimated $20
million he will need next year to be considered a viable candidate
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is out of the country on a family vacation and could not
be reached for comment. McCain is likely to make a formal announce
ment in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant step for him to set up a committee,''
said Howard Opinsky, spokesman for the ``John McCain for President
Ex ploratory Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant signal of his intentions,'' Opinksy said.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Hampshire senator Warren Rudman, who will co-chair
McCain's exploratory committee, told The Republic Tuesday: ``I
think the trend is in the direction he will run, but to say it's a
certainty would be a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is likely to make his first remarks on the subject during
a speech Firday to a conference of conservative leaders at the
Arizona Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   His exploratory committee will become formal today with its
filing at the Federal Election Commission in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The only other candidate to file such papers is a Democrat,
former senator and basketball star Bill Bradley, who formed an
exploratory committee earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The filing is an important step for candidates who must begin
organizing at least by the early part of 1999 to successfully raise
funds, hire campaign consultants and build staffs in key states for
the next presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Some presidential candidates, in cluding Steve Forbes and Lamar
Alexander, who both ran unsuccess fully in 1996, already have
staffs in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans are waiting in the wings, including another
Arizo nan, former Vice President Dan Quayle, and Texas Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's early filing allows him to get a head start on the
early ``money primary,'' in which candi dates must raise about
$60,000 a day through 1999 to amass the war chest necessary to be
considered a serious contender in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman said McCain wants to determine whether he has the ability
to raise the massive sums necessary to launch a presidential
campaign, and to talk to Republicans in key early primary states to
see whether his maverick conservative message will sell in other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman said McCain also must come to a decision with his wife,
Cindy, and his family.
</P>
<P>
   He said McCain will make a formal announcement of his inten
tions in four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rudman and others said McCain, 62, is well-positioned be
cause he has ridden a wave of favorable national publicity over his
role as GOP maverick in fights to pass campaign-finance reform and
to pass a national tobacco settle ment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's truly anti-establishment . . . yet down deep he's a
Reagan Republican,'' Rudman said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also well-known as a Vietname war hero, having served
5 1/2 years as a prisoner of war after his plane was shot down over
Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   He has more than $2 million left over from this year's
re-election campaign that he can use as seed money for his
exploratory cam paign.
</P>
<P>
   The latest campaign finance re ports show McCain continued
amassing funds even after it became apparent his Democrat opponent,
Ed Ranger, would have no chance of unseating the two-term senator.
Mc Cain raised nearly $100,000 after Election Day, the reports
show.
</P>
<P>
   They also show McCain has built a national fund-raising network
that could form the backbone of a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also has formed a politi cally potent circle of advisers,
including Rudman, who served on the Senate Ethics Committee during
the ``Keating Five'' hearings.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was given a mild rebuke for his role in the affair _ in
which he and four other senators were accused of intervening with
federal regulators on behalf of savings and loan kingpin Charles
Keating Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman's presence on McCain's exploratory committee could defuse
the issue in a presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was purely political. John did nothing wrong,'' Rudman said
of McCain's appearance before the committee in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman also could open doors for McCain in New Hampshire, a key
early primary state.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Arizona Republican Sen. Jon Kyl is co-chair of the commit
tee.
</P>
<P>
   Several former Reagan staffers also are advising McCain,
including former chief of staff Ken Duberstein and adviser Michael
Deaver.
</P>
<P>
   Also, McCain has begun putting together a campaign staff that
could form the backbone of a solid presidential campaign. It
includes national GOP pollster Bill MacIn turff, national
fund-raising consult ant Carla Eudy and Opinsky, who served on
Texas Sen. Phil Gramm's failed 1986 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rudman said McCain has re ceived ``significant encouragment'' to
enter the 2000 campaign from a wide array of people, including many
who have offered to provide financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain has acknowledged a legendary distaste for raising cam
paign cash. ``There's a lot of other things I'd rather do _ like
bang my head up against the wall,'' he told The Republic last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Opinsky said McCain's national stature could make it easier to
raise campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are factors in volved which make him a known
commodity that alleviate some of that fund-raising crunch,''
Opinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Opinsky said McCain has re ceived a strong response so far in
national fund-raising circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very compelling figure. There is still a large portion
of Americans who do not know John McCain, but those that do are
very impressed by him and excited by him as a presidential
candidate,'' Opinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy &LR; pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
