   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-STATISTICS (Washington) _ Government data provide the
first gauge of how welfare around the nation has been affected by
the 1996 welfare overhaul law, which gave states lump sums of
federal money and vast new authority to run their own programs. By
Robert Pear. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.) With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-DEFECTORS (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ A top leader of the
Khmer Rouge mutters an apology, saying he is ``sorry, very sorry''
for the suffering he caused the Cambodian people. But the leader,
Khieu Samphan, repeatedly urges Cambodians and foreigners to ``let
bygones be bygones'' regarding the deaths of more than a million
people between 1975 and 1979, when the Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia
and he was head of state. By Seth Mydans. (The story has moved in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Story runs under 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-SOUTH (Ty, Ty, Georgia) _ In last month's election, Rep.
Sanford D. Bishop Jr., a moderate black Democrat, won re-election
convincingly in a rural, conservative district where nearly
two-thirds of the voters are white. Many black politicians have
managed to attract white support in urban, New South areas like
Atlanta. But Bishop's electoral success demonstrates that even in
the most rural and impoverished districts, a significant number of
white Southerners no longer view race as an absolute obstacle to
voting for a black politician who shares their thinking, votes
their interests and hauls home plenty of pork. By Kevin Sack. (The
story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 2,400 words.
</P>
