<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-AUS-SUGAR-COX     12-29 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUS-SUGAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Aggies head for Sugar Bowl
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They were a self-described ``bunch of old
country boys,'' those fightin' Texas Aggies from towns like Freer
and Brownwood, Hillsboro and Kerrville, who took New Orleans'
bright lights and big-city ways by storm 59 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Friday's Sugar Bowl game with Ohio State, the last time
Texas A&AMP;M went bowling in the Big Easy was on Jan. 1, 1940. The
stakes were higher that day, albeit less publicized. The Aggies
held off hometown favorite Tulane 14-13 before a record-setting
crowd of 73,000 in Tulane's own stadium to win A&AMP;M's first and only
national football championship.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, that's a big deal. But on the second day of 1940,
the Aggies learned of their accomplishment while riding the train
back to College Station after a robust night in the French Quarter
celebrating primarily an undefeated (11-0) 1939 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the sports publicity guys who traveled with us came
back through the train and said, 'Hey, did you know you're the
national champions?' `` recalled Howard Shelton, a reserve lineman
and unofficial team historian. ``We said, 'Oh, really? What's that
mean?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite an ending for some pretty illustrious careers for
some of our guys, but there was not all the hullabaloo that you
have now. There wasn't a ceremony or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was _ almost 59 years after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred this past Oct. 10 when surviving members of the 1939
team and family members of deceased players finally received rings
commemorating their championship season. Twenty-four of the 66
members of the team are still living, and 19 attended the ceremony
held in conjunction with A&AMP;M's upset of second-ranked Nebraska. The
men are in their late 70s and early 80s now, but have vivid
memories of their date in the Sugar Bowl and appreciation for the
day in their honor in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the greatest days of my life,'' said Austinite
Harold Cowley, a sophomore end in 1939 whose biggest athletic
moment would come later when he caught a 12-yard touchdown pass
against Alabama in the 1942 Cotton Bowl. ``It was nice to be
recognized like that and get those rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, much has changed since Jan. 1, 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane's on-campus stadium, which had been enlarged shortly
before the game with A&AMP;M to accomodate the largest crowd ever to
see a football game in the south at that time, was razed after the
1974 season, replaced by student housing and a parking garage. The
Sugar Bowl now is played in the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelt Hotel on Baronne Street, where the Aggies returned
after the game still in their uniforms, is now the Fairmont. One
thing hasn't changed, however. Swank Antoine's restaurant, where
the team gathered for a post-game victory meal, is still a major
attraction in the French Quarter and source of several humorous
Aggie memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had about seven or eight forks or spoons in front of us,
and we had no idea which one to use,'' said Roy Bucek, a lineman
and all-American hurdler in track who still lives in his hometown
of Schulenberg. ``We were all just poor, country boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Wimberly's Jim Thomason, a two-time all-Southwest
Conference halfback from Hillsboro: ``There were about 14 courses
and they gave you a little Schnapps or something between them.
After about the third one, you didn't care if you ate anything or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies, who had spent the week before the game training in
seclusion on the Mississippi coast near Biloxi, felt they had the
right to do a little celebrating after completing only the third
undefeated, untied season in their history. The victory over Tulane
was just the second bowl appearance by the Ags _ A&AMP;M defeated
previously unbeaten Centre College 22-14 in the 1922 Dixie Classic
in Dallas that gave birth to the 12th Man legend _ and the Green
Wave represented one of the toughest challenges faced that season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Homer Norton's Aggies trailed Tulane 13-7 in the fourth
quarter. But All-American running back ``Jarrin''' John Kimbrough _
``the bull-shouldered . . . sturdy son of the Texas cow country,''
according to wire reports of the game _ gained 24 of his 159
rushing yards on his second touchdown run of the game to tie the
score. Then Thomason held for Cotton Price's game-winning
extra-point kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, we were glad to get that game over with,''
said Thomason, primarily a blocking back for Kimbrough but who went
on to earn All-American honors of his own in 1940. ``That was the
toughest game we'd ever played in. We were hurting all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason was that unlike a few exceptions today,
players played both offense and defense. ``After a game, you felt
like you'd been run over by a Mack truck,'' said Charles Henke, who
owns a ranch between Fredericksburg and Kerrville.
</P>
<P>
   Henke, who attended Tivy High School in Kerrville, said the
Aggies were optimistic entering the 1939 season despite compiling
only a 4-4-1 mark the previous year. A&AMP;M relied primarily on a
tenacious defense that still holds the school record for fewest
average yards allowed per game (76.3).
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M recorded six shutouts that season. Its closest shaves,
besides the Sugar Bowl, came at Santa Clara (7-3) and in the mud at
College Station in a 6-2 verdict over Southern Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't realize what we were doing,'' Henke said. ``But we
kind of got a little cocky after awhile. We felt we might be pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of the championship team were juniors and returned
the next season to post a 9-1 record and a 13-12 victory over
Fordham in the Cotton Bowl. A&AMP;M's only loss was 7-0 at Texas, but
the Aggies also posted a 7-0 victory on the road against a UCLA
team led by Jackie Robinson, the first black player they had faced
in those days of segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous players from the '39 team fought in World War II _ ``I
got my diploma in one hand and orders to report to Camp Wolters in
Mineral Wells in the other,'' said Henke, who fought in North
Africa and Italy _ and some never made it home. James ``Cotton''
Williams died in Europe on June 19, 1944, after being part of the
D-Day invasion. Derace ``Mose'' Moser and Herbie Smith both died in
1942 in separate crashes of their training planes .
</P>
<P>
   Thomason flew 65 combat missions in the Pacific as a B-25 pilot
before returning and playing one season with the Detroit Lions.
Bucek, an infantry captain, lost his left eye in the Battle of the
Bulge when struck by a piece of howitzer shrapnel that remains
lodged in his right cheek because surgery could cause facial
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football could be tough, but nothing was tougher than
combat,'' Bucek said. ``I'd never been through anything like that,
and never want to be again.''
</P>
<P>
   Surviving members of the team still gather frequently and have
started holding annual reunions _ ``We're the 'meetingest' bunch
I've ever seen,'' Bucek said. Shelton, a retired bank president in
Fort Worth who attended Hillsboro High, is responsible for
organizing the gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fellows seem to enjoy getting back together,'' said
Shelton. ``It's a good group of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, 80, plans to attend this year's Sugar Bowl because one
of his two daughters, both of whom, ironically, graduated from
Tulane, lives in New Orleans and bought tickets to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really too bad that we're not playing Tulane again,'' he
said. ``It could have been the rematch.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Riggs writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
