<SLUG> BC-LCRA-FLOOD-GAUGE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rainfall observers help gather rainfall totals
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Long before technology could monitor floods from
several hundred miles away, a crew of country folks kept an eye on
the Central Texas weather, warning their downstream neighbors when
the rain turned deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Rahe was one of the first to sign up, receiving a metal
rainfall collector in 1939 and instructions to telegraph if floods
knocked out the phones in his hometown of Harper, about 90 miles
west of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 60 years later, Rahe's rainfall collector is still in the
family.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie L. Rahe, his daughter-in-law, has kept the gauge since
1974, a year after Otto's death. Reluctant at first to assume the
family responsibility, Bonnie Rahe has faithfully recorded the
rainfall in her back yard for almost 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have to wade out there, but I can always get to it,''
said Rahe, 72. ``Though sometimes it's frozen up and I can't gauge
it. I have to bring it inside the house here and let it melt.''
</P>
<P>
   In this age of radio-operated river gauges, the information from
Rahe and about 100 other rainfall observers is no longer crucial to
the Lower Colorado River Authority. Still, every bit of data helps
during those first frantic hours as the LCRA struggles to determine
how bad a developing flood will be.
</P>
<P>
   Observers are supposed to call the LCRA when they receive two
inches of rain in 24 hours _ then call again for each additional
inch. Mostly, however, observers fill out a card and mail it at the
end of each month to help the LCRA develop precipitation standards
for different areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's about 100 to 105 I can count on for a card most
months,'' said George Fears, senior hydrology technician for the
LCRA.
</P>
<P>
   When Otto Rahe joined the LCRA's rainfall observers, he helped
form the first flood early-warning system on the Colorado River.
Most observers were ranchers and residents of small towns, and the
foremost job qualification was owning a telephone, said Tom
Donaldson, an LCRA hydrologist.
</P>
<P>
   It's never been glamorous work. Watching the weather often means
getting caught in it, and Bonnie Rahe has endured a few soggy
mornings in pursuit of her data.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it profitable work. Otto Rahe was promised $3.50 a year
and 50 cents for each telephone call to the LCRA. His
daughter-in-law can count on her annual check for $5 this January,
plus $2 per phone call.
</P>
<P>
   The pay is a bargain for the LCRA. Over the years, Bonnie Rahe
has been a dependable observer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been able to do it. I've been sick a time or two,
but it never did rain then, so it didn't matter,'' she said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rahe gauge is in a particularly important site in Harper, a
small town in Gillespie County between Fredericksburg and Junction
Harper sits at the head of the Pedernales River, a flood-prone
waterway that empties into Lake Travis.
</P>
<P>
   Rahe, however, may be the last in her family to carry on the
tradition. ``There's no more family here in town,'' she said. ``And
they'll want someone here in town, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lindell writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
