<HEADLINE>
BOEING REACHES GOAL OF DELIVERING 550 PLANES BY YEAR'S END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE   
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After a miserable year marked by production troubles,
poor financial performance and a top management shakeup of its
commercial airplane business, The Boeing Co. finally came through
on a key promise and goal _ to deliver 550 airplanes by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement will be made Wednesday, followed by a
ceremony at the company's delivery center at Boeing Field.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing source said the 550th plane was delivered Tuesday, with
two days still left in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically, this goal was very important for Boeing,''
said aerospace analyst Paul Nisbet of JSA Research. ``It won't do
anything to improve earnings, but the company said it would do
something and they did it. That's not been the case recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was able to reach its goal by significantly reducing the
number of airplanes in desert storage. As of Sept. 30, the end of
the third quarter, Boeing had 36 undelivered planes in the desert,
which was up from 20 in storage at the end of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Undelivered planes are flown to airfields in the deserts of
California and Arizona for storage because the weather is ideal and
they will not deteriorate. Many of the 36 Boeing aircraft in desert
storage as of Sept. 30 were meant for Asian customers who could no
longer afford them, or no longer wanted them as fleets are reduced.
Boeing had to find new homes for those planes in order to meet its
year-end delivery goal.
</P>
<P>
   It did. Fewer than 10 airplanes will be sitting in the desert by
the end of the year, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people thought they would be able to find new owners
for those 36 airplanes,'' Nisbet said. ``It looked like a very
difficult task.''
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet credited Alan Mulally, Boeing's new commercial boss, for
making sure Boeing did not come up short of its delivery goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally replaced Ron Woodard, who was fired as head of the
commercial business at the end of August. Despite one of the
industry's biggest boom cycles ever, Boeing lost money for the
first time in a half century in 1997 and its production lines were
a mess as it attempted to crank up production to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered 374 planes last year.
</P>
<P>
   In order to reach its goal of delivering 550 planes this year,
Boeing had to deliver a record 182 planes in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Getting those final 182 planes out the factory door was so
critical that Mulally delayed from Nov. 2 until March the next
phase of Boeing's billion-dollar production overhaul that is
intended to improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally wanted Boeing workers to focus exclusively on getting
airplanes delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not want to miss that delivery goal, and it's great
that he didn't,'' Nisbet said of Mulally.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Boeing reached its delivery goal for 1998, an
indication that the company's production difficulties may be over,
Boeing must still improve its financial performance, Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those 550 planes were delivered with no profit,'' Nisbet said.
``If there is a pleasant surprise to the contrary, then I'd be
surprised. But the important thing is they did what they promised
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulally said last week that Boeing still plans to produce a
record 620 airplanes in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing now faces an economic industry downturn. The company
plans to slash its work force by 48,000 over the next two years.
Many of those job losses will come from its commercial business in
the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has told industry analysts it will take a couple
of years before its commercial airplane profit margins improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, Mulally can pull a rabbit out of his hat and make
that happen more quickly,'' Nisbet said.
</P>
</TEXT>
