<HEADER>
A0898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LCRA-FLOOD-GAUGE-     12-29 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LCRA-FLOOD-GAUGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LCRA will spend $7.2 million for early flood warning gauges
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Flash floods can rip 60-foot trees out of the
ground, turn boulders into battering rams and scrape homes off
their foundations, scattering tornado-like devastation over dozens
of square miles.
</P>
<P>
   And no place in the United States is more prone to flash floods
than the Hill Country west of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Starting around Junction, about 140 miles west of Austin, water
quickly collects into the Llano River and tumbles toward the
Colorado River, reaching speeds up to 20 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's always hanging over our heads here,'' said Tom
Donaldson, a Lower Colorado River Authority hydrologist. ``In the
Hill Country, everything can happen so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   With only hours to warn the growing number of people living
along the rivers and lakes of Central Texas, including Lake Travis,
the LCRA is taking steps to improve its weather eyes and ears.
Beginning in January, the river authority will begin a $7.2 million
program to more than double the number of rainfall monitors and
flood gauges on rivers and creeks.
</P>
<P>
   The extra data won't change how the LCRA opens and closes
floodgates on its dams; that will still depend on federal rules
that weigh rising lake elevations against the risk of downstream
flooding. The goal is faster, better information so flood-plain
residents can flee a deluge or prepare their homes for minor
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lead time is always nice,'' said Wes Birdwell, hydrology
manager for the LCRA. ``It's not going to change the number of
people who get flooded,'' but it could save lives, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The LCRA estimates 30,000 houses are within 500 feet of the six
Highland Lakes: Buchanan, Inks, LBJ, Marble Falls, Travis and
Austin. Most of those homes were built in the past 20 years, and
many are in the flood plains, putting thousands of families at
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of development on this river and around these
lakes. A lot of lives get interrupted,'' Birdwell said. ``When
there were just a few fishing cabins on Lake Travis, who cared how
far the lake came up?''
</P>
<P>
   The LCRA has 75 gauges already in place. Over the next five
years, 80 new rain gauges will be installed to measure how much
water to expect in nearby rivers and creeks. Another 21 river
gauges will verify those projections, providing better information
about how high water will rise in lakes and rivers downstream.
</P>
<P>
   A second phase envisions 40 more gauges that will fill any gaps
found after the first round of construction. The cost of phase two
has not been determined, said Ann Boulden, project manager.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the gauges will be upstream of Austin in
the Hill Country, rated by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers as
having, along with portions of Southern California and northwest
Arizona, the highest potential for flash flooding in the nation
</P>
<P>
   The first $4.5 million for the expanded system was allocated in
June, well before this fall's flooding reinforced the grave need
for better information.
</P>
<P>
   Rainfall in the Hill Country was minimal; most local flooding
occurred in a band from Austin and San Marcos to Seguin. But if the
October storm system had shifted 85 miles to the northwest, the
results would have been devastating, LCRA estimates show.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Travis would have risen at least 50 feet, and Town Lake
could have surged over the bridges at Lamar Boulevard, South First
Street and Congress Avenue in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In Bastrop, the Colorado River would have crested 25 feet higher
than during the October floods, likely flooding the downtown. Lake
LBJ would have received three times more water than during June
1997, the worst flood in the lake's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that (damage estimate) _ it scared the hell out of me,''
Donaldson said. ``It still gives me chills, just thinking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Highland Lakes have survived other close calls, including
the remnants of Tropical Storm Charley, which missed the Colorado
River basin by 20 miles and produced floods that killed ninein Del
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, it's only a matter of time before a catastrophic
flood hits the Hill Country. When it happens, the first line of
defense will be the Hydromet, the LCRA's system of river and
rainfall gauges. The oldest gauges were installed in the early
1980s, and all 75 of the current gauges were replaced or modernized
by early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded Hydromet, covering a much wider territory, will add
80 weather sites and 21 gauges to measure how much water is flowing
in rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the weather sites will measure only rainfall and
temperature and cost $15,000 apiece. The rest also will measure
humidity, wind speed, solar radiation and evaporation and will cost
$20,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   River gauges cost $25,000 and use a deceptively simple way to
measure water depth _ blowing bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   A thick, flexible tube is attached to a fixed point underwater,
usually on a concrete pier that supports a bridge. Deeper water
puts greater pressure on the nozzle, making it harder to push
bubbles through the tube. Measuring the subtle change provides an
accurate count of the water's depth, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   A 2-foot-by-3-foot box, usually fixed to the bridge above street
level, contains the river gauge equipment and antennas.
</P>
<P>
   River gauges use electricity, but most weather sites use solar
power because of their remote locations. All sites can operate for
two to three days on rechargeable batteries, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   Data is transmitted on the LCRA's 900-megahertz radio system.
``Anytime we want data, we can go get it,'' Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   Information also can be sent by telephone or radio as a backup.
As a last resort, particularly if flood debris damages a river
gauge, the LCRA sends employees to make visual reports.
</P>
<P>
   No LCRA gauges were damaged in the October floods, but water
reached the bottom of two equipment boxes. Both have been moved to
higher ground, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lindell writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
