<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ENTREPRENEURS PACKAGE &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FINANCE &LR;  _ David Pruitt thought he had a great idea for a new
company when he and Beverly Stewart started 5 Star Medical Inc.
four years ago to make minimally invasive surgery even less
invasive with their skinny fiber-optic endoscopes.
</P>
<P>
   But launching the Hayward company has taken a lot longer, and a
lot more money than Pruitt and Stewart, now his wife, ever
imagined. Like many budding entrepreneurs, they were short on
capital and experience in starting a business but long on
expectations. By Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW &LR;  _ Peter Sinton's small business column.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0903 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-SFCHRON &LR;      12-29 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Snaring Startup Capital  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Pruitt thought he had a great idea for a new company when he
and Beverly Stewart started 5 Star Medical Inc. four years ago to
make minimally invasive surgery even less invasive with their
skinny fiber-optic endoscopes.
</P>
<P>
   But launching the Hayward company has taken a lot longer, and a
lot more money than Pruitt and Stewart, now his wife, ever
imagined. Like many budding entrepreneurs, they were short on
capital and experience in starting a business but long on
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart sold her house and other property to finance the
business. It also took much longer than the expected six months to
design his medical device. And Pruitt now figures it will take
about 10 times his initial $100,000 estimate to make it a
commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Pruitt, 59, who spent most of his career
selling other manufacturers' medical products, has learned some
important lessons. These include turning to experts, developing a
financial plan early and being willing to swap a big chunk of the
company for outside capital.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Pruitt called the Corporation for Manufacturing
Excellence (Manex), a Fremont nonprofit organization that counsels
small manufacturers on how to grow their businesses. For a deferred
consulting fee, Manex helped 5 Star prepare documents required by
prospective investors and even walked Pruitt through the process of
making a proper business presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many cash-starved startups, 5 Star Medical has a
promising product line and sales of about $250,000 a year. One of
its endoscopes, with a catheter as slim as a pencil lead, has been
bought by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration to peer
into turbine assemblies and by university veterinary researchers to
gaze into cat bladders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Despite making five or six endoscopes a month, the company is
still losing money. To become a commercial success, Pruitt figures
he needs to invest heavily in product development and marketing. He
hopes to land $750,000 from a private investor in the next few
weeks and is ready to give up 25 percent or more of the company to
get it.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Planning
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs need to go after capital the way they go after
customers, advises Manex Vice President Robert Johnson. ``They need
a plan,'' he says. ``What usually happens is they go through their
personal cash, their credit cards and friends and family and then
they raise their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Manex, which is subsidized by federal and state agencies,
counsels small manufacturers on production techniques, technology
applications and business practices, including raising capital.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs with a pedigree and a track record who seek $4
million or $40 million may have a good chance tapping a venture
capital fund, which funnels pension and other institutional money
into promising startups. ``But we're usually not dealing with
companies that fit the requirements of &UR;  &LR; venture capitalists on
Sandhill Road,'' says Johnson. ``If you're looking for $250,000 to
$1 million, then creativity comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you can expect anyone else to invest in your dream, you
better demonstrate your own commitment by putting yourself at risk,
advises David Evanson, author of ``Where to go When the Bank Says
No,'' (Bloomberg Press, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   That means borrowing against your savings, your credit cards,
your mortgage or even your 401(k) retirement plan. You might also
go to family and friends before hitting up strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical entrepreneur often goes to the bank first, when
the better strategy is to look for equity financing,'' said
Evanson. ``Equity investors share in the growing value of the
company.'' In addition to venture capital and initial public
offerings, other sources of capital include wealthy private
investors, often called angels.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``knowing where to go is only part of the equation,''
says Evanson. ``Equally important is knowing how to effectively
approach a potential investor.'' That involves developing a
persuasive business plan and preparing credible historical and
projected financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses that don't want to give up a piece of the
ownership, can seek community loan development funds or, if they
have revenues, might use royalty or accounts receivable financing.
</P>
<P>
   Local Programs
</P>
<P>
   There are several Bay Area organizations that help entrepreneurs
plan their businesses and raise capital.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area Regional Technology alliance in Fremont helps young
companies develop new technology products and services and find
financial support. With BARTA's help, companies applying for
federal R&AMP;D funds can get additional matching grants from the
California Technology Investment Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, BARTA has backed about three dozen
Bay Area businesses and distributes about $2 million a year.
Executive Director Alexander Glass says only about one in four
applicants receive nonrefundable grants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Winners have included businesses striving to make new
therapeutic agents to treat rheumatoid arthritis, new types of flat
panel displays and a process for integrating solar cells in roofing
tiles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, BARTA operates in Northern California the Small
Business Administration's Angel Capital Electronic Network
(ACE-Net), which links entrepreneurial companies with potential
individual investors over the Internet. It is estimated that
250,000 angel investors in the United States currently pour more
than $20 billion a year into 30,000 ventures.
</P>
<P>
   BARTA also sponsors investor forums where companies present
their business plans to accredited investors. On February 10 and
11, for example, BARTA will co-sponsor a conference in San
Francisco spotlighting companies that develop environmental
technologies to reduce industrial waste, pollution and energy use.
</P>
<P>
   Another organization that helps local entrepreneurs is the
California Statewide Communities Development Authority. The Walnut
Creek state-supported agency has issued more than $6 billion in
tax-exempt financings since 1987 and has lent some of the money to
small manufacturing companies that can support debt service
payments despite having few assets.
</P>
<P>
   This year it lent about $15 million at attractive 5.5 percent to
6.75 percent interest rates to a dozen local companies for
equipment purchases. It also loans money at slightly higher rates
to select operating companies for land acquisition and building
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Lending Initiatives
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous for-profit organizations also trying to get
small businesses off the ground. One of the largest is the
California Economic Development Lending Initiative, which was
started in 1995 and is supported by 47 banks and other companies.
It loans from $50,000 to $250,000 from a $65 million pool to deal
with ``unmet credit needs, especially of minorities and women,''
says CEDLI President George Williamson.''
</P>
<P>
   One beneficiary is Everett &AMP; Jones Barbecue, which plans to open
in Oakland's Jack London Square in two weeks. The new restaurant
got a five-year loan of $150,000 from CEDLI and another $150,000
from the California Career Bank in Los Angeles for 10 percent
annual interest. ``In addition to being really helpful with
financing,'' says restaurant President Dorothy King, ``they
provided construction management to work with us.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of Internet sites help small businesses check
out financial alternatives or even get a loan. GetSmart, a
2-year-old Burlingame company, expanded last summer its online
offerings from consumer borrowing to small-business lending
options.
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 million businesses in the United States with $250
billion in outstanding loans, so it's a big market, according to
GetSmart. ``The average small business typically takes three months
to find financing that meets their needs,'' said CEO Bill Fisher.
``We can find them an ideal match in minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Small-business owners who provide information about their
business, credit history and financing preferences _ such as
conventional bank loan, equipment loan, accounts receivable
financing or corporate credit card _ get matches with potential
lenders, but not loan guarantees. The Web site is
 &LR; www.getsmart.com &LR;  and the company's investors include Reuters,
Goldman Sachs and Robertson Stephens Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
