<SLUG> BC-FREQUENT-FLIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE MOST FROM THOSE BONUS MILES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If it's free, there must be a catch.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the watchwords for U.S. airlines' frequent flier
programs, undeniably the most successful marketing scheme on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone who has ever tried to redeem mileage for a free seat
can tell you, there are two major problems _ free seats are usually
unavailable for when you most want to fly and keeping track of the
rules can be mind-numbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't keep up with all that's being offered,'' said
Steven Peterson, president of the Travelware service for monitoring
companies' frequent flier accounts. ``It takes a fair amount of
time to figure out and you can wind up being on hold with the
airline for 30 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, plenty of people are willing to do just that. An
estimated 75 million people worldwide belong to some kind of
frequent flier program; airlines generate an estimated $1.5 billion
annually from selling the miles to partners for 2 cents a mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines have realized that if they sell their miles in small
pieces, a lot of them are never used,'' Peterson noted. The money
that airlines receive from partners is more than enough to
administer programs that fill seats that otherwise would have gone
unused, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   The basic concept, launched in 1981 through American Airlines'
AAdvantage (cq) program, gives customers mileage credits tied to
spending on travel staples such as airline tickets, rental cars,
hotels and credit cards. The idea eventually created an entire
cottage industry.
</P>
<P>
   American, for example, offers mileage through five car rental
companies, two dozen hotel chains, real estate, FTD, MCI, Citibank,
AT&AMP;T, Jack Nicklaus/Golden Bear Golf Inc., Bull &AMP; Bear Securities,
along with programs for auto purchasing, dining and fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Promotions abound. Continental Airline's OnePass members can
earn 500 miles by completing a survey; Trans World Airlines'
Get-A-Member program gave miles for referrals; United Airlines
gives 5,000 Mileage Plus miles for California and Pennsylvania
residents who sign up for Green Mountain Energy Resources by Jan.
29.
</P>
<P>
   Even a second-tier flier like America West Airlines devotes 25
staff positions at its Phoenix headquarters to administering
FlightFund programs. ``We continually look at opportunities to
enhance partnerships,'' said spokeswoman Patty Nowack. ``All the
major airlines are pretty competitive in areas like hotels, car
rental, partnerships with other airlines, long-distance service and
flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   You generally need 25,000 miles to qualify for a free ticket.
Get enough miles _ say, half a million, worth $10,000 _ and you
could fly yourself and spouse or best friend around the world
first-class for free.
</P>
<P>
   Sound easy? Guess again.
</P>
<P>
   First, you're going to have to do most of the work yourself
unless you have an exceptionally good relationship with your travel
agent or travel office at work, since airlines don't pay
commissions to agents for flights booked with frequent flier
mileage. ``You might be able to get your agent to help if you give
them a lot of business,'' said Glendale-based agent Amy Bernard
Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Some simple steps:
</P>
<P>
   -- Focus on one or two programs, particularly if you're using
carriers in a frequent flier alliance: United-Delta,
Northwest-Continental or American-US Airways. ``Don't spread out
over multiple programs because it will take a lot longer for you to
reach award levels,'' said Jim Glab, contributing editor at
Frequent Flyer magazine.
</P>
<P>
   -- Once you decide which programs you're focusing on, learn all
the partners. Glab suggests using Web sites rather than waiting for
monthly or quarterly newsletters to stay updated on changes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Be aware of expiration dates, often Dec. 31 of each calendar
year. United, American and Northwest require miles to be used
within a defined period of time; Delta has no expiration but
requires you must fly at least once every three years.
</P>
<P>
   -- Be willing to be flexible, especially on popular routes and
during heavy travel periods. Airlines will be reluctant to give
away what they can sell, so be prepared to travel outside of summer
and during midweek. ``Don't be too rigid,'' Herman said. ``When you
call, have several date choices.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Offer to change planes rather than going nonstop. That may
mean several hours in Cleveland or Houston but remember, free is
free.
</P>
<P>
   -- Be willing to use a suburban airport, such as Ontario or
Burbank-Glendale-Pasadena, for domestic flights and a less popular
European one, like Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   -- Look for deals. Airlines starting to fly new routes or
offering deep discounts will likely to be trying to unload free
seats.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you fly a lot, use resources such as Web sites and
magazines like Frequent Flyer ($24 a year; (630) 574-6000) and
Inside Flyer ($36 a year; (719) 597-8880).
</P>
<P>
   -- Plan before you call. ``Figuring out partnerships and
blackout dates can be very difficult,'' Peterson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
