<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   11 EUROPEAN COUNTRIES PREPARE FOR ONE CURRENCY
</P>
<P>
   After decades of dreams, diplomacy and delays, the single
European currency, the euro, is close to becoming a reality. On
Thursday, 11 European countries are to lock their exchange rates to
the euro, now worth about $1.17, and cede to the new European
Central Bank the power to set interest rates and monetary policy.
The currency will officially be introduced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the euro is quickly catching on. At a supermarket
outside Strasbourg, a mecca for cross-border shoppers, everything
from bananas to televisions has been priced in euros, and French
francs, for months. At upscale restaurants, euro-pricing on menus
is a fashion must. In Paris, 11 giant balloons representing the
participating countries are on display outside the headquarters of
Paribas, the financial-services giant.
</P>
<P>
   MOST STATES MEETING WELFARE RULES
</P>
<P>
   The first official data from the federal government show that
most states are meeting the work requirements of the 1996 welfare
law, with 28 percent of adults on the rolls participating in some
type of work activity, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE MORTGAGE RATES RISE
</P>
<P>
   Five major Japanese banks said they would raise mortgage rates
by as much as 0.8 percent, the first sign that soaring interest
rates will squeeze the already embattled Japanese consumer. A sixth
bank had already raised its rates.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA TO GET $1.35 BILLION LOAN
</P>
<P>
   Twelve foreign banks said they had agreed to lend Malaysia $1.35
billion at an interest rate substantially below what the government
would have to pay to raise much-needed cash on the international
bond market.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG AUCTION LIFTS BOND PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rose for a second day after the Treasury encountered
stronger-than-expected demand at its auction of $15 billion in
two-year notes. The yield on the benchmark 30-year Treasury fell to
5.09 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BP EXPECTS APPROVAL OF DEAL
</P>
<P>
   British Petroleum expects its $48.2 billion acquisition of Amoco
to clear the last remaining hurdle and secure federal regulatory
approval before the weekend, a spokesman said. The Federal Trade
Commission would only say that it was reviewing the merger.
</P>
<P>
   BIG BRITISH COMPANY SEEKS MERGER
</P>
<P>
   General Electric Co. PLC of Britain said it was looking at
Lockheed Martin, Northrop Grumman, Thomson-CSF of France and
British Aerospace as possible merger partners. The British company,
unrelated to General Electric of the United States, said no deal
would be announced before the new year.
</P>
<P>
   HOME SALES ROSE 2.7 PERCENT IN NOVEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Sales of existing homes rose in November to their
second-strongest rate ever, energized by optimistic consumers, low
mortgage rates and job gains. The National Association of Realtors
said that sales of existing homes increased 2.7 percent last month,
to an annual rate of 4.90 million units, close to the record pace
of 4.91 million units in July. For all of 1998, the association
expects sales of existing homes to set an annual record for the
third consecutive year.
</P>
</TEXT>
