<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-BOWL-DEFENSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big defenses go head-to-head in the Big Easy
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Their defenses are each dominant enough to have
earned their own nicknames: ``The Wrecking Crew'' of Texas A&AMP;M and
the ``Silver Bullets'' of Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Each features a star linebacker in Aggie senior Dat Nguyen, this
year's Lombardi Award winner, and Buckeye junior Andy Katzenmoyer,
the 1997 Butkus Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   And each defense, ranked in the top 10 nationally, relies on
quickness and pressure to force the opposing offense out of its
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in philosophy, we're a lot the same,'' Texas A&AMP;M head
coach R.C. Slocum said. ``Ohio State looks to pressure you in
passing situations and we like to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The big difference may be in the teams' secondary, with the edge
going to OSU.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's highly touted secondary, led by consensus
All-American and Thorpe Award winner Antoine Winfield, is second in
the nation vs. the pass and allowed just seven touchdown passes all
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Ohio State's secondary, there's no weakness in
it,'' A&AMP;M offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe said. ``I think
(OSU defensive coordinator) Fred (Pagac) does a great job with the
zone blitzes, kind of the in-vogue thing in the National Football
League right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies 10th-ranked overall defense likes to pressure the
opposing quarterback as much as possible, too. One way they try to
do it is by rotating their defensive linemen to keep them rested
and fresh. Ohio State began doing the same thing this season after
its starters wore down in last season's Sugar Bowl loss to Florida
State.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said he's been pleasantly surprised by his young and
undersized defensive line. (His three starters are sophomores and
two of his three backups, freshman.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big concern at the start of the season,'' he said of
his line. ``As the season progressed, it's really not been.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's defensive line has matured as the season has
progressed as well. Sophomore end Brent Johnson, slated as a back
up to junior James Cotton in spring practice, moved into a
starter's spot almost immediately and led the team in sacks with
seven.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore linebacker Na'il Diggs, too, has become a standout
member of the Buckeyes' second-ranked defense, finishing the
regular season second in team tackles with 74.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' Slocum insists his team is without a true star. But
Nguyen (pronounced Win) has played like one. He leads the team in
tackles with 147 and is the heart and soul of the Aggies defense.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum is concerned Nguyen's sprained big toe could hamper his
quickness and side-to-side mobility, skills the 5-11 linebacker
relies on to compensate for his lack of size. But Nguyen said he'll
be ready to play as he always does.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, OSU's Big Kat will be ready to pounce on an Aggie who
tries to run up the middle. The Buckeyes are the No. 1 defense in
the nation against the run, giving up fewer than 68 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find a weakness in their defense,'' A&AMP;M
quarterback Branndon Stewart said. ``I think their secondary will
be the best we've played.'
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
