<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How Giving Can Mean Tax Break  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; QUESTION: &LR;  Can I deduct the cost of holiday gifts from my company's
taxable income?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANSWER: &LR;  They say it's better to give than receive. But it's
even better if you can display the holiday spirit and get a tax
break at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Internal Revenue Service, you can deduct up to
$25 for business gifts to any one person during your tax year. (See
``Tax info for business'' at  &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   If you give gifts to members of a customer's family, you also
will be limited to the single $25 deductible limit unless you have
a bona fide, business connection with each family member and the
gift is intended for that person's use.
</P>
<P>
   If you and your spouse give gifts, don't expect to double your
deductions, even if you have separate businesses or independent
connections with the recipient. The IRS treats both of you as one
taxpayer. Similarly, if a partnership gives gifts, the partnership
and the partners are treated as one taxpayer and cannot deduct more
than $25 per recipient.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate how this works, if you give three $80 cheese
baskets to a company in thanks for its business and three
executives take the packages home to their families (with whom you
have no business relationships), you can deduct only $75 of your
$240 cost. (That deduction is arrived at by multiplying the three
gifts times the $25 limit.)
</P>
<P>
   Incidental costs such as packaging, insurance and mailing
generally are not included in the $25 per recipient annual limit.
But make sure the costs really are incidental.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if the value of the basket in the above example is
``substantial'' compared to the value of the cheese, you can't add
it to the $25 limit.
</P>
<P>
   Items that might be considered either a gift or entertainment
expenses generally are considered an entertainment expense by the
IRS. But if you give customers packaged food or beverages intended
for their use at a later date, treat it as a gift expense.
</P>
<P>
   Not included in the $25 limit are items costing $4 or less (like
pens) that are identical and widely distributed and have your name
clearly and permanently imprinted on them.
</P>
<P>
   Home Office Write-Offs
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I deduct business expenses such as phone bills, electric
bills and rent from my home business even though I didn't have any
income from the business this year. If yes, is there a limit on
such deductions?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you have a separate phone line for your business, you can
deduct the entire expense, according to Mary Kay Foss of the
Danville accounting firm Marzluft Giles Tulis &AMP; Foss. If you use
your residential line, you can only deduct the cost of itemized
toll calls for business purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Phone bills, like office supplies and postage, are considered
direct business expenses. Electricity and other costs connected
with running your home office such as rent, real estate taxes,
insurance, casualty losses, depreciation, painting and repairs are
considered indirect expenses and you cannot deduct these unless you
show a profit. However you can carry these costs over indefinitely
to future years when you have a profit to offset.
</P>
<P>
   However, before deducting any home office expenses, you must
meet rigid requirements. In general, you're out of luck if you use
a part of your home for both personal and business purposes. For
example, if you run your business out of your den during the day
and watch TV in the same room in the evening, you get no deduction.
There are exceptions if you are a qualified day care provider or
use a part of your house for storage of inventory or product
samples.
</P>
<P>
   According to Topic 509 on the IRS Web site, before you can
deduct business-use-of-the-home expenses, part of your home must be
used ``regularly and exclusively'' as your principal place of
business and the place where you meet and deal with your patients,
clients or customers ``in the normal course'' of your business.
</P>
<P>
   The amount deducted depends on the percentage of your home used
for business. To calculate this, divide the number of square feet
used for business by the total square feet in your home. Or, if the
rooms are about the same size, divide the number of rooms used for
business by the total number of rooms in your home.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on business use of your home, refer to Tax
Topic 509, or Publication 587, Business Use of Your Home. To order
publications and forms, call (800) 829-3676, or download them from
 &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
