<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Governor Declares State of Emergency Over Citrus Crisis  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Governor Pete Wilson declared a state of emergency yesterday in the
four California counties hardest hit by the freeze that chilled the
Central Valley's citrus industry.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson singled out Fresno, Kern, Tulare and Madera counties,
where four-straight nights of subfreezing weather has ruined all of
the lemon crop and a substantial but still undetermined portion of
the orange crop.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he also will ask President Clinton for federal
assistance for those counties, which have suffered an estimated
$591 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The damage done by the recent cold spell has been devastating
to California's orange, lemon and grapefruit crops,'' Wilson said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Because California accounts for about 80 percent of the oranges
eaten as fruit in the United States, the freeze will mean that
consumers across the nation will pay 40 to 50 percent more for
fresh table oranges during the first six months of 1999, a federal
Agriculture Department economist said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But the price of that morning glass of juice likely will remain
the same because the world still has ample supplies of juice
oranges, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if some are diverted to table oranges, it still wouldn't
affect the retail price of frozen concentrate,'' said Annette
Clauson, an agricultural economist with the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Price estimates still are fluid, but based on what's known about
California's crop damage so far, Clauson said the freeze will raise
table orange prices that averaged 62 cents to 64 cents per pound in
October and November.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies of oranges grown for juice in Florida and Brazil still
are strong enough to meet demand, said Bernard Savaiko, head of
futures research at PaineWebber Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brazilian crop looks better than first thought,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration of a state of emergency allows farmers, pickers,
packers and others out of work because of the freeze to begin
receiving up to 26 weeks of unemployment benefits without the
required one-week waiting period.
</P>
<P>
   After the more serious 1990 freeze, about 12,000 agricultural
workers were out of work for as much as a year and the state and
federal governments were slow to declare an emergency, said Joel
Nelsen, president of California Citrus Mutual, a growers trade
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people down here had to wait six months before
they saw any kind of relief,'' Nelsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Growers hope disaster relief enables them to get short-term
loans that will help keep some of the workers employed to repair
and prepare citrus groves for the next season's harvests.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to minimize the impact on local businesses built
around the citrus industry,'' Nelsen said. ``Maybe the wheels of
bureaucracy do move a little more rapidly now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, San Joaquin Valley growers have initiated a voluntary
moratorium on picking and packing any oranges until at least Monday
to give them more time to assess fruit damage. Growers who can't
wait may place a hold on the shipment of any oranges for three
days.
</P>
<P>
   The movement started in yesterday morning in Tulare County,
where some growers bitterly complained that some of their
counterparts were shipping freeze-damaged fruit to recoup losses
and take advantage of rising wholesale prices. But the citrus
association fears that shipping sour or decayed oranges will
literally leave a bad taste in consumers' mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure good fruit is reaching the marketplace,''
said Nelsen. ``This will allow additional hang time on the trees so
there are ample hours for the decay to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimism abounded earlier this week because growers were finding
more undamaged fruit on their trees than they expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that caused a false sense of security,'' Nelsen said.
``On one hand it looks good, but wiser heads are saying something's
not right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
