<SLUG> BC-MA-RAYTHEON-OSBORN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION LEADER TAKES MANAGEMENT JOB AT RAYTHEON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A top union leader has stepped down from his post respresenting
Raytheon Co. workers to take a management job at the Lexington,
Mass. defense contractor, surprising many former allies.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Osborn Jr. announced his resignation as president of
Local 1505 of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
earlier this month. He accepted a new job in Raytheon's personnel
office that begins in January.
</P>
<P>
   The move eliminates one of longer-serving officers of the local,
which represents several thousand employees and is one of the
state's more powerful labor group.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn faces some criticism for changing sides. ``Because he was
president and held other offices for so long, (some members) felt
that he was running out on them,'' said one union member who
attended a meeting in Waltham about ten days ago where the change
was announced. ``People were upset.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview Tuesday Osborne said the change wasn't
improper because he won't have a role in future negotiations. He
also noted the job he has accepted at Raytheon was previously
filled by other former union officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went as long as I could for as hard as I could'' for the
IBEW, Osborn said. He added he wasn't leaving because of any
disagreements over union business. ``I just decided to make a
change in my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn also resigned from the executive board of the state's
AFL-CIO, surprising colleagues at the group where his father,
Arthur Osborn Sr., was president throughout the 1980s. ``He's a
solid trade unionist, so in that sense (his departure) is
disppointing,'' said Bob Haynes, the organization's current
president.
</P>
<P>
   But Haynes defended Osborn's shift. ``It has become a great
strategy of the business community to take the best people from the
labor movement...and companies like Raytheon need the kind of
expertise that Arthur has. He can bring them some sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new job Osborne will help assure the company abides by
previous seniority agreements in its dealings with employees said
Raytheon spokesman Alan Csiky.
</P>
<P>
   During his eight-year tenure as second-in-command of the IBEW
local, Osborn ran the organization's internal operations and
participated in contract negotiations including a controversial
round in 1995. Then, the union agreed to wage concessions that
Raytheon executives said were needed to keep its missile plants in
the state competitive with firms in lower-cost states in the
Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal angered many rank-and-file members, who the next
year voted to oust many key union officers who involved in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn was a rare exception, keeping his job and continued to
serve under the union's new business manager, Michael Zagami. Other
IBEW members, who asked not to be named, said Zagami's popularity
had increased since a more generous contract was negotiated last
summer, and that Osborn probably wouldn't advance further within
the IBEW or the AFL-CIO. Moreover, changes promulgated by Zagami
meant the president's position was no longer a full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Arthur Osborn saw that this was it for him'' within
the local, one IBEW member said. Osborn said he didn't have major
differences with with Zagami or others but said he felt it was time
for a new president to step in.
</P>
<P>
   Zagami was travelling Tuesday and couldn't be reached for
comment. Other union officers declined to comment. As president,
Osborn has been replaced by Stanley Lichwala, an assistant business
manager, according to the local's site on the World Wide Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
