<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      12-29 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: DELTA'S BUSINESS ELITE CLASS; MARRIOTT IN MOSCOW;
FITNESS AT PENNSYLVANIA AIRPORTS; STARWOOD'S FREQUENT-GUEST
PROGRAM; DELAY IN IRS RULE CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (Eds: Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(lb) 
 By JANET PIORKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines' business class will be in a state of flux from
now until next summer on flights to Europe, Asia and Brazil as the
company phases in a new service called Business Elite.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing both first class and existing business class on those
routes, Business Elite is described as a premium service at
business-class fares. It will feature new sleeper seats with more
leg room than the old business class; the seats will have electric
controls for reclining and other adjustments, and personal video
screens. They will also have hookups for laptop computers, and no
passenger will be more than a seat away from an aisle.
</P>
<P>
   The airline is reconfiguring 57 planes and will also have the
new seating on 14 Boeing 777s scheduled for delivery starting in
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking customers to pardon our dust while we make the
conversion,'' said Katie Moussouri, a Delta spokeswoman. ``They may
have inconsistent experiences on Delta.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline stopped selling first-class tickets on the affected
routes this month, and passengers who buy business-class tickets
while the transition takes place may wind up in first-class seats,
in the old business-class seats, or in one of the reconfigured
cabins.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, cabin service will be the same as in Delta's old
business class until spring, when a new Business Elite meal service
will offer a choice of four entrees (including a vegetarian option)
and a self-service snacking station.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative to the gradual transition was to have 57 planes
on the ground being reconfigured simultaneously, Ms. Moussouri
said, adding: ``Our financial guys wouldn't let us do that. Our
customers wouldn't like it either. It would be a big change in our
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline decided to introduce the new service, which is
costing about $314 million, because of the larger size and faster
growth of the business-class market, compared with first class, Ms.
Moussouri said.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott in Moscow
</P>
<P>
   The 234-room Marriott Royal Hotel, set to open Jan. 12 with 234
rooms near the Bolshoi Theater in Moscow, will be the third in a
troika of Marriott hotels in the Russian capital. The others are
the 392-room Moscow Marriott Grand and the 162-room Marriott
Tverskaya. Operated by Interstate Hotels Corp., the three hotels
are owned by Mospromstroy, a Moscow construction company. Each
hotel has a health club, business center and meeting facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the outlook for luxury hotels in Moscow given
Russia's economic woes, Jeroen Gerrese, general manager of the
Marriott Royal, said: ``There is certainly room at the top in spite
of recessionary times. Business travel to Moscow still takes
place.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, ``We have our challenges, no question about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitness in Pennsylvania
</P>
<P>
   Airport Fitness, a Dayton, Ohio, company that operates a health
club in Pittsburgh International Airport, plans to open its second
club next year, in Philadelphia. The Pittsburgh club, beneath the
airport concourse, has treadmills, a Versaclimber, stair steppers,
rowers, bicycles and weight equipment. Single visits cost $11.25.
Michael Michno, the company's founder, said he hoped for an opening
in July at Philadelphia International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Rewards Revamped
</P>
<P>
   Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide will begin a new
frequent-guest program, called Starwood Preferred Guest, in
February. Members of Sheraton Club International and Westin Premier
programs, which the new program will replace, will automatically be
enrolled. (Starwood earlier this year acquired Westin Hotels and
ITT, the owner of Sheraton hotels and Caesars casinos.)
</P>
<P>
   The program will allow members to accumulate points and redeem
awards at more than 550 hotels around the world.
</P>
<P>
   IRS Delays Rule Change
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service has delayed its planned reduction
in the reimbursement rate for business driving, after objections
from several companies that wanted more time to convert computer
software.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction from the current rate of 32.5 cents a mile to 31
cents for employees who drive personal cars for work was scheduled
to take effect this Friday, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   But the IRS decided earlier this month to postpone the effective
date until April 1 to give businesses time to reprogram computers
and change employee manuals.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors are behind the proposed reduction: the falling price
of gasoline resulting from low inflation, and slow depreciation
rates for automobiles, which are holding their value longer, an IRS
spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
