<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-RULES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY IS MONEY-MAKING STUDIO SUPREME FOR 1998
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Mickey's got bragging rights for another year
as the king of Tinseltown.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an asteroid (``Armageddon''), a Chinese heroine
(``Mulan''), an unlikely football star (``The Waterboy'') and a
bunch of bugs (``A Bug's Life''), Walt Disney Co. will edge
Paramount by $18 million to become 1998's domestic box office
champ.
</P>
<P>
   The victory _ Disney's fourth in five years _ is sweet because
the entertainment giant did not move into first until last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a real `Rocky' story for us,'' said distribution
chief Phil Barlow. ``We had a hell of a comeback. We had four very
weak months at the start of the year with $90 million going into
May, but once we released `The Horse Whisperer,' we came on very
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney is expect to finish with $1.103 billion in gross domestic
receipts. Paramount's final total will be $1.085 billion, with
better than 40 percent of that coming from ``Titanic's'' 1998
grosses. That makes 1998 the only time two studios have topped $1
billion. Disney passed the mark in 1994, 1995 and 1996; Sony set
the record last year with $1.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A strong late-year performance by Disney is no surprise. It
usually weighs its schedule toward holiday periods when
family-oriented fare _ ``Toy Story,'' ``101 Dalmatians'' and
``Flubber'' in recent years _ reach the widest audience.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also credit Disney as a strong marketer. ``Disney is a
well-oiled machine with a lot of good product and huge
distribution,'' said Arthur Rockwell, a former studio executive.
``They're very disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the dozen 1998 films topping $100 million, four belonged to
Disney and two to Paramount (``The Truman Show,'' ``Deep Impact'').
``It's remarkable that two companies have done this much business
in a year,'' Barlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its four hit films, Disney generated respectable
performance from ``The Horse Whisperer,'' ``Six Days, Seven
Nights,'' ``The Parent Trap'' and ``Enemy of the State.'' The only
true disappointment for Disney came in October with the
back-to-back releases of a pair of pricey projects, ``Holy Man''
and ``Beloved,'' that performed very poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``Armageddon'' took in the highest gross, Disney's
most profitable movies were ``The Waterboy,'' which cost a mere $23
million to make, and ``A Bug's Life,'' with massive receipts from
foreign, video and toy licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which slumped slightly in 1997 with $880 million at the
box office, has maintained fairly consistent performances despite
limiting the number of releases each to year to around 18 in order
to control costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret is to have good moviemakers making entertaining
movies,'' Barlow said ``It would be even more enjoyable if
production and marketing costs weren't so high.''
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox will finish a distant third with more than $730
million, and Sony and Warner Bros. will each have about $700
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
