<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SALES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA'S REAL ESTATE MARKET UP ANOTHER NOTCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The median home price in the San Fernando Valley
rose 14.8 percent in November compared with the same month last
year, outpacing the county as a whole and highlighting both the
robust economy and tight housing market, according to statistics
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the California Association of Realtors, homes in
the Valley sold during the month for a median price of $178,000, up
from $155,000 in November 1997 and a $10,000 jump from October's
price.
</P>
<P>
   The median price is the point at which half the homes sell for
more and half sell for less.
</P>
<P>
   The area still is being squeezed by the lack of existing homes
and condos for sale, which is driving the median price up, said
Leslie Appleton-Young, the chief economist for the statewide
association.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there has been a rebound in consumer confidence, and
the creation of new jobs and income growth _ both marks of the
area's healthy economy _ are being reflected in the local housing
market, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year when we saw the heart of the California
housing market recovery move from the Bay Area down to Los Angeles
County,'' she said. ``It's kind of running its course in a
reasonable way.''
</P>
<P>
   The median home price in Los Angeles County rose 8.4 percent to
$173,500 from last year's $160,000. The market in neighboring
Ventura County also showed signs of health, with an 8.2 percent
jump to a median of $210,000 from $194,000.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 1998 is turning out to have the strongest housing market
the state has seen in the past 20 years, Appleton-Young said.
</P>
<P>
   But the association expects an 8 percent drop in sales and a 4
percent jump in the median home price in 1999, in part because the
economy will show signs of slowing as the manufacturing sector
feels the effects of a decline in demand for exports.
</P>
<P>
   Even taking that into consideration, however, next year still
should be the fourth strongest market the state has seen in those
20 years, Appleton-Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's all relative,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
