<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER FAVORS SOWARD RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ The father of USC junior wide receiver R. Jay Soward
said Tuesday that he is leaning toward telling his son to return
for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Soward said he will not pressure his son to bypass the
NFL Draft and return to USC, but is currently inclined to advise
him to come back because R. Jay Soward shares those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to decide, not me,'' Rodney Soward said. ``But I know
what's best for him. We're interested in him being a productive
individual, not just to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   After consulting with everyone from NFL scouts to agents, Rodney
Soward said he was assured his son would be a first-round draft
choice if he makes himself available for the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't mean anything to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Soward said he planned to hold meetings next week with
some of those same people he consulted, but might cancel them if
his son decides to return to USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just might have to meet with Coach (Paul) Hackett,'' Rodney
Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   Soward did add that no final decision has been made regarding
his son's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he says he wants to go, that's another situation,'' Rodney
Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   Good as gone: The Trojans' chances of retaining linebacker Chris
Claiborne are not nearly as good. After an observer told Claiborne
he would miss him after Thursday's game against Texas Christian in
the Sun Bowl, Claiborne just smiled and nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Hackett said defensive tackle Aaron Williams
(sprained ankle) was sore Tuesday and remains limited. Linebacker
David Gibson and tailback Chad Morton, who also have sprained
ankles, have improved enough that Hackett said both will probably
start.
</P>
<P>
   Huge favorite: Hackett is astonished that the Trojans remain
16-point favorites for the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine a team as young as ours being in a position
to be that kind of favorite,'' Hackett said. ``We remember the Cal
game.''
</P>
<P>
   USC led Cal 31-10 before losing 32-31.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales: About 38,000 tickets have been sold for the game
at the 51,171-seat Sun Bowl. The last time USC played in the
contest, in 1990 against Michigan State, the game drew 50,562, the
second-largest crowd in Sun Bowl history.
</P>
<P>
   USC has sold more than 1,500 tickets while TCU has sold more
than 4,000 for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the turf: USC returned to the Sun Bowl on Tuesday
because Hackett wanted an extra practice on the artificial surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we came here because a lot of things are different
(than on grass),'' Hackett said. ``The speed and timing change.
It's such a difference from what we're used to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
