A0974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-DEADPLAYER-COX     12-29 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-DEADPLAYER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Highly-regarded athlete Porter collapses, dies
 &HT;    By Darryl Maxie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dante Porter left church just before 1 p.m. Sunday, to
take his mother to work and to attend a 2:30 p.m. memorial service
for a fellow Chamblee High School athlete, baseball player Edward
White.
</P>
<P>
   Porter, the basketball team's star, never made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a funny feeling when I didn't see Dante in that crowd,''
said Becky Chambers, who taught Porter U.S. history all last year.
</P>
<P>
   Only two weeks after committing to play at Furman, Porter
collapsed in the driver's seat while backing his car out of a
driveway and died. And in the span of four days, a happy holiday
season in Chamblee has turned more tragic than anybody could have
expected.
</P>
<P>
   White, an All-DeKalb County first baseman who was to play next
year at Georgia Southern, died unexpectedly on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Like Porter, White was 17. Both were seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we had projected (White) to help us out,
pitching-wise,'' first-year baseball coach Steve Adley said. White,
an imposing 6 feet 4 and 225 pounds, batted .439 last year with
three homers and 18 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Porter was a 6-2 forward who started four years for the
basketball team and was averaging 31.2 points through eight games
this season _ including a 56-point effort in an 81-76 loss to
Etowah at a Thanksgiving tournament. He led DeKalb County in
scoring (27.9 points a game) and rebounding (11.3 per game).
</P>
<P>
   He died of heart problems that went undetected despite three
physical exams in the last four months. He was the nephew of
Chamblee coach Perry Abrams and his wife, Julia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical examiner said he had an enlarged heart,'' Julia
Abrams said, ``and we never knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter had a heart murmur since he was a young boy, but it was
never considered serious, and doctors said it was something that
might pass as he grew bigger and stronger. Perry Abrams said he
never took any problem lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never could've figured this,'' the coach said. ``He had
three physicals, man. I checked. I looked. When I was growing up
and going out for the basketball team, James Tate fell slap out,
died of a heart attack. That stuck with me all my life, so I'm
overly careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even experts on enlarged hearts _ a condition known as
hypertrophic cardiomyopathy _ concede that the condition can be
difficult to detect. Screening tests known as echocardiograms can
reveal it, but because the test costs between $400 and $800, it's
seldom given unless a doctor knows to look for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would probably only pick up one case in a thousand kids,''
said Dr. Bruce Brundage, a cardiologist in Bend, Ore., and a
spokesman for the American Heart Association. ``The only time we
recommend screening (for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy) is if someone
in your family has it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
