<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PLAYOFFS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Against Cards, Smith could become playoff rushing king
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Emmitt Smith has broken so many records during
his nine seasons in the NFL, he was unaware that another milestone
is within his reach.
</P>
<P>
   Smith needs 153 yards to catch Hall of Fame running back Franco
Harris as the No. 1 rusher in the history of the NFL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dallas Cowboys prepare for Saturday's playoff game
against Arizona at Texas Stadium, Smith took several moments to
ponder the significance of another record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take 149 yards and a victory,'' said Smith, breaking into
a big grin.
</P>
<P>
   Smith knows his legacy in league history is secure. Winning
playoff games is more important to him than reaping individual
honors. Besides, if the Cowboys beat the Cardinals, he'll have
another crack at Harris' record.
</P>
<P>
   For players such as Smith and good friend Michael Irvin, the
playoffs mean everything in their professional lives. Both remember
the pain and humiliation of last year's 6-10 season. A year ago,
they spent the end of December cleaning out their lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember coming in, getting my stuff together, and
leaving,'' Smith said Tuesday. ``There was a feeling of relief
because of everything we went through. I'll put it like this: Last
year was like suffering. You don't want to suffer any more. You
just want someone to put you out of your misery. When it finally
ended, I was glad it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   With that failure behind them, the Cowboys are eager to return
to the playoffs. They are 12-3 in playoff games during the 1990s.
Meanwhile, the Cardinals have not been to the playoffs in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona might be the perfect team for Smith to play against. In
two games against the Cardinals this year _ both resulting in
Dallas victories _ Smith rushed for 118 and 122 yards,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas won those games by a combined 73-38 score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had success against them, but there's no guarantee I'll
have success again this week,'' Smith said. ``If we play like we're
capable of playing, with the line performing like it's been all
year, there is a good chance we'll all have success.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be particularly sweet for Irvin, whose string of 117
straight games with at least one reception ended the last time the
Cowboys played the Cardinals. Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman rarely
looked Irvin's way, partly because he was coverered by one of the
league's best defenders, Aeneas Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin has accepted the loss of the streak. He did not accept his
team's absence from the 1997 playoffs, though.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, like Smith, has tasted individual success in the
playoffs. He has 83 playoff catches in 15 games, which ranks second
to Jerry Rice's 120. As he stood in front of his locker Tuesday,
the 11-year receiver reminded some bystanders about the importance
of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it was a shock when (the season ended),'' he said.
``We knew it was coming. We were on such a downslide. Today is a
stark contrast to the way we felt then. It's great now. Everything
is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Including a few records.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES _ One day after cornerback Deion Sanders visited a foot
specialist in South Florida, he was listed as doubtful for
Saturday's game. Sanders said the sprained big toe on his left foot
has not improved, but he wants to try to return to practice this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had the easiest schedule in the league, according to the
NFL. The combined winning percentage of the Cardinals' opponents
was .395 (101-155). By contrast, the winning percentage of the
Cowboys' opponents was .461 (118-138). The first five picks of the
1999 NFL draft will be taken by Cleveland, Philadelphia,
Cincinnati, Indianapolis and Washington. Depending on the results
of the first week of the playoffs, Dallas will pick between 22nd
and 24th.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,000 tickets remain for Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
