<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUS-COTTON-BOWL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT facing Bulldog defense in Cotton Bowl
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Greg Davis got a VCR for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Not as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   As a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, on bowl selection Sunday, the Texas offensive
coordinator quickly realized his holiday visions would not be of
the sugarplums-dancing-in-the-head variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out Mississippi State was our bowl opponent, I
thought, 'There goes Christmas,''' Davis said. ``There's a lot of
extra time in the film room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The basis of their defense,'' said Texas quarterback Major
Applewhite, ``is confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past two seasons, the Bulldogs have run an
unconventional 3-5 set with a noseguard and two ends up front
backed by an inside linebacker, two outside 'backers and two strong
safeties (a.k.a. ``Dog'' backs) bracketing the offensive set.
</P>
<P>
   The key isn't the alignment. The key is the multiple looks the
Bulldogs give once the ball is snapped, with a variety of line
twists, and off-beat blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our scout team probably had its most fun week,'' Davis said.
``We lined them up and told them to move to a certain spot at the
snap and let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State's hopes of stopping an offense led by Heisman
Trophy-winning halfback Ricky Williams and a potent passing game
rest on using its speed and as much deception as it can create. The
Bulldogs haven't been particularly stout against the run, allowing
147.4 yards a game, but ranked third in the Southeastern Conference
in pass efficiency defense.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lee Dunn, the Bulldogs' third-year defensive coordinator who
as one of the pioneers of the pressure defense built successful
units in stays at South Carolina, Mississippi and Arkansas, said
the Bulldogs' frenetic style is a byproduct of the evolution of
passing offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have much choice,'' Dunn said of the move. ``People
give you so many four-wide (receiver) looks that you have to have
five DBs. It's really not fair to put a defensive end or linebacker
on a wideout.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said he considered switching to a more conventional defense
to take on Williams' strong rushing presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to shelve what we were doing and change everything
for the ballgame,'' Dunn said. ``But we've had so many kids hurt we
had to shelve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to put backup linebacker Barron Simpson (5 feet 11
inches, 221 pounds) at linebacker alongside Edward Smith and Larry
Campbell in a 4-3 set, replacing one of he defensive backs. But
Simpson and Campbell have been hurt, forcing Dunn to stick with the
nickel secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have something up our sleeve,'' Campbell said. ``We
might change things up.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing they can't do is bulk up overnight. The Bulldogs
defense has a 5-11, 235-pound noseguard, a 176-pound strong safety
and and average weight of only 218 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to a couple of engagements with Texas this week. I'm
sure they looked at our size and saw how small we are,'' Smith
said. ``I'm sure they think their size will make up for it. But we
have speed.''
</P>
<P>
   At South Carolina, Dunn's defense was known as the ``Fire Ants''
because they made up for a lack of size with a nasty bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard to figure out a nickname for this bunch,'' Dunn
said. ``They can make you feel wonderfully happy one minute and the
next minute you want to choke them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's hoping for the wonderfully happy bit, and his team is
eager to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams don't know about us,'' said cornerback Robert
Bean. ``Then they play us and give us our props. When we stop Ricky
Williams and the passing game, they'll see how good we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
