<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST BOWLS SUFFER IN BCS FORMAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At a team press conference in Century City on
Tuesday, UCLA's Tony White recalled how, as a budding linebacker in
New York and Texas, he dreamed of playing in every bowl but the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said, `I'm going to play in (begin ital)this(end
ital) bowl. I'm going to play in (begin ital)that(end ital) bowl,'
'' White said. ``The Rose Bowl was just too big (to contemplate).''
</P>
<P>
   I hope White's first Rose Bowl _ Friday afternoon against
Wisconsin _ will be everything he couldn't imagine. Just as I hope
the peewee linebackers of 1999 will hold the Rose Bowl in as much
awe as he did.
</P>
<P>
   But sadly, neither seems likely. And you can blame the BCS, the
first-year Bowl Championship Series, whose unintended consequence
is the dented prestige of 22 of the 23 postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS, by letting a computer grind all season, has given us a
national-championship game at last. This time it will match No. 1
Tennessee and No. 2 Florida State on Monday in the Fiesta Bowl in
Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   That once looked like a promising idea, at the very least a step
in the right direction, toward an eight- or 16-team playoff system.
But now we know the BCS system, as it stands now, is a New Year's
Eve glass of warm champagne, a net loss for college football.
</P>
<P>
   Because if you proclaim one bowl as (begin ital)the(end ital)
championship game, you turn the rest of them into a kind of
football NIT. Consolation prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by declaring that (the Fiesta) is (begin ital)the(end
ital) bowl game to play in, it does take a little something from
all the others,'' White agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, none of the Bruins is willing to say he's disappointed
to be playing in the Rose Bowl, although all of them regret the
loss to Miami that cost them a shot at the Fiesta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rose Bowl is still a big game, and we're playing a good
team,'' said Ryan Nece, another UCLA linebacker. ``I don't think
you can downplay the Rose Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a good game, too, with each team going to Pasadena
with a chip on its shoulderpad; UCLA because of the ridicule
directed at its defense, Wisconsin because of the general
skepticism about its 10-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rose Bowl (begin ital)is(end ital) being downplayed. So
are the Holiday, Gator, Cotton, Sugar and Orange bowls, not to
mention a dozen bowls that probably deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Or haven't you read?
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's USA Today devoted a full inside page to four articles
on the Fiesta Bowl. Other games, all being played (begin
ital)before(end ital) the Fiesta, get a line each under ``1998-99
bowl schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's Sports Illustrated features a 10-page, three-article
Fiesta Bowl Preview. For other games, refer to ``The Week in TV
Sports,'' where third-ranked Ohio State is described as ``holding
fast to the slimmest of hopes for a national title.''
</P>
<P>
   Slimmest, or none? This year, if you aren't in the official
title game, how are you going to win the official title? And if
there's some unofficial title at stake here as well, then why did
the manufacturers of the BCS go to all the trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun of the pure bowl system was that in most years
it kept more than two schools in contention for the national
championship _ at least through the New Year's celebration.
</P>
<P>
   A school ranked as low as No. 3, No. 4 or even No. 5 in the
Associated Press and USA Today/ESPN polls could imagine some weird
combination of events that would get it to No. 1. Let's see, if we
win by 40, and they lose a close one, and they won big, and they
(begin ital)tie(end ital), and an asteroid hits the state of
Florida . . .
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time to move on, leave those innocent days behind. Fans
demand a champion be crowned on the field, not in the fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   So be it. But can't we do better than this half-baked chunk of
fruitcake?
</P>
<P>
   Of course we can: Set up a playoff that restores the major bowls
to their glory by using them as the quarterfinal, semifinal and
final games.
</P>
<P>
   The major obstacle, bigger than the scheduling headache, is the
political power of conferences like the Big Ten and the
Southeastern, each of which will bank a projected $28-$33 million
in bowl payouts under the current system, hard to match even with
the TV riches a playoff should produce.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll bet that after this season, when the non-Fiesta bowls
get as much attention as a Libertarian Party convention, the bowl
promoters will be quite willing to make a playoff work. Even a
lover of bowl tradition has to favor a playoff over this.
</P>
<P>
   Nece tried to blame the slow Rose Bowl ticket sales on the fact
``you've got a president who's a little shaky and an economy that's
unbalanced,'' and on UCLA's disappointment in Miami and this year's
$100 ticket price. Why don't we blame El Nino, for auld lang syne?
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's fall and the prices' rise have a lot to do with making
Friday's Rose Bowl one sick granddaddy. But don't be surprised if
stadiums are emptier and television ratings are down for most of
the non-title games across the country this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that a full-fledged playoff is the only way to return
the Rose Bowl and its brothers to the stature that you and I and
Tony White remember. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
