<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1004 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LARRY-LADN     12-29 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LARRY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS' LARRY MEANS BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ Around the house he shares with four other USC
football players, Lawrence Larry is the safety net.
</P>
<P>
   Rent check due? Lawrence will take care of it. Problem for the
landlord? Just tell Lawrence. Did somebody forget to pay the cable
bill? Lawrence will remind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Lawrence, we'd be in trouble,'' roommate and wide
receiver Billy Miller said. ``Our entire household falls apart. He
thinks he's the daddy of the house. He's like the brother everybody
has.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry just turned 22 this month, but acts with the composure and
style of a man years older. His USC career ends Thursday against
Texas Christian in the Sun Bowl, and he's handling it with the same
grace he does in most situations. Not too sad about leaving
college, or too happy to finally graduate. He's always on an even
keel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude is everything comes to pass,'' Larry said. ``I'm
thankful for the years I've had at USC. Who knows about the future?
I live day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   It might sound like Larry lives in a potential Animal House _
considering he shares a large house near campus with Miller,
cornerback Daylon McCutcheon, fullback Marvin Powell and tight end
Lonnie Ford _ but Larry's tunnel vision toward academics will allow
him to graduate from USC in May with a degree in business
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived with him four years,'' Miller said. ``We all joke
about how hard Lawrence studies in school, but whatever he does we
know he'll be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry's football career hasn't always gone the way he hoped, but
he's never let it affect him academically. It's an example of the
responsible nature he has demonstrated since coming to USC as a
prep All-American from Littlerock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very mature,'' USC defensive line coach Ed Orgeron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that a lot,'' Larry said. ``A lot of it has to
do with experience. I was driving a car in the sixth grade. I went
to clubs with my brother when he turned 21, and I was only 16. I've
already experienced a lot of things that most guys are just now
learning about.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times at USC when Larry could have transferred, or
quit, or complained to coaches. But instead he decided to take
things ``like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some adversity early in my career. My expectations were
high,'' Larry said. ``But it made me stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the problems occurred two years ago. After making
an impression as a reserve defensive end during his freshman
season, Larry was poised to become a starter at linebacker his
sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere along the way, then-defensive coordinator Keith
Burns lost faith in Larry and basically shut him out of the playing
rotation. He appeared in 10 games, but had just six tackles his
sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good freshman season. Then I had a year where I was
missing in action,'' Larry said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns admitted after the season that he did not have confidence
in Larry, and the rift was eventually patched up, although Larry
never complained about his treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The following season, Larry moved back to defensive end. He
seemed to find his niche, starting several games. He had his best
game against Stanford, forcing a fumble that set up a field goal
and recovering a fumble that set up a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Although coach John Robinson _ and Burns _ were fired after his
junior season, Larry felt this year would be his best, in part
because he would get a fresh start with a new coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Only an ankle injury has slowed him down, but he
has started the Trojans' past six games and been one of their most
consistent defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawrence is a conscientious person and fought hard to come
back from that injury,'' Orgeron said. ``He's playing his best
football right now. He does a lot of unseen things for us. He's got
so much leadership and pride.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't exactly be considered a star-studded career, but Larry
will leave USC a contented person. He doesn't think he would have
been happier at Notre Dame, or Colorado or any of the other schools
he considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been what I wanted football-wise,'' he said. ``I
don't look at my career as being miserable. I don't regret
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry wouldn't mind trying out for an NFL, World League or even
Canadian Football League team, but he's also planning to become an
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   He's already lined up investors to start a trucking business
that will probably be based in the Antelope Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the first of many ventures,'' Larry said. ``I want
to start a trucking business. This summer. We're going to be
transporting sand and gravel.''
</P>
<P>
   But Larry makes it clear that even if he starts with just one
truck, he'll be the CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan on being a truck driver,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
