<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Child Prostitute as Victim
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ The government issued guidelines aimed at treating
child prostitutes as victims of abuse rather than as criminals and
at marking their employers and clients for prosecution. The latest
annual figures, for 1995-1996, show that 177 youths under 17 were
convicted of prostitution and another 207 were formally cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Batons vs. Truncheons
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British police are being warned that the growing
substitution of longer and heavier American-style batons for the
11-inch wooden truncheons traditionally carried by officers has
resulted in an increased number of brutality complaints. The report
from the independent Police Complaints Authority says that British
police forces should instruct their members in restrained use of
the new weapons to reduce the possibility of serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Former Officials Released
</P>
<P>
   MADRID _ Spain's highest tribunal, the Constitutional Court,
authorized the release from jail of former Interior Minister Jose
Barrionuevo and his deputy, Rafael Vera, while it considers their
appeals. The men were convicted in July for their roles in a
kidnapping in 1983 during a campaign against Basque separatist
terrorists. The government last week reduced their 10-year
sentences by two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Preparing for the Worst
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ Gen. R. Jayaswal, director general of medical
services for India's armed forces, told reporters that doctors and
paramedics are being trained to deal with injuries sustained in a
nuclear blast as well as the effects of chemical weapons. India
exploded its own nuclear device in May, followed by its rival,
Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
