r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURNED-TEEN-LADN     12-29 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNED-TEEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BADLY BURNED HIGH SCHOOL STUDENT EXUBERANT UPON RELEASE FROM
HOSPITAL
</HEADLINE>
 (Also moving in the ``n'' California news files) 
(Daily News Staff Writer Patricia Farrell Aidem contributed to this
story) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Leaving the hospital where he spent more than a
month recovering from life-threatening burns, Christopher James
paused, popped up through the sunroof of a limousine carrying him
home and pumped his fist triumphantly in the air.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment of pure joy Tuesday in the middle a miraculous
recovery from burns to his face, hands and windpipe caused when a
science experiment went awry in November.
</P>
<P>
   With youthful exuberance, James, 17, exchanged high-fives with
friends and exulted in his recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great. When I go home I'm going to have a party,''
James said, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Carolyn, was more subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to put into words,'' she told reporters Tuesday
during a reception at the Grossman Burn Center at Sherman Oaks
Hospital. She compared his release to his birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than when we brought him home for the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   James and two other Hart High School students were burned Nov.
25 during a science experiment on the Santa Clarita Valley school's
football field. Students were using cans to launch tennis balls
when methanol fuel used in the experiment exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said there was a chance James wouldn't survive the
third-degree burns sustained to his face, hands and upper body in
the experiment gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   And even if he did, burn victims can suffer so much
psychological trauma it alters their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Go tell that to James.
</P>
<P>
   When the young man was released Tuesday, he not only looked and
sounded exuberant _ but he possessed the same wise-cracking humor
friends say pulled him and them through the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they liked me but I guess they do,'' James
joked of the outpouring of support from loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   On a more serious note, the Hart High School senior offered
thanks to his family, to God and to Jesse Honea, 17, crediting him
for saving his life. Honea threw James to the ground, putting out
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think personally it's made me a stronger person,'' James
said. ``Normally, you don't go through something like this _ so I'm
now a stronger person inside.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, doctors feared his vocal cords might have been burned
beyond repair since he had inhaled superheated air during the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   However, James' throat has healed well, evidenced Tuesday as the
young man fielded rounds of questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Leading surgeon Dr. Peter H. Grossman called James ``an amazing
man'' who maintained such a strong spirit he wound up comforting
his visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time ... when I wasn't sure if Chris was going to
survive,'' Grossman said. ``I wasn't sure. But Chris was.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's cake and punch party at the hospital drew a small
group of close friends and relatives. Friends gave him a
compact-disc player and a radio in the shape of a monkey.
</P>
<P>
   Looking confident in a baseball cap, James' facial scars
appeared to have healed well, except for reddening across his face.
He's expected to return to high school and he plans to attend
college.
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference, James and a few of his buddies were
whisked away in a dark blue limo to a party awaiting him at home.
</P>
<P>
   James' humor was little surprise to his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know Chris he's always like that. Even in the worst
possible situation he's cracking jokes,'' said his friend Ivan
Pecel, 17.
</P>
<P>
   James' neighbors posted signs on his street and at his house
welcoming him home to Stevenson Ranch, a suburb about 25 miles
northwest of Los Angeles. Balloons were tied to his street sign and
giant greetings hung on the garage of the family home.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and neighbors checked in, elated that the teen was home
and showing good signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the accident, doctors began removing dead skin and
replacing it with grafts, covering the burns with cadaver skin.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said James will require continued therapy to help him
regain full use of his upper body, arms and hands and that he
likely will undergo reconstructive surgery on his face and hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
