<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Strasbourg, France) _ The launch of a new currency, the
euro, on Friday represents the single most important change on the
Continent since the end of the Cold War. In getting to this point,
11 European nations have for the first time adopted a common
economic policy that has reined in public spending, reduced debt
and tamed inflation. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-CURFEW (Hamilton, Scotland) _ Hamilton is the first
community in Britain to impose a curfew on its young people, with
special child safety police officers questioning anyone they know
to be under the age of 16 on the streets after 8 p.m. and taking
them home if they cannot supply a sound reason why they are out. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-SOUTH (Ty, Ty, Georgia) _ In last month's election, Rep.
Sanford D. Bishop Jr., a moderate black Democrat, won re-election
convincingly in a rural, conservative district where nearly
two-thirds of the voters are white. Many black politicians have
managed to attract white support in urban, New South areas like
Atlanta. But Bishop's electoral success demonstrates that even in
the most rural and impoverished districts, a significant number of
white Southerners no longer view race as an absolute obstacle to
voting for a black politician who shares their thinking, votes
their interests and hauls home plenty of pork. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-TOWN (Brooksville, Ala.) _ If the Rev. James Henderson has
his way, the division of church and state in this tiny hamlet will
be so narrow, a single Bible verse, ``Love thy neighbor,'' would
cover it. Henderson and some 140 other residents of Brooksville, an
unincorporated community in northern Alabama, want to form a town,
but not one in which mortal elected officials would have the power
to hand out liquor licenses, levy taxes and rezone land for strip
malls and industrial parks. Instead, Henderson said, they want a
town guided by the hand of God. The King James Bible would be the
town charter, the Ten Commandments, its ordinances. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-STATISTICS _ Government data provide the first gauge of
how welfare around the nation has been affected by the 1996 welfare
overhaul law, which gave states lump sums of federal money and vast
new authority to run their own programs. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
