<P>
   FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column: There
are now seven coaching vacancies in the NFL, thanks to the wave of
dismissals on Monday, when the ax fell on five head coaches from
Baltimore to Seattle. One of those dismissed was Ray Rhodes, whose
departure left just two black head coaches. Now the question again
facing the league is whether teams will make a real effort to
interview black candidates for the current openings, and hire
several of them, or whether the situation won't change much at all.
By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MONTEREY-WINES (Undated) _ For California winemaking in the late
'70s, if Napa and Sonoma were the diplomatic equivalents of Paris
and London, Monterey was considered Bucharest. When mentioned at
all, Monterey was slammed for producing cabernets that tasted a lot
like the local asparagus. But for 20 years Dan Lee has been in the
thick of things as the region's growers and winemakers, after
ripping out the cabernet vines and replacing them with chardonnay
and pinot noir, have pushed Monterey into serious contention as a
producer of top-quality, exciting wines, with the best yet to come.
By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT8,9) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Proust had his madeleine. For
me, the catalyst was seared foie gras with pomegranate seeds and a
spicy pear and pepper chutney. Proust's little cake sent him on a
journey back in time, but my savory plate made me contemplate the
future. And it looks very promising. When this epiphany occurred I
was sitting in Tabla just after it opened. What intrigued me was
the fact that the ingredients went together in a way that seemed
completely natural. Looking around, I realized that everything
about the restaurant felt natural. Only a week old, Tabla seemed to
have been open for years. A momentous change has occurred as the
booming economy has bolstered chefs' and restaurateurs' confidence
to a whole new level. American restaurants have finally come of
age. By Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-TRENDS (Undated) _ As exhilarating as the fast-moving
food world can be, over the past few years, it has felt more like a
car speeding out of control. Trends have bombarded us from all
directions; cookbook sections in bookstores have grown into
complex, multicolored labyrinths; restaurant dishes have become
feats to deconstruct, both physically and sensually. Even home
cooking, which so often evolves out of restaurant cooking, has
become muddled. Now, just as chefs tossed aside overwrought French
cuisine to revel in the simplicity of nouvelle cuisine, many
contemporary cooks are pulling away from fusion cooking and
free-wheeling experimentation and heading in an entirely new
direction _ toward simplicity. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-POULTRY (Undated) _ The USDA lifts its ban on imports of
raw poultry from France, a boon for connoisseurs of foie gras; now
we'll get it from geese, not just ducks. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
