<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-STRADTNER-NYT &LR;      12-29 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STRADTNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLORIA STRADTNER, 72, PROTECTOR OF ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Conn. ) 
(rl) 
 By RICHARD SEVERO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you saw her at all, you'd see her in a cemetery
late at night. She'd be clambering about one of those huge
cemeteries in Brooklyn and Queens, the ones beneath the flight
paths to La Guardia and Kennedy; graveyards with names like
Evergreen, Mount Neboh and Cypress Hills. She was there on the
hottest summer night when New Yorkers without air &UR; - &LR; conditioners
couldn't sleep &UR; ,  &LR; and she was there when the temperature was below
zero and the snow was hip-deep and nobody was awake.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the polished marble sentries guarding the dead of a great
city, Gloria Marie De Martini Stradtner looked only for life.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stradtner, who died on Dec. 22 at the age of 72, looked for
stray animals. She looked for the thousands of dogs and cats
abandoned every year by people who, having tired of their pets,
thought not of bringing them to an animal shelter but of leaving
them in a cemetery. Humans may think of cemeteries as woodland-like
sanctuaries. But for animals, they are only places to starve to
death in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   But Gloria _ as everyone called her _ was determined that this
was not to be. Not for her strays.
</P>
<P>
   And so for 50 years or maybe more (nobody can remember when she
did not make the rounds of the graveyards at night), she would go
forth, lugging large bags of dog food and cat food and traps of the
type that cannot hurt animals. She would bait these traps and go
back to her car and wait. In an hour or so, she would return to her
traps. Sometimes, she would entrap a dozen animals or more in a
single night, her prisoners of love. And then she would feed them.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stradtner never had much money, and so to supplement the
dog and cat food she bought with her Social Security money she
would take jobs working in catering halls, even when she was
getting on in years, so she could scoop up the scraps and bring
them to her strays. When she was younger, back in the 1950s, she
worked as a clerk and data entry specialist for IBM. But she did
not mind doing menial work in a catering hall. Not if it meant she
could feed the animals.
</P>
<P>
   And after she fed them, she would spend the next day making the
rounds of veterinarians, imploring their help to neuter the dogs
and cats (they usually charged her reduced fees). And then she
would visit the shelters, asking them to take and care for the
abandoned pets.
</P>
<P>
   One shelter was Pegeen Fitzgerald's Last Post Animal Sanctuary
in Litchfield County, Conn., near the Massachusetts line. They try
to specialize in housing cats there, but when Mrs. Stradtner showed
up with dogs from the graveyards of New York, they took in dogs,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would estimate she saved thousands of animals,'' said Jeanne
Toomey, who runs Last Post. ``She was wonderful. She'd name dogs
and cats in the cemetery and she'd bring them up here. Nobody could
refuse her.''
</P>
<P>
   She visited animal sanctuaries in Long Island, upstate and in
New Jersey, too, and nobody refused her in those places, either.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, her friends would go with her on her night visits.
Michael Puccino, an executive with a Manhattan computer consulting
firm, and his wife, Anne Marie, a veterinary nurse, would help
whenever they could. And the cemetery workers helped, too. When it
was bitter cold, the workers in at least one cemetery opened the
door to a heated mausoleum so the strays could spend the night
there. In another cemetery, they built little igloos in the
bitterest part of the winter, hoping that Mrs. Stradtner's strays
would use them to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Puccino told her more than once that cemeteries are not the
safest places to be after dark. But she scoffed at such advice.
``She was the most adventurous, the liveliest individual you'd ever
meet,'' Puccino said. When she was in her 70s, everybody thought
she was in her 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, somebody stole her car, which was parked on a
Brooklyn street near the house on Chestnut Street where she lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called me, and she didn't care about the car,'' Puccino
said. ``She was angry because there were 100 pounds of dog food in
the trunk.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last summer, there was a dog she was worried about. She called
the dog Peekaboo because it peeked around gravestones at her.
Peekaboo kept having litters; one time, she delivered 10 pups. Mrs.
Stradtner was determined that Peekaboo be spayed, but Peekaboo was
elusive. She would come when Mrs. Stradtner called her name, but no
closer than 10 feet. Peekaboo was quite wild, covered with fleas
and ticks, and she trusted nobody.
</P>
<P>
   One day about six weeks ago, Mrs. Stradtner's speech became
slurred. Puccino spoke to her on the telephone and asked her if she
had been drinking. He knew she had not been drinking. She never
drank and had not smoked for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed with the Puccinos briefly, and Puccino had her
examined at Southside Hospital in Bay Shore. Doctors said she had
cancer. It had started in her lungs and spread to her brain. Then,
she moved to Lenox Hill Hospital in Manhattan; she knew somebody
who worked there.
</P>
<P>
   She called Puccino on Dec. 20, two days before she died. Puccino
said she wanted to make sure that Peekaboo had been spayed (she
was) and that her own two dogs, Lance and Ivy, would be taken care
of after she died (he promised her they would be).
</P>
<P>
   People who knew her were not sure Tuesday about her next of kin.
She had been married to a man named Stradtner for three years,
maybe 40 years ago. They had no children. Her sister, Gladys
Semino, had predeceased her.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody found a poem she was believed to have recently written,
and at her funeral last Saturday, it was read. It was entitled
``Weep Not'' and began this way:
</P>
<P>
   Do not weep for me when I am gone
</P>
<P>
   For I have friends in the great beyond.
</P>
<P>
   All the little ones I used to feed
</P>
<P>
   Will come to me in my time of need.
</P>
<P>
   They will purr and bark in great delight,
</P>
<P>
   And I will hold and hug them tight.
</P>
<P>
   Oh what a great day that will be
</P>
<P>
   When my furry friends all welcome me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
