<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYER AGENTS RIP STERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA players union is run by agent David Falk?
Hogwash. The union is only interested in protecting high-salaried
players? Nonsense. Players have not made significant concessions?
Baloney.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the primary messages Tuesday as three player agents
who represent primarily the NBA's lower class addressed a
conference call of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Glass, Steve Kauffman and Jerome Stanley _ all members of
the union's agents advisory committee _ pleaded the players' case
while shooting down ``tremendous misconceptions'' being promoted by
commissioner David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   The trio of agents _ who represent 33 players, only one of whom
makes more than $5 million a year _ said the union has conceded
most of the Kevin Garnett-type high-end salaries. What they're
holding out for, they said, are measures to restore the middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Stern) has the best deal he could have ever hoped for,'' said
Stanley. ``This is the first sports industry to cap the top-end
salaries. The top end has already been sacrificed. At what point
does it become enough?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the players' most recent proposal, players with fewer than
10 years in the league would be subject to firm caps on their
salaries. Players with 10 years or more would still be entitled to
earn whatever a team is willing to pay _ but even those deals would
be subject to a heavy luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
   The union has also agreed to longer rookie contracts and lower
annual raises for all players, and the agents predicted a majority
of owners would vote for the union's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think David Stern a few years ago, in his wildest
dreams, thought he could get this (cap on salaries),'' said
Kauffman. ``This is a monumental concession.''
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point, however, is the union has not backed away
from its insistence on earning up to 57 percent of league revenues.
Stern hasn't budged beyond 53 to 54 percent, with each percentage
point representing about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the agents aren't convinced the commissioner even wants a
deal. Glass said he is baffled at Stern's stance in light of the
union's concessions and wondered if he hadn't decided long ago to
cancel the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does appear to me, when you look at what's been given . . .
that they may not want to have a season. That may be a
possibility,'' Glass said. ``And I don't know what the reason is
for that. You'd have to ask them.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the agents' comments Tuesday, Stern said, ``They
can say anything they want about me, but they are not neutral
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern has scheduled a meeting of NBA owners Jan. 7 and will
recommend cancellation of the season unless the union accepts the
league's current offer. Union leadership has already rejected that
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the final offer has been rejected, I don't understand why
you need to wait until the seventh,'' Stanley said. ``If it's over,
then it should be over today, and if it's not over then everybody
needs to strap up and get back to work and lets stop the
gamesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kauffman, ``Commissioner Stern has to move an inch. . . .
He can't just sit up there in his palace and continue with his
condescending attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern's threats, and his attempts to divide the union by calling
for a players vote on the league's deal, are simply part of the
league's strategy to extract every possible concession, the agents
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has been a well-orchestrated, preplanned
negotiation,'' Stanley said. ``It's probably been in the works for
24 months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
