<HEADLINE>
KINGS' BODGER OUT; COYOTES' DRAKE SUSPENDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kings defenseman Doug Bodger received a right
neck, chest cervical and shoulder strain and bruise, was left black
and blue from shoulder to elbow, can't lift his right arm above his
shoulder and probably will miss at least one game.
</P>
<P>
   And for inflicting this smorgasbord of damage with a nasty
boarding penalty during the Kings' 4-2 victory Monday night in
Phoenix, Coyotes winger Dallas Drake received a four-game
suspension from the NHL on Tuesday. At the time of the incident,
Drake received a five-minute major penalty and a game misconduct
from referee Mick McGeough.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension -- one game longer than what Kings defenseman Rob
Blake received for a slashing major earlier this month that left
Vancouver's Harry York with a bruised arm -- was issued following a
telephone hearing involving Drake and Colin Campbell, the NHL's
vice president of hockey operations. Campbell ruled that Drake had
intent to injure on the play.
</P>
<P>
   `The league views hits from behind as dangerous play,` Campbell
said, `and injuries resulted from Mr. Drake's illegal conduct.`
</P>
<P>
   Bodger is doubtful for the Kings' game tonight against the San
Jose Sharks at the Forum. The suspension will cost Drake $20,833.33
of his $1-million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Solid Storr (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   A key to Monday's victory was the play of goalie Jamie Storr,
who kept the Kings in the game early with numerous difficult saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie came up with a couple of huge stops at key times,''
Coach Larry Robinson said. ``It's what goaltending is about. It's
not stopping 50 shots, although when a goalie does that he can
steal a game. But when a goalie makes key stops at the right times,
that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also praised defenseman Steve Duchesne, who has been
the Kings' biggest disappointment this season, a player who
frequently has been an offensive non-factor and a defensive
liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Duchesne probably played his best game since he's been
with the team,'' Robinson said. ``Things were working and he made a
much more concerted effort not to do anything too fancy, just play
good, safe hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne created several scoring chances with deft
stickhandling, avoided the turnovers that have plagued him, and
several times chose to remain in a safe defensive position rather
than go deep into the offensive zone to pursue a puck he had less
than a 50-percent chance of reaching. Bad decisions on such plays
have been one of his biggest problems all season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
