<HEADLINE>
BOTHA DISSECTING TYSON ON TAPE 
HOLMES GETS A TEXAS LICENSE 
HOLYFIELD-LEWIS A HOT TICKET 
JOHNSON TO RISK TITLE VS. TAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
 (ATTN: Nev., Texas, N.J. , Fla.)  
 (bl) 
By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being a sacrificial lamb is not part of the strategy for
Francois Botha when he meets Mike Tyson on Jan. 16 in Las Vegas in
a heavyweight bout. Botha has been watching tapes of Tyson's two
losses to Evander Holyfield, and he plans on deploying the same
strategy that Holyfield did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guys, like Bruce Seldon, who went against him were
scared,'' Botha said during a telephone conference call from his
training camp in Las Vegas on Tuesday. ``They ran away from him and
closed up so he was able to pick his shots. That's when Tyson wins.
You have to hit him, counter him or tie him up. Smothering him is a
good move. You've got to get him back on his heels, moving back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson believes that Holyfield was deliberately head-butting him
in the second fight, and he believes it was part of Holyfield's
strategy. Cut and bleeding, Tyson snapped and bit both of
Holyfield's ears. He was disqualified in the bout and the Nevada
State Athletic Commission subsequently revoked his license. Tyson's
license was reinstated Oct. 19 and Botha is his first opponent in
18 months. Botha doesn't believe Tyson will snap in the ring
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows all eyes are on him,'' Botha said. ``If he does
something wrong he'll never fight again in his life. After I beat
him, he'll still be able to make money. But if he snaps again,
he'll never make money again.''
</P>
<P>
   Botha is looking for bigger and better things after his Tyson
bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fight most heavyweights wait for,'' Botha said. ``It
can put you up there where you belong. If I knock out Tyson, I'll
be the biggest thing in boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes Gets a Texas License
</P>
<P>
   Even though his Jan. 23 bout in Houston against George Foreman
is on the ropes, Larry Holmes is moving forward. Holmes obtained
his Texas boxing license on Monday and is awaiting the letters of
credit from the promoter Roger Leavitt that will assure the purses
for the fight. Those letters were supposed to be forwarded to
Foreman and Holmes last week, but they weren't. Leavitt did not
return a telephone message left at his New York office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman already has $1 million of the $9 million he is supposed
to earn for the fight and Holmes has $400,000 of the $4 million he
is to earn. Both deposits are nonrefundable to Leavitt in the event
the bout is scuttled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no postponement, no cancellation, no change in
anything; the fight is going forward,'' said Jay Newman, a
spokesman for Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreman-Holmes bout is in a tough spot in terms of possible
pay-per-view sells. It falls between Tyson-Botha, which will be
broadcast on pay-per-view by Showtime Entertainment Television on
Jan. 16, and Oscar De La Hoya-Ike Quartey, which will be shown on
TVKO on Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield-Lewis a Hot Ticket
</P>
<P>
   With no Knicks basketball on the schedule, the hottest ticket at
New York's Madison Square Garden is for the Evander
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight unification bout March 13. With
more than two months to go before the fight, 15,000 of the 19,800
seats have been sold and the bulk of the promotion for the bout has
yet to occur.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are priced from $1,500 for ringside to $100 for seats in
the upper level of the arena. Most of the remaining tickets are for
middle-level seats that cost $1,000, $750 and $500. The bout will
be broadcast on pay-per-view by TVKO.
</P>
<P>
   Two other shows will keep the Garden busy until the
Holyfield-Lewis show. A welterweight championship fight between
Felix Trinidad and Pernell Whitaker is close to being completed for
the main arena Feb. 20 and a heavyweight bout between Shannon
Briggs and Lou Savarese is being scheduled for the Theater on Feb.
27.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson to Risk Title vs. Taylor
</P>
<P>
   _ Reggie Johnson, the International Boxing Federation
light-heavyweight champion, will defend his title against Will
Taylor on the undercard of the Briggs-Savarese show Feb. 27. The
fight could pave the way for Johnson to meet Roy Jones Jr. in April
for a light-heavyweight unification bout. Jones is scheduled to
fight Richard Frazier, a New York City police officer, in
Pensacola, Fla., on Jan. 9 on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jimmy Thunder has been selected as the opponent for Andrew
Golata on the Jan. 30 heavyweight doubleheader in Atlantic City,
N.J.. Michael Grant will fight Ahmad Abdin in the other bout. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
