<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIESTA-ECON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWL IS A FIESTA FOR HOTELIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the greenbacks they will spend, Arizonans should welcome
Tennessee fans singing ``Rocky Top'' and the Florida State faithful
whooping it up with their war chant.
</P>
<P>
   To the uninitiated, those collegiate battle cries can fray the
nerves, but local hoteliers and other tourist-related businesses
like the sound of ringing cash registers associated with Fiesta
Bowl visitors _ to the tune of $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much Fiesta Bowl officials estimate the championship
college football game Monday and all the associated festivities
will pump into Arizona's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Tostitos Fiesta Bowl, a championship game between
Nebraska and Florida, contributed $96.8 million to the local
economy, according to an economic impact study that the Arizona
State University College of Business completed for the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A skeptical economics professor thinks that figure is inflated,
but hotel managers say there's no disputing the fact that the game
brings a surge in visitors at a time when most leisure and business
travelers are home for the holidays and when many hotels are
virtually empty.
</P>
<P>
   Sports-related economic-impact studies are at best an estimate,
and the accuracy varies widely, said Mark Eschenfelder, an
associate professor of economics at Robert Morris College in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to think of the Fiesta Bowl is how different will
the community be because the event was held there,'' said
Eschenfelder, who teaches a course on the economics of sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, based on the size of your economy, it's not that much
of a boost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The game will bring in a lot of visitors and a positive economic
impact from spending on lodging and souvenir T-shirts, but many of
the items are manufactured elsewhere, so the ``money leaks out of
the area pretty quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eschenfelder also rains on the Fiesta Bowl's parade of
volunteers and corporate sponsors who make the game and dozens of
other related events possible.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the Fiesta Bowl, he asked, what other charities and
causes would benefit from those corporate donations and volunteer
efforts?
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Fiesta Bowl gives Arizona a lot of
national exposure, Eschenfelder said.
</P>
<P>
   And that does influence people's decisions to visit Arizona,
said Brian Kinghorn, director of sales at The Buttes in Tempe,
which is hosting Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   More directly, the Fiesta Bowl fills hotel rooms. Not only for
The Buttes and the Scottsdale Plaza Resort, which is hosting
Tennessee, but for other Valley hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 game attracted 50,000 visitors who stayed an average of
four nights, according to the ASU economic-impact study.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels in Tempe and Scottsdale, closer to Sun Devil Stadium,
benefit the most from the influx of football fans, said Tom
Silverman, owner of Embassy Suites Scottsdale, which will fill all
of its 311 rooms Sunday and Monday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the hotels are full, it goes right down the line to help
restaurants, rental-car agencies and retail shops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For many hotels, the Fiesta Bowl surge helps at a slow time of
year, according to Joe Forster, vice president of sales and
marketing at the Scottsdale Plaza Resort. Hotel occupancy drops off
from the middle of December through the first or second week of
January, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no demand for rooms, so visitors can get a nice room in
a Scottsdale resort for as little as $90, but during the Fiesta
Bowl that same room goes for $240 a night, Forster said.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale Plaza Resort has the advantage of hosting
Tennessee. The football team is occupying 150 rooms. Without the
team, the resort would have sold only 34 rooms on Monday night,
said Forster, a Fiesta Bowl committee member.
</P>
<P>
   From an economic standpoint, this year's Fiesta Bowl probably
will be the best ever, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a championship year, anybody could make this successful,''
Forster said. ``The trick with the bowl is to find a way to impact
the economy and have people here in a non-championship year.'' &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 2325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
