A1148 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZ     12-29 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASSITER PICKS OFF WEEKLY AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals safety  &UR; Kwamie Lassiter is expected to be named NFC
Defensive Player of the Week today for his four interceptions in
Sunday's victory over San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   He would be the third Cardinals defender to win that honor this
season, joining defensive end &UR; Simeon Rice and strong safety  &UR; Tommy
 &UR; Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter's four interceptions tied an NFL record and helped the
Cardinals advance to Saturday's NFC wild-card game at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was, if he paid off the quarterback or
the (San Diego) coach, but he just had an incredible feel for the
ball,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter received another honor Tuesday when he was named the
Miller Lite NFL Player of the Week. He is only the second defensive
player to get that honor.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals quarterback &UR; Jake Plummer won the award last week.
</P>
<P>
   Lassiter had eight interceptions, an NFC high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny how things work out,'' Lassiter said. ``I only
start five games and have eight interceptions. It's the most I've
had at any level.'' &QL; 
Call waiting &QL; 
Cardinals defensive coordinator  &UR; Dave McGinnis learned Tuesday that
he and Buffalo offensive coordinator  &UR; Joe Pendry are on the Chicago
Bears' short list to replace  &UR; Dave Wannstedt as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting,'' said McGinnis, a longtime assistant
with the Bears. ``Again, I've never pursued any of that stuff.
Obviously, us winning is the catalyst to anything anybody wants to
do. That's all I'm concerned about, us winning and doing the job I
have here. I've got a good job and good situation here, and
obviously, all we have to do is keep winning and all that other
stuff will take care of itself.'' &QL; 
Calling all fans &QL; 
The Cardinals will have a fans playoff celebration from 1 to 5 p.m.
Thursday at the new Warner-Hardy Sports Complex, just north of the
training facility. There will be food vendors, interactive games,
autographs and free merchandise from the team shop. Admission is
free.
</P>
<P>
   And for those fans wanting to attend Saturday's game in Dallas,
the Cardinals are offering a chartered travel package for $749. The
cost includes round-trip airfare on America West Airlines, ground
travel to the Holiday Inn Select in North Dallas as well as to
Texas Stadium on game day, a game ticket and a Cardinals T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will depart Phoenix on Friday and return after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested should call Baker's Travel at 998-8922. The
trip is subject to cancellation if a minimum requirement is not
met. &QL; 
Still hurting &QL; 
Receiver  &UR; Frank Sanders, who suffered a bruised left knee against
the Chargers, missed practice Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said no structural damage was found in
Sanders' knee and he should be able to play against the Cowboys. &QL; 
In God's hands &QL; 
A day after he was declared out for Saturday's game, Cowboys
All-Pro cornerback  &UR; Deion Sanders was upgraded to doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   ``With God, all things are possible,'' said Sanders, who has
played only 25 snaps since suffering a sprained big toe on his left
foot against the Cardinals on Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end  &UR; David LaFleur, who has been slowed by fluid on his
right knee, practiced on a limited basis Tuesday. &QL; 
Short shots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive tackle &UR; Mark Smith, who missed two of the
past three games because of an ankle injury, will return to the
starting lineup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL informed the Cardinals that they will draft eighth (from
San Diego) and 20th, their own pick. If the Cardinals advance in
the playoffs, the pick could drop to 21st. The choice can't drop
any lower unless the Cardinals reach the Super Bowl. &QL; 
Lee Shappell and Tim Tyers contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
