<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      12-29 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Because everyone else even remotely involved in the 183-day NBA
lockout seems to be holding conference calls these days, the agents
decided to have their voices heard Tuesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Agents Steve Kauffman, Keith Glass and Jerome Stanley, all of
whom represent mostly middle- and lower-class players, claimed NBA
commissioner David Stern is attempting to use strong-arm tactics to
get a new collective-bargaining agreement that will greatly benefit
owners, even if it means canceling the season.
</P>
<P>
   The agents' response to such a threat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have the season, they have the season; if they don't,
they don't,'' said Glass, who called the owners' negotiating
tactics ``disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman, Glass and Stanley said the negotiations had been
scripted in an effort to drive a wedge between the union members
and their leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's been the case,'' Stanley said. ``I think this
has been a well-orchestrated, pre-planned negotiation. It's
probably been in the works for 24 months, ever since they began to
see what the effects were of the '95 deal (when player salaries
began to skyrocket).
</P>
<P>
   ``And they realized that during the '95 deal they should have
done things differently; they decided that what they were going to
do is push the issue to this point. I believe it is a scripted
negotiation on the part of management.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern and deputy commissioner Russ Granik say if there is no
progress in negotiations, they will recommend canceling the season
when the league convenes a meeting of its Board of Governors on
Jan. 7. Union executive director Billy Hunter and a large number of
players and agents insist they are bluffing.
</P>
<P>
   All three agents took issue with the league's insistence the
season should not fall by the wayside without a vote by the union
membership on the owners' latest proposal. Hunter, who rejected the
NBA's proposal at a Sunday meeting with Stern, has stated many
times he will not present an offer he thinks is unacceptable for a
vote of the union membership.
</P>
<P>
   The agents agreed with Hunter's stance and cautioned against a
secret ballot by the union, even though several players have said
lately they will ask for just that before allowing the season to
slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is another calculated, manipulative gesture by
management,'' said Stanley of the call for a vote. ``They know that
to open it up to a vote at this time and allow them a chance to
turn their P.R. machine on would create some dissension. They know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley contested the league's stance by demanding the owners
vote on the union's proposal, apparently forgetting the league
plans to do just that at the Board of Governors meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be doing that on Jan. 7, and it is the unanimous
recommendation of our committee that it be rejected and no further
proposals be made,'' Granik said. ``So we're doing it on Jan. 7.''
</P>
<P>
   The agents stressed the concessions the union has made _
limiting high-end salaries, agreeing to a four-year rookie scale
and reducing annual raises _ while blasting the inflexibility of
the owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinary,'' said Kauffman, who characterized Stern
as arrogant and condescending. ``I can't overstate the concession
that's made when you sacrifice the top-end guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think David Stern a few years ago in his wildest
dreams thought he could get this. It's a monumental concession.
That can't be understated.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Figure out) how much money the Los Angeles Lakers will save
by not having to pay Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant what they
would have had to pay under the old deal,'' he said. ``That's the
offer we're making. At what point does it become enough? At what
point do owners stand up to their negotiator and say, `Hey, we've
already gotten enough. Let's move forward.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stern points to the concessions the owners made in their last
proposal _ increasing the percentage of revenues that will be
devoted to salaries, increasing minimum salaries, adding an
exception to the salary cap to help beef up the league's middle
class and accepting the union's 10-percent limitation on the escrow
fund, which is designed to act as a hedge against salary
overspending _ as proof they are interested in negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern said the owners do not want to give in on such items
as ending opt-out clauses and voiding a player's Larry
Bird-exception status should he be traded in the last year of his
contract, because they drive salaries beyond the percentage of
revenue they would like to devote to salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis, if the percentage is too high, it's not
a good deal for the owners,'' Stern said. ``The concessions we have
made still retain some risk, but that's all the risk the owners are
prepared to take on.''
</P>
<P>
   So the battle lines have been drawn.
</P>
<P>
   No more negotiating sessions are scheduled, even though the
agents indicated the union likely will draw up one final
counterproposal to submit to the owners in a last-ditch effort to
save the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern and Granik insist the owners will not give up any more
concessions and say Sunday's proposal was basically a
take-it-or-leave-it deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Stern expects the players to accept the deal under duress,
just because he's threatened to cancel the season, that won't
happen,'' Stanley said. ``To hold hostage the game for anything
more than what's available right now borders on greed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
