<HEADLINE>
BOULUD'S MISSING JEEP; NEW YEAR'S AT THE FOUR SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He Can't Even Get A Car Stolen Here
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How easy is it to misplace a car in Manhattan? Ask
chef Daniel Boulud.
</P>
<P>
   One day in late November, an employee at Boulud's soon-to-open
reincarnation of his famous restaurant, Daniel, parked Boulud's
blue Jeep Cherokee on East 80th Street near East End Avenue. The
employee could have sworn he parked it somewhere else. The result:
He thought it had been stolen, and Boulud reported that to the
police.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Jeep sat _ and sat and sat _ on East 80th. After a
few weeks, someone, evidently frustrated by the loss of a precious
parking space, scrawled on the windows, ``Hey NYPD: I Am a Stolen
Car'' in big letters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that helpful tip, traffic police officers, who festooned
the car with tickets, never checked to see whether it had been
reported stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic agents do not carry computers with them when they
write the summonses,'' said officer John Seidl, a police spokesman.
``So they can't run the plates to see whether parked cars are
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, would that be the thing to do?'' he added.
``Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery was finally solved on Monday, when Mark Sauter, the
executive vice president of APB Online, a news service devoted to
crime news, spotted the Jeep while walking along the street. Sauter
traced the license plate back to Boulud, and alerted him and the
police.
</P>
<P>
   Georgette Farkas, an assistant to Boulud, said no one was really
blaming the employee who lost the Jeep. ``It happens to
everybody,'' she said. ``The thing that amazes us is that a car can
sit somewhere that long in the city and not get stolen,'' she
added. ``There's a holiday story in there somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   No Shower Singing
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Barbara Cook, the cabaret legend and former Broadway
ingenue, has shared the stage with an impressive list of stars in
her career. But she does not plan to share it Thursday night with
Philip Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more accurately, with Philip Johnson's fountain.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a lavish, $800-a-person New Year's Eve feast, Ms.
Cook will perform at the Four Seasons, the first time the landmark
restaurant designed by Johnson has ever had a live performance.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a problem: The tranquil Pool Room, where she is to
sing, also has a fountain that spills into the pool and elegantly
muffles the conversations of the deal-making diners. It would
not-so-elegantly muffle Ms. Cook's soprano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they're dealing with it,'' she said Tuesday,
on a break from rehearsing. ``I think when I come out I'll just
throw a few coins into the pool and ask them to turn that fountain
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian Niccolini, a managing partner of the restaurant, said he
would make sure she does not even have to ask. ``She was basically
going to be competing against Philip Johnson,'' he said. ``And
that's no good. The fountain will be silent while she is singing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that if she wanted the pool turned into a huge bubble
bath, he could accommodate that as well. ``Anything for her, and
anything to make this evening a success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Niccolini explained that the restaurant had decided to feature
singing and a midnight meal for about 120 _ with beluga caviar,
black truffles, and Perrier-Jouet champagne, among other delicacies
_ for the first time this year basically because New Year's Eves
past had been, well, depressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would come in and eat and leave for parties,'' he said.
``At midnight the only people left here were the staff. And they
would pop a few bottles of champagne. It's time to give some life
to the Four Seasons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
