<SLUG> BC-FBC-DAYNE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYNE STAYS ON TRACK AT WISCONSIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Wisconsin junior running back Ron Dayne
continues to prepare for the biggest football game of his career,
he is content knowing that one of his life's biggest decisions has
already been made.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is this: Dayne, who has rushed for 4,845 yards in
three seasons (including bowl games), is staying in school for one
more year. He won't be turning pro and he has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   While he had been expected to make no announcement until after
Friday's Rose Bowl, Dayne felt getting it out of the way early
would take some pressure off and allow him to get prepared for
UCLA. It will also give him some time to visit family back home in
Berlin, N.J., after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to come back to Madison (Wis.) early and make
the decision,'' Dayne said Tuesday. ``I wanted to go home and stay
home for a little while because I haven't been home for two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   While he will be spending time with his year-old daughter Jada,
and her mother, Dayne's girlfriend Alia, Dayne also has plans to
visit his uncle, a pastor, who raised Dayne after Dayne's parents
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers and the Bruins will face off in the Rose Bowl on New
Year's Day. Dayne, who carried the ball 268 times in 1998 and
gained 1,279 yards, is expected to play a huge role.
</P>
<P>
   While Miami running back Edgarrin James had a big game against a
lackluster Bruins defense on Dec. 5 and led his team to a 49-45
victory, the soft-spoken Dayne, known to his teammates as the
``Great Dayne,'' is neither overconfident nor cocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one running back,'' he said. ``It ain't like every
running back did that (against UCLA), so you can't really use that.
I just want to go out and play hard and do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout 1998, Dayne has been plagued by injuries and
criticism of his straight-up running style. Yet if he gains 155
yards against the Bruins in the Rose Bowl, he will have 5,000 yards
career rushing.
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt he will get the ball. The question is, how
many times?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he carries it 50, that's a pretty good barometer,'' said
Brad Childress, Wisconsin's offensive coordinator. ``We're going to
win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Since head coach Barry Alvarez took over at Wisconsin nine
seasons ago, his teams have compiled a 32-2 record when rushing 50
or more times.
</P>
<P>
   But, what if Dayne only gets half that many carries?
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what 25 they are,'' Childress said. ``You know
sometimes you can have a one-play drive or a five-play drive or a
10-play drive before you score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, it's no secret we're going to hand him the football,''
he continued. ``And (the Bruins) are going to stack the line of
scrimmage and try to prevent him from running the football.''
</P>
<P>
   But coach Alvarez cautions against believing the Badgers are
simply a one-man team, in spite of Dayne's considerable
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got three All-Americans on this team,'' he said.
``That's two besides Dayne.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Alvarez doesn't think the Bruins' performance
against Miami's James is any indication of how they'll do against
Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't paid much attention to that game,'' he said.
``I thought that game was an aberration. I don't anticipate things
going that way on Jan. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how things go, Dayne admits the Badgers need to
win the Rose Bowl as a tribute to departing seniors who joined the
team after it won the 1994 Rose Bowl against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important,'' Dayne said. ``But it's important for the
guys under them, too. We've got to come back next year and play, so
we just want to go out and do our best, and hopefully come home
with a win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
