<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-RULES-1st-lede-writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY IS MONEY-MAKING STUDIO SUPREME FOR 1998
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Clarifies standings in last graf) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Mickey's got bragging rights for another year
as the king of Tinseltown.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an asteroid (``Armageddon''), a Chinese heroine
(``Mulan''), an unlikely football star (``The Waterboy'') and a
bunch of bugs (``A Bug's Life''), Walt Disney Co. will edge
Paramount by $18 million to become 1998's domestic box office
champ.
</P>
<P>
   The victory _ Disney's fourth in five years _ is sweet because
the entertainment giant did not move into first until last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a real `Rocky' story for us,'' said distribution
chief Phil Barlow. ``We had a hell of a comeback. We had four very
weak months at the start of the year with $90 million going into
May, but once we released `The Horse Whisperer,' we came on very
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney is expect to finish with $1.103 billion in gross domestic
receipts. Paramount's final total will be $1.085 billion, with
better than 40 percent of that coming from ``Titanic's'' 1998
grosses. That makes 1998 the only time two studios have topped $1
billion. Disney passed the mark in 1994, 1995 and 1996; Sony set
the record last year with $1.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A strong late-year performance by Disney is no surprise. It
usually weighs its schedule toward holiday periods when
family-oriented fare _ ``Toy Story,'' ``101 Dalmatians'' and
``Flubber'' in recent years _ reach the widest audience.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also credit Disney as a strong marketer. ``Disney is a
well-oiled machine with a lot of good product and huge
distribution,'' said Arthur Rockwell, a former studio executive.
``They're very disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the dozen 1998 films topping $100 million, four belonged to
Disney and two to Paramount (``The Truman Show,'' ``Deep Impact'').
``It's remarkable that two companies have done this much business
in a year,'' Barlow said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its four hit films, Disney generated respectable
performance from ``The Horse Whisperer,'' ``Six Days, Seven
Nights,'' ``The Parent Trap'' and ``Enemy of the State.'' The only
true disappointment for Disney came in October with the
back-to-back releases of a pair of pricey projects, ``Holy Man''
and ``Beloved,'' that performed very poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``Armageddon'' took in the highest gross, Disney's
most profitable movies were ``The Waterboy,'' which cost a mere $23
million to make, and ``A Bug's Life,'' with massive receipts from
foreign, video and toy licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which slumped slightly in 1997 with $880 million at the
box office, has maintained fairly consistent performances despite
limiting the number of releases each to year to around 18 in order
to control costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret is to have good moviemakers making entertaining
movies,'' Barlow said ``It would be even more enjoyable if
production and marketing costs weren't so high.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony will finish a distant third with about $750 million,
followed by 20th Century Fox and Warner Bros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-29-98 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981229.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKC-UMASS-DAVIDSON-BOS     12-29 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
MINUTEMEN FALL IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-UMASS-DAVIDSON-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Jim Greenidge 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ There was a nice flow to their game in the
first half, and that's why the University of Massachusetts
Minutemen were up, 42-27, on Davidson. But then the visitors made a
fierce comeback in the second half, taking the confidence out of
the Minutemen and making the basket look a whole lot smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson outscored UMass, 48-24 in the second half and 11-2 in
overtime, to post a major upset, 75-66, before 6,506 at the Mullins
Center last night. As the clock was winding down in regulation as
well as in overtime, the UMass players were looking around for
someone to take the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson improved to 5-5, but its other wins came against
ordinary teams Bowdoin, Elon, Southwest Texas State, and Washington
College.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats outrebounded the Minutemen, 45-38, scored 52 points
in the paint, and had 16 off second-chances. UMass, which fell to
3-6, was a mere 6 of 20 from the field the second half, and did not
score a field goal in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Mack had 24 points for UMass, 20 in the first half. Ben
Ebong flipped in 17 for Davidson, one of four Wildcats in double
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our themes for the past three weeks has been chip away,
chip away, keep chipping away, and if we could define the story, it
was chip away,'' said Davidson coach Bob McKillop. ``Look at the
clock and look at the score. A 15-point lead was now 10, and 10 was
now 5 and all of a sudden we were going for a tie.''
</P>
<P>
   UMass was evil from the foul line, hitting only 17 of 33
attempts. In one stretch, it missed 10 consecutive free throws.
Lari Ketner was 6 of 15 from the stripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started to score and the ball gets tight,'' said UMass
coach Bruiser Flint, whose team had 14 turnovers, 11 the second
half. ``We've talked about making plays the entire year. We need a
foul shot, make a foul shot. We need a rebound, get a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see it, we were scared to shoot it the second half.
We would pass out to guys and we were right under the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing a variety of defenses, Davidson got within 10 points,
47-37, on a Landry Kosmalski layup with 15:33 left in regulation.
Then it was down to 5, 52-47, with Kosmalski putting in the rebound
of a missed free throw. Finally, with 1:45 left, Ebong made his
third straight field goal, tying it at 62-62. Davidson had the last
shot in regulation, but point guard Ali Ton missed a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   UMass then had its problems in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hesitated because it was missing shots and it was
compounded by missing foul shots and the groans in the stands go
up,'' McKillop said. ``They heard that and they didn't want to hear
the groans again. They felt failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint wonders about his senior leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we're 3-6, somebody's got to step up and do
something,'' the UMass coach said. ``We have poor leadership. The
big rebound, the big shot, the big foul shot, who will make them?
Somebody's got to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   UMass's Atlantic 10 opener is Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
