u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-BUSH-PARADE-COX     12-29 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BUSH-PARADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elephant, 25 bands to trumpet in new governor
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post Capital Bureau
</P>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Miss Florida USA, 25 marching bands and a
NASCAR stock car will parade in honor of the newly inaugurated Gov.
Jeb Bush on Tuesday ahead of a symbol of Florida's new domination
by Republicans: a circus elephant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for all Floridians,'' said inaugural parade Chairman
Rusty Price of the one hour, 45 minute march through downtown
Tallahassee. ``We think it will be the most exciting one yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade has 87 elements in it, from Florida Highway Patrol
motorcycles to the families of Bush; his lieutenant governor, Frank
Brogan; a marching band composed of musicians from South Fork and
Martin County high schools (Brogan was once Martin County schools
superintendent); the six Cabinet members; the seven Supreme Court
justices; Florida A&AMP;M University's famous Marching 100; the
Budweiser Clydesdales; the Port St. Lucie Jazz Band; and the
BellSouth stock car of Lakeland's Joe Nemechek.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing up the rear will be a pachyderm from Sarasota-based
Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus _ in honor of the first
time since Reconstruction that Florida will simultaneously have a
Republican governor, Senate president and House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, George and Barbara Bush will attend their son's
swearing in on the Old Capitol steps.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Billy Graham, a longtime friend of the Bush family,
will give the invocation and benediction.
</P>
<P>
   The parade, to start at 1:30, will be only one event in the
``Florida Festival,'' the final day of Bush's three-day
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   A prayer breakfast is planned at FAMU at 7 a.m.; the swearing-in
ceremony will take place at noon; a Governor's Mansion open house
is to start at 2 p.m. along with a street fair; and a laser light
show down Adams Street will wrap up the day at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   All events are free and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
