<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-29 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ As another cool, foggy morning dawned over beignets
and coffee in the French Quarter, there was the story in the sports
section of the paper, staring up in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   It told of Peyton Manning, the local hero, returning to his
hometown after a rookie season in the NFL that had been filled with
impressive numbers and glowing compliments, along with the first
payments in a six-year, $48 million contract from the Indianapolis
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   If you were like most readers from the Garden District to the
Irish Channel, you might have nodded your head at young Manning's
good fortune and absent-mindedly rubbed your shoulder, wondering
what it would be like to be able to throw a football for such a
cozy living.
</P>
<P>
   If you were like Branndon Stewart, believing you have the arm
and all the talent, you might have shook your head in disgust at
what could have been.
</P>
<P>
   But not if you really were Branndon Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``People misread me and my emotions,'' the Texas A&AMP;M quarterback
said. ``They seem to have made up their minds how I'm supposed to
feel _ maybe it's how they believe they would feel in my place _
and that's made for some things that have been said and written
about me that are just wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe things haven't worked out during the past few years the
way a lot of other people thought they would. But that hasn't made
me angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrets about my college years? Yeah, I have one. I broke up
with my girlfriend for about eight months. Now we're back together,
and that's good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest? Well, you have to understand that I'm a very
religious person, and I believe that whatever happens is God's
will. He has a plan for me, and it will eventually become clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart had his own plan back in 1994. Having quarterbacked
Stephenville High to a 16-0 record and the Texas state
championship, he was going to enroll at Tennessee and compete for a
job with this other hotshot passer named Manning.
</P>
<P>
   On the scale of bad decisions, it was like putting all your
money into the development of the 8-track tape player or the
Betamax. And it would create a permanent link between the two young
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was naive,'' Stewart said. ``There weren't many kids at my
little high school who had gone on to play college football at the
Division I level. I didn't really know anything about how it worked
or what would happen. I figured that things would unfold slowly,
that I would get to Tennessee and be an understudy for a couple of
years and then get a chance to compete as a starter as a junior or
senior. I guess I didn't understand the pressures and the realities
of big-time college football.''
</P>
<P>
   At Tennessee, where the Volunteers play before crowds of 106,000
at Neyland Stadium, nothing is slow in unfolding, and the
competition between Stewart and Manning over who would run the
offense for four years began immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart played in 11 of 12 games his freshman season, but the
handwriting was on the wall, and he transferred to A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not because I didn't think I had the talent to compete,'' he
said. ``I could see how things were going. I think Peyton was
probably more advanced than me in terms of understanding offenses,
reading defenses. It was just best that I went elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, returning home to Texas to play for the Aggies
brought different kinds of pressure from fans, most of whom
believed his arm was going to carry them to national championships
and some of whom even went so far as to label him a bust after he
lost the starting job to Randy McCown.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now, the Aggies are in the Sugar Bowl to face Ohio State in
large part because of Stewart and his 324-yard, three-touchdown
performance in the Big 12 championship win over Kansas State when
McCown was sidelined with a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit ironic, perhaps, that in a city where so many broken
dreams have been washed down Bourbon Street, Stewart has come to
fulfill his.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I thought the college experience would be like,''
he said. ``Some ups, some downs, a learning thing. I came to go to
school, to have some fun, to play some football. I've done all
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'd love to give the NFL a try. That's up to whether
somebody wants to give me a chance. I see Peyton on TV, and I see
other quarterbacks, and I believe I can do those things. If it
doesn't happen, my life will go on in a different way. No anger. No
jealousy. No regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people might not want to believe this, but I got
everything I expected out of my college career.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, an education.
</P>
</TEXT>
